window.__QUIZ_SUBJECT__=[{"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DEBORAH", "question": "Describe how Deborah led her people to victory.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the death of Ehud, the judge, Israel sinned against God again and God delivered them into the hands of Jabin, a Canaanite king.    Sisera was the commander of Jabin's army. His army had 900 iron chariots at their disposal and they oppressed the people of Israel for twenty years.    The Israelites cried out to the Lord and the Lord decided to save them. At the time, Deborah, the wife of Lappidoth, was a prophetess and a judge in the land. She told Barak, the son of Abinoam, to gather 10,000 men from the tribe of Naphtali and Zebulun to fight against Sisera. God promised to draw the army of Sisera to river Kishon and to deliver him into Barak's hands.  Barak accepted to go on one condition. He said he would go only if Deborah would accompany them. Deborah accepted to go with them but she prophesied that the glory of killing Sisera would go to a woman.    Barak gathered 10,000 men from the tribe of Naphtali and Zebulun and encamped on Mount Tabor in readiness to engage Sisera and his army.    When Sisera heard that Barak had gathered his army on Mount Tabor, he also gathered his army and matched against them. He matched his army to the river Kishon. There, the Lord delivered Sisera and his army into the hands of Barak. The Lord routed them. Sisera disembarked from his chariot and fled on foot. He fled and at the invitation of Jael, hid in her tent.    Sisera asked for water and Jael gave him milk. Sisera slept and she covered him with a blanket. Sisera told her to stand by the gate, if someone asks whether she had seen him, she should say no. Then Sisera fell into a deep sleep. Jael took a tent peg and drove it into his temple, killing him. As Barak pursued Sisera, he met Jael. Jael took him and showed him the dead body of Sisera. That very day, God subdued the Canaanite king, Jabin and his country and Israel knew peace again.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Mention three ways by which women today are contributing towards national development.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- By participating in politics.  - By being employable and adding to national economy.  - Enlightened women demonstrate equal abilitieswith enlightened men.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "Give an account of the division of the kingdom of Israel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "As prophesied by Ahijah (1 Kings 11:31-35), the house of Israel was divided into two kingdoms. This division, which took place approximately 975 B.C., after the death of Solomon and during the reign of his son, Rehoboam, came about as the people revolted against heavy taxes levied by Solomon and Rehoboam.    During Rehoboam's reign, the tribe of Judah and the majority of the tribe of Benjamin accepted Rehoboam as their king. They became the kingdom of Judah, or the southern kingdom of Israel, with its capital at Jerusalem.The other 10 tribes and the remainder of the tribe of Benjamin - usually spoken of as the Ten Tribes - chose Jeroboam as their king. The collective Ten Tribes retained the title of Israel, and became known also as Ephraim, which was the dominant tribe. It became the northern kingdom, with headquarters at Shechem in Samaria.    On the whole, Judah remained more faithful to Jehovah. Almost as soon as the northern kingdom of Israel was established, it went into apostasy. Although great prophets such as Elijah and Amos ministered in the kingdom, the people worshiped false gods and adopted many practices of Baalism.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "What unwise policies of Solomon led to it?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The forced labour was an infringement upon the rights of the people resulting into hatred against Solomon.   Another unwise policy of Solomon was the giving away of twenty Israelite cities to king Hiram of Tyre to compensate for the services and supplies he received from the king.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Narrate the story of Daniel in which his faith was put to test.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Daniel in the lion's den is one of the most familiar stories in the Bible. Even though Daniel was an old man at the time, he refused to take the easy way out and abandon God. The threat of an agonizing death did not change his trust in God. Daniel's name means \"God is my judge,\" and in this miracle, God, not men, judged Daniel and found him innocent. When the lions' den event occurred, Daniel was in his 80s. Through a life of hard work and obedience to God, he had risen through the political ranks as an administrator of this pagan kingdom. In fact, Daniel was so honest and hardworking that the other government officials—those who were jealous of him—could find nothing against him to cause him to be removed from office.  So they tried to use Daniel's faith in God against him. They tricked King Darius into passing a 30-day decree that said anyone who prayed to another god or man other than the king would be thrown into the lions' den. Daniel learned of the decree but did not change his habit. Just as he had done his whole life, he went home, knelt down, faced Jerusalem, and prayed to God. The wicked administrators caught him in the act and told the king. King Darius, who loved Daniel, tried to save him, but the decree could not be revoked. The Medes and Persians had a foolish custom that once a law was passed—even a bad law—it could not be repealed.  At sundown, they threw Daniel into the den of lions. The king could not eat or sleep all night. At dawn, he ran to the lions' den and asked Daniel if his God had protected him. Daniel replied, \"My God sent his angel, and he shut the mouths of the lions. They have not hurt me, because I was found innocent in his sight. Nor have I ever done any wrong before you, O king.\" (Daniel 6:22, NIV).  Scripture says the king was overjoyed that the prophet had survived his night with the wild beasts. God had sent an angel to shut the mouths of the lions. Daniel was brought out, unharmed, \"...because he had trusted in his God.\" (Daniel 6:23, NIV)    King Darius had the men who falsely accused Daniel arrested. Along with their wives and children, they were all thrown into the lions' den, where they were immediately killed by the beasts.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "What two suggestions would you give to a present-day priest who faces opposition in his work of evangelization", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Advise him to continue to grow in faith.  - Advise them to maintain their integrity", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION B>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Narrate the story of the healing of the leper and indicate the significance of the instructions given by Jesus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "A leper knelt before Jesus and besought him to heal him. Jesusstretched out his hand and touched him saying, \"be clean\". Immediately, the leper was healed; he became clean. Then Jesus warned him not to tell anybody or spread the news, but to go to the priest and offer, for his cleansing, what Moses commanded as a proof to the people. But he went out and began to spread the news such that the crowd that gathered around Jesus made it  difficult for him to enter openly into the town. Jesus remained in the  countryside where people came to him from all over the place.    The significance of the instructions given to the cleansed leper by Jesus were:   - Jesus wanted to keep his messiahship secret because it was  yet too early to expose himself as, he needed some time for his teaching to  permeate people's hearts to enable them fully appreciate the true meaning of  his messiahship through his death on the cross and salvation for man.   - Again, his teaching ministry was of greater importance than his healing ministry.  - Jesus obeyed the Mosaic law, especially as it was in accordance with God's law of mercy and kindness.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION B>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "In what two ways does God still perform miracles today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- God continues to perform miracles of healing through doctors, nurses, surgeons, etc.   - Many Christians have been healed because of their faith.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "How does John describe Jesus as the Lamb of God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When Jesus is called the Lamb of God in John 1:29 and John 1:36, it is referring to Him as the perfect and ultimate sacrifice for sin. In order to understand who Christ was and what He did, we must begin with the Old Testament, which contains prophecies concerning the coming of Christ as a \"guilt offering\" (Isaiah 53:10). In fact, the whole sacrificial system established by God in the Old Testament set the stage for the coming of Jesus Christ, who is the perfect sacrifice God would provide as atonement for the sins of His people (Romans 8:3; Hebrews 10).    The sacrifice of lambs played a very important role in the Jewish religious life and sacrificial system. When John the Baptist referred to Jesus as the \"Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world\" (John 1:29), the Jews who heard him might have immediately thought of any one of several important sacrifices. With the time of the Passover feast being very near, the first thought might be the sacrifice of the Passover lamb. The Passover feast was one of the main Jewish holidays and a celebration in remembrance of God's deliverance of the Israelites from bondage in Egypt. In fact, the slaying of the Passover lamb and the applying of the blood to doorposts of the houses (Exodus 12:11-13) is a beautiful picture of Christ's atoning work on the cross. Those for whom He died are covered by His blood, protecting us from the angel of (spiritual) death.    Another important sacrifice involving lambs was the daily sacrifice at the temple in Jerusalem. Every morning and evening, a lamb was sacrificed in the temple for the sins of the people (Exodus 29:38-42). These daily sacrifices, like all others, were simply to point people towards the perfect sacrifice of Christ on the cross. In fact, the time of Jesus' death on the cross corresponds to the time the evening sacrifice was being made in the temple. The Jews at that time would have also been familiar with the Old Testament prophets Jeremiah and Isaiah, who foretold the coming of One who would be brought \"like a lamb led to the slaughter\" (Jeremiah 11:19; Isaiah 53:7) and whose sufferings and sacrifice would provide redemption for Israel. Of course, that person was none other than Jesus Christ, \"the Lamb of God.\"", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "In what two ways is this description significant to Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Christians must turn away from sinfulness.  - Jesus is the final sacrifice.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "What happened to Stephen after he had referred to the Jewish Council as stiff-necked people, uncircumcised in heart and ears?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The stoning of Stephen is recorded in Acts 7:54–60, but this story really begins in Acts 6, when Stephen starts performing signs and wonders. Members of the local synagogue find themselves ill-equipped to argue with Stephen (Acts 6:8–10), so they lied about him until the Jewish leaders eventually brought him before the Sanhedrin to be judged (Acts 6:11–15).    Here, Stephen boldly recounts the history of Israel and accuses the Sanhedrin of repeating their ancestors' mistakes by killing Jesus:    \"You stiff-necked people! Your hearts and ears are still uncircumcised. You are just like your ancestors: You always resist the Holy Spirit! Was there ever a prophet your ancestors did not persecute? They even killed those who predicted the coming of the Righteous One. And now you have betrayed and murdered him—you who have received the law that was given through angels but have not obeyed it\" (Acts 7:51–53).  This enrages the members of the Sanhedrin. It wasn't the first time Jesus' followers spoke in front of the Sanhedrin and proclaimed Him the Messiah—or even the first time Christians criticized Jewish leaders about His death. Peter and John had done so in Acts 4 and got off with a warning. And in Acts 5, the Sanhedrin was ready to execute the apostles until one of their own talked them out of it.    Their fury was left simmering, and Stephen brought it to a boil that overflowed. Here they were yet again, with a Christian standing before the Sanhedrin, accusing its members of not following the law and murdering the Righteous One.    \"When the members of the Sanhedrin heard this, they were furious and gnashed their teeth at him. But Stephen, full of the Holy Spirit, looked up to heaven and saw the glory of God, and Jesus standing at the right hand of God. \"Look,\" he said, \"I see heaven open and the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God.\"  At this they covered their ears and, yelling at the top of their voices, they all rushed at him, dragged him out of the city and began to stone him. Meanwhile, the witnesses laid their coats at the feet of a young man named Saul.    While they were stoning him, Stephen prayed, \"Lord Jesus, receive my spirit.\" Then he fell on his knees and cried out, \"Lord, do not hold this sin against them.\" When he had said this, he fell asleep.    And Saul approved of their killing him (Acts 7:54–8:1a).    Right after personally condemning the members of the Sanhedrin, Stephen claims to have a vision of God—a vision that surely reminded them of another memorable encounter they'd had a few years before. As He stood before the Sanhedrin, Jesus proclaimed, \"And you will see the Son of Man sitting at the right hand of the Mighty One and coming on the clouds of heaven\" (Mark 14:62).", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Of what significance was this episode to the Early Church?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It led to evangelism outside Jerusalem.  - It led to the persecution of the early church", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION C>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Explain what Paul called Spiritual Gifts in 1 Corinthians and how he likened them to the human body.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The nine gifts as enlightened by St. Paul are as follows;  i. The utterance of wisdom  ii. The utterance of knowledge  iii. Faith  iv. Gift of healing  v. The gift of working miracles  vi. The gift of prophesy  vii. The gift of distinguishing between spirits (discernment)  viii. The gift to speak in tongues  ix. The gift to interprete tongues.  All these gifts Paul said, are inspired by the same spirit who apportions to individuals as he wills, but the manifestation of the gifts in the individual is for the common good of the body of Christ (the church). Paul likened these gifts to the human body with different parts and different functions all playing an important role for the good of the entire body. So it is with Christ; by one spirit we were baptized into one body of Christ. Paul, in his analogy, went further to say that God has arranged the different parts of the body to be mutually interdependent and necessary for the existence of the entire body. Some parts which seem to be weaker are indispensable. The parts which people consider less honourable are invested with greater honour; the unpresentable parts are treated with greater modesty which our presentable parts do not require. God created the body that there might be no discord, if one member suffers, all suffer together, if one member is honoured, all rejoice together. In the same way, in the body of Christ (that is the church); God has appointed apostles, prophets, teachers, workers of miracles, healers, administrators and speakers in various kinds of tongues. All must use their gifts to the glory of God and for the growth of the church.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION C>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "What is the significance of this teaching to the Church?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "It emphasized the overall need for unity in the church.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What did Paul, from his personal example, teach the Thessalonians about dignity of labour?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul wrote to theThessalonians on the dignity of labour. He rebuked and disowned those brothers in the church who lived in idleness for they were not living according to the laid down rules of the church. He encouraged them to imitate his exemplary life. He did not in any way like idleness, neither did he depend on their material support for living. He worked for his earning and paid for what he ate.  Paul did not imply that anyone who work in the house of God should not be entitled to wages. He had to put his teaching into practice by saying if anyone would not work, let him not eat.  Paul particularly mentioned those members whom he heard had refused to work but were relying on others. He commanded them to do away with such habits. He finally warned that if any member should refuse to listen to his instruction, such a member should be isolated. This would make him to be ashamed of himself with a view to rethinking his actions. The church, Paul warned should not regard such members as enemies but they should be treated with all human sympathy.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "State two ways by which Christians should uphold this teaching.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Christians should be proud of their jobs.  - Christians should not be lazy.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Describe how Paul dealt with the problem of the Corinthian Christians who did not believe in ressurection.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul wrote to the Corinthians to counter the wrong teaching imparted to them. In the first place, he reminded them about his early teaching on the subject which they accepted and hoped would give them justification and salvation if they continued in true faith in Christ. Paul told them that he delivered the doctrine of resurrection to them as he received it; that Jesus died for their sins, was buried and has risen on the third day according to the scriptures. As proofs of his resurrection, he appeared to his disciples including Peter, James and five hundred others. Lastly, he appeared to him Paul, the least of the apostles, being a persecutor of the church.  He wondered why some unbelievers should deny the resurrection of Christ if there were such abundant and clear evidence to prove it. Paul averred that Jesus could not have been raised if there was no resurrection and, if he was not raised, then his preachings and those of others would have been in vain. This means that preachers would be guilty of deception and misrepresentation of God. These would render their faith useless and make them remain in sins. If Jesus did not resurrect, then the dead in Christ remain perished and those who are still alive with faith in Christ stand to be pitied. But the fact remains that Christ has been raised from the dead and has become the first fruit among those who have fallen asleep. Paul stated further that death first came through the first Adam, so also life after death has come to man through jesus Christ. God has put every thing under Christ's authority and through his grace, Christians are assured of life eternal.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1995>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1995", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "What is the significance of the ressurection of Christ to Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Victory over death has been won for the children of God by Jesus.  - By raising Jesus from the dead, God has shown the world that Jesus is His son.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "How did Moses prepare the Israelites for the covenant with God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God had specific instructions on how the Israelites were to prepare to make the new covenant. Before making the covenant, God brought Israelites to the foot of Mt. Sinai and asked Moses to ask them if they were willing to make the covenant with HIM. GOD asked them to enter into a personal relationship as a community with HIM.    The Israelites agreed to make a covenant. They agreed to obey all God's commands. God wanted to confirm that Moses was His true prophet. He therefore told Moses that He would come in a thick cloud to meet Israelites. In preparation for God's coming on Mt. Sinai.  The Israelites were to:    - Make themselves holy by washing their clothes (garments)  - Mark the boundaries on the foot of the mountain to prevent any person or animal from climbing the mountain.  - To abstain from sexual relations.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Why was this preparation necessary?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This is important to reinforce the Holiness of God.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Who was Naaman? Narrate the story of Naaman", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Naaman was a commander of the Syrian army. He was leprous. He tried everything he could to heal his leprosy, but there was no solution. An Israelite slave girl in the service of Naaman's wife suggested that if Naaman could go to Samaria, there was a prophet there who could heal his leprosy. Naaman took to the girl's advice and collected a letter from the king of Syria to the king of Israel informing him of Naaman's predicament.  The king of Israel was sad when he received and read the letter. He queried whether he was God to kill or make alive that a word was sent to him that Naaman should be cured by him of his leprosy. Elisha, the prophet of God then in Israel learnt that the king had rent his clothes. He sent to the king that Naaman should be sent to him, Naaman went to Elisha who instead of praying  for him or laying his hands on him directed that Naaman should go and wash  himself seven times in the River Jordan and he would be cured of his leprosy.  Naaman doubted, and wondered if Abana and Pharpar, the rivers of Damascus were not better than all the waters of Israel. Could he not wash in them and be cleaned? He decided to return to Damascus with great annoyance and disappointment, but his servant persuaded him to do what the man of God had  commanded. He yielded to the advice of his servant, and went into the river  Jordan. He dipped himself into it seven times and he became so clean that his  skin, according to the bible, became fresh as of a new born baby.  Seeing this, Naaman returned to Elisha with some precious gifts to present to him as gratitude and sign of thanksgiving, but Elisha rejected them. Naaman requested that he should be allowed to collect a small quantity of earth from Israel to Damascus. His request was granted. He put the sand in a corner of his house and said henceforth, he would serve the God of Israel.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Mention two important lessons which Naaman learnt from his healing", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He learnt that the God of Israel is the one true God.  - He learnt that God is a forgiving God.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "I am no prophet nor a prophet's son; but I am a herdsman, and a dresser of sycamore trees \"  Give an account of the event which led to this statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When social injustices and religious malpractices of Israel had reached its peak, Amos condemned the social and religious immoralities among the people. The priest of the royal sanctuary at Bethel, Amaziah reported Amos to the king accusing him of conspiracy and sedition. Amos was then ordered to go back to Judah where he belonged, to prophesy and earn his living there. He was warned never to prophesy in Israel again because it was a royal sanctuary. Amos replied Amaziah that it was when he (Amos) was tending the flock that the Lord sent him to prophesy to Israel.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "What else did the speaker say on this occasion?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Since Amaziah stood against his prophecy, he pronounced the following curses on him:    - Amaziah's wife would become a harlot in the city.  - His sons and daughter would be slained by the sword.  - His land would be divided by line.  -  Israel would surely go into exile, away from its land.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION B>4", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Describe the baptism of Jesus as recorded by Matthew and indicate its purpose.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When John the Baptist was baptising people, Jesus came to him to be baptised in the river Jordan John wished Jesus to baptise him and not him (John) to baptise him (Jesus). Jesus asked John to baptize him so as to fulfil all righteousness. John consented and Jesus was baptised. As he came out of the water, the heavens were opened and the spirit of God descended upon him like a dove and a voice came from heaven saying: \"This is my beloved son, with whom I am well pleased\".  Jesus' baptism was important in the following ways:  - The baptism marked Jesus' call to public ministry as a God-sent Messiah.  - Jesus accepted baptism by immersion in order to give his approval to the Jewish ritual of a symbolic cleansing of sin.  - Jesus did not sin, yet he wanted others to be free from sin.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "What was Jesus' teaching about himself as the Living Bread?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "On two occasions, Jesus miraculously fed thousands of people in the wilderness, reenacting events from Moses' day when God provided manna from heaven for His people in the desert. The day after Jesus first fed the people, many returned, hoping for more food.  Instead of performing another sign, Jesus claimed that He Himself was the Bread – the Manna that had come down from heaven. He had come from heaven into the wilderness of the world, amidst a spiritually-wandering people who saw themselves in a theological exile. Jesus then went further than simply associating Himself with bread; He said that whoever would come to Him would never hunger again.    In the agrarian culture of first-century Jews, having bread was essential to survival. There was no endless supply of bread (in dozens of varieties) available at the local market. Simply put: without bread, there was no life. Even today, almost everything we eat comes from something else that has died. Dead animals provide us with meat. Dead wheat gives us bread.   \"I am the Bread of Life\" is another way of saying: \"Without My death, you cannot live.\" Just as bread is the essential element in the human diet, Jesus says that He Himself is the foundation for spiritual life. Without His death, no one else can live. Those who come to Him will never again be hungry. Those who believe in Him will never again thirst. Through His death, we live.    John describes many people turning away and rejecting Jesus after the \"Bread\" speech. Many today will also find it too hard to swallow that Jesus is more than just one religious teacher in a diverse grocery-store selection of beliefs. Yet, Jesus' words remain true. Whoever eats the bread that He gives (His flesh) will live eternally. The \"open-minded\" and \"diverse\" people who leave room for belief in other religious figures will starve to death.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what two ways is this teaching significant ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Living bread means word of God.  - Faith in Jesus is assurance for everlasting life", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Describe the circumstances in Antioch which led to the commissioning of Paul and Barnabas for their missionary journey.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the church of Antioch were many teachers and prophets. There was Barnabas, Lucius, Manaen and Paul. One day, as they were worshiping and fasting, the spirit of God told them to set apart Paul and Barnabas for a special work He wanted them to do. After they had laid their hands on them, they sent them away on the first missionary journey with John accompanying them.    The trio travelled to Seleucia, Cyprus till they got to Salamis, where they preached in their Synagogue. They went through the whole Island and when they got to Paphos, they encountered a false prophet called Bar-jesus, meaning Elymas. The proconsul of the town was called Segius Paulus and a man of great intelligence. He invited Paul and his team over because he wanted to hear the word of God. Bar-jesus was with the proconsul when Paul and his men got there and this Bar-jesus man would not allow the proconsul to hear the word from Paul. So Paul rebuked him and cast a temporary blindness upon him by the name of God. When the proconsul saw what had happened, he believed.    There in Paphos, John left the team and went back to Jerusalem but Paul and Barnabas went on to Perga in Pamphylia.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Narrate their experience at the Island of Cyprus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul and Barnabas traveled together through the island of Cyprus and the province of Asia (modern Asia Minor) preaching the gospel in the first missionary journey (Acts 13). The name Barnabas means \"son of encouragement,\" and encouragement was his first function in Paul's life. When the newly converted Saul/Paul came to the Christians at Jerusalem, they were afraid of him. But Barnabas built a bridge between Saul and the other Christians, vouching for the reality of his faith and ministry (Acts 9:26–27). Later, news reached Jerusalem of a burgeoning church in Syrian Antioch, and Barnabas was sent to encourage the believers there (Acts 11:22). Many people began coming to the Lord and joining the church, so Barnabas sought out Paul and, finding him, brought him to Antioch. The biblical account calls Barnabas \"a good man, full of the Holy Spirit and faith\" (Acts 11:24). While Paul and Barnabas were still in Antioch, a prophet named Agabus foretold a famine, and the church determined to send relief to the brothers living in Judea (verses 27–29). They sent Paul and Barnabas to deliver the gift (verse 30).  After that, the Holy Spirit chose Paul and Barnabas to be missionaries (Acts 13:2), and the church of Antioch sent them off. Paul and Barnabas took John Mark along as a helper and traveled through many Gentile areas with the gospel. They were \"men who . . . risked their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ\" (Acts 15:25). Halfway through their journey, Mark left Paul and Barnabas, and this became a point of contention later. As they planned a second missionary journey, Paul and Barnabas disagreed on whether to take Mark again. Paul was determined not to bring him, due to his forsaking them previously. Barnabas, ever the encourager, was unwilling to leave John Mark behind. A \"sharp disagreement\" arose between them, and they parted ways. From that point on, Barnabas traveled with John Mark, and Paul chose Silas as his companion in ministry (Acts 15:36–41). Later, we see indications that the rift was healed, and Paul considered Mark \"helpful\" in the ministry (2 Timothy 4:11).", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION C>7", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "From Paul's letter to the Romans, explain the term  Justification  and state the conditions for its achievement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Justification can be explained as a process of being acquitted from sin by God. It is a process by which man's sin is forgiven and over looked by God as a saving grace for eternal life.   The conditions for the achievement of justification can be stated as follows: Justification is a gift of God's grace. It cannot be attained by man's effort or his perfection. It was the wish of Jesus to carry man's sin on the cross, therefore, man has the choice of rejecting it, but the consequence of rejection is destruction, A Christian, therefore, has to believe in the resurrection of Jesus as a first step to justification. It is the confession of a man's faith with his mouth that can earn him salvation.  Those who are trusting in the righteousness of the law (Jews and Gentiles) have fallen short of the Grace of God. Those who would be accepted by Jesus when he comes back are those who accept him in faith.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Give an account of Peter's teaching on Humility in relation to Christian living.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul's teaching to the Philippians was to give them a sense of humility among themselves. As at the time, Paul wrote the message, great disunity existed among the church members as a result of lack of humility.    Paul used the case of Jesus Christ to show them what humility is all about.  He said Jesus was in the form of God, but He did not count Himself equal with God.  He took the form of an ordinary servant and was born in the likeness of man.    In the human form, he humbled Himself and became obedient unto death, even on the cross which was considered as one of the worst forms of death.  For this reason, he said, \"God has highly exalted Him and given Him a name which is above every other name, that at the name of Jesus, every kneel must bow and every tongue confesses that Jesus is the Son of God to the glory of God the Father'' (Phil 2:9-11).", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Mention any two situations in life today that call for the manifestation of true humility among Christians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The presence of opposition to the gospel.  - To be good example in societies.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "What is Prayer?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Prayer is giving our attention to God in a two-way spiritual relationship where we talk to God and also listen to Him.  The most basic definition of prayer is \"talking to God.\" Prayer is not meditation or passive reflection; it is direct address to God.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1996>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1996", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "List four types of prayers and give four reasons why some people's prayers are not answered by God", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Prayer of supplication  - Prayer of thanksgiving  - Prayer of intercession  - Prayer of thanksgiving    REASONS FOR UNANSWERED PRAYERS  - Wrong motives  \"When you ask, you do not receive, because you ask with wrong motives, that you may spend what you get on your pleasures.\" – James 4:3  - Unconfessed sin  James tells us that the prayer of the righteous is powerful and effective. (James 5:16) If, however, we don't find ourselves in a righteous state, we are praying ineffectively.  - Pride  But he gives us more grace. That is why Scripture says:\"God opposes the proud, but shows favor to the humble.\" – James 4:6   - Doubt  But when you ask, you must believe and not doubt, because the one who doubts is like a wave of the sea, blown and tossed by the wind. – James 1:6", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Narrate the first account of the creation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the beginning, before the heavens and the earth was created by God, the earth was without form, it was void and full of darkness. Water was all over the surface and the spirit of God was moving on the surface of the water.    On the first day, God commanded that there should be \"light\" and there was light. God separated the light from the darkness. he called the light \"day\" and the darkness he called \"night\".    On the second day, God created the firmament, also called the heavens. He separated the waters above from the waters below. The water above, he called firmament.    On the third day, God created dry land and vegetation. God commanded the water below to gather at one place and dry land emerged. The dry land he called \"earth\" and the gathering of the water he called \"the ocean\" or the Sea. After that God commanded the earth to bring forth grasses and trees that bore fruits.  On the fourth day, God created the luminaries. He created the Sun, the Moon and the Stars. The Sun is to rule over the day and the Moon to rule over the night. He said the luminaries should determine the signs, seasons, years and the days.    On the fifth day, God created the Sea creatures and the birds of the air. Every kind of creature that resides in the Sea, God created. Then every creature that flew in the air was also created.    On the sixth day, God created four-legged animals and all creeping creatures. On the same day, God created man in His own image. He created both the male and the female on the same day. God blessed the man and woman and asked them to multiply and fill the earth.    God gave to man, as food, the fruit-bearing trees. He saw that all the things he had created were good.  On the seventh day, God rested. He had finished the work of creation. He blessed the day and hallowed it.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "In what two ways does this account demonstrate the nature of God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Man has a special place in creation  Man, created on the sixth day, was the final act of creation. He was created out of the spoken word of God (out of nothing). He was created in the image of God and blessed by God – privileged in the sight of God.  - God is sovereign  God's sovereignty brought the world into existence – he is powerful.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "How did David spare the life of Saul?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Even though Saul was prone to paranoia and madness once it became clear that David was going to take his place on the throne of Israel, there were times when he came to his senses and thought clearly. Today's passage describes one of these lucid moments, which occurred after David spared Saul's life.    After David's escape from Saul in the wilderness of Maon because Saul was called away to fight the Philistines, David and the men following him set up camp at Engedi on the west side of the Dead Sea (1 Sam. 23:24–29). Engedi is known for having several large caves, and as chapter 24 opens, we see that David and his men were hiding in the innermost parts of one of the caves (v. 3). Saul entered the cave to relieve himself, and David snuck up behind him and cut off a small piece of his robe (vv. 1–4). He would later show the piece of the robe to Saul in order to prove that he was not looking to kill Saul and replace him on the throne of Israel (vv. 8–15).  David's actions were quite remarkable. As his men told him, he had the opportunity to put an end to Saul's threat once and for all. Yet, David spared Saul's life, because he did not have any right to kill the Lord's anointed (vv. 3–6). David knew that the kingdom had been given to him by the Lord (16:1–13); however, he knew also that the throne had to come to him in God's appointed timing. He was not permitted to take it by force. God never told David to assassinate Saul, and for David to do so would mean that the kingdom would come to him by illicit means. Saul, as we have seen, was willing to hold on to his throne by murder, but David understood that it is better to live away from the palace in obedience to God than it is to violate God's will and sit on a throne. He was content to rest in the Lord's sovereignty and to let God exact vengeance on Saul at the proper time, for vengeance belongs to the Lord (Deut. 32:35). Truly, David was a man after God's own heart.  By sparing Saul's life, David convinced the king temporarily to stop fighting against him (1 Sam. 24:16–22). More importantly, his actions revealed the work of the Lord in his life. Only one transformed by divine grace could stay his hand in such a situation. Matthew Henry comments, \"David had a fair opportunity to destroy Saul, and, to his honor, he did not make use of it; and his sparing Saul's life was as great an instance of God's grace in him as the preserving of his own life was of God's providence over him.\"  David stayed his hand not because Saul deserved to live but because he was not Saul's appointed judge. The Lord did not commission him to execute Saul, so he had to leave vengeance to the Lord. Although there are times when we must pursue earthly justice, we likewise are called to leave vengeance to God. Only He can exact perfect vengeance, so let us pray that the Lord would give us the strength not to take vengeance unlawfully.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "What two lessons can we derive from the story?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Christians should be forgiving.  - Christians must respect God's word.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION A>3", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "3", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "Describe Hosea's marital experience and how it demonstrates God's love for Israel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God told Hosea to marry a harlot and have children with her because the land of Israel had committed harlotry by worshipping other gods. Hosea went to marry Gomah, the daughter of Diblaim.    Gomer gave birth to a son and God asked Hosea to name the child, Jezreel, meaning God would punish the house of Jehu for the blood of Jezreel.     Gomer bore a second child, a daughter this time. God told Hosea to call the child 'Not pitied' meaning God would no longer have pity on Israel. God said he would not forgive Israel.     Finally, Gomer had another son. God told Hosea to name the child 'Not my people', meaning God had rejected Israel from being His people and that He was no longer their God. In the early days of their marriage, there was a lot of love between the couple but later, Gomer became unfaithful. She started going after other men, defiling the marriage. Consequently, Hosea sent her away, he divorced her.     Gomer went through many difficulties as a divorcee. She became aimless; she looked for her lovers but never saw them. Finally, she became a slave.    Many years later, God told Hosea to go and bring Gomer back to the marital home. So Hosea went to purchase Gomer from her slavery. He bought her for 15 shekels of silver, a homer and a lethech of bailey. He told her to come back home and stop the harlotry and not to belong to another man anymore. Hosea also promised to be faithful to her. The story of Hosea and his marriage to Gomer was similar to the relationship between God and Israel. Yahweh had chosen Israel as a special race to be his people and he became their God.     Initially, their relationship was very good until Israel started to go after gods just Gomer did. For her behaviour, God refused to continue to be their God and rejected them from being his people. God left Israel to be carried into slavery and they suffered all kinds of indignities in the hands of their masters.     However, because the love God had for Israel, he went back to bring them back to himself. He restored them to their former position.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION B>4", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "4", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Narrate the parable of the Sower and state two lessons that could be drawn from it.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Parable of the Sower was told to the crowd that had gathered around Jesus. Jesus tells the story of a sower who scattered seeds on four different types of soil. The first type of ground was hard and the seed could not sprout or grow at all and became snatched up instantly. The second type of ground was stony. The seed was able to plant and begin to grow, however, it could not grow deep roots and withered in the sun. The third type of ground was thorny and although the seed could plant and grow, it could not compete with the number of thorns that overtook it. The fourth ground was good soil that allowed the seed to plant deep, grow strong, and produce fruit.  Jesus used this parable to explain to his followers and the disciples how there are different responses to the saving Gospel of Jesus Christ. The sower in the parable is Jesus and the seed is the word of God (both Jesus's spoken word and today the Bible). The hard ground represents someone with a hardened heart full of sin that hears the word of God but does not accept it. Satan is able to keep this person from growing at all. The stony ground is someone who shows interest and awareness in the Gospel, yet his heart isn't fully convicted so that when trouble comes to his faith is not strong enough to stand. The thorny ground is a person who receives the Gospel but who has many other idols and distractions in life - worries, riches, and lusts, which take over his mind and heart and he cannot grow in the truth of God's Word. The good soil is someone who has heard and received the Word of God and allows it to take root and grow within his life. This person represents true salvation that bears good fruit.    LESSONS  - It teaches positive gospel  - Do not merely listen to the word, live by it.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "What demands did Jesus make of the prospective disciples he encountered?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "One day, Jesus was on his way to Jerusalem. A man met him and said he wanted to follow him. Jesus told the man that foxes have holes and birds have nests but the son of man has no place to lay his head.    Jesus himself asked another man to follow him but the man said he should be allowed to go and bury his father before he comes to follow Jesus. Jesus told him that he should allow the dead to bury their dead. Jesus told the man to go and spread the word of God.    A third person said he was willing to follow Jesus, but he should be allowed to go and inform family and say farewell to them before following. Jesus told this would-be disciple that anyone who puts his hand to the plough and looks back is not fit for the kingdom.    - The man who demanded to follow Jesus thought it was a thing of pleasure to follow Jesus as a disciple. So the answer Jesus gave was to let this man know that following him was a sacrificial thing and it is full of suffering.  - Another man said he wanted to go and bury his father. When Jesus said let the dead bury their dead, he was saying that the disciples must forget about the cares of the world they are leaving behind as they followed Jesus. The disciples must be ready to give up everything.  - Another man wanted to go and bid goodbye to his family before he comes to follow Jesus. Jesus' reply means that following him required a total and full commitment. Every other relationship is less important than the relationship with God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Explain any one of the demands made of them by Jesus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Disciples Must Be Willing to Surrender an Earthly Home  \"The foxes have holes and the birds of the air have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay His head\" (Luke 9:58).    When Jesus came to earth, He came as a humble servant. Paul said that Jesus \"emptied Himself, taking the form of a bond-servant, and being made in the likeness of men\" (Philippians 2:7). Paul explained to the Corinthians that Jesus left heaven for us, showing an example of sacrifice: \"For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though He was rich, yet for your sake He became poor, so that you through His poverty might become rich\" (2 Corinthians 8:9). He was willing to give up His home in heaven in order to come to earth – a place where He would have \"nowhere to lay His head\" – in order to help us.    \"The disciple is not above his master\" (Matthew 10:24, KJV). Therefore, we must be willing to sacrifice what Jesus did. Just as He was willing to leave His home in heaven and not even enjoy the real comforts of an earthly home, we may need to give up the same.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Describe the event in Bethany which made Jesus speak of himself as the \"Resurrection and the Life\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"I am the Resurrection and the Life\" (John 11:25) is the fifth of the seven \"I am\" statements of Jesus. Lazarus was dead. Earlier, Jesus had heard that His good friend was sick, but instead of going to visit Lazarus, Jesus \"stayed where he was for two more days\" (John 11:6). He explained to His puzzled disciples that the sickness was \"for God's glory, that God's Son may be glorified through it\" (v. 4). After Lazarus died, Jesus began a journey to Bethany, Lazarus's home. Significantly, when Jesus informed His disciples that Lazarus was dead, He simply said His friend was \"asleep, but I am going there to wake him up\" (John 11:11).  Outside Bethany, Lazarus's sister Martha went out to meet Jesus. \"If you had been here,\" she said, \"my brother would not have died.\" Such was her faith in Jesus' power to heal. Jesus replied by assuring Martha that her brother would rise again. Martha responded again in faith: \"I know he will rise again in the resurrection at the last day.\" At this point, Jesus makes His fifth \"I Am\" statement in John's gospel, \"I am the resurrection and the life,\" and He follows it with a call to faith: \"He who believes in me will live, even though he dies, and whoever lives and believes in me will never die\" (John 11:21-24).", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "What two lessons can we draw from the declaration?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-  Believers in Jesus Christ will experience resurrection because, having the life Jesus gives, it is impossible for death to defeat them.  - Jesus shows that neither Death nor time is an obstacle to Him.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION C>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What advice did Paul give on the use of individual talents in his Epistle to the Romans?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul desires a society where there is no exaggerated view of one's self esteem but, rather, an environment where people reflect sober judgement.  Instead of thinking of himself too highly, a man should measure himself by the standard of what he believes by faith.  Paul pointed out that the body consists of many members which perform different functions and he reminded the Romans that though they were many, yet, they were one body in Christ. Individually, they were members of one another, though gifts might differ according to the grace given to them. They  must use the gifts for the benefit of the community and church – if prophecy,  in proportion to their faith; if service, in their serving. He who teaches, in his teaching; he who exhorts, in his exhortation; he who contributes, in liberality; he who gives aid, with zeal; he who acts of mercy, with cheerfulness.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION C>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Identify two ways of applying your talents.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- For the benefit of the church  - Seeking God's guide before use", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Describe Paul's reaction to the gift which he received from the Philippians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Philipians dispatched through Epaphroditus some monetary gift to Paul while he was in prison in Rome. To show his gratitude and appreciation for the gift from the church which he had founded, Paul wrote to the church expressing his gratitude. His joy, however, was based on the spirit of sacrifice that motivated their action.  In giving and receiving, the Philippians received Paul and God's approval. He (Paul), therefore, prayed that God might continue to satisfy all their needs according to His riches in glory as long as they sustained their faith in Christ Jesus.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Identify any two ways by which you can manifest a true sense of giving in your community.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Meeting the needs of the under privileged, the aged and the sick in society by offering voluntary service to them.  - Joining youth organizations for more organised welfare services to society.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Give the main features of Paul's letter to Philemon", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Philemon is the shortest and perhaps the most personal of Paul's epistles. It is a letter addressed to a private individual; as such, it does not include much doctrinal content. Nevertheless, Paul's plea for Philemon to reconcile with the slave Onesimus illustrates how the doctrines of the gospel apply to daily life—in this case, showing that our relationship with Jesus Christ brings us into a familial relationship with all other followers of Christ and highlighting the importance of mercy and forgiveness.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1997>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1997", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "State two reasons why a Christian should forgive others.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- In order to receive forgiveness for our sins, we need to forgive others.  - Forgiving others allows us to overcome feelings of anger, bitterness, or revenge.   - Forgiveness can heal spiritual wounds and bring the peace and love that only God can give.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Describe how Joshua was selected as Moses' successor.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Moses went up to Mount Nebo and viewed the land of Canaan. He knew he could not step there because of the punishment of God for his disobedience at the waters of Meribah.    Moses requested God to appoint someone after him, to lead the people out and to bring them in, in other words, to appoint a successor after him, Moses. God told Moses to appoint Joshua the son of Nun, a man full of the spirit of God as his successor to lead the people to the land of Canaan. God told him to lay his hands on him.    God further instructed Moses to set Joshua before Eliezar, the Priest and all the people of Israel and give him a charge before the people. He was to transfer some of his honour to Joshua so that the people may obey him. He said, Eliezar shall inquire of the Lord for him and at Joshua's command, the congregation shall go out and at his command, they shall come in.  Moses did according to the instructions God had given him. He laid his hand upon him and commissioned him as the Lord had said.    Later, Moses died at the age of 120.    After the death of Moses, the Israelites started to take possession of the land. First, the tribe of Judah and Simeon fought against the Canaanites and Perizzites and defeated them. They fought against the Jebusites and defeated them.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Mention two previous associations of Moses and Joshua.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- On one occasion, Moses sent twelve spies to spy the land of Canaan and Joshua was part of the group. When they came back with the report, it was Joshua and Caleb that encouraged the people that with the help of God, they could conquer the land and therefore they should not be afraid.       - On another occasion, Joshua accompanied Moses when he went to the mount of Sinai to collect the two tables of the Ten Commandments God had asked Moses to come and collect.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION A>2", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Narrate the first anointing of Saul by Samuel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Saul the Benjaminite was from a family of wealth and was handsome (1 Sam. 9:1–2), so he looked the part of the king. But aside from these qualities, there was little to indicate that he should be the ruler of Israel. He was, after all, from the tribe of Benjamin, not from Judah, Levi, or Ephraim—tribes that had been given leadership roles or that had produced significant national leaders for Israel such as Moses, Joshua, and Samuel (Gen. 49:8–12; Ex. 2:1–9; Num. 13:8, 16; Judg. 1:1–2). In fact, Saul himself clearly was not expecting to be made king, for he did not understand why Samuel gave him such honor after he met the prophet (1 Sam. 9:15–27).  But after feasting with Samuel and his guests, Saul was anointed by the Lord \"to be prince over his people Israel\" (10:1). God anointed Saul through the ministry of Samuel, and we can discern at least a twofold significance to this use of oil to mark out Saul as the king. First, before the institution of the monarchy, only the priests were anointed with oil (Ex. 29:1–9), signifying their dedication to God for a special task. By anointing the kings of Israel, the Lord showed that He established the monarchy. Israel asked for a king with the wrong motives, but the monarchy was ultimately God's gift to His people.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "Describe the experience of Jonah as he fled from the presence of God to Tarshish.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God asked Jonah to go and preach to the people of Nineveh because their wickedness had come up to him in heaven. However, Jonah did not want to go because he believed that God was a merciful God and would forgive them if he preached to them and they repent. Meaning Nineveh would never be punished for their wickedness.    Jonah went to Joppa and paid a fare to escape from God to Tarshish. When the ship set sail from Tarshish, Jonah was aboard. He went deep inside the ship and fell asleep. On the high Seas, there arose a great storm that threatened to break the ship apart and everyone on board was praying to his god to help save the situation while Jonah was still asleep. The Seafarers, at a point, threw some of the luggage on board into the Sea to make the ship lighter but it did not help.    The Captain of the ship went to Jonah and told him to also call upon his God to come and save them. After some time, they cast lot to see on account of whom they were facing the situation in which they were and the lot fell on Jonah. They all quizzed him about his occupation, his nationality and his race. Jonah confessed that he was a Hebrew and a servant of the God that made the Oceans and the dry land.  They people became afraid when they heard this and inquired from Jonah what they must do. Jonah told them to cast him into the Sea because he was the cause of their problem. They refused to throw him into the Sea and rather tried to contain the situation. After some time, when they realized that they could not stabilize the ship and the storm was getting even stronger, they threw Jonah into the Sea and God sent a big fish to go and swallow Jonah.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "State two lessons that could be learnt from his flight", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- People must learn from other people's experiences and turn to God.  - There are dangerous consequences awaiting those who disobey God.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION B>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "How did Jesus describe himself to the Samaritan woman in St. John's Gospel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In John's Gospel the Samaritan woman at the well is the first person to whom Jesus openly reveals himself as Messiah. The pious Jewish leader, Nicodemus, did not hear the words that Jesus tells this foreign woman when she states her belief in the coming Messiah: \"I am he, the one who is speaking to you\" (John 4:26). This is also the longest private conservation Jesus had with anyone in the New Testament (John 4:7-26). Verse 4 says that Jesus \"had to [Gk: edei] go through Samaria.\" The use of edei (had to) makes it clear that this is a divine appointment. It was not geographically necessary for Jesus to go through Samaria, and Jewish travelers normally traveled around Samaria. Jesus and his disciples entered a Samaritan village, and the disciples went to buy food (v. 8) while Jesus sat by the well because he was tired. A woman from the nearby village of Sychar came for water.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION B>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "In what two ways does the teaching apply to Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Christians should not be discriminatory.  - Jesus is a good sample for Christians' life.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "\"See, you are well! Sin no more that nothing worse befall you\". Trace the events that led to this statement in John's Gospel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There was a feast of the Jews which Jesus attended in Jerusalem. There, by the sheep gate was a pool called Bethzatha by which laid a multitude of invalids. There, Jesus met a man who had been lying ill for thirty eight years and asked him if he wanted to be healed. The man said that he had no man to carry him into the water. Jesus healed him by asking him to take his pallet and walk. The man was healed and he took up his pallet and walked. This happened on the Sabbath day. The man who had just been healed by Jesus was accused by the Jews of contravening the Sabbath law by carrying his pallet on the Sabbath. They enquired from him the man who bid him to carry his pallet on the Sabbath. He was unable to identify the person who had cured him and gave him the order. Jesus had withdrawn from the crowd to avoid curiosity.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "What two lessons can be derived from this story?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Sickness can be associated with sin, therefor we must avoid sin.  - Jesus has power over all illnesses", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "What led to the selection of Matthias as one of the Apostles?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When Jesus began his public ministry, he chose twelve disciples to follow him for three years (Luke 6:12-16). However, when Judas Iscariot betrayed Jesus and thereafter killed himself (Matthew 27:1-10), the disciples needed to find a twelfth man to replace Judas.   They'd narrowed down the candidates to two people: Joseph (also known as Justus) and a man named Matthias (Acts 1:12-26).     Both of these men had followed Jesus during his public ministry – since John the Baptist baptized Jesus and witnessed his resurrection. They just didn't have the title of the original twelve.   After praying and doing a practice known as casting lots, the lots landed on Matthias. He was chosen to replace Judas Iscariot.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "How was the selection conducted?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The person must have witnessed the baptism of Jesus by John.  - He must have been a companion of Jesus.  - He must have witnessed Jesus' ministry on earth up to the time he was crucified.  - The apostles prayed for God's guidance in the selection, cast lots for them and the lots fell on Matthias and he was counted among the twelve apostles.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION C>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What did Paul teach on the need for order in society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Apostle Paul in his letter to the Roman Christians presented scriptural basis for the need and aim of orderliness among Christian community. He advised them to be subject to the governing authorities. He made them to recognize that every authority comes from God and that rulers are God's representatives. Disobedience to the governing authorities means disobedience to God.  Also, Paul made them to realize that the rulers exist for the good of the society and that those who show good conduct are friends to the rulers, while the lawless and non-conformists are enemies to the rulers. As servants of God, rulers exist to punish the offenders for the good of the society. Paul then stated thus: \"Let every person be subject to the governing authorities.  For there is no authority except from God and those that exist have been instituted by God.  Therefore, he who resists the authorities resists what God has appointed and those who resist will incur judgement. For rulers are not a terror to good conduct, but to bad. Would you have no  fear of him who is in authority? Then do what is good and you will receive his approval, for he  is God's servant for your good. Therefore, one must be subject, not only to avoid God's wrath  but also for the sake of conscience. For the same reason you also pay taxes, for the authorities are ministers of God; pay all of them their dues, taxes to whom are due, revenue to whom revenue is due, respect to whom respect is due, honour to whom honour is due\". The point Paul is stressing here is that the act of governance is within the will of God. Every ruler  therefore has the backing of God. Government is for the purpose of security and stability of the society. If there is no government, there will be anarchy and lawlessness. To this end, anyone who disobeys those in authority, disobeys God, since the ruler is God's instrument for social cohesion.  Finally, Paul said for there to be order, peace, stability and protection of the rights of the citizens, the government and the citizens have to perform their civic responsibilities. He said the Christian citizens were to practice love, which he described as the summary of the commandments and the fulfillment of the law. In addition, they should eschew such negative tendencies as drunkenness, debauchery, licentiousness, quarelling and jealousy but put on the armour of light, by exhibiting a lifestyle that is worthy of emulation, as a mark of people in Christ.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION C>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "List four ways by which a Christian can show that he is a responsible citizen.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Self-discipline, obedience to the government  - Teaching good ethics and morals through youth organizations  - Keeping away from anti-social behaviours like drug addiction and trafficking, armed robbery etc  - Keeping the law and obeying the constitution  - Payment of taxes, rates and other duties", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "What did James teach on partiality?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to James, Christians should do away with partiality as they hold on to the faith of Jesus Christ. James admonished the people to show equal attention to the rich and to the poor among them. For example, he said if any rich man comes to the church he/she must not be accorded more attention than he deserves and the same not shown to the poor who comes to the same church.  According to James, if anybody fails to demonstrate the the virtue of impartiality, that person makes a distinction among them and has become a judge with evil agenda.    James reminded the people that God has chosen the poor in the world to be rich in faith and to inherit the kingdom that has been promised to those who love him.    He recalled how the rich maltreat the poor in many ways, for example, how the rich oppress the poor and drag them to court. He drew the attention of the people to the royal law which states that one should love his neighbour as himself. He told them that partiality is sinful.    To James, anybody who observes the whole law but fails in one is guilty of breaking all the law. For example, God says there should be no adultery and also says thou shall not kill. If therefore, you do not commit adultery but you kill, it means you have broken all the other laws. James appealed to the leaders to speak and also act like those who going to be judged under the law.    Finally, he said judgment is without mercy to those who do not show mercy, yet mercy triumphs over judgment.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "Identify two effects of partiality in society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It promotes distrust and unhealthy rivalry.  - It brings disunity among various groups.  - It can lead to civil unrest.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "What did Peter mean when he referred to Christians as a chosen race?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter described Christians as a chosen race and a royal priesthood. He explained to them that they are a peculiar people of God and a holy nation, God's own people.    Initially, it was the Jews who regarded themselves as the special people of God, the descendants of Abram, chosen by God. When Jesus came, they rejected him as part of God's plan of salvation. For this, God took away that special position of the Israelites and gave it to those, who through faith believe in Jesus. That makes them a chosen generation. According to Peter, Christians have replaced the Jews, who lost their position because they were unfaithful to God. Now God wants the Jews to behave in ways that justify them as believers.     Peter told them to eschew their former love for carnal things, maintain good behaviour before unbelievers, so that even if they do not speak well about them, on the Day of Judgment, they will confess their righteousness.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1998>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1998", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "How did he expect them to behave to civil authorities?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Respect for elders, school authorities and laws of the country.  - Submit themselves to all human institutions.  - Submit to the emperor or the governors sent by him to reward the just and punish the wrong-doers.  - Should not use their freedom as a pretext to do evil.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "Describe the main features of the covenant between God and Abraham in Canaan.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When Abraham was 99 years old God appeared to him and made a covenant with him. Basically, God required of Abraham to walk blamelessly with him in exchange for increase and multiplication him.    God covenanted with Abraham, to make him a father of a multitude of nations. He promised to make him a highly fruitful person and that nations and kings would come out of him. According to God the covenant was to extend to the descendants of Abraham after him in many generations to come. God also added the land of Canaan as an inheritance to the descendants of Abraham.    As part of the covenant, God changed the name Abram to Abraham meaning a father of a multitude of nations. Another aspect of the covenant was that God promised to be his God and to be God to all his descendants throughout the generations to follow. On the part of Abraham, God required him to undergo circumcision and to circumcise all male members of his household, including free born and slaves. Also any male born in his house must be circumcised on the eighth day. God warned that those who refused to be circumcised would be cut off from the covenant.    God also added blessings for Sarai, the wife of Abraham. He changed her name from Sarai to Sarah to reflect the fact she was going to become the mother of nations. He promised to give Abraham a son by the womb of Sarah.       Abraham thought this was a joke because Sarah was advanced in age and therefore humanly speaking, she could not bear children. He rather requested that God should make Ishmael great in his sight. But God insisted that Sarah shall have a child of her own. He also promised to bless Ishmael and make him great.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "What two lessons do we learn from the event?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Covenants are significant because it ensures that the parties to the covenant enjoy a peaceful relationship with each other.  - Covenants are important because they are able to hold a nation together.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "Describe God's intervention on behalf of Elijah.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After three years, God told Elijah to go back and show himself to Ahab. When Ahab met Elijah, he addressed him as the trouble maker for Israel. Elijah denied the accusation and said Ahab was the trouble maker for Israel because he had encouraged the worship of Baal in Israel.    Elijah instructed the king to assemble all Israel on Mount Camel together with the 450 worshipers of Baal and 400 worshipers of Asherah. The aim is to prove which god is more powerful, Yahweh or Baal.    On the D-day, the whole of Israel gathered on mount Camel, including the four hundred and fifty prophets of Baal. Elijah told the people to stop having two opinions. He said Baal is god they should follow and Yahweh is God they must follow him. Elijah asked for one bull each to be given to him and to the Baal prophet. Elijah asked that the prophets of Baal kill one of the bulls and cut it into pieces and put it on wood. He, Elijah too would do the same. The Baal prophets should call on the god to burn the sacrifice and he, Elijah would also call on his God to consume the sacrifice by fire. The god that is able to answer by fire is the one that must be worshiped.    Elijah told the Baal worshipers to start because they were more. The Baal prophets called on their god from morning till noon but there was no answer. At a point, Elijah started making fun of them. He advised them to shout louder because probably their god was asleep, busy or traveled. However, there was no answer.     Elijah called the people together, repaired the altar of the Lord which was in ruins and dug a trench around the altar. He arranged the wood, cut the bull into pieces and laid it on the wood. He asked that water be poured on the sacrifice. That was done and the water drenched the sacrifice and filled the trench. The prophet Elijah prayed to the Lord and the sacrifice was consumed by fire. When the people saw this, they bowed down and worshiped the Lord, saying, \"The Lord, he is Lord! The Lord, He is Lord\"  Elijah commanded that all the Baal prophets and asked that they bring them to the Kishon valley, where he slaughtered them.    Elijah prophesied that there was going to be rain. He told Ahab to go and eat. While he was gone, Elijah went back to Mount Carmel and prayed for the rains. Anticipating that the rain was surely coming, Elijah sent word to Ahab to go down to Jezreel so that rain does not stop him. The clouds became black and the rains fell in torrents. At about the same time, Ahab was riding a horse to Jezreel, the spirit of God came upon Elijah and he ran ahead of Ahab and got to Jezreel before him.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "State two lessons about the nature of God in this story.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The prophets of God must stand firm when they are persecuted.  - Men of God should speak against evil in their society.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "Why was a new covenant established during the time of Jeremiah?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jeremiah had closely observed Israel's faithlessness towards their covenant with God and their apostasy in serving the useless gods of other nations. He diagnosed the fundamental reasons for their infidelity and unfaithfulness to God's covenant and attributed it to the fact that it was written in slabs of stone and thus, external. Although, the old covenant was sealed with the blood of animal, such blood was not capable of offering lasting union with God. Hence, Jeremiah introduced a new theory that unless man's soul unites with the spirit of God, no amount of verbal proclamation would produce a lasting effect. This is a new covenant because the heart of man is the only thing that can unite man with God. Under this new plan, the law would be written in people's individual hearts — unlike the old external law which was written on tablets of stone. According to Jeremiah, although God remained ever committed to His part of the covenant, Israel deviated. But if the new covenant comes from within, Jeremiah believed a lasting knowledge of God would result and God Himself would be their God.    Therefore, the need for any man to teach another to know the law would no longer be there and God would forgive their sins. He would gather His people from all the nations (from exile) and return them to Judah in safety. Henceforth, He would be their God, and they would be His people — both parties would remain faithful to each other.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "State two consequences faced by the Israelites for breaking God's covenant", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- No escape from defeat and destruction by their enemies so long as they were unfaithful.  - Famine and drought would be their lot in their homeland.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Narrate Jonah's message to the Ninevites and their response to it.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The people of Nineveh were evil in their ways. They did many evil things to one another. They were wicked. They did not help those in trouble. They did not feel sorry for all the wrong that they had done and they continued to do.    God told the Prophet Jonah to go and call the people of Nineveh to repentance otherwise He would destroy them. At first he refused and ran away from God's directive to Tarshish but later went to the town of Nineveh and called the people there to repentance. God said through Jonah that Nineveh would be overthrown in forty days time. The people felt sorry of all the bad things that they had done. They repented by proclaiming a fast, putting on sackcloth, the king arose from his throne, removed his robe, and covered himself with sackcloth and sat in ashes and asked God for forgiveness. And, God forgave them.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "State two lessons that could be drawn from this story.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Acts of evil are not condoned by God.  - God loves all as long as the sinner repents.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Describe the Lukan account of the annunciation of the birth of Jesus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Six months after Elizabeth, the wife of Zechariah had become pregnant, an angel of the Lord, called Gabriel, visited a virgin, called Mary, who had been betrothed to a man from the line of David, called Joseph.    Angel Gabriel said to Mary, \"O favoured one, the Lord is with you.\" This greeting troubled Mary and she wondered what kind of greeting it might be. The angel calmed her down by saying she should not be afraid because she had found favour in the sight of the Lord. He said, Mary would conceive and bear a child to be called Jesus. Knowing that she had not been with any man and was still a virgin, Mary asked the angel how that was going to be possible, but the angel said the Holy Spirit would come upon her and she would become pregnant and the child to be born shall be called Holy. Then the angel hinted that even her kinswoman, Elizabeth was also with a child and the pregnancy was about six months old and therefore, with God nothing is impossible. Mary said to the angel \"Behold, I am the handmaid of the Lord; let it be to me according to your word.\" Then angel Gabriel left.    Getting close to the time Mary was due to have her child, a decree was passed by Caesar Augustus for a census to be carried out. Everyone was expected to go to his or her village to be enumerated. So Joseph also went to his village, Bethlehem, together with Mary who was by this time, heavily pregnant. While in Bethlehem, Mary's final moments to deliver came and she was successfully delivered of a baby boy. The child was wrapped in a swaddling cloth and laid in a manger because there was no room in the available hotels for them to lodge in.    That same night, there were some shepherds out in the field, looking after their flock. An angel appeared to them and the glory of God shone around them which frightened them. The angel told them not to be afraid because he had brought them good news. The good news was that, in the city of David, Bethlehem, a savior, Christ the Lord, had been born. They shall find the child wrapped in swaddling clothes in a manger. Immediately, many other angels joined the angel and they sung praises to God. After the angels had left, the shepherds decided to go to Bethlehem and see things for themselves. They hurried to Bethlehem and found Mary and Joseph with the baby lying in a manger. Then the shepherds told the people what had been told them on the field about the child and everybody was wondering about what the shepherds had said but Mary kept the sayings in her heart pondering over them. The shepherds returned, praising God for the things they had heard and seen.    After eight days, baby Jesus was circumcised according to the laws of the Lord which He covenanted with Abraham. He was named Jesus, which was the name that the angel mentioned before he was even conceived in his mother's womb. The custom in Israel was that every male child that opens the womb of a woman shall be called Holy to the Lord. As part of the custom, a pair of turtle doves or two young pigeons shall be sacrificed. When the time came for this custom to be performed, because Jesus was the first male to open his mother's womb, Jesus was sent to Jerusalem for the purification ceremony according the laws of Moses.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "In what two ways is the Lukan account different from that of Matthew?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- One of the ways in which Luke's account differs from that of Matthew is that there was no mention of an angel visiting Mary in Matthew; it was Joseph who encountered the angel in a dream. Also the name of the angel was not mentioned.    - Another way in which the two accounts differ is that Luke did not record that Joseph tried to secretly divorce Mary when he discovered that she was pregnant, only Matthew recorded this.    - Another difference between the two accounts was that Matthew did not say anything about Elizabeth as was done in the book of Luke.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION B>6", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "6", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Narrate the story of the Transfiguration as contained in the Synoptic Gospels.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus took Peter, James and John apart to a high mountain. He was transfigured before them and his face shone like the sun and his garment became white as light. There appeared to them Moses and Elijah talking with Jesus about his departure. Peter and the other disciples were heavy with sleep though awake enough to see his glory and the two persons. Peter said, \"Lord it is well that we are here, let us build three booths, one for you, one for Moses and one for Elijah.\" As he spoke, a bright cloud overshadowed them and they were afraid. A voice was heard which said,\"This is my beloved son with whom I am pleased, listen to him.\" The disciples fell on their faces. Jesus asked them to rise, and not to fear. Jesus commanded them to tell no one what they had seen until the son of man was raised from the dead. They asked him why the scribes said that Elijah must first come to restore all things. Jesus told them that Elijah had already come, but they did not know him and so they did to him whatever they pleased, in the same way, he said, the son of man would suffer in their hands. The disciples understood that he was referring to John the Baptist.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION B>7", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "7", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Give an account of the resurrection appearances of Jesus Christ as related in St. Matthew's Gospel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the Sabbath, getting towards the early morning of the first day of the week, Mary Magdalene and the other Mary came to the tomb.    There was a great earthquake before their arrival and an angel of the Lord had come down from heaven and had rolled the stone from the entrance of the tomb and had sat on it. The appearance of the angel was like lightning and his dress was as white as snow. At his coming, the guards fainted.    The angel told the women not to fear. He said he knew the women were looking for Jesus who was crucified. Then he informed them that Jesus had risen as he had said while he was alive. He invited the women to come and see where Jesus had laid and quickly go and tell the disciples that Jesus had risen from the dead. The angel told the women that Jesus had gone ahead of them to Galilee and that they shall meet him there.    The women left the tomb quickly with fear, mixed with joy. They run to tell the disciples. On the way, Jesus met them and greeted them. They worshiped him. Jesus told them not to be afraid but rather go and tell the disciples to go ahead to Galilee where they shall meet him.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION B>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "How did Gamaliel save the apostles during their trial by the Sanhedrin?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "It came to pass, one day, that the High Priest and the party of the Sadducees put the Apostles in a common prison because they continued to preach in the name of Jesus.    At night, an angel of the Lord came and opened the prison doors and released them. The angel instructed them to go into the temple and preach to the people about life. In the morning, the Apostles entered the Temple and preached to the people they found there.    That same morning, the High Priest had called together his Council. He had sent that the Apostles be brought to appear before them. When the officers went to the prison to bring the Apostles out, they did not find them there so they came back to report to the High Priest and his Council. When the High Priest and the Captain of the Temple, heard this, they were confused and did not know how this was going to turn out. As they were still thinking about the matter, somebody came from the town and told them that the people they were looking for were in the Temple preaching to the people. The Captain of the Temple and the officers went to bring them, but without any violence because they feared that they might be pelted with stones if they used force.    The Apostles were set before the Council and the High Priest asked them whether they had not warned them not to preach in the name of Jesus. They asked them why they had filled the whole of Jerusalem with their teachings and blaming they the leaders for the death of Jesus. Peter and the Apostles told them that they could not obey men; the only person they obeyed was God. They accused the Council of killing Jesus by hanging him on a cross and they spoke about how God had exalted Jesus and raised him to be on God's right hand side in paradise. When the Council members heard this, they became very angry, especially the Sadducees who did not believe in the resurrection of the body. They wanted the Apostles to be killed.  Then arose Gamaliel, a teacher of the law and an expert in the Jewish traditions. He was also a member of the Council of Jerusalem and also a Pharisee. He ordered the Apostles to be put outside for a while. Then he told his fellow Council members to be careful what they did with the Apostles.      He drew the attention of the Council to one Theudas who started a movement sometime earlier and drew a following of four hundred men. He spoke about how Theudas was killed and all his followers were dispersed. He also spoke about how Judas the Galillean, also arose during the census and also drew a large following. Gamaliel said this man was also killed and all his followers were scattered. Gamaliel advised the Council to leave the Apostles alone in the present case. He said if what the Apostles were doing was a human undertaking, it was surely going to fail but that if it was of God there is nothing they, the Council, can do about it. Rather they would be found to be opposing God. The Council took his advice.    They called the Apostle back into the Council and beat flogged them. They then charge them not to preach about Jesus again and allowed them to go. The Apostles were happy that they had to suffer indignity for the sake of Jesus. After this, they went into the Temple everyday and in the homes and preached about the gospel of Jesus Christ.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION B>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Identify two qualities that can be attributed to Gamaliel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He was courageous  One would have thought that Gamaliel would be frightened by the number he was against but he was not. That shows courage.    - He was kind  Another quality of Gamaliel was that he was kind. He did not support the taking of innocent lives, even the lives of people perceived to be against his religion.    - He was tolerant  Gamaliel was a tolerant man. Though the religion that was being propagated was alien to what he knew, he was still willing to tolerate their opinion.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>9", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "How did Paul prove that Christians are children of God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to Paul in his epistle to the Galatians, he stressed that man was a slave under the law, but was redeemed through faith in Jesus Christ. With the coming of the son of God – Jesus Christ, our faith in him has made us children of God. Through our baptism in Christ, we have put on Christ. Therefore, Jesus is already in us. Because of this, there is no distinction of race or sex. If we are Christ's children, then we are Abraham's offspring by faith, hence heirs of God's promise. We can not be fully matured if we remain like children in our faith. We were subject to the elemental spirits of the universe, but God in His infinite mercy sent His only son to redeem those under the law and to adopt us as sons. We can then call God our father as adopted sons. So, through Jesus, we are no longer slaves, but sons and rightful heirs of eternal life.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "Explain Paul's teaching on resurrection.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul starts out in 1 Corinthians 15 by reminding them that Jesus did die and was raised from the dead for the salvation of man. This is the foundation of the gospel. Next Paul states that there were witnesses of the resurrection of Jesus, not only by His disciples but by more than 500 people. Paul wrote 1 Corinthians approximately 20 years after Jesus' death and resurrection. It would be very hard to argue or dispute that many credible witnesses. Paul begins his discourse on the resurrection of Jesus by stating that salvation is not possible without Jesus' resurrection, and those who were preaching this, preached the truth. Paul further illustrates this by stating that Jesus will raise those who are dead in Christ. If this is not the case, Jesus was not raised either. Paul describes Jesus as the first fruits of the resurrection for His time in history, and subsequently this resurrection is made available for all of humanity from Adam on down for those who are in Jesus.    Next, Paul reiterates the fact that there is a resurrection for the dead, and there need not be a baptism for the dead by those who are alive. Paul states further that when a believer is raised unto the resurrection of Jesus, there will be a new body and immortality. There is victory for the believer by the resurrection of Jesus!    1 Corinthians chapter 15 clearly addressed the resurrection of Jesus. In addition, Paul mentions the resurrection of Jesus in Romans 1:4 and 6:5; Philippians 3:10-11, and in 2 Timothy 2:18 where he addresses the issue of only a spiritual resurrection (that was not a literal physical resurrection) as Paul dealt with the false teaching of the Gnostics in 1 Corinthians 15. This false teaching taught that it was more or less an allegory.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Give two reasons why the resurrection of Jesus is of great significance to Christians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Without the resurrection, Jesus' death would go without divine interpretation and endorsement.    - Without the resurrection, none of Jesus' promises would be trustworthy.     - Without the resurrection, there would be no model of sacrificial living.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Explain the concept of 'Giving' as outlined in Paul's second letter to the Corinthians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This letter offers a great deal of personal insight into Paul's life that is not present in any other New Testament book. However, in chapters 8 and 9, his letter also clearly reveals God's plan for His people to give to others. Paul first focused on the generous example of the Macedonian churches, largely Gentile, who gave to their Jewish Christian brothers and sisters in Jerusalem. Then he exhorted the Corinthian believers to make donations of their own to the work in Jerusalem. Several realities about Christian giving become clear in these two chapters: Christians give generously according to, and at times beyond, their financial abilities; Christians give their money across racial and national lines; Christians who make commitments to give should follow through with those promises; and Christians should give cheerfully, rather than under compulsion.  By so doing, they will receive unlimited enrichment and blessing from God for their good works, enrich the saints physically and multiply their thankfulness to God. It is, therefore, a test of their Christian life and the acceptance of the gospel of Christ which will reflect God's glory. And, as for the saints, i.e, the recipients, their prayers for the Corinthians would be boundless. In conclusion, Paul gave thanks to God for His gift of Jesus which is beyond human experience and a demonstration of God's supreme example of giving to all.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "In what two ways can a Christian provide relief for the suffering of others?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Setting up special funds for the needy in the society.   - Sponsorship of the course of the poor by well-to-do Christians.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Why, according to Peter, should Christians rejoice inspite of the trials they may be going through?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter exhorts Christians to rejoice in the hope of the glory which awaits them owing to the resurrection of Jesus Christ. Although in this present life, their joy might be limited by the trials and persecutions that would come their way, such trials and persecutions are meant to prove the genuineness of their faith and make them to reap the rich reward of salvation when Jesus is revealed.    In order to fully realize the hope of salvation, Christians should live holy lives in the full knowledge that God, the impartial judge would take note of their sufferings on the day of judgement. Furthermore, they should not forget that Jesus himself passed through greater suffering. If they were reproached for the name of Christ, they should count themselves blessed. They should, however, not suffer as murderers, thieves, or for any wrong doing but if they suffer for Christ, they should not be ashamed. They should instead, glorify God for on that day, judgement would begin with those who call upon the name of God and the fate of the unbelievers might be terrible.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>1999>SECTION C>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "1999", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "What two virtues should Christians manifest to show their joy?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- They should remain sober and hopeful of the glory and salvation that would be theirs when Jesus would be revealed.    - They should always praise God both in time of sadness and joy.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Narrate the second creation story", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Narrate the second creation story   When God has completed the creation of the heavens and the earth (as His first creation) , there were no plants or vegetation as there was no rain, except dew that watered the earth from the heavens. And there was no man to till the soil. Therefore God formed man from the dust of the earth and breathed into his nostrils whereby man became a living being.  God then planted a garden in Eden in the East, and there He put the man whom He had formed to care for the garden. Out of the ground, the Lord made to grow every tree that is pleasant to the sight and good for food including the tree of the knowledge of good and evil which man was forbidden to eat. Eating of this forbidden fruit will lead to disobedience to God by man the consequences of which are death. God permitted man to eat of all the other fruits.  The Lord made four rivers to flow out of Eden to irrigate the garden and divided it into four areas and named them as follows: Pishon which waters the while land of Havillah with precious metals and stones. Gihon flowing around the land of Lush, the third Tigris flowing to the East of Assyria and the forth Euphrates.  To prevent Adam to be a alone, God caused him to a deep sleep where he took a rib and created a woman as Helper for Him named Eve. Then God created all other living things / creatures and the man was charged to give them names. Adam called the helper woman (Eve)", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "In what two ways were the functions assigned to man in this account significant", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-   Acceptance and maintenance of marriage institution.  -  Obedience to God   -   Man was to act as God's agent in furthering the works and of various types of vegetation", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Describe the return of the exiles from Babylon during the reign of Cyprus", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "During the first year of King Cyprus of Persia a decree was issued to the effect that God of heaven had directed him to build a house for Him in Jerusalem. Homer he directed the interested Jews among the exiles are allowed to return to Jerusalem to build the temple. Such returnees should be assisted with silver, gold and other necessary materials including freewill offering to God for the proposed building in Jerusalem. Thus legal and financial assistance were promised and given.  In quick response , the heads of families, the priests and the Levite's and others who were touched by this request by physical assistance in cash and kind including beast. All the vessels looted from the temple by Nebuchadnezzar were brought out, counted and handed over to Sheshbazzer, the head of the returnees. The first batch of about 50,000 were led to Jerusalem, and the building of the temple completed twenty years later.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Give two reasons for the positive response from the people.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-   freedom was seen as a blessing while slavery was seen a curse to any person or nation.   -   The feeling of nationalism and patriotism was made possible.   -  The return was a confirmation of God's promise to His people.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Identify the action taken by King Solomon which are commended as marks of his wisdom.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Before Solomon begins is reign as the King in Israel. God asked him to request from Him his heart desires. Solomon quickly asked for wisdom that will enable him rule his  the children of Israel judiciously. God was pleased and therefore added riches to him, and with the promise that should he remain loyal like his father David, He would grant him long life.   During the trial between two harlots, Solomon applied the true wisdom in his verdict. He was also famous for his many songs, proverbs, botanical and scientific knowledge. In all, one of his greatest accomplishments was the building of the temple which he built for the Lord in Jerusalem and dedicated with singing, dancing and sacrifices. He prayed to God during the dedication of the temple with devotion not only for his people but also for natives who would pray to God of Israel facing the temple in Jerusalem.   During his time, he brought the Ark of covenant of God from its formal modest place of abode into the temple. Also included was his business interest which brought a lot of wealth and progress to his country.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "State two unwise decisions taken by King Solomon.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Solomon's introduction of difficult labor  - Solomon's marriage to natives women and their gods. III. Solomom 's imposition of heavy taxation .", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Describe the circumstances which brought Amos face to face with Amaziah, the priest of Bethel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This was the time when social injustice and religious malpractice of Israel had gotten to the peak. Amos condemned all these social and religious deficiencies and also denounced the high places of Israel, that God would rise against the house of Jeroboam with the sword.  Thus Amaziah the priest of bethel sent word to King Jeroboam ( Ben Josh) that Amos has conspired against him and the land is not able to bear all his words. For he has said that Israel must go into exile. Hence to Amos, Amaziah said 'O seer, go, flee to the land of Judah, eat bread there and prophesy there, but never again prophesy at Bethel'. To this Amos however replied ' I am no prophet, nor a prophet's son, I am herdsman and dresser of sycamore trees'. The Lord withdrew me the flowing the flock to go and prophesy to my people Israel. Therefore hear the word of the Lord for ordering to shut up. ' Your wife shall become a harlot in the city, your sons and daughters shall die by the sword and you shall die in an unclean land, Israel shall surely go into exile away from its land.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Give two reasons why those that opposed God should be condemned.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- There acts are evil and poisonous to others.  - For violation of God's order, precepts, commandment of will.  - Those who antagonized God's authority as our creator should be condemned.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Highlight  the main features in Luke account of the birth, the circumcision and the presentation of Jesus in the temple.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the year of the great census, Joseph and Mary, his pregnant wife went to Bethlehem from Nazareth in compliance with the Emperor's order regarding the census.   The absence of rooms in the Guest houses in Berhelehem made Joseph took Mary to a manger where she was delivered of her son Jesus. The Shepherds in the field learnt of the birth of  Jesus from Angel's proclamation and went to manger to pay the new born child a visit.   The child was circumcised and was named Jesus after eight days. He was brought to the temple in Jerusalem for thee performance of rites of purification of the mother and the appropriate sacrifice was offered. There was a devout and upright nan of God named Simeon... to whom it was revelead to him that he would not see death, until he had seen the Christ . Simeon tool the child (Jesus) in his hands and blessed God.   Then he said the 'Lord, now let your servant depart in peace, according to thy word, for mine eyes have seen thy salvation which thou has prepared in the presence of all people'. He prophesied that Jesus was set for the rise and fall if Israel but that a sword would pierce through the soul of Mary.   Jesus parent puzzled at all that Simeon said about the baby, but kept it secret in their mind. There was also an old widow prophetess, Anna, who came to the temple at that same moment and gave thanks to God for the new born child, Jesus.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Give two reasons for the two rituals of circumcision and the temple presentation", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jesus was a Jew by birth, it was necessary that he must be circumcised on the eight day.   -  The law of Moses stated that all male Jews that opened their mother's womb must be dedicate to the service of God in the temple.   -  The circumcision was also a confirmation of the covenant entered into between God and Abraham which is a physical symbol of the covenant.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MARK 1: 16-20; 2: 13-17", "question": "Relate the account of the mission of the Twelve according to Synoptic", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Twelve main disciples of Jesus were sent out and charged to heal l infirmities, diseases and unclean spirit. There were commandment not to go to the Gentiles nor enter the cities of Samaria, but rather go the lost sheep of the house of Israel and preach, saying that the Kingdom of God is near. They were to make the sick whole raise the dead, cleanse the lepers and cast out demons. You received without paying, give without pay, they should also give without being paid.  They were command not to take anything, no money, gold nor Silva, no copper in your belts, nor bag for your journey , nor two tunics, nor sandals, nor a staff for the labourer deserves his food/ wages.  As a follow up, whatever village or house they enter into, they should find out and stay with the worthy person in it and salute the house with peace. If the house is worthy, their peace will remain there, but if not, their peace will return to them. They were so warned that Amy house which did not receive them, on getting g out, they should shake off the dust under their feet as a testimony against it, for it would be tolerable, on the day of judgment for Sodom and Gomorrah than for that hostile house. The disciple were also commanded to remain in any house that receives them, eating or drinking whatever was offered, for the labourer deserves his wages.   Lastly, Jesus cautioned that they were being sent out as the sheep amongst the wolves, therefore they must be as wise as serpents.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "State any four qualities requires of today's evangelists", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Evangelists must have a constant means of livelihood.  - They must achieve spiritual maturity and moved standard .  - They must be fluent in language of communication for positive inspiration.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Narrate the Synoptic account of the Resurrection of Jesus, bringing out the role played by the women.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Early in the morning on the day after the Sabbath, Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of James went to the tomb an Angel told them that Jesus has risen and that the disciples should go to Galilee and see him there. They went to see the other disciples, Jesus met them and said 'Hail'. They took hold of his feet and worshipped him.  Jesus told them not to fear but to go and tell the other disciples to meet him in Galilee. Some of the guards went into the city and told the chief priest what had happened. Consequently, they conspired with the elders and bribed the soldiers with money to say ' His disciples came by night and stole him away while we were sleeping. And if this comes to the Governor's ears we will satisfy him and keep you out of trouble'. So they took the money and did as they were told .   The story has been spread among the Jews to this day. They worshipped him, but some doubted. Jesus said to them ' All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Go therefore and make disciples of all nations, baptising them in the name of the father, and of the son and of the holy spirit. Teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you, and lo I am with you always, to the close of the age.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "In what ways is the resurrection significant to the Christian faith?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It gives the courage and the Hope that the God will serve is the living God.   - It shows that death is the genesis of the new phase or eternal life .  - Like the three women ministered to Jesus even unto death, Christians should be ready to serve.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Give an account of how Philip preached the Gospel message to the Ethiopia Eunuch.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The angel of the Lord directed Philip toward Gaza after he had finished his work in Samaria. At Gaza, Philip met the Ethiopia Eunuch returning home from the worship at Jerusalem.  Philip who was directed by the spirit of God to join the Ethiopian Eunuch in his chariot heard him reading from prophet Isaiah. He then queried the Eunuch if he understood the passage. And the Eunuch responded that he could not, except somebody guided him. This made Eunuch invite Philip into his chariot. The passage he was reading was about 'the sheep being led to the slaughter or a lamb before its shearer is dumb... 'He then asked Philip whom the prophet was referring to, whether himself or somebody else?  Philip acquired experience from this passage and began to preach the good news of Jesus to him. As they came to a body of water, the Eunuch was baptized by Philip. In the process, the spirit of the Lord came upon Philip and the Eunuch did not see him anymore. Thus he left the spot as a happy man.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "In what two ways was the Episode important to Christianity?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- All Christians are mandated to evangelize.  - The gospel went beyond Jerusalem, Judea through Samaria and into the Gentile territory.   -  There is a need for divine inspiration.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "What was Paul's exposition of the concept of justification by faith, in Romans?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The term justification is described as being free from moral sin by God. It is a state in which man's sin is overlooked by God as a saving grace to eternal life.   Justification is a gift of God's grace. It cannot be acquired by man's effort or his perfection. Christ took it upon himself to carry man's sin on the cross, the choice is for man to reject it and perish. A Christian therefore has to believed in the resurrection of Jesus as a first step to justification. Man must confess his faith with his lips and actions which will earn him salvation.   Both the Jews who had trusted in the righteousness of law, and Gentiles in their ignorance have fallen short of God's grace. With the coming of Jesus, only those who accept him in faith will be accepted.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "What was Paul's exposition of the concept of justification by faith, in Romans?Mention any four fruits to be derived from this account.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Freedom from sin  - Acceptance by Christ into eternal life.  - Saving grace to eternal life.   - Christ had carried our sin on the cross of Calvary that is why we don't need to be encumbered with guilt.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "Explained the concept of New Life in Christ as taught by Paul.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "New life in Christ demands that a believer strips himself of the old clothing in readiness for the new life. He should therefore begin to live a Christ-like life having been buried with Christ through resurrection of power.   Paul in the light of the above regards ideal Christians as those who have been buried with Christ through baptism and rised with him through resurrection power. This group of people he said are dead to sin and sin can no longer hold them back. Such must therefore live a new life by disciplining their flesh in order to yield its evil desires which run contrary to the conditions of the new life.   Good Christians must dissuade from the life of immorality, impurity, evil desires, greed, anger, bad temper, malice, slander and shameful language. Christians must not lie to one another because they are in a new life.   In the new life, Christians should be admonishing each other and do everything in the name of Jesus, giving thanks to God the father through him. Thus there should be no difference as Christ is all in all. Also as God's chosen people. Christians must imbibe tenderness of heart, kindness, humility, gentleness, patience, endurance, and bear with one another.  Christians should forgive one another as God has forgiven them. Christians should crown all the virtues with love which is the perfect bond of union. They should let peace of Christ reign in their lives and be thankful. The enriching message of Christ should make an impact in their activities. They should encourage one another in all wisdom with Psalms, hymns and spiritual songs. All things must be done in Jesus name.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "What four necessary steps must a new member in the church take before initiation into a new life.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- First preaching and hearing the words of God.  - Confession of sins by words of mouth after believing in the word of God.  - To fellowship together with other Christians ans living Christ-like life.  - Ensuring the spread of gospel.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Give the highlight letter of Paul's letter to Philemon.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul started his letter by first give thanks to God for the love which he learnt Philemon had in serving the Lord and towards the church of Christ. As Philemon's benefactor, Paul admitted he had the right to order him to do his request, he would however not use compulsion but peesuation, in order to take back his formal slave, Onesimus, who has wronged him but had now become Paul's son in Christ again. Onesimus had formally made himself un-useful to Philemon but now aa a Christian he had become useful to both Philemon and Paul.   Onesimus back in the love of Christ, though he would have preferred to have him ( in his service in Rome). He would however not do so without first getting Philemon's willing consent in order to remove any shade of command. Paul then suggested that peradventure Onesimus had parted from his master (for a short while) so that at his return, he might have him forever but this time, no longer as a slave but (more essentially) as a Christian brother. He therefore appealed to Philemon, if he still respected Paul as a brother in Christ to receive Onesimus back as he would receive Paul himself. If Onesimus owed him anything, he should charge same on his own account with assurance that he would pay it back on his next visit. In the meantime he should prepare a guest room for him and pray to God to make his visit a reality.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Explain the term 'Forgiveness'", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Forgiveness is the tendency or willingness to pardon and let go of injury or wrong done to you by another whether physical, moral or mental, Forgiveness can only be complete when it is couple with forgetfulness. ' to ere is human and to forgive is divine'. It is only God that forgive holistically while human being can only pardon. Forgiveness is a pardon that comes from the inner heart due to God's love.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "State the main features of Peter's counsel to wives and husband in their relationship.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter in his first epistle dealt on how women - wives in particular should summit to their husband. For by so doing showing good behaviour toward their husbands, they will be able to win the hearts of the unbelieving husbands to God, especially in  response to the reverent and chaste nature which they exhibit. He further encouraged that wives should not attach too much importance to external adornments ( like the excessive use of trinkets, gold ornament, hair braiding, show -off dressing etc) But lay more emphasis on moral probity before God which is a precious as an imperishable ornament. Wives should see Sarah as a role model for she hoped in God and respected her husband in obedience as her Lord. To peter, if they maintain that standard as wives, they will rightly bear their own children by faith.   On the part of the husbands, Peter encouraged them to live understandingly with their wives, in accordance with their knowledge of God's character and will, knowing that they are the weaker vessels. They should treat them with love and honour. This is to ensure that their prayers as joints heirs by the grace of God might not be hindered by an ungodly actions on their parts.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2000>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2000", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "List three consequences of instability in the family.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Increase in the rate of divorce due to extreme materialism and selfishness which characterized the relationship today.  - Instability of the family may lead to instability in the nation.   - When there is no love between husband and wife, the family does not experience peace hence trouble every time", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "What is covenant?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "A covenant is a solemn agreement between two people/parties concerned, each vowing to live to its own pledges as per the terms of the covenant. There are two types of covenant.   I. Parity covenant: This is a type of covenant whereby the two parties concerned are equals   II. Suzerain covenant: This is covenant  between two unequal parties. Failure not to abide by the rules that governed the covenant may lead to the termination of it.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "How God proved to Abraham that he would Honour the covenant", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I.  God's promises that Sarah would bear a son for Abraham in his old age, came to fulfillment.  II.    God's assurance of his faithfulness to Abraham despite the skepticism exhibited by Abraham due to His old age and infertility of Sarah, he still proved his supriority by establishing his covenant with him by making Sarah bear a son, called Isaac.  III.  God would bless Ismael with children but Sarah would bear a son to be called Isaac same season the following year.   IV. Sarah conceived and bore a son which Abraham called his name Isaac and circumcised him after eight days. Abraham celebrated with feast to God by keeping his covenant", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "Narrate the event which leads to the reconciliation between David and Abner.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Great war occurred after the demise of Saul between the house of David and Saul for sovereignty. Whereas Abner take over the position of the leadership of the army and made himself mighty at the expense of Ishboshet, the son of Saul, who pointed an accusing finger on Abner for having an affair with his father's wife, Rizpah. This upset Abner and he questioned if he had become 'a dog's head' to be insulted on a matter concerning woman.  Without hesitating he made it public that he won't pledge his loyalty to the home of Saul anymore and vowed to transfer same to the house of David. Abner sent a letter to David, asking David to enter into an agreement with him, before he could handover all Israel to him. David then vowed to consider his request only if he first wife, Micah would be restored to him because he suffered much to get her betrothed to him. David then got a message across to Ishboshet to restore Micah to him and he accepted.   Abner talked to the elders of Israel, to crown David aa the king of Israel, as he was already chosen by God to govern the Israel.   The twenty man delegate ldewelfome before to David at Hebron were highly welcome. Here Abner guaranteed David that he would Israel to sign an gather agreement with him to reign over them. Abner was sent off amicably after the covenant by David and Israel was sealed.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "What two lessons could be derived from this ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Leaders should entertain peace in regardless of the situation.   II. David made use of the bad situation to get his kingship crown through reconciliation with victory which perhaps his army might not have been able to get easily against Saul's Army.   III. Leaders should imbibe the spirit of forgiveness as david forgave his chief foe, Abner, who had been waging unjustifiable war against David.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Describe Solomon's dreamboat Gibeon", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the death of David, Solomon, his son ascended the throne. He loved God and walked according to his father's statues, laws and ways. t the commencement of his reign, during the course of his visit to Gibeon to sacrifice to the Lord, Gos appeared to Solomon in the dream and asked him to make a request according to his desires. Solomon began with commendation for the Lord's doing, who had great love for David, his father in giving him a son to succeed him, because he had walked before him and remained faithful to God. As a littlrbchild Solomon found himself in the midst of God's great and chosen people who could not be numbered. He asked God for wisdom and understanding which is the principal things for governing his people and the vision that will enable him to eiffereciate between good and evil. God was pleases in his request since he did not make a request for riches and the lives of his foes, God decided to add to his request those things that he never made request for such as riches, honour and even the lives of his enemies so that none before or after him could be like him. God made a pledge that if Solomon could keep his statues and commandments  he would lengthen this days.  When Solomon arose from his dream, he made a sacrifice to God in Jerusalem and feasted with his servant.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "For what two reasons would you approve of Solomon's request on this occasions?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. There is a great need of wisdom at that tender age to rule this state.   II. God's wisdom is the principal device for young king to be able to handle futuristic conflicts   III. With God's wisdom no problem in his government  and Israel lived amicably.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "What was God's message to the people of Israel through Isaiah when they offended Him.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Isaiah compares the rulers and the people of Israel with Sodom and Gomorrah and he wants them to listen to the instructions or word of God. He baffled why the people of Israel they so delighted in their numerous of sacrifices of burnt offerings or fats of well fed beasts. According to Isaiah God were not interested in these sacrifice and their deceptive appearance in God's courts, which have become an abomination before God.   In Isaiah's idea, God hate their new moon, Sabbath and other religious feasts because they were define with all sorts of immorality. God according to Isaiah, would turn away His eyes from their outstretched hands and would not pay attention to them when they render prayer because their hands were soiled with blood. In order to appease the wrath of God, they must:   a. wash themselves clean by removing eil from their activities.   b. they must negate evil and do good.  c. seek justice and stop to oppress the poor.   d. take the defend of the fatherless and please for the widows.   e. respond positively to God's invitation to dialogue with him. .", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "In which two ways are these issues still prevalent in your society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Oppression of the poor and the weak by the rich and powerful people are common in our society.   II. Moral deficiencies among our youth, which is reflected in the way of dressing, expression, non dedication to the right path.  III. people give sacrifices to their numerous lesser gods and pay homage to it.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "From the sermon on the mount, state how Jesus handled the issues of adultery, divorce and swearing.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Adultery: in Jesus teaching from the sermon on the mount, he told the people that old testament laws or Mosiac laws prohibited adultery but added ' I say to you that everyone who looks at a woman lustfully has already committed adultery with her in his heart'. He continued, if their right eye would cause them to sin, it should be plucked out. It is better to loose one member than to loose the whole body in hell fire and that, if their right hand would cause them to sin, they should cut it off.  Divorce: the law further stated that anybody who divorces his wife let him give her a certificate of divorce. ' But I say to you that everyone who divorces his wife, except on ground of unchasity/ immorality or adultery makes her an adulteress and whoever marries a divircesd woman commit adultery.   Swearing: The law of Moses also prohibited swearing falsely. One must however live up t to expectatiom of whatever he/she had sworn to do. Jesus however taught them not to swear at all either by heaven for it is the throne of God or by the earth for it is God's footstool or by Jerusalem, the city of the great king/ God. Do not swear by your head for you cannot make one strand of your hair black or white. Let what you say be simply yes or no, anything contrary to this comes from the devil.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Indicate two lessons to be drawn from Jesus' attitude to these practices.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Swearing was totally disapprove by God because it comes from the devil or Satan but this was the case with the Jews.   II. Jesus makes a man who marries a divorced woman guilty of the sin of adultery, while the Jew believe man seldom commit adultery but a woman does. This segregating attitude of the Jews against womennia therefore condemned by Jesus.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "' teacher, what shall I do to inherit eternal life? How did Jesus deal with this questions.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This question was asked by a popular lawyer and also to put him to test. Jesus then asked him what was contained in the law stated about how he was reading it. The then lionized the law stating, ' you should love the Lord your God with all your heart... and love your neigbour as yourself'. Jesus further commanded him to go and do that and he would inherit eternal life. But the lawyer what to to justify his question, asked to know who his neighbour was. Then Jesus told him a parable, how a man who was travelling from Jerusalem to Jericho fell into hand of robbers, he was beaten up thoroughly, stripped and was left half dead. Thereafter a Priest, and later a Levite saw him, and passed by on the other side. But later on, a Samaritan came by and saw the injured man, gave him first aid and took him on his beast to inn and deposited some money for further treatment and care. He also promised to return and pay whatever would be extra cost spent on the man.   Jesus then asked the lawyer which of the three who saw the injured man proved to be his neighbour. The lawyer answered that the one who showed mercy. Then Jesus asked him to go and do likewise", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "In what two ways should Christian show concern for others.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. They should show concern for the less privilege, the sick and the elderly ones.   II. To show total repentance, Christians should learn how to forgive those that wronged them.  III. Christians should share with others those physical and spiritual needs like the spriture of God and physical assets at their disposal which they received freely through the grace of God.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Trace Matthew's account of the crucifixion and burial of Jesus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "While the soldiers were escorting Jesus on the way to Calvary they came upon a man called Simon of Cyrene who was compelled to carry the cross of Jesus. At Golgotha which means the place of skull, they offered him wine mixed with gall which when he tasted it he could nor drink. After Jesus was crucified, his garment was shared by casting lots and they sat down to keep watch over him there. Over his head they put the charge against him which read, 'This is Jesus the king of the Jews'. Two robbers were crucified along with him, one each on the right and on the left.   Those who passed by derided Jesus, nodding their heads and saying, 'you, who would destroy the temple and rebuild it in three days, save yourself. If you are the son of God, come down from the cross'. Even the chief priest with the Scribes and elders mocked himbsaying ' He saved others, he cannot save himself. He is the King of Israel; let him come down now from the cross, and we shall believe in him. And one of the robbers who were crucified along with him also reviled him in the same way.   From the sixth hour. There was darkness over all the land until the ninth hour when Jesus cried with a loud voice ' Eli, Eli la' ma sabach-thani?' meaning ' My God, My God, Why has thou forsake me?'  Some of the bystanders hearing this said ' This man is calling Elijah' to come and save him. At one time he was given Vinegar to drink and Jesus cried again with loud voice and gave up the ghost.   Simultaneously, there was earthquake and rocks were split while the saints who had fallen asleep were raised. The Centurion and the guards trembled with fear and exclaimed. 'Truly this mab was the son of God\".   There were also many women there looking on from afar, who had followed Jesus from Galilee, ministering to him, among whom were Mary Magdalene, and Mary the mother of James and Joseph, and the mother of the sons if Zebedee.  Burial   When it was in the evening came a rich man from Arithmathea named Joseph who also was a secret disciple of Jesus. Then Pilate ordered the body to be given to him. Joseph took the body wrapped it in a clean libel shroud, and laid it in his own new tomb which he had hewn in the rock and rolled a great stone to the door of the tomb before he left the place.   Mary Magdalene and other Mary were sitting outside the sepulchre to witness the burial.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Give account of the work of Philip in Samaria.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Following the death of Stephen, there were great persecutions, which resulted in the church being frighten and the people scrammed from Jerusalem to other places, including Judea, Samaria e.t.c. there they preached the gospel that made many people to convert to thr or faith.  Philip was one of the seven deacons that fled to Samaria and preached the Gospel of Christ there. Many were converted when they heard and some the miracles being performed.   Demons were cast our from those possessed while those that fell ill received their healing, paralyzed and lame were also healed. There are great joy in the city of Samaria when they discovered that unclean spirits were driven out of many who were losses, crying out with a loud voice.   On the course of preaching, Philip came across a man called Simon who previously was practicing magic in the city and surprised the nation of Samarte saying he is great but indulged in deceitful deed, making many people believed he possessed the power of the most high God. Simon was also converted and baptized by Philip.   At due time, the Apostles in Jerusalem started feeling the impact of the gospel in the Samaria, hence they sent Peter and John to witness the great work in the city of Samaria, they were impressed with what they saw. As they prayed they laid their hands on the new concerts to receive the Holy Spirit.   Peter however rebuked Simeon, who though he can buy the Holy Ghost with money. Peter said ' Your silver will perish with you...' Simeon became afraid at the action of Peter and asked Peter to pray for him.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "In what two ways were the activities of the Holy Spirit manifested in Samaria?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Manifestation of miracle working power.   II. Several sick people received healing.  III. The evil activities of Simon was exposed and condemned.   IV. There were new converts from among the unbelievers.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Explain why Paul advocated submission to the people in authority", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul instructed that everybody should obey or be subject to constituted or governing authorities. For there is no authority except those from God and all exiting ones are from God, and such any resistance will definitely earn God's wrath or judgment.  Rulers are no terror to good conduct, but no bad conduct. Good citizens should not entartain any unnecessary fears about those in authority as long as they obey the rulers and receive commendation of the governing authority, for they are God's servant. On the other hand, if they do wrong, they should be afraid and prepare for the consequences that follow i.e punishment for the wrong dormers.  To live as a good citizens, they should always maintain clear conscience, by paying their taxes, perform other civic duties as at when due and five respect to constituted authorities. Authorities dies not wield the sword in vain. He is the servant of the Lord to execute God's wrath on evil doers. Everyone must be subject to civil authorities to avoid God's wrath. In order to maintain a clearer conscience. Christian citizens should give respect/honour to whom honour is due.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "State four ways by which you can help your school authority to maintain law and order in your school.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Regular payment of tuition fees/levies   II. Adapting oneself holistically to school works, studies, games and extra curricular activities.   III. dissuading from the members of secret societies or cult.   IV. Avoiding all form of examination malpractices, pilfering and other evil devices.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "What did Paul teach the Philippians about humility?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In letter of Paul to the Philippians, Paul beseeches us as Christians to possess a sense of love, share in the spirit, affection and sympathy in order to complete the joy of being Christians by being in unity with one another.   Paul warns them to dissuade from any deed of selfishness and conceit, but they should wear modesty. Through this means, they could count others first before themselves. They should follow Jesus Christ, whose humility should be a pattern for them. Jesus was in form of God, but did not equate himself with God , instead, he humbled himself as a servant, until the point of death. As a result of Jesus' humility, God highly exalted him both in heaven and on earth. Jesus is the Lord to the glory of the father.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight two ways by which a Christians could manifest the spirit of humility.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. By exhibiting love and sympathy toward others   II. By putting aside selfishness and deceit because this are negative tools that hamper humility.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>11", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "How did James prove that 'faith apart from works, is dead?'", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "James in the teaching, on faith and works beseeched the Christians to be doers of the word and not hearers only. To James, nobody can lay claim to being good Christians unless he puts into daily practice what he is being taught and the precepts of God as explained by Jesus. He explains this concept with the analogy of someone who observes his face in a mirror, as mere hearer of God's word who immediately, turns away from the mirror without further examination of himself.   On the other hand, a doer of the word is the one who looks into the perfect law of Jesus Christ which is the law of liberty and with perseverance and practice does not forget easily, but act on it and receive God's blessings.  James further said that truly religious man must muzzle his tongue but one who fails to do that decries himself and his religion is in vain. True religion entails visiting of the orphans and widows and keeping oneself unstained from the world and maintaining purity before God.   To analyze his teaching, James gave a biblical instances of faith and works operating in juxtaposition with works. When Abraham heard and obeyed God he showed his readiness to sacrifice his only son, Isaac, it proved that his faith would have been incomplete without taking the appropriate action. Abraham thus believed God and it was recorded for him as righteousness, and he was called the friend of God having been justified by his works and not by faith alone. Same was said of the harlot at Jericho (Rehab) who had faith in God and this manifested when she saved the lives of the spies from her countrymen who wanted to eliminate them.  She instead prepared the free escape routes for the spies, by this action, she was justified. Finally, James ascertain that faith without work is dead.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Explain Peter's advice to the elders and members of the church in their interpersonal relationships.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter focuses on the roles, duties and responsibilities of Christians leaders in the church of Christ.   He explained that the elders are to take good care of the flock of God under their charge willingly and selflessly, they shouldn't do so because of their selfish desires for the murdane gains or by a domineering attitude towards those people under their leadership. But through their exemplary lives or eagerness that come from the heart and lay a good example to be enumerate by the flocks so that at due time they will attain the crown of glory.  They should pro vide spiritual guidance for the young Christians and lead them to overcome the devil.  The young onea were also urged to be humble and subjected to the elders of the church as God humiliate the proud and exalt the humble. They should take the good advice of the elders, respect them and use them as their spiritual patterns.  To the churches, Peter advised that the Christians among the Gentiles are advised to humble themselves under the mighty hand of God for them to be exalted.  For the leaders, Peter recommended humble approach. They should leave or cast all their anxiety in the able hands of God who cares for them. They should in all soberness resists the devil and be firm in the faith against the temptation of Satan who is always around the corner to lead the spiritually weak ones to destruction of hell.  Finally, they should be armed with faith and patience, and should remember that suffering is part of the Christian calling and it will lead to eternal life in Christ who has eternal dominion. This suffering according to Peter would not last, but the God of grace who called them to eternal glory will restore, establish and strengthen them.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2001>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2001", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH~~LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA~~LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES~~LEADERSHIP ROLES : DEBORAH", "question": "State two duties of a good church leaders.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. The first priority of the elders should be to take good care of the flock ( spiritual and physical )  II. Evangelism should be encouraged by the elders.  III. A good church leaders he must live a modest life style.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>1", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "1", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "identify Joseph's talents and show how he applied them as as a leader.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Joseph was one of the seldom leaders in the history ocox the Israelites. He had some unique talents which he put to implementation in every leadership position he found himself.  Joseph was fond by his father more than his eleven brethren and he always reported his brother's bad deeds to their father. He was a dreamer and had a gift to decipher visions. He illustrated his dreams to his brothers and to his father. Because of this, his father corrected him and his brother showm hostility towards him. As an obedient and honest child, his father sent him to see the welfare of his brothers who colaborated on sighting him from afar and sold him into slavery, thereby attempting to frustrate God's plan for him  As a slave in Egypt, God prepared him with the gifts of perseverance and faith. He knew what was right and avoided all forms of immorality. Even when he was captured unjustly he endured all the suffering and became a faithful friend to his fellow captors.  He interpreted the dreams of his fellow captors. The chief butler proved ungrateful to Joseph for two years he did nothing to help him . Afterwards Pharaoh had dreams which Joseph layer interpreted. From prison, he was promoted as Governor of Egypt and was give infinite power. He showed extraordinary management ability as governor.   His modesty and love made him keep at level head, even when hia brother, who no longer reoongnized him, came to get food in Egypt. Through a mumber of examination, he got them to confess their past guilt and misdeeds or wrongdoing. Like a real leader, he pardon them and recognized with them. Finally, he sent for his father and ensured that he lived his final days in place.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Give an account of the destruction of Jerusalem by the Babylonians during the reign of King Zedekiah.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Zedekiah was made king of Judah by Nebuchadnezzar, the king of Babylon. Zedekiah rebelled agianst the King of Babylon and Nebuchadnezzar sent troop against Jerusalem. The invasion lasted for nineteen months and the resultant famine forced the king of attempt to flee from the doomed city by night. He was overcome, captured and sentenced. His sons were killed before his very eyes and was blinded and taken in chaines to Babylon. Later, Nebusaradan ( the captain of  the body guard or a servant of the king of Babylon) came to Jerusalem with mandate to destroy the city. He burnt the temple, the king's house and every great house. The wall round Jerusalem was destroy. Many more Israelites were taken to Babylon leaving only the poorest of the land to be vine dressers and ploughmen. The last traces of the splendour of Solomon were also taken as booty to Babylon.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Identify four causes of social unrest today in Africa.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "1. Social injustice   ii. Political instability   iii. corruption  iv. there is a huge dichotomy between the rich and the poor.  v. oppression of the poor.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Relate the story of the healing of Naaman.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Naaman was the head of the Syrian army, he had a leprosy. A slave girl assumed that if he would go to Samaria, a seer would heal him. He took a letter from the King of Syria to the King of Israel telling him that he was sent by his commander to him to be healed of leprosy. When the King of Israel got the letter, he torned his clothes and said '  Am I God, to kill or make alive, that this man sent word to cure a man of leprosy'.   When prophet Elisha heard that the King had torn his clothes, he intervened and asked that Naaman be sent to him. He said, 'let him now come to me that he may know that there is a prophet in Israel'. Naaman went to Elisha and was told to go and wash himself seven times in the River Jordan and be cured of the disease.   He was upset that Elisha's advice, and asked if ' rivers Ababa and Pharpar of Damascus were not better than all the waters of Israel? ' Could I not wash in them and be clean' He turned his chariot to return to Damascus in great rage.  However, on his way, his servant humbly beseeched him to retum and do as the prophet says. Naaman yielded and went to River Jordan, dipped himself seven times into it, and became heal. He returned to Elisha to show his gratitude and implored him to accept some of his gifts but Elisha decline.   Then,Naaman pleaded to be allowed to carry home to Damascus a small quantity of soil from Israel a coner of his house to signify that henceforth, he would serve the God of Israel.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSIONS DURING AHAB’S REIGN", "question": "How does the name of God glorified through his misfortune.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Obedience to the word of God is essential, if one obeyed.  ii. Naaman's miracle make other nations worshipped Yahweh.  iii Elisha declined gifts from Naaman showed that God's talent is free and it shouldn't be monetise.  Iv. His healing shows that God of Israel is only the true God.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Describe the social life of Israel during the time of Amos.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There was general persecution of the poor by the rich ones. The rich ones sold the righteous for silver and the needy for a pair of shoes. The poor had no just trial in the courts and the level of prostitution was so high that a man and his father could go into the same woman. At the altar the rich men sat in clothes given as pledge to them by the poor debtors and they also drank at the altars, wine of those that had been fined. Their women fed fat on the proceeds of their husband's oppression of the poor and drank wines from the bowls. Amos called them Cows of Bashan.  The rich built stone houses and lived in great luxury with proceeds derived from the unfair treatment of the poor. In the markets, the rich used false weight and measures. In spite of various forms of punishment such as famine, drought , blight and mildew, locust infestation and all the curses of Egypt, they still continued in their evil and refused to listen to the voice of God but desired the 'Day of of the Lord'. Amos cautioned them and said they should be prepared for total doom that would come from God's wrath.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Mention four vices condemned by Amos which are still rampant in your society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. Oppression of the poor by the rich ones: the poor were been marginalise by the rich ones by underpaying them for the services rendered.  ii. Cheating in business: Some rich ones at cunning when there is a business agreement between them and the poor, in fact they try to put them aside ans dominate.  iii. Injustice in the court: the rich bribe the judge that made judgement to be in their favour.  IV. Luxury: the rich lived an extravagant lifestyle and feed themselves to the fullest in expense of the poor.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "Narrate the story of the temptation of Jesus according to Matthew.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After hia baptism, Jesus was led by the Holy Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil. He fasted for forty days and nights and at the fasting, he was very hungry. The devil came and told him that if he were the son of God, he should turn the stones into bread. He replied that it was written that man shall not live by bread alone. The devil them took him to the pinnacle of the temple and said to him ' if you are the son of God, throw yourself down, for it is written, ' He will give his angels charge of you', and Jesus replied him that ' again it is written, ' you shall not tempt the Lord your God'.   After this, the devil took him to a high mountain and showed him all the kingdoms of the world, and their glory and said to him. 'All these I will give you it you will fall down and worshipped me'. Jesus said to him. ' Begone, Satan! For it is written the devil left him and the angels came and ministers to him.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "In what two ways were the temptations significant for Jesus in his ministry.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. The temptation confirmed the divinity of Christ.   ii. The temptation prepared Jesus Christ for his early ministry.   iii. The way the temptation was handled shows that Jesus is not a political and economical messiah.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Relate the parable of the Prodigal Son.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The parable of the prodigal son has it that a man had a two sons. The younger of the house asked for his own share in his father's propriety. After collecting his share, he left his native home and spent it lavishly in careless living. A great famine arose in the country he was and made him to be in want and he was forced to descend to the most debasing employment of feeding swine. He later came back to his senses and he contemplating to return to his father and tell him not to receive him as a son but as hired servant. While he was yet at a remote, his father saw him and ran and hugged him. The son humbly begged his father to take him back simply aa a servant not as a son. However, the servant were asked to clothe the son with the best robe fitting for the guest of honour, give him the ring and the shoes and then killed the fattened calf so that all might share in the father's gladness.   So, the son was restored to his formal position and they began to make merry. The elder one came, heard the sound of the celebration and when he made inquiries, the servants told him that ' your brother has come and your father is making merriment for him'  The elder brother was unhappy an would not come in until his father came and entreated him. He complained that since he had been serving his father faithfully, he had not one day celebrated with him and his friends but when his son of his came who had wasted his wealth, he killed a fatted calf for him.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "What three characters traits did the elder brother exhibit?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. Jealousy   ii. pride   iii. Lack of respect   iv. anger   v. selfishness", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "How did Jesus use his encounter with the Samaritan woman to illustrate that he is the living water.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus met the Samaritan woman by the well and asked her to give him water to drink. She puzzled how a Jew could ask her, a Samaritan, fid a drink. Jesus told her it was so unfortunate that she did not know the person that was asking him for a living water. The Samaritan puzzled how he could provide water without a vessel to get the water from such a deep well. She said she was sure she could not be greater than Jacob, the great grand father if Israelites who gave them the well which Jacob himself and all his descendants and their animals drank from. Jesus said emphatically that whoever drank of the water he would never thirst again, for the water he would give would never thirst again, for the water he would give would become a spring of water to eternal life. The woman asked Jesus to give her the water so that she would not come to draw  water again.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "State two lessons that can be derived from the episode.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. In Jesus there is no discrimination.   ii. Christianity supersedes Judaism   iii. Jesus has come to give eternal life and men should desire it.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Discuss Saul's experience on his way to Damascus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Saul, a persecutor of the church asked the high Priest for letters of introduction to the synagogues at Damascus, so that if he found any one belonging to the way, he could arrest and bring him to Jerusalem.  As he near Damascus, he saw a great light, fell to the ground and heard a voice saying, ' Saul, Saul, why do you persecute, me?' 'Who are you Lord', Saul asked and the voice replied, ' I am Jesus whom you are persecuting'. Immediately, he became blind and was led to Damascus, where he remained, without food for three days.  In Damascus, there is a disciple called Ananias who was sent by God to the house of Judas in Straight street to enquire of Saul of Tarsus. The Lord said that Saul was praying and in a vision, he had seen Ananias laying his hands on him, so that he might receive his sight. But Ananias argued saying that he had heard from many about '... this man, him, so that he had done to the saints at Jerusalem, and how much evil he had done to the saints at Jerusalem, and how he got authority from the chief priests to bind all who called upon thy name.'   But the Lord described Saul as a unique instrument to carry the name of Jesus to the Gentiles and Kings and the Sons of Israel.   Ananias obeyed the Lord and came to Saul and called him 'brother Saul', he told him that the Lord Jesus who appeared to him on the road had sent him that he might regain his sight and be filled with the Holy Ghost.   Immediately, something like scales fell from Saul's eyes and he regained his sight. Saul then arose and was baptized, and he ate some food and become strong.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "How significant was his experience to his future life?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "i. Saul become a victim for the early church as the Lord had predicted.  ii. Saul became an apostle to the Gentiles and from then they enjoyed peace.  iii. Saul was transformed for being a persecutor of the church to the defender of the church.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>9", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "'If any one will not work, let him not eat' Explain the circumstances which led to this statement", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "One of the major themes dealt with by Paul in his letters was the second coming of Jesus Christ. He spoke of the imminence of the great occasion and the need for Christians to lead a good life in readiness for Jesus at his second coming.  Some Thessalonian Christians were led to the misconception that the Parousia was just around the corner. They felt there was , therefore, no need for them to exert themselves in further physical work, what mattered was to watch and pray. When Paul received the news that some Thessalonians had folded their hands and refused to work and that they had even constituted themselves intone nuisance for the others, by either preventing them from their work or by solely depending on them for their bread, he had to write to them in very firm terms in order to disabuse the minds of such that whoever refuses to work should not eat. People should honestly apply themselves to work, without eye-service, as if they were serving the Lord.   He reminded them that when he was with them he not parasitic, although he had the right to depend on them  for his physical needs. He had worked with his own hands in order to maintain himself and be, for them, an example worthy of emulation. It was therefore compulsory for the lazy to get down to work with their hands. But should they not need his advice they should be boycotted to their shame.  However, he warned that they should not be treated as enemies, but warned and redirected with brotherly love, to retrace their steps and do the right thing.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What according to Paul, are the signs of the Parousia?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul encouraged the church Thessalonians not to be sad for the dead one as people without hope do. He said through Jesus, God will bring up those who have fallen asleep in Him.  - Those who are alive will not precede those who are asleep  - The Lord will come with a cry of command coupled with Archangel's call and the sound of the trumpet of God and the living will join the dead in the cloud to meet Jesus  - Paul encouraged them not to be quickly shaken in mind in respect of the coming of the Lord will not come until a rebellion against God directed by the man of lawlessness come by pass. He said he who now restrains it, will do so until he is out of the way and then the lawless one whose coming, by the activity of Satan, will be with power, pretension, sign, wonder and wicked deception, will be repaved. For those are to perish and to those who refuse to love the truth and be saved God will send a strong delusion to make them believe what is false. He who does not believe the truth but has pleasure in unrighteousness will be condemned.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "State three lessons in Paul's explanation relevant to Christian living", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Jesus will surely reign over Satan   Ii. Death is only physical, life will continues after death  iii. Christian should avoid excessive sadness over their dead.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>11", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Give the highlights of Christ's resurrection appearance as outlined in I Corinthians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "St Paul reminded Corinthians of the content of the Gospel of salvation, which he had already preached to them. This included the fact that Jesus died for the sins of the world, he was buried and was raised on the third day in accordance with the scriptures, He appeared to Cephas and the twelve and later to more than five hundred brethren at one time, some of which were still alive while some had fallen sheep. Then, he appeared to James and all the apostles. Last of all, as to none untimely born, he appeared also to Paul who being the least of the apostles was unfil to be called an apostle because he had persecuted the church of God.  - The grace of God towards Paul made him what he was for Christ and such grace was not in vain. It made Paul to work harder than any of those who received Christ before him.   - if there was no resurrection, it means that Christ had not been raised and the apostlic preaching and the Christian faith should have been vain for the apostles must have been misrepresenting God who they preached had raised Christ from the dead.   - If Christ had not been raised, then their faith was futile. They remained in sin and the dead in Christ had perished.   - it was for this life that Christians hoped in Christ, then they should have been the most pitied of all men.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Explain Peter's concept of a good citizens.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter began with a general admonished to Christians to be subjected, for the Lord's sake, to every human institution. Whether it is to the emperor as the supreme authority on earth, or to the government appointed by him to oversee the administration with delegated powers to punish offenders or reward those who do right, for this is the will of God, the ultimate power behind these earthly authorities. He said that by doing the right thing, they would put to shame the ignorance of foolish men. He admonished them to live as men free from the curse of the law and not to misuse their liberty as a pretext for evil. He said they should rather live as servants of God with the fear of God. They should honour all men, love the Christians brotherhood and honour the emperor.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2002>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2002", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Identify any three qualities of a good citizens", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. He should have love for this nation and its legitimate institutions, both civil and religious   ii. He should obey all laws and regulations set up for the smooth administration of the country.  iii. He should pray for the nation's leaders, asking God to imbibe them with the wisdom to rule with the fear of God.  iv. He should be altruistic, have due regard for others and ensure to live at peace with the Bible Explanation citizens must never be party to any subversive movement or aid abet any form of corruption and immorality.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Narrate the second creation story.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the day that God made the made the Earth and the Heavens, the earth was covered with mist water covered the whole face of the ground. Then, then Lord formed man out of the dust of the earth and breathed the breath of life into his nostrils. God planted the Garden of Eden and put man there. In addition to the garden, God cause trees to grow and provide shelter and a source of food to man, God caused trees to grow and provide shelter and a source of food to man, God also planted the tree of life, and the tree of the knowledge of good and evil in the midst of the garden. He cause a river, which was divided into four, to surround the garden and supply water to it. Man was given the liberty to till the garden and supply water to it. Man was given the liberty to till the garden and was also allowed to eat freely of the trees except the tree of the knowledge of good and evil to avoid spiritual death. God saw the need to find a helpmate for man, since it is not good for man to stay alone. God gave man the authority to name beast, birds and all crawling animals he has created. God cause a deep sleep to befall man and made a woman out of his ribs for Adam. Man recognised his similarity with the woman and called her woman because she was created out of his rib.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "In what four ways did God provide comfort for man?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Provision of water to give constant supply to the garden  II. Provision of trees, beasts and birds for food among others  III. God provided suitable environment in the garden of Eden.  IV. God made a suitable partner for Adam in the person of Eve.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "Describe David's reaction to the death of the child born to him by Bathsheba", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "David committed adultery with Bathsheba, Uriah's wife and had a child. For this, God was displeased. God sent prophet Nathan who decreed the death of the child was struck with sickness. When David realized that God was displeased with his act, he interceded for the life of the child and fasted and laid upon the ground. The intercession and admonition of the elders did not change God's anger, and the child died on the seventh day.   Out of fright, the servants could not report to David lest hr harmed himself. The news of the death of his son was later reported to him. On hearing the news, he arose and had his bath, anointed himself and changed his apparel. He later went to the temple, worshipped God for answering his prayer and requested for food. His servant were surprised at his behaviour.  David fasted and wept so that would reverse his intention to take the son's life. Unfortunately, the child died and he thought fasting is no more necessary. David summed up his courage and believed that he could go to the child but the child could no more come to him.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "What two lessons can be learnt from this reaction.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God reserved the right to give and take anything from us at will. Again all human beings should submit himself to the will of God. In every situation we find ourselves we should give God praise.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "Trace the event that led to Elijah's pronouncement of drought in Israel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "From the story, it is revealed that when Ahab, son of Omri became the King of Israel in the thirty-eight year of ASA, king of Judah. He turned away from Jehovah's comandement and did evil in the sight of the Lord more than all his predecessors, he also walked in the sins of Jeroboam the son of Nebat. After taking Jezebel, daughter of Ethbaal, King of Sidon as wife .   Jezebel introduced the worship of Baal which Ahab approved and worshipped. King Ahab later built an altar for Baal and also made Asherah. Ahab institutionalized the worship of Baal made it a national religion in Israel and people were forced to comply with his directives. People that did not worship Baal were persecuted. God became angry, and sent prophet Elijah. Who then pronounced, drought in the name of the Lord, Yahweh", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "What lessons can be learnt from the action of Elijah?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Elijah's action shows that the weakness of a leader may ruin a nation. Ahab's weakness enables Jazeb to replace Yahwism with Baalism as the national religion. God is always on hand to defend course hence the call on Elijah to defend Yahwism.  Most people still have moral courage to challenge unpopular authority, most inter-religion marriage has its consequences.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Explain Isaiah's prophecy to the rulers and people of Israel on the wortessness of empty rituals.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Prophet Isaiah addressed rulers and the people of Israel and called upon them to listen to the teaching and the commandments of God and his divine will.   The man of God was equally worried about the genuineness of their rituals, their sacrifices and their burnt offerings. The prophet of God stated that God was tired of their wrong doings. He was not interested in their sacrifices of animals. He advised that they should worship God in the temple and approach God with cleanliness and holiness of heart., not with incense or offerings, God equay stated that their new moon. Sabbath, and other festive occasions were no longer pleasing to the Lord. The prophet put it to them that when they spread their hands in prayer, what God were their blood-stained hands. According to the prophet, God will no longer have respect for their prayers.  However, the prophet of God put it that to avert God's anger they were required to make themselves spiritually clean and remove all evil from their lives, in addition to that, they must pursue righteousness and justice, and stop all oppression of the poor. They were also advised to defend the fatherless, and plead the cause of widows. The prophet sounded a note of hope that God was still interested in their plight if they are ready to change. The man of God added that should they come to repentance, God will forgive their sins no matter the nature of the sins. The prophet, assurer them that if they were willing and obedient to do the divine will God, God will restore them to enjoy the fruits of their land and its full benefits. The prophet warned them on the dangers of sin and how they would be devoured by the sword.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MATTHEW 4: 18-25; 8: 18-22; 9:9-13 ;", "question": "Highlight Jesus' sermon on the mount under the following headings:", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "I. Treasures ii. The sound eye iii. Serving of two masters  Treasure: Jesus taught the multitude on the need to lay up treasures in heaven where moth and rust will not consume and where thieves will not break in and steal. He warned them against laying up treasures on earth where thieves and moth will break in and steal. This admonition was necessary because where one's treasures is, there would be his heart also.   Sounf Eyes: Jesus was of the view that if the eye is the lamp of the body. Jesus taught them that if the eye is sound, the whole body will be full of light. On the contrary if the eyes is not sound, the whole body will be full of darkness, they were to be careful that if the light in them is darkness, the darkness would awesome.   Two masters: Jesus taught them that it is not possible for one person to serve two masrers , since he will either hate one and live the other, or be devoted to one and despise another. Jesus admonished them to serve God rather than mammon", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Give two reasons why misuse of earthly wealth can lead to serious consequences for a nation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Misuse of earthly wealth can lead to serious consequence for a nation. Going by Jesus teaching, earthly wealth is synonymous with mammon and abuse of it leads to extreme selfishness and lack of concern for other and this will bring about suffering to the entire nation. Outright use if earthly wealth leads to the worship of materialism. When this happens, such a nation loses its spiritual balance, becomes ungodly and gradually degenerates until, it perishes like Sodom and Gomorrah. Misuse of earthly wealth widens the gap between the rich and the poor. Oppression of the poor by the rich will become the order of the day. In social parlance, the situation brings about general underdevelopment since the wealth of the nation is not well utiled.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Explain how Jesus healed the demoniac.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When Jesus and his disciples arrived at the land of the Gerasenss which is opposite Galilee, there was a man who had demons. Before now, theam had lived naked in a cemetery. When he met Jesus, he fell down before Jesus and cried with a loud voice, and begged him not to torment him, for the demon that torment him was violent so Mich that it drives him into desert.   As the Demoniac broke the fetters of iron; Jesus asked to know his name, when he answered Legion, for many demons had entered him. The demons in him implore Jesus not to send them into the abyss, but demanded that they be sent to hill side, where a large herd of swine were feeding. As Jesus obliged, the demons, immediately left the man and entered the swine, the swine rushed into the lake and got drowned. The shepherd were worried and fled to s report what they saw. The demoniac was later seen beside Jesus, well dressed and full of confidence. Most people that saw what happened were terrified, while eye witnesses narrated their story to others.  On seeing Jesus miracle, the inhabitants of Gerasenes sought to expel Jesus from their land because they were afraid. Jesus left the neighbourhood by a boat. When the demoniac instead on going with Jesus he refused and entreated him to go do declare the goodnews of what God has done.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "Give two reasons why the devil were sent into the swine.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God had to send the demons into the swine bexaus they were evil that must be destroyed. The Jews also regarded the swine as unclean animals that were not tolerated. Therefore, Jesus merely used an evil to destroy another one. Jesus would not allow the demoniac to go with him since he wanted his fame to spread abroad.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MARK 1: 16-20; 2: 13-17", "question": "Describe the miracle of 'walking on the sea' according to Mark", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus directed his disciples to get into the boat and go before him to the other side, after feeding the five thousand. This was done to dismiss the crowd. Jesus later went to the mountain to pray. In the evening, the boat was already out on the sea while Jesus was alone on the land. Jesus got to know that the wind was blowing against the boat at the fourth watch, Jesus walked on the sea when there was no boat to convey him. When the disciples noticed Jesus as he was approaching them they were afraid because they though he was ghost. They therefore cried out. Jesus assured them to take heart and not to exercise any dear since the person on the sea is him. Soon, Jesus entered the boat while the wind ceased instantly.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MARK 1: 16-20; 2: 13-17", "question": "In what two ways is this miracle significant?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "From the story, it is clear that Jesus had openely manifested himself to his disciples as the son of God (Messah), by walking on the sea. He demonstrated that he has power over nature. Jesus disciples exhibited lack of faith when they became surprise at seeing Jesus walking on the sea.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "Narrate the events on the Day of Pentecost", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The disciples were together in one place on the day of Pentecost, when a sound came from heaven and filled the house. Suddenly there appeared on their heads tongues as of fire. The disciples were filled with Holy Spirit and they spoke as the spirit led them. Various people who dwelt in Jerusalem as well as the disciples also spoke in tongues.   Other people who heard them were amazed, and were forced to asked whether the disciples were not all Galileans and wondered why they all spoke in diverse tongues. Some by standers mocked them that the disciples were drunk.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "State two ways in which the Holy Spirit still influences the life of Christians today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Through the Holy Spiri, active evanglism still foes on today. Former citadels of atheism are crumbling giving way to acceptance of the Gospel. The Holy Spirit is still assissting the world which has gone crazy which hatred, envy, man's inhuniry to man, indiscipline, murder, corruption etc. The Holy Spirit, is recognised as the lonely voice in the wilderness, appealing to human conscience to be more humane and ensure survival of human race. The Holy Spirit, is helping through economic pressions, the Holy Spirit still provides the church with the strength to carry on. Through the Holy Spirit miracle of healing are daily being recorded in our churches and hospitals.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>9", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "9", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "How did Paul prove to the Galatians that Christians are children of God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The notion that Christians were children of God was clearly shown in Paul's teaching on faith. His teaching further showed that the Christian were no longer held under the law. According to him, all Christians are sons of God through faith in Christ Jesus, baptism to them means putting on Christ. To them there is no discrimination (neither jew nor Greek, neither male nor female, neither slave nor free born) to any believer in Christ Jesus He held the view that if we all are in Christ we are all Abraham offspring and heirs, because of the provision of the promise and the convenant. According to Paul their sonship can be compared to a slave who owns the estate, but could not exercise control because he is held bound by the guardian.  At appointed time, God sent His son born of a woman to liberate those who were held under the law. This redemption, enabled them to be adopted as sons and have their freedom on our adoption as sons through faith, we receive the spirit of His sons in our hearts, since we are redeemed through Christ we seize to become slaves but sons of God and fellow heirs of the kingdom.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "What were Paul's view in his letter to the Colossians on interpersonal relationship in the Christian family?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul's teaching on this chapter was basically on the need for wives to be subject to their husbands, since this is what God excepts from Christians ( The man represents God as the Head of family). He also admonished the husband to love their wives by being humane and kind to them. To children, he urged them to obey their parents in everything for by so doing, they please God, Paul warned fathers against provoking their children lest they become violent, in the same vein he adviced slaves to obey earthly masters in everything not with eye service but in singleness of heart, their service should be with the dear of God, since God will reward their faithful service.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Mention four ways of avoiding conflicts in the family.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The husband and wife should act as a role model by religiously playing their expected roles for the children to emulate. The couples should strive to understand themselves by making peace at all times. Fathers should be tolerant with their spouses. Again, parents should be counselling their children and not provoking them to avoid conflict, the family must develop Prayer life. Parents should bless their children rather than cursing them, they should exercise prudence in their financial dealings and avoid cursing the children.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>11", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "11", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "How did Paul use the case of Onesimus to emphasize the concept of forgiveness.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Paul believed that Philemon's slave, Onssimus, had run away, with goods stolen from his master and later sought refuge in Rome where he met Paul in prison. Apostle Paul wrote a letter seeking forgiveness for his runaway Slavs to Philemon. Since Paul converted Philemon, he would have expected him to oblige his request and abide by gmhis will, but because of his conviction it would be wrong to assume such authority over his spiritual son, (Philemon). He rather preferred to write him not as a command but with a spirit of love and persuasion, on behalf of Onesimus who had become his (Paul's) own son in Christ. His letter was necessary since Onesimus had become a born-again Christian. Paul taught it wise to send Onesimus back to Philemon with love. Ordinarily he would have liked to retain Onesimus as his assistant, but he rather opted to send him to his master. Since it was Paul's strong conviction that Onesimus departure from Philemon was for his moral and spiritual growth, now that forgiveness is in place there would be permanent reconciliation between master and slave.   Onesimus would now be accepted back as a Christian brother not as slave. Paul believed that if Philemon still regarded him as a true Christian partner and brother, he should extend a similar regard to Onesimus and accepted his claim to undertake all outstanding bills that Onesimus must have owed him, with the view to paying them. Paul believed that if his plea to Philemon for Onesimus should succeed he would to spiritually refreshed.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Why did Peter advice Christians to rejoice despite the trials they may be going through?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Since the hope of glory that awaits the Christians was enormous because of the redirection form the death of Jesus. Paul exhorts them to rejoice. He advjced them not to lay claim to the present life which might be limited by trials and persecution, since such trials are more rest of their faith.   According to him, they should have confidence in the fact that Jesus himself passed through greater suffering than they were passing through.  Their suffering will make them reap the great reward of salvation when Jesus is revealed to them. For them to gain insight of this hope (of salvation) they should live holy lives, having the knowledge that God, the impartial judge, would reward their suffering.   He eqy state that if they are cursed for the sake of Christ. They shall count themselves blessed since they are not suffering as murderers , thieves or for any wrong-doing, they should glorify God for their tribulation. According to Paul, if judgment unbelievers would be unbearable.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2003>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2003", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "State two virtues which Christians should manifest to show their joy.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Christians should desist from the nature of the men of this world. They should remain sober expectant of the salvation and glory that would be theirs whem Jesus shall be revealed to them. Total submission and reverence to God should guard them jealously since God is an important judge. They should be steadfast in their faith, and refuse to be shaken by the cares of this world and the machination of the enemy, giving praises God in bad times and in the season of joy should always be part of their lives.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Give an account of the capture of Jericho", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Joshua strictly followed the grand plan of God for the capture and conquest of Jericho. The arrangement started with a procession led by warriors, followed by seven priests with seven trumpets, while another group of priests formed the rear guard bearing the ark of the Lord, and simultaneously the trumpets blew continually as the procession marched around the city of Jericho once a day for six days. After each march, they came into the camp and spent the night there. There, they were warned not to shout until Joshua gave them the order to shout. On the seventh day, they rose early and marched around the city in the same manner seven times. At the seventh time, when the priest had blown the trumpet, Joshua commanded the people to shout, adding that the Lord had given them the city.The people did as instructed and the walls of Jericho fell down flat. The people straight into the city and took it.    Joshua instructed the people to destroy the city with fire and only Rahab, the harlot who spared two spies, together with her household, were not destroyed. All precious stones, gold, silver and bronze were kept in the Lord's treasury.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "What three lessons can be drawn from the incident?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Obedience is key to success - Joshua obeyed God's command on the grand plan to capture Jericho and he succeeded  - The essence of faith is also pointed out as Joshua's faith in God made him follow through with God's plan for His people  - The story shows the sovereignty of God over all things. God has the power and authority to do all things  - God's defence for His people is also seen as God gave the city to the people especially given the fact that Joshua trusted in Him.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "What circumstances led to the rejection of Saul as King over Israel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Saul's disobedience to God was the root cause of his rejection as King over Israel. God instructed Samuel to tell Saul to destroy Amalek totally, without leaving anyone or animal behind because the Amalekites obstructed the Israelites when they came out of Egypt. Saul carried out this assignment but not in accordance with the exact instructions he was given.  Saul spared Agag, King of Amalek's life and brought some choice animals for himself which he told Samuel, when the latter found out, that the people had brought the animals for the sake of offering sacrifices unto God. This act of blame shifting and lack of repentance by Saul instigated Samuel to denounce him as King over Israel. Saul held the garment of Samuel while the latter turned to leave his presence, and Samuel's garment got torn. Samuel thereupon, declared that as Saul had torn his robe, the Lord had torn the Kingdom of Israel from him and had given it to his neighbour.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Mention three lessons that can be learnt from this rejection", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Disobedience leads to suffering and condemnation from God. Saul was not only rejected as King, he was also tormented by evil spirit and made mentally unstable.  - Greed is disastrous - Saul was moved by greed as reserved precious animals for himself and saved Agag's life.  - God is omniscient, man cannot do anything in secret without His knowledge.  - Obedience is better than sacrifice - what God desires his our obedience and faithfulness not the offering of mere sacrifices  - We should learn to accept responsibility for our wrong doings and beg for forgiveness instead of blame shifting like Saul did.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "How did Josiah react to the contents of the Book of the Law found in the house of the Lord by Hilkiah?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "King Josiah, eight years old when he began to reign as King over Israel, showed keen interest in the will and ways of God. In reparation of the temple, the book of law was discovered by Hilkiah, the high priest. Josiah immediately sent Hilkiah, Shaphan, the secretary and others to investigate the root of this discovery and its implications from the prophetess, Huldah. The book of law's content relates to the message of the Lord to bring destruction upon Judah for all atrocities committed.  Josiah was humbled by the content of the book of law and summoned all the elders of Israel to whom he read the contents of the book to as well. He made a covenant to walk with the Lord and keep His commandments, testimonies and statutes with all his heart and with all his soul. And upon this proclamation vigorous religious cleansing and reforms were carried out in Israel by King Josiah.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "State any four of Josiah's reforms", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He ordered the priests to bring out all the vessels made for Baal and Asherah and burn them  - He abolished witchcraft, sorcery, soothsaying, divination and their idols  - He broke down the houses of the male cult prostitutes where all forms of sexual deceitfulness in the name of appeasing the god of fertility were done  - He restored the feast of Passover and commanded the people to keep it as it is written in the book of covenant  - He carried out religious reforms up to the northern kingdom- destroy their shrines at the high places in the city of Samaria.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "Explain how Ezekiel was commissioned as a prophet", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Ezekiel saw the glory of God in a vision shown to him, he was overwhelmed and he fell upon his face. Then a voice came to him saying: \"Son of man, stand upon your feet, and I will speak with you\". The spirit of the Lord came upon Ezekiel as a way of prophetic commissioning. The Lord warned him that the people of Israel were stubborn and rebellious but he should not be afraid of either their outward appearance or attitude.  God commanded Ezekiel to open his mouth and eat what He would give him. When he looked, it was a written scroll upon which were words of lamentation, mourning and woe. When Ezekiel ate it, it was as sweet as honey in his mouth. God in fully preparing Ezekiel for the prophetic mission hardened his forehead so that the people may fear him and at least give him some respect and listen to God's message through him.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Identify two lessons that can be derived from his experiences.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- God calls people and prepares them by commissioning them for service  - God prepares people He sends on prophetic and missionary activities  - God's message must be delivered regardless of all forms of opposition or confrontation on the way, by people or societal hindrances  - God's word is sweet and delightful -the symbolism of the scroll ate by Ezekiel typifies this.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Outline the Lukan account of the birth of Jesus", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Luke's account of the birth of Jesus is as follows:  - Angel Gabriel was sent to a city in Galilee named Nazareth. The angel informed Mary Virgin that she had been favoured and although she was surprised, the angel said she would conceive in her womb and bear a son and the child would be named Jesus. The child would be great and would be called the son of the most High; and the Lord God would give him the throne of his father, David and He would reign over the house of Jacob forever.  - Mary queried the angel as she had no husband and the angel clarified that she was going to be conceived through the Holy Spirit and the power of God will overshadow her.  - Mary accepted this message accordingly and she became pregnant by the power of the Holy Spirit and close to the time of her delivery, Augustus Caesar declared a census in the Roman Empire and so Joseph and Mary had to travel to Bethlehem to be enrolled.  - In the course of their enrolment, Mary gave birth to Jesus and the baby was wrapped in swadling cloths and laid in a manger because there was no place for them in the inn.  - The angels of the Lord appeared to them and they were filled with fear but the angel disabused their fear and then the host of Heaven started rejoicing. The shepherds watching over their flock at night glorified God also for all they had witnessed.  - On the eighth day, the child was circumcised and named Jesus. He was brought to the temple for purification in the temple in Jerusalem, whereupon Simeon saw Him and blessed His parents. Anna, a prophetess also gave thanks to God for the birth of the saviour and spoke of him to all those expecting the redemption of Israel.  - Mary and Joseph returned to Nazareth in Galilee after this ceremony and there, Jesus was brought up.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "What two lessons can be learnt from the circumstances of Jesus' birth?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The humble nature of one's birth does not hinder one's greatness in life  - Mary conceived through the power of God and the Holy Spirit, this signifies the sovereignty of God over all things including the unimaginable  - We should show regard for constituted authorities and exhibit good citizenship qualities like Mary and Joseph did, enrolling to be countered in the process of which Jesus was born.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>6>a>i>A", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "A", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Discuss Jesus' sermon on the mount under the following headings:    Adultery", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Adultery: Jesus modified the Mosaic law that forbade adultery by saying that any one who looks at a woman lustfully has already committed adultery with her in his heart. He said that if one's right eye would cause one to sin, it should be plucked out as it is better to lose one member than for the whole body to be lost in hell and even if one's right hand would cause one to sin, one should cut if off.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>6>a>i>B", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "B", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Discuss Jesus' sermon on the mount under the following headings: divorce", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Divorce: The law was that whoever divorces his wife should give her a certificate of divorce. However, Jesus said, \"...anybody who divorces his wife, except for unchastity, immorality or adultery makes her an adulteress; and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery\".", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>6>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Discuss Jesus' Sermon on the Mount on: Neighbours and enemies", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus taught that we should seek the welfare of our enemies and pray for them as well. Hatred should not be tolerated as those who practise love are sons of God. If we love only those who love us, we have no reward and if we greet only our brothers and friends, we are still like the unbelievers. We should rather strive for perfection just like our heavenly father.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Mention two lessons that can be derived from Jesus' teaching on adultery and divorce", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Lust must be avoided essentially, this is the basis of Jesus teaching on adultery.  - Divorce should ordinarily not take place in a marriage. Therefore, unchastity must be avoided in marriage.  - Any thing that want to obstruct our entry into God's kingdom must be avoided at all cost", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "How did Jesus describe himself as the 'Door' and the 'Good Shepherd'?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "'He who does not enter the sheepfold by the door but climbs in by another way is a thief and a robber, but he who enters by the door is the shepherd of the sheep' - Jesus said. Since the gate remains open, the sheep hear his voice and he calls his own sheep by name and leads them out for pastures. The sheep will not follow a stranger, because they do not know his voice. Jesus identified that all those who came before him were thieves and robbers, but the sheep did not listen to them. He said He is the door and if anyone enters by Him, he will be saved, and will go in and out and find pasture.   Again, Jesus outlined the qualities of a good shepherd and said if he was the good shepherd for he would lay down his life for the sheep in his own accord and would take it back.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "In what two ways is this teaching relevant to Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jesus as the door means He is the only way to salvation   - Jesus as the shepherd indicates His love and compassion for mankind as He provides care and security for mankind as the shepherd does to his sheep.  - By saying that He laid down His life, Jesus was referring to His death on the cross - sacrifice made for the redemption of mankind from sin.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Trace the circumstances that led to the death of Ananias and Sapphira", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the communal spirit in the early church, where everyone sold their properties and contributed the proceeds to the church was widely encouraged without anyone being forced to comply since it was by free will and a sense of obligation and commitment to the church's welfare and progress.  However, Ananias and Sapphira in order to receive similar accolades received by those who had complied with this obligation, also sold their own property but rather than bring the whole proceeds, they kept back some and brought part of it to the church.  Peter rebuked them sharply for this act of dishonesty, saying they have not lied to men but God. Ananias immediately fell down and died after receiving this rebuke and he was buried right away.Sapphira, Ananias' wife also lied just as her husband did. She was also rebuked and died also.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Indicate two lessons that could he drawn from this incident", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Dishonesty and deceitfulness against God can lead to death. The story of Ananias and Sapphira clearly points at this.  - Honesty is key to progress and fulfilment of blessing. Act of charity should not be done for self-appraisal.  - No man can deceive God, Ananias and Sapphira thought they could successfully do this and they paid severely for it.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What was Paul's advice on the right attitude to Civil Authority?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "St. Paul in his epistle to the Romans, admonished christians to be regard the constituted authorities as every authority is of God created for maintenance of orderliness on Earth. Hence, anyone who resists the civil authorities resist God and as such will face the wrath and judgement of God.  People should perceive the constituted authorities as terror to Godly conducts and for conscience purposes, they should be subject to those in positions of authority.  St. Paul advised christians to pay their taxes, give honour to whom it is due, and respect to whom respect is due. Therefore, Christians are expected to be law-abiding as well as showing right attitude to governance of their community by discharging their responsibilities.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "State three ways in which a Christian can demonstrate the qualities of a good citizen", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Through the payment of taxes, rates, levies and all other compulsory and social welfare bills  - By being law-abiding and showing compliance attitude to rules thereby encouraging general moral conducts  - By shunning membership of secret cults and Anti-social groups  - By actively contributing to activities of social advancement and humanitarian attitude.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Give an account of Paul's teaching on dignity of labour in Thessalonians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "St. Paul warned against laziness and idleness by advising christians to work hard and diligently avoiding dependency upon others. Paul supported his teaching by using an example of himself while he was among them, he did not depend on the church for his sustenance, as he worked diligently to earn a livelihood. Even though he could have solely depended on the church being an evangelist.  St. Paul emphasized the statement that  'if anyone will not work, let him not eat.'  This is basically to encourage such lazy person to be hard working. Upon this, he condemned the acts of those idle among them in Thessalonia and advised them to engage in productive activities and live a decent life.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "In what three ways does the church uphold the teaching today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Churches today now create empowerment programmes and opportunities for their members - e.g. awarding contracts of construction of the church to some them.  - Establishment of schools, hospitals and vocational trainings and workshops.  - Preaching against idleness and indecent living.  - Creating employment opportunities for its members through an existing networking relationship.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Highlight James' message on effective prayer", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "St. James encouraged Christians to pray believing that God will answer their prayers and no matter the temptation and trials, they should be steadfast in faith and prayer. To James, anyone who doubts, may likely not receive answers to their prayers. 'For he who doubts is like a wave of the sea that is driven and tossed by the wind.' Again, christians must not ask wrongly. They must pray according to the will of God and with right motive. For this reason, they should ask for God's wisdom to direct them in the right thing to ask God.  St. James added that christians must confess their sins before God and take active steps towards forsaking their sins so that God can hear their prayers, for the prayer of the sinner is an abomination before God and the prayer of the righteous answers fervently.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Identify any three factors that can hinder prayer", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Unrighteousness - the prayer of the sinner is like an abomination before God  - Lack of faith in God that the prayer will be answered  - Asking wrongly, God knows what is best for us as His children  - Unforgiving spirit on the part of the person praying.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2004>12", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2004", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "12", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "How did James prove that 'faith' apart from work, is dead'?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to St. James, Christians must combine their faith their work, for faith without work is in itself dead. He asked the question that, will anyone who needs food and clothing come before his fellow christian for help and instead of giving him what he needed, and the Christian say  'Go in peace; be warmed and filled' . To St. James, such expression of faith without any active work or effort towards solving the problem at hand is of no use.  St. James used the examples of Abraham and Rahab respectively to buttress his point. Abraham was justified by his work when he not only expressed faith in God but actually offered Isaac as a sacrifice to God on the altar. This was reckoned to Abraham as righteousness. Similarly, Rahab, the harlot, was justified by her work when she received and protected the messengers sent to spy Jericho.  James concluded by saying that just as the physical body without spirit is dead, so also faith without work is dead.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DEBORAH", "question": "Give an account of the war between the Israelites and the Canaanites during the time of Deborah", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "During the reign of Deborah as a Judge in Israel, Israel was under the oppression of King Jabin of Canaan. Israel consulted Deborah and she invited Barak, a warrior in Israel informing him that he was the one God was going to use to liberate Israel from Jabin's oppression. Deborah accompanied Barak to the battlefield as Barak asked that she did.   God gave victory to Israel and brought Sisera, Jabin's Army Commander to shame as he ran in escape for his life, seeing as his chariots had been killed. Sisera was killed by Jael, a woman under whose shield he ran into. Thereupon, Israel was liberated from the oppressive rule of Jabin.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DEBORAH", "question": "In what three ways can Christians benefit from the leadership qualities displayed by Deborah?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Gender difference is not in any way a limitation to leadership. The exceptional leadership quality of Deborah nails this point to a standstill  - Christians must prioritise honesty, integrity, and uprightness - these were distinctive leadership qualities of Deborah  - Courage and sound intelligence is required for successful leadership.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Describe five signs given to Saul by Samuel as a proof that the Lord had anointed him King of Israel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Saul, the son of Kish met Samuel when he (Saul) went out with a servant to look for his father's ass. Samuel informed him that the Lord had apointed him as King over Israel and the following were the confrimation signs;  - Saul would meet two men by Rachael's tomb in Benjamin's territory  - The two men would inform him that his father's ass has been found and that his father was anxious to see him  - Saul would meet three men at the Oak of Tabor, on their way to Bethel to worship  - One of them carrying three kids, another carrying three loaves of bread and another a skin of wine. They would greet and give him two loaves of bread  - He would afterwards, meet a band of prophets coming down from the high place with musical instruments, the spirit of the Lord would come mightily upon him and he would prophesy with them and be transformed.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "What two moral qualities can be derived from this episode?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- God usually give signs delibratively to show that He is at work and will guide his people until his promise for them is fulfilled.  - True prophecy will be fulfilled despite all odds  - God authorizes His people and He is interested in their leadership.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>3>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Discuss the circumstances that led to the healing of Naaman", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Naaman, the army commander of Syria went to Elisha, the prophet to be cured of his leprosy. Elisha sent his servant to inform Naaman to go bath seven times in the River of Jordan and he would be well. Naaman was annoyed and wondered whether the rivers in Syria weren't even better off than the River Jordan. However, Naaman's servants persuaded him to obey and as he did as instructed by Elisha, he was healed immediately.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>3>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "What incident followed this reaction?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After Naaman was healed, in the spirit of gratitude brought some gifts to Elisha. Elisha refused to accept these gifts. Naaman then left with his left, he was later followed thereafter by Gehazi, Naaman's servant, who said that Elisha has asked for some of the gifts because he had to entertain some visitors.  Naaman gave him two talents of silver in two bags with two festal garments. Gehazi hid these gifts and denied going after Naaman or receiving any gifts from him. For this act of dishonesty, Elisha cursed Naaman's leprosy upon Gehazi and his generations yet unborn.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Identify two virtues that can be learnt from the entire episode", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The salvation of God is free - Elisha's rejection of Naaman's gifts demonstrates this as the praise and appreciation belongs tp God and not the man of God.  - Greed and dishonesty can ruin a man's life and even a generation of children yet unborn.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>4>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "Mention the names of Hosea's three children", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The children of Hosea are - Not Pitied (Lo Ruhamah), Not My People (Lo-Ammi), and Jezreel.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>4>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "Explain the meaning of each of the names", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The first son, Jezreel symbolizes God's impending punishment for the house of Jehu for the blood of Jezreel and His intention to put an end to the kingdom of Israel.  \"Not Pitied\" means that the Lord would no longer love or pity the house of Israel because of their sins.  \"Not My People\" means that the people of Israel were no longer to be regarded as God's people and God would no longer be their God.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "In what three ways are names significant in your society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The prevailing circumstances of the day usually influence the naming of a child  - Names signify the position and title held by one's parents at one's birth  - Names bear consequences and are reflective of the implications of certain activities that had been done in the past. e.g of one's ancestors.  - Names signify religious identity as well.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MATTHEW 4: 18-25; 8: 18-22; 9:9-13 ;", "question": "Give Matthew's account of the call of the first four disciples of Jesus", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to Matthew's account, while Jesus was walking by the sea of Galilee, He saw two brothers, Simon Peter and Andrew, casting a net into the sea, and He said to them, \"follow me, and I will make you fishers of men.\"  Immediately, they left their nets and followed him. Going a little further, Jesus saw the sons of Zebedee, James and John mending their nets with their father in the boat. He called them and they followed him.  As Jesus passed on after healing the paralytic man, he saw a man called Matthew sitting at the tax office and He said to him,  \"follow me,\"  and Matthew rose and followed Him.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "State three reasons why Jesus required disciples", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Continuation and Sustenance of His earthly ministry - the disciples were called to discharge the duties even after Christ's ascension into Heaven.  - Jesus needed disciples to widely spread the gospel and the christian mission all across  - Jesus needed disciples as witnesses to the word of God and His redemptive powers.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Narrate the parable of Lazarus and the Richman", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "At the gate of a certain rich man clothed in purple and fine linen and who feasted every day, was Lazarus, a poor man, full of sores -which dogs lick regularly- and desiring to be fed with whatever fell from the rich man's table. Lazarus later died and was carried by the angels to Abraham's bossom. The rich man also died, but was taken to hell where he remained in perpetual torment. When he lifted up his eyes, he saw Abraham and Lazarus afar off and called out that Lazarus dip the end of his finger in water and cool his tongue as he was in anguish in the flame.  Abraham reminded the rich man of how he lived a good life on earth and how Lazarus experienced the opposite and unfortunately, there is a big demarcation between the hell and heaven and no one could cross this over to help him. The rich man pleaded that Abraham sends someone to preach repentance to his brothers on earth but Abraham to him that they should rather listen to the prophets of God on earth and if they do not listen to Moses and the prophets, there is no possibility that they will be convinced by someone who raises from the dead to preach to them.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "State three ways by which Christians can use their wealth for the benefit of the society", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- By extending charitable attitudes and outreaches to the poor and less privileged people  - By initiating and supporting humanitarian projects to combat hunger and poverty in the society  - By donating cheerfully to the building of the church and other similar projects.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Give an account of the trial of Jesus before Pilate", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus was arraigned before Pilate after His trial by the Sanhedrin. Pilate asked whether the allegation brought against Him was true, as being the King of the Jews but Jesus gave no response or defence to this allegation. Now, at the feast of over, since it was customary that a prisoner be released, Pilate asked the people whether they wanted Jesus or Barabbas, a chronic criminal released.The people cried that Barabbas be released and that Jesus be crucified.   Although, Pilate's wife had warned him not to have anything to do with the matter, and Pilate washed his hands publicy implying his innocence of Jesus' blood and crucification, Pilate delivered Jesus to be crucified. The soldiers then took Jesus away, stripped off His clothes and wore Him a Crown of thorns. They mocked Him saying,  \"Hail, king of the Jews.\"  They then led Him to be crucified.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "In what two ways are people denied justice in your society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Falsification of evidence and accusations  - Through prevention of justice and bribery  - Persistent and deliberate delay of justice.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>8>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "\"Saul, Saul, why do you persecute me?\" Describe the circumstances that led to this question", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Saul had collected a letter of introduction to the synagogue in Damascus in a bid to arrest christians in the city and bring them back to Jerusalem for persecution. However, as he approached Damascus, a bright light from heaven struck him, he fell down and he heard voice \"Saul, Saul, why do you persecute me?\". Saul asked who the speaker was and the voice replied \"I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting. Rise and enter the city and you would be told what to do.\"", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>8>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Outline the events that took place after the quotation in 8(a)(i) up to the baptism of Saul", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The companions of Saul were too dazed to talk or act. Saul discovered he was now blind and he was helped into Damascus. He was there for three days without food or water. Meanwhile, the Lord spoke to Ananias in a vision to go to the house Judas and ask for Saul of Tarsus. Although Ananias hesitated by complaining to God about the news he had heard about Saul's relentless persecution of Christians, the Lord insisted that Ananias go pray for Saul to regain his sight for Saul has been chosen as an instrument for the proclamation of the gospel.  Ananias did as the Lord instructed and Saul regained his sight - some scales fell off from his eyes. Saul was then converted and baptized.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what two ways did this experience affect Saul's life?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Saul's life and mission were transformed from persecution of Christians to defence of Christianity and preaching of the gospel.  - Saul became a believer of the word of God, he witnessed the sovereignty of God and became advocate of Christ, purged of his ignorance.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What is Paul's advice in his epistle to the Romans, on the use of individuals talents?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The crux of St. Paul's teaching on the use of individuals talents is that those gifts and talents be used to the glory of God. He gave analogy that as the different parts of the body work for a collective goal and interest or welfare of one body, so also do our individual talents in the one body of Christ.  And so despite the diversity of these talents, they must be used for the benefit of the community and the church as well. Hence, those who teach should do so faithfully and effectively, those who contribute should do so wilfully and cheerfully with the requisite zeal and mercy all for the benefit of the church.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Identify three functions of spiritual gifts", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Promotion of cordial relationship among Christians in the community of faith  - They are instrumental for the betterment of the entire church community  - They are given to the church for the purpose of glorifying God  - They signify unity in diversity of the church.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Why, according to Paul, should believers prepare for the second coming of the Lord?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The second coming of Jesus Christ will be sudden, much more like the appearance of thieves at night - this is why St. Paul advised that Christians be prepared for His second coming. Additionally, since the second coming of Christ will not happen except the son of lawlessness and deceit is revealed, Christians need to be watchful and sober so that they are not misled by those parading themselves around as the main Christ before the Messiah Himself appears.   And seeing as the hope of our salvation is the resurrection and ascension of Christ Jesus, Christians are to be prepared as the Lord Jesus would save us from destruction when he appears. Summarily, Christians are brace up and encourage one another in the spirit of preparedness for the second coming of Christ.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "State two reasons why this second coming is significant", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The second coming of Christ is significant, being the period of God's intervention into the affairs of the world  - It will be a day of punishment for the wrongdoers and salvation and glory for the righteous people who have not been misled.  - The Lord will destroy all elemental spirits and negative spiritual forces of the earth on that day.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "What advice did Paul give in his epistle to the Colossians, about family life?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "St. Paul's advice was premised on two focal points - love and obedience - as the strongest pillars for upholding and sustaining a good family life. Upon this therefore, wives are to submit themselves respectfully to their husbands while the husbands love their wives in return. The children should respect their parents in all ways while the fathers should not provoke their children, lest they become discouraged. Also, slaves are to obey their earthly masters diligently and doing this with the fear of God without hypocrisy of trying to please God.   Compliance to all these, will make for a good interpersonal relationship in the family.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "In what three ways can the family be firmly established?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Through expression of love and respect for one another  - Through obedience of wives to their husbands and children to their parents  - Through effective communication between the children and their parents  - Through prayer in unity.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Outline Peter's instructions on good citizenship", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "St. Peter emphasized Christians must subject themselves to the constituted authorities - respecting the Governors and their institutions which have been created to punish wrong doings and praise Godly actions- by so doing, Christians will put to silence the ignorance of the foolish men.  In the same vein, christians were advised not use their freedom as pretext for evil, they should honour all men, love the brotherhood and live as servants of God having the fear of God in their minds.  By extension therefore, St Peter advice centers on the need for Christians to support the civil authorities and discharge responsibilities required of them as citizens.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2005>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2005", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "In what three ways can Christians act as good citizens today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Through the regular payment of taxes, rates and levies  - Through the act of patriotism and loyalty to one's country  - Through devotion of support to civil society organizations advocating humanitarian and true charitable causes.  - Through compliance to rules and regulations èven to as little as traffic light regulations, environmental sanitation and cleanliness.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL", "question": "Explain how Eli failed as a parent.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen is 1st Samuel 2.    Eli had two sons Hophni and Phinehas, they were young men who treated God's offereing and sacrifices disrespectfully. They took part of the best parts of the offering for themselves which was supposed to be sacrificed to God, they had no respect and regard for God. Eli was a failed parent because after he heard of all the evil his sons did, he only rebuked their acts and did not do anything to stop the unholy act. His sons  continued to do evil and also giving false prophecies.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL", "question": "In what six ways did Israel suffer as a result of Eli parental responsibility", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Samuel 7.  -  Philistines engaged the Isreal to war  -  Three thousand Isrealites lost their lives in that war.  -  Israel was defeated in the was against the Philistines.  -  Hophni and Phinehas the sons of Eli were killed in the war.  - The Philistines Captured the Ark of the Lord duriing the war  -  Eli's Daughter Inlaw, Phinehas wife heard of the news, had a shock, was delivered the baby prematurely and died..   - Those who survived the war ran away.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>1>c", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "c", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL", "question": "State three lessons that can be derived from the attitude of Eli", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in  1st Samuel 2, 1st Samuel 3 and 1st Samuel 7.    - Parents should not only be cautious of how they impact and make changes in the society, lives or organisations, they should also do same in their homes by raising God fearing Children.  - We should learn to take God warnings and laws very seriously.  -  For every disobedience to Gods laws there is always a punishment.  -  Parent should raise their Children in the way of the Lord.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "What circumstances led to the dismisal of Gehazi?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Kings 5    Elisha healed Naaman by telling him to go wash himself at Jordan seven times for his healing to be perfect, without collecting a charge from him. Elisha refused the gifts offered to him by Naaman. But Gehazi went behind his Master (Elisha), to meet with Naaman and lied to him that some visitors came to his master (Elisha) unexpectedly, so he requested for a talent of silver and two festal garments. Naaman asked that he accepts two talents which his servant carried for Gehazi. Gehazi collected the gifts andd secretly sent Naaman's servants away.    When Elisha asked where he had gone, he lied and denied going anywhere. Elisha cursed Gehazi that Naamans leprosy be transfered to him and his generation. From that minute Gehazi left the presence of Elisha a leper.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "State three lessons that can be learnt from Gehazi's conduct.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Kings 5.    - The sin of one person can affect multitudes and generations.  -  It is not good to seek and covet what is not yours.  - It is a sin to lie.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>3>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Explain how Nehemiah received the news about the state of affairs in Jerusalem", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Nehemiah 1 : 5 - 11.    Nehemiah met with Hanani, a man from Judah in Susa the capital of Persian empire. Nehemiah asked how the Jews were doing. Hanani told Nehemiah that the Jews where encountering lots of trouble and that the walls of Jerusalem and the gates have been destroyed. When Nehemiah heard this he was worried so he prayed and fasted for days.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>3>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Relate Nehemiah's prayer when he received the news", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Nehemiah 1 : 5 - 11.    Nehemiah asked for forgiveness on behalf of himself and his fathers, for they have not kept the commandments as commanded by Moses. He then asked God to remember his word that if they were unfaithful that he will scatter and restore them to the place he has chosen for them, if they repent and keep his commandments. He later prayed that God be merciful and help them succeed.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Identify three virtues that can be learnt from Nehemiah's reaction", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen as Nehemiah 1 : 5 - 11.    -  It is good fone to be prayerful in order to be successful.  -  We should also learn to pray for our country.  -  We should have faith in God and trust in his words  -  We should learn to represent our country well even in hard hard time, we should be patriots.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "Outline Jeremiah's Message about the sins of Judah", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Jeremiah 1.    According to Jeremiah the people of Judah were sinful and unfaithful to God. They abandoned God that save them from the hands of the Egyptians and brought them out of slavery and bondage, the God that led them through the wilderness and provided for all their needs till they got to the place he has provided for them.    The rulers of the land went against God prophesied through false Gods like Baal.    The people went about digging cisterns which could not hold water and made sinful relationships with other nations and forsaking God. Jeremiah also stated that the fear of God was not in the people anymore as they worshipped other gods upon every high hills and green trees.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "State two consequence of such sinfulness", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Jeremiah 1.    -  There was destruction on Israel by other nation.  -  There was no water for farming and livestock.  -   God will not accept their offerings.  -  There will be famine, pestilence will attack the land and they will be attacked by the sword.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "What circumstances led to Jesus' declaration of himself as the \"Bread of life\"?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 6    After feeding 5,000 people Jesus was on a boat going to the other side of the sea. Then some group of people asked Jesus a question and through this question Jesus understood that were seeking his face not because of his miracles, teachings or signs and wonders but  they all followed him because of food. So he admonished them not to labour for the physical loaf and temporary satisfaction they derive from it but they should labour for eternal life. The people asked Jesus to prove that he truly is the Messiah and by doing that they will believe him as the true  Son of God. Jesus then reminded them that it was not Moses that gave their fathers Manna from heaven but God himself did. Their fathers believed was God sent. Jesus gave them assurance that God can give them the bread that leads to eternal life. The people were happy after hearing this and demanded that Jesus gives them a life giving bread always.    It was at this point that Jesus told them , \"I am the bread of life, he who comes to me shall not hunger, and he who believes in me shall not hunger again.\"", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Identify three moral lessons in this story.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 6    -  Christians should not only look out for signs and wonder, they should not be miracle seekers alone.  -  Man should not live by bread alone but by the word of God.  -  Christians should rely on Jesus.  -  We should be careful of how we believe in people because of the material things they have to offer.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>6>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MATTHEW 4: 18-25; 8: 18-22; 9:9-13 ;", "question": "Relate Jesus' sermon on the mount under the following heads    Worldly possession", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 6 : 16.    Jesus in his sermon on the Mount admonished his followers not to lay their treasures on earthly things, rather they should lay their treasures in heaven where it will be safe, because where your treasure is, there will your heart be. No one can serve two masters at a time because he would have to hate one and love the other one, or he will be respectful and devoted to one but despise the other. You cant serve God and Mammon.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>6>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MATTHEW 4: 18-25; 8: 18-22; 9:9-13 ;", "question": "Relate Jesus' sermon on the mount under the following heads    Anxiety", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 6 : 16 - end.    Jesus in his teachings also thought that people should not be anxious over life, they shouldn't be a anxious over what to eat, what to wear, drink and their body. According to Jesus life is more than food and other luxuries. Jesus said that even the birds of the air do not sow, neither do they reap but God provides and feeds them, humans are more valuable than the birds.   Jesus then asked if anyone can add to their life by being anxious. He was wondering why they should be anxious about material things. The lilies also do not toil nor spin but they are adorned than King solomon in his days. He said, God who clothes the grass will clothe them, Men of little faith. Then Jesus drew a conclusion that people should seek first the Kingdom of God and His righteousness and every other thing shall be added.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MATTHEW 4: 18-25; 8: 18-22; 9:9-13 ;", "question": "What three lessons can be learnt from this teaching?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 6 : 16 - end    - Christians should seek the Kingdom of God first.  - God is our great provider.  - We should not be worried about tomorrow God will take absolute control.  - We should serve God alone and not let anything distract us", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Explain the Lukan account of the resurrection", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 24.    The dawn of the first day, a woman went to the tomb with spices. When she got to the tomb , she and the spices realized that the stone at the tomb has been rolled away from the entrance of the tomb. So she went inside with the spice and could not find the body of Christ, the two men who stood there were scared. They then asked why they were looking for someone who was alive among the dead, then they were reminded what Jesus said in Galilee when he was alive that; The son of man will be delivered into the hands of sinful men and be crucified, and on the third day, will rise again. She remembered the words of Christ and went to tell the apostles that and they did not believe here", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "State three lessons that can be derived from this episode", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 24.    - Jesus conquered death with his resurrection so also all believers will overcome death.  - The day of the resurrection was on a sunday.  - The prophesy of Jesus must surely come to pass.  - The faith Christianity is based on the resurrection of Christ.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Trace the events that led to the election of Mathias as one of the Twelve.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Act 1 : 12 - end    Peter in a meeting with the early church explained to the people why they need to replace Judas after he betrayed Jesus and following his suicide attempt.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Highlight three guidelines that should be borne in mind while conducting election", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Act 1 : 12 - end    - The election must be free and fair  - People to be elected should be christians and faithful  - Those that will be elected should be given considerations on theb character of person before being elected", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Outline the features of the New Life in Christ as stated by Paul in Colossians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Colossians 3    Paul told the Christians in Colossians to put their minds to things above and depart from all sinful practice. They should put on new nature, show love, be kind, be compassionate, care for the needy and be patient. They should forgive one another, live in peace and allow the peace in Christ Jesus to to guide their hearts and be thankful.    Christians should also not forget to allow Gods word dwell in their heart always, they should abide richly by it, teach it to others. They are also advised to sing hymns, spiritual songs and also sing psalms. They should know that whatever is done in words and deeds should be done in the name of Jesus.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Identify three practices which can have a negative a negative effect in any Christian Community", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Colossians 3    -  Unforgiveness  -  Bearing false witness  - Immorality  -  Idolatory  -  Selfishness  - Pride  - Selfishness and Jealousy", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "How did Paul treat the problem of idleness among the Thessalonian Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 1 - 18    Paul got the news of how some Thessalonians refused to work on account of their imminence of the Parousa, so they became lazy and prevented others from working and also denied them of bread. Paul wrote against this in his letter and commanded the Thessalonian believers to stay away from any person among them that refused to work. Paul told them that he didn't defraud anyone but worked hard to earn his living. Despite the fact that he had the right to do so as a Preacher of the word to depend on them but he has chosen to live an exemplary life by working hard. Paul then instructed the people that whosoever choose not to work should not eat. He later encouraged the lazy Thessalonians to work hard to earn a living, after which he passed a judgement that anyone who refuses to work and obey what the letter has instructed should be isolated.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Give three reasons why Christians should engage in gainful employment", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 1 - 18.    - When Christians engage in gainful employment they become motivation and inspiration to people around them.  - As a gainful employed Christian you are able to help those that depend on you and yourself.  - When one is gainfully employed as a Christian it brings about happiness in service to God.  - Gainfully employed Christians are not easily tempted financially.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Explain James' concept of works in relation to faith.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In James teaching on faith and works, he told Christians to not only be the hearers of the word alone but also the doersJ ames in his teaching said that nody can claim to be a good Christian except he puts into practice what he has been taught as intrsucted by Jesus. He uses the analogy of someone who looks at his face in the mirror and after that turns away without further examination as one who is only the hearer and not the doer of the word.    James alo explained who the doer of the word is. He said a doer of the word is one who looks into the perfect word; law of Jesus Christ which is the law of liberty and perseverance with practice, they do not forget  easily but dwell and live by it which in the end grants them God's blessing.     According to James, a Christian practices true religion by reaching out to the needy, helping the widows and keeping oneself pure before the Lord.    James gave biblical instances to make further clarification on the concept of works in relation to faith by using Abraham as an example. Abraham obeyed God and was ready to sacrifice his son Isaac. It shows that his faith would have been stained if he hadn't taken the right step. James also used Rahab the harlot at Jericho who had faith in God and saved the lives of Gods servants from men of her Country who wanted to kill them. After all this James then said that faith without work is dead.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what three ways can Christians demonstrate their faith in their daily life?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Christians should obey the authority above them.  - They should participate in church activities.  - They should be a good citizen of their country.  - They should give alms and help the less priviledge.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "What did Peter teach on interpersonal relationship among Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in  1 Peter 5 : 1 - 11.    Peter taught about the roles and responsibilities of Christian leaders in the church.    He explained that the leaders of the Church should take care of their members with all their heart, doing so willingly and selflessly. According to Peter they should not get involved in their duties with the desire of getting gains that are of this world or by using a domineering attitude but they should live an exemplary life so that the members can emulate them.    He also advised that they should be the spiritual guide of young people.    Peter advised the young people to humble before their leaders because God humiliates the proud and lifts the humble. He also admonished them to see the elders as their spiritual models.     Lastly he then advised the elders to have faith and be patient, they should have it in mind that suffering is part of the calling of Christians which leads to eternal life", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2006>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2006", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "State two factors which may cause conflict in the society", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Corruption and Bribery.  - Selfish actions and pride.  - Lack of the spirit of unity.  - Backbiting   - Gossiping  - Tribalism and greed", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "Highlight the covenant promises which God made to Abraham", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The covenant promises between God and Abraham are:  - Promise to make Abraham great and a chosen nation.  - Making Abraham a blessing to all the people of the earth.  - The promise to possess the land the of Canaan.  - God promised to bless those who bless him.  - He promised him a son.  - God promised to be God to Abraham and his generation.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what three ways are these promises significant to Christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- By this process a new relationship between man and God was established using Abraham as a Model.  - Through the promise of God to Abraham Christians can confidently see themselves as children of God-      The beginning of new knowledge in Christianity was revealed.  - Christians now see Abraham as the father of prophets including Jesus when it comes to Christian Faith.  - As christians followed the traits of Abraham's type of faith it makes the a receiver of his type of blessing.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Describe the escape of the Israelites from Egypt", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the last plague which was the death of the Egyptians first sons, Aaron and Moses were urgently summoned by Pharaoh and were ordered to take the Isrealites and all they have. He said \" rise up and go forth fro among my people, both you and your people and you flocks and serve the Lord as you have said and bless me also.\"    Then the Israelites left Egypt after 430 years stay with about 600,000 men, and a mixed multitude including Jewelry of silver, gold clothing taken from the Egyptians, their kneading bowls and bones of Joseph for Burial in Canaan.     They jouneyed from Succoth on the memorial night of a vigil kept to the Lord. No provision was taken from Egypt,  they baked unleavened bread on their way. Though Moses was not afraid of war but did not lead them through the way of war like Philistines to prevent their being attacked so they don't regret and return and return to Egypt . But he took them round by the way of wilderness towards the sea.    They camped at Etham at the edge of the wilderness where the Lord led them with a pillar of cloud in the day and of fire in the night which did not depart from them to continue their journey. They also later encamped in Pihahmiroth, between Mitgol and the sea, in front of Baal - ziphon, as Pharaoh will want to pursue them. The Lord said that He would get glory over Pharaoh and the Egyptians shall know that He is the Lord.     Pharaoh on realising his losses for allowing the Israelites go, pursued the Israelites with his chariots and horsemen and came close to the Israelites. The Israelites were scared so they questioned the Moses why he had brought them out of Egypt to die in the wilderness. Moses told them to be still and assured them of the working power of God. God instructed them to keep moving forward and ordered Moses to stretch forth his rod and the sea parted and the Israelites crossed the sea walking on dry land while the sea formed a wall on both sides.    The Egyptians rushed in with their horses and chariots then the wheels got stuck in the mud. The Egyptians struggled to cross over to the other side before the tide returned but their efforts were in vain. The Lord fought for the Israelites against the Egyptians.    Jesus them ordered Moses to stretch forth his hands over the sea for it to return to normal. Then the water returned killing all the Egyptians and its chariots trapped in the middle of the sea. This made the Israelites believe and fear God and His servant Moses.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what two ways was this promises event significant to christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Nobody should claim supremacy over or claim to be equal with God nor take the glory that belong to God for themselves, all the glory must be to God.  - God has power over all creatures.  - It is the first part of the freedom from the Egyptians that brought about the establishment and of a new state and religion.  - God is  responsible for the appointment of leaders.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "How did David react to the assassination of Abner?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Samuel 3    A delegation of twenty men with Abner transfered their loyalty from the house of Saul to David's. He assured David to gather all Israel for a Covenant David for him to reign over Isreal.  After the plans have been sealed with David's soldiers, he sent Abner away to gather all Israel for the Covenant.     When the soldiers of David arrived with Joab from a raid. Joab was angry at hearing that Abner visited and thinking he had come to spy. He reproached David and later sent message to call back Abner from the Cisten or Sirah, without Davids knowledge.      At Hebron, Joab took Abner aside into the midst of the gate pretending to be discussing with him privately. There he striked him in the belly and he died for the blood of Asahel.     DAVIDS REACTION:     (i)      He fasted till sunset which pleased the people.  (ii)     David instructed that Joab and the people rend their clothes and wear sack cloth to mourn Abner.  (iii)    David Cursed Joab that ''may the guilt of Abner's murder fall upon Joab and all his father's house\".  (iv)    Though David genuiely morned Abner but he also mockingly asked why great soldiers as Abner should be killed in sudh manner.  (v)     He followed Ner to bury Abner at Heebron, he lifted up his voice and wept aloud with allm the people at the grave of Abner.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "Indicate two lessons that can be learnt from this incident", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Samuel 3     - We should learn to forgive our enemies as David forgave Abner with all his heart, for us to have peace and work together in  unity.  - On the side of Abner we should learn not to trust an old rival.  - Jaob failed to forgive Abner for killing his brother Asahel in the battle.  - Forgiveness is a must and we must learn to imbibe it as all the parties never forgave each other.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Explain how the faith of Shadrach, Meshach and Abednego was tested in  Babylon.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Daniel 3.    The King of Babylon, King Nebuchadnezzar made a golden image and assembled all the noble men and women of the land to come worship the image on the day of its dedication. He announced that all the Royal Musicals and everyone subjected to him were to bow and worship the image.     Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego were also part of his subjects. King Nebuchadenezzar added that anyone who refuses to bow and worship the image will be cast into burning fire.     The time came and as soon as the sound of music was heared by all the subject that were there and ready, they all bowed down and worshipped the image  but Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego the Jews refuse to bow and worship the image. The officials at Babylon known as the Chaldeans saw this and reported to King Nebuchadnezzer by alerting that the Jews have refused to bow and worship the image and have disobeyed his orders. The King was angry but he decided to give the Jews more time to bow down and worship the image or they will have to face the consequences. The Jews ( Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego) told King Nebuchadnezzar that they cannot give him any answer and will not bow down to worship the image, they concluded that the God they serve will deliver them. When the King heard this he was angry in his spirit and ordered the fire to be heated up seven time more, while his guards where asked to throw the three Jews Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego into it.  Immediately they did as the King had ordered. But the men that threw the three Jews into the furnace died as a result of the heat that caught up with them from the fiery furnace but Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego that were tied up with their clothes and thrown into the furnace were not burnt.    As the three Jews were thrown into the furnace the King was surprised that he saw four men in the fire contradicting the number of people thrown into the fire. Then  King Nebuchadnezzar said that the fourth person the furnace looked like the son of God, King Nebuchadnezzar came near the fire and called the three Jews out. They answered the King and Came out of the and to everyone's amazement they hard no burns on them. The King started the praising the God of the Jews that did not allow the Jews get burnt, he promoted the Jews and commanded that anyone who speaks against the God of the Jews will be cut into  pieces and the his house made a dung hill. Because there was no god that can deliver its people the way the God of the Jews delivers His own.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Give four examples of cultural practices which are contrary to the christian faith in your society", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Daniel 3.  - Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego showed the absolute faith they had in the God the served and were not moved by the King's threats.  - The way Shedrach, Meshach and Abednego were bold even when death was in front of them is a feature that most Christians should imbibe.  - The three Jews never groomed any form of doubts in their minds.  - The incident happened in Babylon and not in Israel which show how God is the God of all who believes in him and are ready to serve him with all their heart. God does not help a particular tribe or race neither is he the God of a particular country but the God of all.  - The occurrence between the Jews and  King Nebuchadnezzar in Babylon show that God is a God that can be trusted no matter the situation we find ourselves.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Give an account of Mary's encounter with Angel Gabriel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 1    The same Angel Gabriel that promised Zachariah the birth of his Son John after six months went to visit a virgin in Nazareth the name of the virgin is Mary, she was from Judah and was engaged to Joseph who was from the lineage of King David, Joseph was a carpenter.    When Angel Gabriel came visiting, he greeted her by calling her the favoured one and also told her that the Lord was with her. Mary didn't understand why she was greeted that way. The Angel told her not to be afraid that she will have a child and and his name will be called Jesus, the Son of the Most high God and that the Lord will give him the throne of his father David. Mary immediately asked the Angel how she was going to bear a child because she doesnt have a husband yet. The Angel explained that she is going to conceive by the Holy spirit that the Holy spirit will come upon her.     The Angel wanted to assure her that it was a message from God , the Angel told her that her Cousin Elizabeth has also conceived a son which is six months old in her old age as she was a barren woman. According to him nothing was impossible for God to do. Mary then replied the Angel that she wished the words and prophecy of God be fulfilled.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "State two significant points in Mary's reply to the Angel's announcement", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Bible Passage: Luke 1    -  Mary had fear on how she was going to relate the message to Joseph on their engagement which was to take place one year before their marriage.  - She also had fear as to how the Angel greeted and addressed her so she wondered what he strange greeting meant.  - Mary accepted in totality that since it is the Will of God she was open minded to it. This shows she is a true child of God.  - She was also amazed at how possible it is to conceive a child without a man as her husband. She had doubts after the Angel her of her cousin Elizabeth six month old pregnancy. But when she saw Elizabeth she was filled with excitement.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Describe the roles of Joseph of Arimathea and the woman in the burial of Jesus", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 19.    There was a man Joseph from the Jewish part of Arimathea and a rmember of the Jewish council, a very respected  member of the council, known as the Honourable Councillor. He was a rich man and good man and also a secret disciple of Jesus Christ.     Joseph of Arimethea asked Pilate to allow him take the body of Jesus, Pilate gave him permission so he came and took the body of Jesus.     Nicodemus also came with a mixture of aloes and myrrh that weighed a hundred pounds. They took Jesus and tied him in a wrapper of linens which has fragrant as the burial custom of the Jews approves. There was a the garden where there was also a tomb, a new tomb, so Joseph of Arimathea rolled away the stone at the tomb and Jesus was layed there.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "THEME FROM THE FOUR GOSPELS AND THE ACTS OF THE APOSTLES     In what three ways was Joseph's action significant", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 19.    (i)      The gospel of Jesus Christ was for all, it cut across both the poor and the rich, reasons why Joseph of Arimethea and Nicodemus were who were rich men sacrificed their time and money to Jesus a good burial.  (ii)      This shows that anyone who dies righteously should be given a befitting burial just as shown by Joseph of Arimethea at the burial of Jesus Christ.  (iii)      The death of Jesus fulfilled the prophecy in Isaiah about how the grave of Jesus was made with rich people present at his death.  (iv)     Christians should learn to love one another, sacrifice for one another and be there for one another. Joseph of Arimethea was an example because he gave his new tomb out for the burial of Jesus.  (v)     The action that Joseph of Arimethea took by burying Jesus immediately was in line with the Jewish Law which states that \" A man who was hanged should not remain on the tree all night\".  (vi)     It shows that as Christians we need to make sacrificial efforts to moving the gospel our Lord Jesus Chris forward Just as Joseph of Arimathea did.   (vii)    Jesus Christ in his time was hated by the Jews but many were so fond of him that they followed him till His death.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Narrate the event that portrayed Jesus as the \" Resurrection and the life\".", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 11.    Mary and Martha who were sisters to a friend of Jesus Christ whose name was Lazarus sent for Jesus that their brother Lazarus who lived in Bethany was ill. Jesus replied Mary and Martha that the illness of their brother his friend was not unto death. Jesus didn't go to Bethany till after four days that He had recieved the news. By the time he got to Bethany with His disciples, He met many of the Jews consoling  Mary and Martha on the death of their brother Lazarus.    Martha heard that Jesus had arrived and encountered Him by saying that their brother wouldn't have died if He had came when He got the news but she also had the believe that whatever Jesus asked from God will be granted. Jesus said to Martha that Her brother Lazarus will arise from the death again. Martha said to Jesus, \"I know He will rise again but in resurrection which is on the last day\". When she said this Jesus said to her ''I am the resurrection and the life, He who believes in me, though He dies shall live and whosoever lives and believes in me shall never die.\"      After that Martha confessed that she believed in Jesus as the son of God. Later on Jesus called Lazarus from the grave to come forth and Lazarus rose from the dead and came forth.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "THEME FROM THE FOUR GOSPELS AND THE ACTS OF THE APOSTLES     What lessons can be drawn from this declaration?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 11.    - The event of the raising of Lazarus was to the glory of God and not man.  - The raising of Lazarus from the dead shows that Jesus is an example of the Kingdom of God, it also proves that Jesus is the way, the truth, life and light to mankind.  - God remains faithful to those that will always believe in him   - Those who trust, believe and serve God will rise from physical death and live an eternal life in heaven.  - Believers who who are faithful will never die in vain.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Explain how Herod opposed the early church.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Acts 4.    After the church spread from Jerusalem to Judea, King Herod joined with opposition to the church. Herod went ahead to kill James who was the brother of John, when  Herod saw that the Jews were pleased with it he went ahead and took hold of Peter and put him in prison with plans or torturing him immediately after passover.      When the day came, Peter was tied up and kept between two soldiers when the Angel of the Lord appeared to him ordering Peter to follow him. They passed all guards, all gates and even the outer gate which opened on its own. At the time when  all this happened, Peter was thought he was dreaming.    When they got outside the outer gate, the Angel of the Lord left him andd he became conscious of himself and realized it wasn't a dream but of a truth an Angel had delivered him from the hands of Herod.     Peter then went straight to the house of Mary and knocked , Rhoda heard his voice and ran back with joy to welcome him. Peter the narrated his story and later departed from the place.     The following day on hearing about the news of Peter's escape, Herod had to execute all the guards for not being able to keep up with the task given to them.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Identify two consequence of this opposition", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Acts 4.    The consequences of Herods opposition include:   (i)  The opposition on the church made the apostles stronger and zealous, it boosted thier effort towards making the church one to reckon with and also making the church a success.  (ii)  The opposition on the church also made the church increase go further than just Jerusalem and Judea, even others outside these localities were given more reason to be a part of the church.  (iii) The opposition in an attempt to weaken the church made the gospel of Jesus more popular.  (iv) The opposition of Herod against the church was also to used to fulfil Jesus Christ's word of going into the world to preach the gospel and winning souls to Christ because the opposition made it possible  (v)  The opposition instead of being a tool to hinder the church from growing and also being a blockade to the spread of the gospel became an awareness creating tool for the apostles and believers.  (vi) The opposition also led to repentance of some opposers like Paul of Tarsus he was one of those behind the death of many Christians during this period including Stephen.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Outline Paul's message on justification.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Roman 3, 4 and 5.    Justification is the process whereby mans' sins are overlooked and God declares him righteous. It is the act of showing that something is right and reasonable, an act where humans are free from the penalty that comes with sin and being guilty. Justification brings peace with God and also access to his grace that keeps us standing.    Justification is God's gift to man which start when he gave up his son Jesus Christ on the cross of Calvary , He washed away our sins through the blood which he shed on the cross for our sins hence our sins where justified. Now it is left to us to either accept Christ as our Lord and personal savior, be saved and justified.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "State two conditions of the  attainment of justification", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Roman 3, 4 and 5.    The conditions of attaining Justification in the following.  -  Have the faith and believe that Jesus Christ died and resurrected for our our sins.  - Confess your sins and totally have faith in Christ Jesus as your Lord and personal savior, the confession should be done with the whole of your heart.  - You must be from sin, you must not steal, tell lies and be faithful in the things of the Lord.-      The person must have a good character and exhibit the attitude of love and care towards his/her neighbor, must also love God and have the fear of God in him.  - Have a reconciliation with the things of the Lord, reject sin and avoid the wrath of God.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "According to Paul, what are the signs of the parousia?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Thessalonians 4 and 5.    - Jesus Christ will descend from heaven with the mighty sounds of trumpet and those that are dead in Christ will rise.  - There will be false prophets, false signs, false messages and false miracles will take place just to deceive people from the true word and signs of His coming.  - Those who do not believe in the law will try deceive those who believe and might lead them to condemnation.  - According to Paul to the Thessalonians, the second coming will be followed by the coming of the lawless one with signs and wonders, they are called the sons or perdition.  - Those who will be alive till His coming should not be worried about the time but should have it in my and live a life worthy of His kingdom.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "State three lessons relevant to christians in Paul's explanation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Thessalonians 4 and 5.    - Christians should always live a life the depicts true salvation, they should always live a Christ like life in order to be candidates of Heaven.  - They also learnt that there is no particular or stipulated time for the Parousia's coming and Christians should not worry about it because it would be sudden, without a notice.  - There is need to teach the word continuously without laxity and also help other Christians who are weak in their faith so that they can grow strong in faith.  - We have also learnt not to worry about those that died before the Parousia.  - It was learnt that Christians should always be prepared.  - We also learnt to be careful so we don't get deceived by those that are lawless.  - According to Paul's teachings we have also learnt to always have our heart, body soul and spirit ready for the day of the second coming.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "How did Paul convince the Galatians that christians are children of God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Galatians 3.    When faith came into existence it was at that point that Christians stopped being bound by the law. We are now Children of God who through Jesus Christ we have been redeemed and justified that whosoever believes in him will not die. The death of Jesus Christ redeemed us from the law and now we are justified by our faith in God through Christ Jesus.  When we were under the law were slaves and couldn't exhibit our full potential, we had great things, within and outside but they were trampled upon and taken from us because we were enslaved under the law. But when God sent his son Jesus Christ who was born by a woman to redeem us from under the law so that we might receive grace to be called the Sons and daughters of God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Indicate two ways Christians should manifest themselves as children of God.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Galatians 3.    The Christians Manifest themselves as Children of God by showing the following characteristics.    - They should be obedient to God's word and be faithful servants, serving Him with all their hearts.  - They should live a Christ-like life by following the steps of Christ.  (iii)     They should also be the hearers and the doers of Gods word.  (iv)     Christians should also learn not to be weighed down by the things of their passions and love for the things of this world.  (v)      They should always praise, worship and thank the Lord in their good and bad times.  (vi)      As Christians we must learn to forgive and love our neighbours.  (vii)     Christians should avoid discrimination, hate and racism.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Explain Peter's description of Christians as \" a chosen race and a Royal Priesthood\"....", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Peter 2 : 9.    Peter explained that as the children of God were not just children of God, according to him they are a \" chosen race and Royal priesthood\" because God himself called out of darkness we represent him, Christ in us and we in him. Before we were called into God's kingdom we belonged nowhere and now we are refered to as the children of God living on God mercy.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2007>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2007", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Give two examples in a Christian's daily life to support the above description.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Peter 2 : 9.    - They have to be obedient  - Their life must not conform to that of the word.  - Keeping and obeying the laws of the land and authority above them  - Rendering social services thats helps the growth of the community.  - Helping people in need by involving in charity works.   - Preaching the word of God.  - Loving their neighbor as they love themselves.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Give an account of Joseph's first encounter with Pharaoh", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 41    Joseph encounter with Pharaoh started as a result of Pharaoh's several dreams which he couldn't interpret.    Pharoah needed someone to interprete his dreams but couldn't find anyone so it happened that at a time in prison was Pharaoh's Butler who had a dream. Joseph was able to interprete it for him and later on Joseph interpretation of the dream came to manifest.     Butler was released and restored back to his former position according to Joseph's interpretation.     Two years after Pharoah needed someone to interprete his dreams so Butler recommended Joseph to Pharoah as one who can interprete his dreams perfectly well.    Immediately Pharaoh sent for Joseph and after he was cleaned up he appeared before the king.     Pharaoh narrated his dreams to Joseph, that he was standing at the bank of a river, where seven fat cows came came and fed on the grass, then came some other cows after them, this other cows looked very hungry, thin and poorly taken care of, Pharaoh said he had never seen such kind of thin and hungry cows in Egypt before, he continued and said that the thin, hungry and unhealthy cows ate up the healthy and fat ones but still remaained thin and hungry as they were.    He also narrated the second dream that he saw seven ears full and good and another seven ears withered and thin. The seven thin ears swallowed up the seven good ones. Pharaoh's wise men coudn't interprete any of them.    Joseph told Pharaoh that his dreams were revelations of what he was about to do in the land of Egypt.     He told Pharoah that the Seven good cows and seven good ears are the seven good years of harvest and plenty while the seven thin cows and the seven bad ears are the years of Famine in the land of Egypt. He said to the king that there will be seven years of plenty and seven years of famine in the land of Egypt.     Joseph advised the King that in order for him to overcome the problems that comes with the famine that he should appoint men to oversee the land and that this appointed men should take 20% of the harvest of the land during the years of plenty and save it under the authority of Pharaoh in preparation for the years when there shall be famine.     So Pharoah appointed Joseph as the Overseer of all the affairs in the land of Egypt, he said \" I have set over the land of Egypt, I am Pharaoh and without your consent no man shall lift up hand or foot in all the land of Egypt\". Pharaoh took his Signet and gave it Joseph as a symbol of authority, dressed him in a garment of fine linen and beautiful gold, and people shouted before Joseph \" Bow to your knee\"    Pharaoh then gave Joseph a name which is Zaphenathpaneah and also gave him a woman Asenath the daughter of  Portiphera the priest of On.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "State any three qualities of his that earned him Pharaoh's favour", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 41.  - He had the ability to interpret King Pharaoh's dreams and also gave solution to it where others couldn't.  - He was humble when he interpreted the Kings dreams and also very respectful.  - Joseph always had the fear of God in him in whatever he does.  - He was chosen by God to be favoured.  - He was a person who loved and cared for everyone around him, even when he was in prison. Reason why he was recommended by Butler who was once a prisoner.  - He had wisdom but was proud of what great ability he has.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "Narrate the story of the death of the first child born to David by Uriah's wife.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Samuel 12.    David had sinned against God through the sin of Adultery.     He killed Uriah just because he wanted to cover his sin of Adultery with Batsheba, Uriah's wife.     Uriah died in the battle field and immediately King David took in Uriah's wife Bathsheba to be his woman. God was angry and so he sent Nathan to David. David confronted Nathan himself telling him that he has sinned against God, Nathan replied that he has been forgiven by God and that he will not die but the first child  he was going to have with Bathsheba must surely die.    God struck the child with a certain illness and the child was very sick. David went to the Lord in prayers and fasting, pleading for mercy so that the child will be healed, he prayed earnestly rolled on the floor and refused to eat, seven days after in the child's illness, the child died. When David heard that the child was dead he washed him clean, anointed himself then he went to the house of the Lord and made where he praised and worshiped the Lord.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "THEME FROM THE OLD TESTAMENT     State any three lessons to be derived from the episode", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Samuel 12.    - For every sin there is a consequence.  - David worship and praised God even in his trials and tribulations.  - No good thing comes out of any evil perpetrated by anyone, the end result is always bad.  -  We should not be covetous, David coveted what was of the house of Uriah and took it forcefully.  - We should be contented with what we have. David wasn't contented with his wives.  -  David feared God  - God is a merciful God and will forgive our sins.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Describes Saul's battle with the Philistines on Mount Gilboa", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Samuel 31.    The Philistines went into war with the Isrealites, during the war Saul had few soldiers left at war, then they fled  after the defeat by the Philistines leaving Saul to himself.     The Philistines caught up with Saul and his three sons including Jonathan and killed them all.     Saul the king was also badly injured, he couldn't take it all in then he ordered his armor bearer to kill him with his sword instead of the uncircumcised Philistines killing him and making jest of him. His amour bearer couldn't do it, so Saul killed himself by falling upon himself then the amour bearer seeing this also killed himself.     When the people of Isreal who lived beyond Jordan saw this they left their cities and ran away.     The following day the Philistines came to take all that belonged to the Isrealites that were dead, they discovered King Saul among the slain and his children among the slain enemies . Seeing this they cut of Saul's head, took off his armour and passed the good news to their Idols and the people.    The hung the body of Saul on a wall in their city and his armor was kept in one of their temples.    When the people of Jabesh Gilead heard of the evil and shame that befell Saul , the strong men of that land went at night to recover the body of King Saul and that of his children which was later burnt at Jabesh Gilead. They later fasted and mourned them for seven days.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Give two reasons why the outcome of the battle could be blamed on Saul.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Samuel 31.    - Samuel spirit warned Saul on the defeat but he refused to yeild, if he had yielded and called for peace the reverse would have been the case and all what happened wouldn't have happened.  - Saul was full of pride and didn't allow David to stay in Isreal, if not his presence would have averted the holocaust.  - Saul at the time of the battle had lost his connection with God he no longer recieved instructions from God and the spirit of God had also left him.  - The reason for the defeat at Mount Gilboa was as a result of Saul's disobedience to God's instruction as regards Amalek, this was also the reason why God departed from him.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Relate the experience of Jonah as he fled from the presence of God to Tarshish.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Jonah 2 and Jonah 3.    Jonah was called by God to go to the Nineveh and preach His word to the people of that land employing them to repent from their wickedness which had come before Him.     Jonah in a bid not to do that which God has commanded him, went against God's will and decided to go to Tarshish away from God's presence.     On his way, there was a storm. The storm was sent by God to hinder him from going to Tarshish but go to Nineveh were He sent him.    The people in the ship and fellow passengers were afraid and cried to their god to deliver them, they threw their luggages into the sea peradventure it was too much for the ship so they hope the ship gets light. Jonah was sleeping when all this happened, the captain of the ship confronted him and told him he was supposed to be praying to his God instead of sleeping. Then they decided to cast a lot and it fell on Jonah as the cause of the heavy storm. The captain questioned Jonah asking him where he was coming from, his country and his reason for embarking on the journey. Jonah made it known that he was an Hebrew and was running away from the Lord. Jonah then requested of the people in the ship should throw him into the sea because he had disobeyed God.    At this point God had already prepared a big fish to swallow Jonah up and immediately Jonah was thrown into the sea, the big fish swallowed him up. He was in the belly of the fish for three days and three nights, while he was there, he kept praising, praying to God and also thanking him.  Jonah thought of his deed and disobedience to God and though of a chance to be allowed into Gods presence and look upon his face again. He was lifted in his spirit because when he calls upon the name of the Lord he still answers him. He then made a vow to make a sacrifice unto the Lord.    Jonah was vomitted by the fish immediately after his prayer at a place near Nineveh, at this point God's message came to Jonah again the second time, telling him to go to Nineveh and do that which he the Lord has sent him. Jonah yielded to God's word this time and went straight to Nineveh, where he preached the word for and told the people that \"In forty days time Nineveh will be overthrown\".     The people heard this, they repented, believed in God and trusted in His word, they proclaimed a fast and put on sackcloth from the old people to the young ones.  When the message also got to the King of Nineveh, he took off his cloth, wore sackcloth and sat on the floor, he then made a decree that in Nineveh that \" no man, herd or flock, is to taste anything, they are not to eat or drink anything but both man and animal should wear sackcloth and everyone must call on God earnestly and also turn from his wicked ways, that hopefully God may turn from his anger and forgive the people of Nineveh and deliver them from destruction.     God saw all they did and how they had repented from their wicked ways, so God forgave them and did not pass the Judgement of destruction on the people of Nineveh.    God provided shelter for Jonah by providing him with a plant that grew overnight and later was eaten by worms. When the sun rose and beat Jonah he regretted more about the dead plant and prayed that God make him die, God asked why and he confessed that he was angry and that anger equals death.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "THEME FROM THE OLD TESTAMENT     Give two moral lessons that could be learnt from his flight", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Jonah 3.    (i)       It is not good to be disobedient, Jonah was disobedient to God's order and hence caused the storm that almost took the life of other travellers.  (ii)      Nobody can stop the plans of God, Jonah thought he could run away from the sight of God at the detriment of God's plan but God showed him that when He says yes no man can say no, so He caused the storm and made the fish to swallow and vomit him at a place near Nineveh to deliver his message to the people of Nineveh.  (iii)      Learnt that there is nothing God cant use to do His work, all power belongs to God and He created all thing and has sovereign authority over them. He proved that by ordering the fish to swallow and vomit Jonah at that particular place.  (iv)      God is an Ominipresent God, He was with Jonah even in the belly of the fish  (v)       God is a merciful God, He had mercy on the people of Nineveh, we should always learn to ask for forgivness and acknowledge our sins just the way the people of Nineveh did.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "Explain Luke's account of the healing of Demoniac.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Mark 5 : 1 - 20    When Jesus and his disciples arrived at a country called Gerasenes is right opposite Galilee. In that place there was a man who lived naked among the tombs and had demons.     Immediately Jesus stepped out he met this demoniac, the demoniac fell down before Jesus and pleaded with Jesus asking him not to torment him, the demons in the man were so violent that they drove him into the deserts after breaking all his fetters and chains.     Jesus looked at him and asked for his name, he replied saying \" Legion, for we are many\".  The demons who knew who Jesus was and what he was capable of doing to them begged Jesus not to cast them into the bottomless pit but pleaded that Jesus sends them into the swine feeding by the hillside and Jesus cast them out and sent them into the swine.     After the demons had gone into the swine, the swine rushed into the lake and drowned there. Some herdsmen saw the and ran to the city to relay the news of what had happened, they all gathered to be a witness of what had happened. When the people came they saw the demon possessed man sited, and well dressed and was calm right beside Jesus.     The people of that land were afraid and requested that Jesus should leave their land. The man that was formerly possessed with demons begged that Jesus should allow him go with him. But Jesus said to him to go away into the city and tell the people how much the Lord has done for him. The demon possessed man obeyed and did as Jesus has asked him to.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "Give two reason why the evil spirits were sent into the swine", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Mark 5 : 1 - 20    - They were sent into the swine because they were not meant to live in the body of the man.  - They were also sent into the swine because they tormented the life of the man and he had no power to be in charge of his own body and decisions.  - The demons were sent into the swine because they requested to be sent there.  - God also sent the demons into the swine because they were evil and destructive.  - Allowing the demons to dwell among people can be very dangerous.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Outline the parables of the  lost sheep and lost coin", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 15 : 1 - 10     THE LOST SHEEP   This parable was said by Jesus as a result of the Pharisees and Scribes who murmured and questioned Jesus because He welcomed sinners and dined with them. Jesus then replied with the Parable saying that \"What man among you, if he has a hundred sheep and loses one of them, does not leave the ninety-nine in the wilderness and go after the one which is lost,  until he finds it?  And when he has found it, he lays it on his shoulders, rejoicing.  And when he gets home, he calls together his friends and his neighbors, saying to them, 'Rejoice with me, because I have found my lost sheep!\".     Jesus made them to realize that just as He would rejoice over a lost sheep. He would also rejoice with great joy when one sinner repents than rejoice over ninety-nine righteous people who do not need to repent. This made them understand he was trying to save a soul by being with the sinners.     THE LOST COIN   In an attempt to explain further, Jesus went ahead to narrate the parable of the lost coin, he said  \" Or what woman, if she has ten silver coins each one equal to a day's wages and loses one coin, does not light a lamp and sweep the house and search carefully until she finds it? And when she has found it, she calls together her friends and neighbors, saying, 'Rejoice with me, because I found the lost coin!'  In the same way, I tell you, there is joy in the presence of the angels of God over one sinner who repents [that is, changes his inner self—his old way of thinking, regrets past sins, lives his life in a way that proves repentance; and seeks God's purpose for his life].\"", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "In what two ways are this parables significant?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 15 : 1 - 10    The significance of this parable are:    - God is always ready to welcome sinners and is happy on every occasions when lost souls are won to Christ.  - A sinner is refered to as the Lost sheep or the Lost coin.  - God is a shepherd and even though there are many sinners out there who do not believe in God and those also who have disobeyed God, God is always in search for them and hasn't rejected them because they are still his sheep.  - God is love and he loves everyone irrespective of who you are.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Give an account of the trial of Jesus before the high priest", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 22.    Judas betrayed Jesus which led to his arrest in Gethsemane by armed soldiers of the high Priest. They arrested and led him to Caiaphas where the High Priests, scribes and elders gathered. These elders were called the Council of the Sandherin.     The Council of Elders gathered witnesses against Jesus who accused him of several things including:  (i)       He was claiming to be the son of God, which they believe he wasn't.  (ii)      They also accused him of being an impostor, who came into the country illegally.  (iii)     He was also accused of telling the people not to pay tax, which was against the law of the land.  (iv)     He was accused of calling himself the king of the Jews  Then the High Priest questioned Jesus if of a truth he was the Son of God. He replied using the many record of the Bible , in the book of Matthew and Mark were he was refered to as \" I am\" , in Luke \" you say  I am but you will see the Son of Man coming down at the right hand of power coming with the cloud of heaven\". This was seen as blasphemy in the land of and was declared guilty by the Sanhedrin.     During this time Peter denied Jesus. Later on Jesus was transferred to Pilate to be sentenced because the Jew has no authority to sentence one to death.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : PETER’S DENIALS", "question": "THEME FROM THE FOUR GOSPELS AND THE ACTS OF THE APOSTLES     Describe Peter's behaviour during this period.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 22.    (i)       Peter was very defensive at first and wanted to save Jesus from those who wanted to arrest him so he brought out his sword and cut off the ear of one of those that came to arrest Jesus, his name was Malchus, he was the slave of the High Priest.  (ii)      Few minutes later he stayed away from the soldiers that took Jesus away and watched them from a distance.  (iii)    Because he didn't want to suffer he denied Jesus when he was questioned by the Jews because he wanted to save his his own life.  (iv)    He was very supportive even though other disciples abandoned Jesus.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Narrate the story of how Lazarus was raised from death", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 11.    Mary and Martha who were sisters to a friend of Jesus Christ whose name was Lazarus. They sent for Jesus that their brother Lazarus who lived in Bethany was ill. Jesus replied Mary and Martha that the illness of their brother his friend was not unto death. Jesus didn't go to Bethany till after four days that he had recieved the news. By the time he got to Bethany with his disciples, he met many of the Jews consoling  Mary and Martha on the death of their brother Lazarus.    Martha heard that Jesus had arrived and encountered him by saying that their brother wouldn't have died if He had came when He got the news but she also had the believe that Whatever Jesus asked from God will be granted. Jesus said to Martha that her brother Lazarus will arise from the death again. Martha said to Jesus,\"I know he will rise again but in resurection which is on the last day. When she said this Jesus said to her '' I am the resurection and the life, he who believes in me, though he dies shall live and whosoever lives and believes in me shall never die.\"  After that Martha confessed that she believed in Jesus as the son of God.    After Martha has confessed that Jesus asked people to remove the stone from the grave, Jesus asked the people to remove the stone from the grave, but Martha told him that her brother has been dead for some days and there will be odour from his body. But Jesus asked them to believe that they will see the glory of God of manifest.     They took away the stone away the stone and Jesus looked up to heaven and said \" Father I thank thee, that thou has heard me, I know that thou hearest me always ,but I have said this on the account of these people standing by, that they may believe that thou did'st send me\".  Then after he had said all this Jesus cried with a loud voice \" Lazarus, come forth\". Immediately he said, Lazarus who was dead for some days came out of the tomb with his legs and hands bound with bandages while his face was wrapped with cloth. Then Jesus said to the people to unbind him.     The Jews who were there with  Mary the sister of Lazarus after seeing this believed in Jesus and their faith was renewed.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Give two lessons which the story teaches Christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 11.    -  The event of the raising of Lazarus was to the glory of God and not man.  - The raising of Lazarus from the dead shows that Jesus is an example of the Kingdom of God, it also proves that Jesus is the way, the truth, life and light to mankind.  - God remains faithful to those that will always believe in Him   - Those who trust, believe and serve God will rise from physical death and live an eternal life in heaven.  - Believers who who are faithful will never die in vain.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "With reference to Paul's epistle to the Philippians, explain how Jesus demonstrated humility.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Philippians 2 : 1 - 11.    Paul was filled with joy because the Philippians were actively involved in the spreading the work of God and how great it will be when they keep doing his work together one mind and also humbly. He then employed all christians to share with love, one accord and one spirit in order to complete that joy that comes with being christians and living in peace with one another.     To be sure that they were of one spirit, Paul said to them that they should not be selfish but see other as people who are better than they are. He said they should not only look out for personal interests but look out for the interests of others too. He employed them to live a life of Christ, looking to Jesus Christ as an example to selfless humility, Christ was humble that he did not regard himself as an equal to God but instead He assumed Himself as a servant of and being made in the likeness of man became completely human being without sin, He became completely man and completely God. He also humbled himself to die on the cross for our sins, for this reason He was exalted by God and his name was placed above all other names, and at the mention of the name of Jesus every knee shall bow and all tongue will confess that Jesus Christ is Lord.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Mention two ways one can exhibit this virtue.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Philippians 2 : 1 - 11.    - One can exhibit this form of humility by being selfless and helping the society the live in.  - This virtue can also be exhibited by one being satisfied and contented with what he/she has.  - By being godly and obeying the commandments of God.  - It can also be exhibited when one doesn't have a pride in regards to his or her achievements in life.  - By putting one total hope in God as the sovereign ruler of the world.  - By always puting God first in whatever you do.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>10", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "10", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "Outline Paul's teaching on spiritual gifts", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in  1st Corinthians 12.    Paul in his teaching about spiritual gifts stated that, spiritual gifts are are gifts of grace from the Lord, as in born talents bestowed on us as humans by God himself.  According to him the spiritual gifts can be tested through checking if the person say \" Jesus is Lord\" it is of the God but if the person says \" Jesus is cursed\" it is of the devil.     Paul enlisted nine spiritual gifts which includes:   i.    Word of wisdom  ii.   Word of Knowledge  iii.   Faith  iv.   Healing Power  v.   Miracle Working  vi.   Prophecy  vii.  Differentiating between spirits.  viii.  Speaking in tongues and interpreting of tongues.    Paul then further explained this spiritual gifts by comparing it with the human body and its parts, Paul said that the whole parts of the human body had a very important role that it plays and this specific roles can't be carried out by other parts.     If a part of the body is not available to carry out that important role, no other part can do it, the whole parts of the body work together. God has created the whole parts of the body to work in relationship with one another to make the body perfect just as he had wanted it to be.     According to him, some weaker parts are granted with greater respectability to avoid misunderstanding in the body. if one body rejects the entire body suffers. So also with spiritual gifts, they work hand in hand with one another.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Highlight how James proved that  \" faith apart from work is death\"", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Hebrews 11 : 1 and James 2 : 14 - 26.    According to the Bible, Faith is the substance of things hoped for and evidence of things not seen, for by this the men of old gained approval. James in his teachings on faith called upon christians to be not only the hearers of the word but also the doers of them. He also taught that they christians should do away with deceit.    He then continued by letting them know that  (ii)   Faith is the foundation upon which christianity was built. True christianity requires practical manifestation one's faith by obeying the word of God in totality.  (ii)      By faithfully practicing what the word of God states without doubt.  (iii)     By withdrawing from doing evil to others and saying bad words against them.  (iv)     He also showed being faithful by doing that which the word of God teaches.  (v)     By living a life that is christ-like just as we are called christians for being like Christ.  James made the believers to realize that anyone who doesn't keep to all what was stated with His faith cannot be a true child of God, He is just a hearer of the word alone and not the doer.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Mention two  deeds of faith", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Hebrews 11 : 1 and James 2 : 14 - 26.    - By caring for the needy and with all faith in God to replenish and bless your efforts.  - By teaching the word of God to uphold fellow believers and to convert sinners.  - Taking out time to be of service to God in His vineyard by being a member of a workforce in the house of God.         - By visiting and giving assistance to the orphans, widows, widowers and the poor.  - By living a life that is right in the face of the Lord both in words and in deeds.  - By also doing that which the word of God says.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Relate the teaching of James on effective prayer", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in James 5 : 16 - 18.    Prayer on its own is a means of communication between man and God. It is a medium which man relates his problems and predicament to God. The act of praying is one that we learnt from Christ.     According to James, faith is what you need to have for effective prayers and answers from God. Prayers are effective if one asks without doubts. If he doubts, he is like the wave of the sea that is driven and tossed by the wind. A man who is double minded will receive nothing from God.     So for effective prayer, one needs to be strong in faith and certain.    Anyone suffering should pray to God and let any one who is happy sing praises to the Lord.     He also said that anyone who is sick should also call on the elders of the church to pray for him and anoint him with oil in the name of the Lord. The prayer of by faith of a sick man and the Lord will raise him up and if he has committed sins he will be forgiven.    James also admonished that we should pray for one another and forgive one another of our sins. The prayer of a righteous man has great power in its effects. He also used Elijah as an example who prayed that it should rain for and it rain for three years.     James in his teaching on effective prayer he also mentioned the types of prayer that should be prayed and in the order that it should be done.. The process of prayer according to James include include:  (i)     Thanking God  (ii)     Confessing your sin  (iii)    Petitions  (iv)    Dedication  (v)    Interceding  (vi)   Thanking Him for what He has done, what He is doing and what He is yet to do.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2008>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2008", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Give four causes of unanswered prayers.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in James 5 : 16 - 18.    - When the person that is praying doesn't have faith.  - Not repenting from personal sin.  - When there is lack of concentration in prayer.  - Unforgiving spirit  - Having worldly desires.  - And not working whole-heartedly for God.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "List the event of the six days of creation in chronological order", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 1.  - God created light and darkness.. and the light was called \"Day\" and the darkness \"Night\".  - God created the Firmament.  - God created the Land, Sea and Vegetation.  - God created the sun the Moon and the Stars.  - God created the birds of the air and all Sea creature.  - God created all animals that live on land and Man.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Explain the concept of man as the image of God", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 1 : 26 - 28    Man was created as God's image, man has a soul and spirit.     When God looks at man He sees himself hence His love for man heightened. Man enjoys a heartily relationship with God because God made it so, so that a personal relationship will coexist between man and God.     Man was given the right to make his own choices, due to fact that man was created in God's ( who has power to do all things at his own will) image. Man was given the power to rule over every other creature on earth, no other creature is above man, man was given dominion over them all. And God blessed man in all his ways.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>1>c", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "c", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "State three implications of the sovereignty of God as portrayed in the creation story", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 1 : 26 - 28    - The sovereignty of God shows that man should never try to take authority from God, He reigns supreme.  - Nothing in man's life is impossible for God to do. He created him and can handle every of his needs. Nothing is impossible when Man  puts his trust in God.  - God has no beginning and end, He is God forever.  - God is not a human being and shouldn't be referred to as one.  - God is the source of life and creator of life, nothing on this earth exist on their own but by God.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "How did Moses become the son of Pharaoh's daughter?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Exodus 2.    When the ruler that ruled Egypt was defeated, a new Pharaoh came into existence in  Egypt who did not know who Joseph was. The new Pharaoh looked around Egypt and realized that the number of Israelites was much and feared that one day they the Israelite might dominate Egypt.     He then made a decision to enslave the Israelites, so he appointed task masters over the the Israelites. In order to reduce their number, the new Pharaoh ordered the midwives in Egypt to kill every male born child of the Hebrew women. The Midwives had the fear of the Lord in them and did not obey the new Pharaoh.    There was a family of the levite who at this time had a male child , the name of this child would be called Moses. After about three months that Moses parent took care of him without the knowledge of anyone, they couldn't hide him anymore. So his mother took him, placed him in a basket and went to drop him at the River Nile where Pharaoh's daughter usually came to take her bath. Pharaoh's daughter saw him picked him up and gave him the name Moses. Pharaoh's daughter needed a woman to take care of the baby so with the aid of Moses sister, Pharaoh's daughter employed a Hebrew woman who happened to be Moses' mother to take care of the baby.     Moses' mother took care of Moses till the age when he was old enough to be Pharaoh's daughter 's child just as she has requested.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Explained three ways in  which this prepared Moses for his future leadership roles.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Exodus 2.    - He was raised in a royal house so he understood all about royalty and the authority that guides and rules Egypt.  - He was able to understand better how much his people have suffered, which prepared him for the plans of God.  - He understood the culture of both his people and the Egytians.  - With the time he was with his family he developed love for his people.  - He understood the political standards of the Egyptians.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Write notes on Solomon's request for wisdom.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 3 : 5 - 28.    After Solomon was crowned as King in Gibeon, that night at his palace God appeared to him and requested of Solomon to ask for whatever he wanted in the name of Lord and that it shall be given on him. Solomon in turn replied and asked that the Lord should give him wisdom and understanding to rule and guide his people. He wanted God to give him the wisdom to know that which is good and that which is bad.    God hearing King Solomon's request was happy that unlike everyone else Solomon didn't request for long life, wealth and other riches of this world.    As a result of this God gave Solomon wisdom and a mind that discerns which was greater than that of all kings that were before him, God also added riches and honored him above every other man on earth, God also promised to give him long life. All this was promised by God if only Solomon will keep his commandment like the way his father David did.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Give three ways Solomon's request was tested and proved", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 3 : 5 - 28.    There were two harlots who lived together, they were both pregnant and on the same night they had their sons together.     One of the Harlots mistakenly slept on her son and he died. When she woke up and saw what had happened to her son as a result of her mistake, she quickly exchanged her dead baby with that of the other harlot which was alive.     By the morning of the next day there a fight and they went to king Solomon to help them settle their misunderstanding by deciding who the owner of the child which was alive was.      Solomon then ordered the child be divided into two, one side of the baby for each of the two harlots. Immediatly the king made this order, the true mother of child screamed that the child shouldn't be killed but instead be given to the one falsely claiming to be the owner of the child, instead of killing the baby.     But the harlot that was falsely claiming to be the owner of the child was happy about the judgement of the king.     After this reaction by both women the King knew who the real mother of the baby was and ordered that the baby be given to the woman that protested that the baby shouldn't be killed.     With this the King showed great wisdom and the whole of Israel and its neighbors were assured that of a truth God's wisdom is with King Solomon.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "Narrate Elijah's flight to Mount Horeb.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 19 : 1 - 18.    This event happened after the contest at Mount Carmel between Elijah and the prophets of Baal for supremacy. Ahab narrated the tale of how Elijah killed the whole prophets of Baal with the sword, just immediately Jezebel heard the whole story narrated to her by Ahab, she sent a message to Elijah threatening to kill him just the way he had killed the Prophets of Baal.     Elijah the prophet of God became afraid after he heard the threats of Jezebel and ran away to Beersheba leaving his servant behind. He wandered around the wilderness and there he asked that God should take his life that he wasn't better than  his fathers while he sat under the broomstick tree. While sleeping under the tree the Angel of Lord came to him for the first time asking him to ''Arise and eat\", the Angel fed him with cake and water. The Angel woke him up the second time to eat so as to prepare him for the journey that awaits him, Elijah woke up ate and drank water and with the strenght of the food he had eaten, he journeyed for forty days and forty nights to Mount Horeb where he stayed in a cave and the Lord asked him what he was doing in a cave, Elijah replied and said \" he was jealous of God that Isreal had forsaken God's convenant, thrown down his altars,  also killed his prophets and that he alone was left but the people still seek to take his life. Elijah was instructed to go and stand at Mount Horeb before God. On Mount Horeb there came a great mighty wind, earthquake and fire and then a small voice.     On hearing this voice Elijah came and stood at the mouth of the cave and wrapped his face around his mantle. The second time the voice came and questioned Elijah why he was at the mouth of the cave , he gave the previous reply as he did th first time. God then ordered him to return to the wilderness of Damascus.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSIONS DURING AHAB’S REIGN", "question": "In what three ways did God plan to punish the house of Ahab and Isreal?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 19 : 1 - 18.    - That the place where the dogs licked up the blood of Naboth is the same place that the dogs will lick up the blood of Ahab.  - Evil shall befall Ahab  - God said and I will make your house (descendants) like that of Jeroboam the son of Nebat, and like the house of Baasha the son of Ahijah, for provoking Me to anger and making Israel sin.  - The Lord also spoke in regard to Jezebel, saying, 'The dogs will eat [the body of] Jezebel in the district of Jezreel.'  - The dogs will eat anyone belonging to Ahab who dies in the city, and the birds of the air will eat anyone who dies in the field.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Relate the parable of the good samaritan", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in  Luke 10 : 25 - 27    An expert in the Mosaic law, a lawyer stood up and said to Jesus \"Teacher, what must I do to inherit eternal life\", Jesus replied \"What is written in the law, have you read it?\". He replied Jesus saying \"You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart, and with all your soul, and with all your strength, and with all your mind; and your neighbor as yourself.\" Jesus said to him \"You have answered correctly, do this and you will live\" so he went further asking Jesus who his neighbor was.     Then Jesus replied by telling him the Parable of the good Samaritan, Jesus said  \"A man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho, and he encountered robbers, who stripped him of his clothes and belongings, beat him, and went their way, leaving him half dead. By coincidence a priest was going down that road, and when he saw him, he passed by on the other side. A Levite also came down to the place and saw him, and passed by on the other side of the road. But a Samaritan who was a foreigner and was traveling, came upon him; and when he saw him, he was deeply moved with compassion, and went to him and bandaged up his wounds, pouring oil and wine on them to disinfect the injuries; and he put him on his own pack-animal, and brought him to a place where he was taken care of. The next day he took out two denarii, which was a two days' wages and gave them to the keeper of the place, and said, 'Take care of him; and whatever more you spend, I will repay you when I return.'  Which of these three do you think proved himself a neighbor to the man who encountered the robbers?\" Jesus asked.  He answered, \"The one who showed compassion and mercy to him.\" Then Jesus said to him, \"Go and constantly do the same.\"", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "State three ways the parable illustrates the concern for one another", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 10 : 25 - 27.    - The Samaritan showed love and concern by helping his neighbor even though he never knew him.  - The Samaritan knew the man that lied on the floor injured was a never minded but showed him love, this shows that we should care for everyone irrespective of the tribe and country they came from.  - If we are to render help to people will should do it in full and not half way. The good Samaritan helped the injured man fully.  - The Samaritan was on a journey and aware the would come across anyone who might be needing help. This shows that we should always be prepared to render help to the needy.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Explain Jesus teaching about himself as the  living water and bread of life", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 4 : 7 - 15 and John 6 : 25 - 40.     AS THE LIVING WATER     Jesus on His way from Galilee went through Samaria and met a woman at Jacob's well. Jesus then asked the woman for water but the woman refused and said that Jesus was Jew and can't be given water by her. Jesus said to her that if she has an idea of the person that was requesting to be given water she would not react in such manner but will ask to be given the \"living water\" instead. Jesus then explained further that whosoever drinks from the well (Jacob's well) will thirst again but whosoever drinks from the living water will never thirst again. Jesus also said that the water that He offers gives eternal life. He added it is a spiritual gift that permanently quenches thirst.      AS THE BREAD OF LIFE     After the miracle of which Jesus fed the people with fishes and bread at the sea of Galilee, the next day when the people came but couldn't find either Jesus or his disciple so they went searching for Him. When they found him on the other side of the sea they asked him \"When did you get here\". Jesus answered and said to them  \"I assure you and most solemnly say to you, you have been searching for Me, not because you saw the signs attesting miracles, but because you ate the loaves and were filled.'' Then He admonished them that they should not work for food that perishes but they should work for the \"Bread of life\" which he (Jesus) offers them, the food that leads to eternal life.     Jesus said to them, \"I am the Bread of Life. The one who comes to Me will never be hungry, and the one who believes in Me as Savior will never be thirsty, for that one will be sustained spiritually\". According to Jesus, He made it known  to the people that He didn't come down from heaven just for His own purpose but to do the will of God that has sent Him. And also anyone who believe in Jesus the son God will on the last day be raised up into heaven by God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Mention three ways in which man is denied of the  bread of life  today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 4 : 7 - 15 and John 6 : 25 - 40.    - Through lack of Knowledge of the Word of God.  - The lack of faith in God.  - Poverty, this makes them wish for earthly things to satisfy their materialistic desires.  - Not being spiritually alert.  - When there is famine in the land, hunger pushes people to give up on their faith.  - The problems they encounter in their day to day activities.  - Sickness and diseases.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Discuss the crucifixion and burial of Jesus Christ", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 27 : 32 - 66.    The crucifixon of Jesus was done according to the laws of the Romans. Jesus carried the cross after a while and couldn't carry it anymore. Then a Jew by the name Simon from Cyrene was made to carry the cross of Jesus. At a place called Golgatha, they gave Jesus a wine mixed with gall to drink. He was later nailed to the cross and His cloth taken from and divided by the soldiers who crucified Him which they shared among themselves.    Over the cross was written \" This is Jesus, the king of the Jews\" while on his left and right side were two robbers who were also nailed to their own cross. People mocked Him including the Chief Priest, Scribes and the Elders, they mocked him that He saved others but could not save himself. At a time darkeness fill the land till 3:00.     Jesus complained of thirst and instead of being given water, was given a sponge filled with vinegar. Jesus on the cross prayed that God should forgive those that crucified Him, for didn't they know what they were doing, before He said his final words \" It is finished\" and died.      Immediately He died, the curtain of the temple splitted into two. Afterwards there was an earthquake, the tombs opened and rocks broke to shreds. A rich man by name Joseph who was from Arithmathea and also a secret disciple of  Jesus and influential, requested for the dead Body of Jesus. He treated the body well by wrapping it in a clean linen and took Jesus to a tomb of his which was new, he buried Jesus there and covered the tomb with a great stone.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "What two lessons can Christians learn from the Jesus' words on the cross?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 27 : 32 - 66.    - Christians will face persecutions so we believers should be prepared for it.  - As Christians we should pray for our enemies.  - That no matter who we are,The Lord will forgive our sins if we accept Him as our Lord and personal saviour just as the thief who was also nailed to the cross confessed.  - We should not give up on God no matter the situation we find ourselves.  -  We should always forgive our enemies and not hold a grudge against them.  - The words of Jesus on the cross and the event of his death taught as that there is a life after death.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Describe Philip's missionarry activities in Judea and Samaria.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Act 8 : 1 - 38.    In Jerusalem, a great problem arose and the church was persecuted that it scattered throughout the Judea and Samaria. Saul went to houses of the people, dragging both men and women to prison but those outside Jerusalem still went about preaching the word but those and Philip went to Samaria and preached there.     In Samaria many people believed the teaching of Philip as they saw the miracles he perfomed and those of them who believed in the kingdom of God and in Jesus were baptized, even Simon the magician also believed. Peter and John were sent to Samaria and on getting there they prayed for the people so that they recieve the Holy Spirit, they did this by laying their hands on them and they recieved the  Holy Spirit. Simon who was formally a magician wished he had such powers so he offered them money so as to be given the power. He was rebuked by Peter and was asked to repent and ask for forgiveness. The Angel of the Lord appeared to Philip and told him to follow the road that goes from Jerusalem to Gaza, where he met an Ethiopian Eunuch, a minister in Candace, queen of Ethiopia. They had come to Jerusalem to worship, Philip joined the eunuchs and preached the word of God to him, the eunuch repented and was baptized.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "State any three problems facing Evangelism in your country", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Beliefs and cultures  - The lack of zeal  - Change in time  - The advent of different types of laws  - Civilization  - Lack of facilities and finance to push the word forward", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight Paul's teaching that Christians are the Children of God", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Galatians 2, 3, 4.    When faith came into existence it was at that point that Christians stopped being bound by the law. We are now Children of God who through Jesus Christ we have been redeemed and justified that whosoever believes in Him would not die. The death of Jesus Christ redeemed us from the law and now we are justified by our faith in God through Christ Jesus.    When we were under the law were slaves and couldn't exhibit our full potential, we had great things, within and outside but they were trampled upon and taken from us because we were enslaved under the law. But when God sent his son Jesus Christ who was born by a woman to redeem us from under the law so that we might receive grace to be called the Sons and daughters of God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "THEME FROM SELECTED EPISTLES     Give two implications of  the doctrine of sonship of God  for Christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Galatians 2 : 23 - 29 and Galatians 4; 1- 7    (i)      This implies that we are not just ordinary people but sons and daughters of the most high God, because we have been redeemed through Jesus Christ.  (ii)      As Christians we now have the ability to go to God and request for our needs.  (iii)     Christians are a part of God fulfilling his word that he will Make Abraham a father of many nations.  (iv)     With Christ overcoming sin and with us taking the being of Christ we now have the power to overcome sin.  (v)      As Christians we do not discriminate, racially or tribally and even when it comes to denomination. We are believed to be one.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "What was Paul's teaching on Humility in his letter to the Philippians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Philippians 2 : 1 - 11.    Paul was filled with joy because the Philippians were actively involved in the spreading the work of God and how great it would be when they keep doing His work together one mind and also humbly. He then employed all christians to share with love, one accord and one spirit in order to complete that joy that comes with being christians and living in peace with one another.     To be sure that they were of one spirit, Paul said to them that they should not be selfish but see other as people who are better than they are. He said they should not only look out for personal interests but look out for the interests of others too. He employed them to live a life of Christ, looking to Jesus Christ as an example to selfless humility, Christ was humble that he did not regard himself as an equal to God. Instead He assumed himself as a servant of and being made in the likeness of man became completely human being without sin, He became completely man and completely God. He also humbled himself to die on the cross for our sins, for this reason He was exalted by God and His name was placed above all other names, and at the mention of the name of Jesus every knee shall bow and all tongue will confess that Jesus Christ is Lord.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "In what three ways is this teaching relevant to Christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Philippians 2 : 1 - 11.    - It brings about the blessings of God to the people  - It promotes patience  - It increases the ability to forgive one another and continue is faith  - It helps Christians how to be selfless and and tolerant of one another  - According to the word of God, God hate those that are proud and he uplifts those that are humble.  - Humility brings respect to the life of every Christian", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight Peter's admonitions on inter-personal relationship among believers", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Peter 5 : 1 - 11.    Peter taught about the roles and responsibilities of Christian leaders in the church. He explained that the leaders of the Church should take care of their members with all their heart, doing so willingly and selflessly. According to Peter they should not get involved in their duties with the desire of getting gain that are of this world or by using a domineering attitude but they should live an exemplary life so that the members can emulate them. He also advised that they should be the spiritual guide of young people.    James advised the young people to humble their leaders because God humiliates the proud and lifts the humble. He also admonished them to see the elders as their spiritual models.   Lastly, he then advised the elders to have faith and be patient, they should have it in mind that suffering is past of the calling of Christians which leads to eternal life.    They should also cast all their anxiety on him. Peter continued by telling the believers to be watchful that the devil is going about seeking for whom to devour. They should resist the devil in their faith in God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Mention three major causes of conflicts amongst Christians today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Peter 5 : 1 - 11.    - Corruption and Bribery  - Selfish actions and pride  - Lack of the spirit of unity  - Backbitting   - Gossiping  - Tribalism and greed  - Being envy and Jealous of one another  - The love of the wealth of this world", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Outline Paul's teaching on  dignity of labour .", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 1 - 18    Paul got the news of how some Thessalonians refused to work on account of their imminence of the Parousa, so they became lazy and prevented others from working and also denied them of bread.     Paul wrote against this in his letter and commanded the Thessalonian believers to stay away from any person among them that refused to work.     He told them that he didnt defraud anyone but worked hard to earn his living. Despite the fact that he had the right to do so as a Preacher of the word to depend on them but he has chosen to live an exemplary life by working hard.     Paul then instructed the people that whosoever choose not to work should not eat. He later encouraged the lazy Thessalonians to work hard to earn a living, after which he passed a judgement that anyone who refuses to work and obey what the letter has instructed should be isolated.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2009>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2009", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Give four roles the church can play to encourage productivity among Christian youth.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 1 - 18    - The church can create organizations that cater for the needy.  - The church also should establish a group where its members can visit and get encouraged by talking to some set of people or elders who have the spirit of God and vast understanding of the word.  - The church also should create groups in charge of youth affairs because a large percentage oof attention is usually drawn to the youths and more is also expected from them.  - Proper and detailed teaching of the word should not be found wanting.  - The church should also provide an avenue for the youths to acquire skills to boost their employment opportunities", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Outline in Chronological order the first creation story", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 1.    - God created light and darkness.. and the light was called \"Day\" and the darkness \"Night\"  - God created the Firmament  - God created the Land, Sea and Vegetation  - God created the sun the Moon and the Stars  - God created the birds of the air and all Sea creature  - God created all animals that live on land and Man  - On the seventh day God rested", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Give three reasons why man is regarded as the crown of creation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 1.    - Man was created in the Image of God.  - Man was given authority by God to rule over every creature of the world.  - Man has a relationship with God that no other creature has.  - Man was a god because he was created in the image of God.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Narrate the dreams of Pharaoh.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 41.    Pharoah needed someone to interprete His dreams but couldn't find anyone so it happened that at a time in prison there was a man by the name Butler who had a dream while in prison and Joseph was able to interprete it for him and later on Joseph interpretation of the dream came to manifest. Butler was released and restored back to his former position according to Joseph's interpretation.     Two years after Pharoah needed someone to interprete his dreams so Butler recommended Joseph to Pharoah as one who can interprete his dreams perfectly well.    Immediately Pharaoh sent for Joseph and after he was cleaned up he appeared before the king. Pharaoh narrated his dreams to Joseph, that he was standing at the bank of a river, where seven fat cows came came and fed on the grass, then came some other cows after them, this other cows looked very hungry, thin and poorly taken care of. Pharaoh said he had never seen such kind of thin and hungry cows in Egypt before. He continued and said that the thin, hungry and unhealthy cows ate up the healthy and fat ones but still remaained thin and hungry as they were.    He also narrated the second dream that he saw seven ears full and good and another seven ears withered and thin. The seven thin ears swallowed up the seven good ones. These two dreams Pharaohs wise men coudn't interprete it.    Joseph told Pharaoh that his dreams were revelations of what he was about to do in the land of Egypt. He told Pharoah that the seven good cows and seven good ears are the seven good years of harvest and plenty while the seven thin cows and the seven bad ears are the years of famine in the land of Egypt. He said to the king that there will be seven years of plenty and seven years of famine in the land of Egypt.     Joseph advised the King that in order for him to overcome the problems that would come with the famine, he should appoint men to oversee the land and that this appointed men should take 20% of the harvest of the land during the years of plenty and save it under the authority of Pharaoh in preparation for the years when there shall be famine.     So Pharoah appointed Joseph as the Overseer of all the affairs in the land of Egypt. He said \" I have set over the land of Egypt, I am Pharaoh and without your consent no man shall lift up hand or foot in all the land of Egypt\". Pharaoh took his signet and gave it Joseph as a symbol of authority, dressed him in a garment of fine linen and beautiful gold, and people shouted before Joseph \" Bow to your knee\".    Pharaoh then gave Joseph a name which is Zaphenathpaneah and also gave him a woman Asenath the daughter of  Portiphera the priest of On.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "In what three ways did the interpretation of the dreams affect Joseph and his people.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 41.    - Joseph was brought out of prison took the position of a ruler in Egypt second in authority to Pharaoh  - He became the reason why the Hebrew could come into Egypt as slaves but respected people  - He became the tool to fulfilling God's plan for the children of Israel  - He was seen as one who saved the Hebrew and they had better life until the new Pharaoh came into power.  -  As a result of interpreting Pharaoh's dreams, it also brought about the fulfilment of his dream that his brothers and family will bow down to him  - The interpretation of Pharaoh's dreams made it visible that Joseph had leadership skills  - The interpretation of Pharaoh's dream helped him to reunite with his father Jacob before his death", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "Give an account of the meeting between Elijah and Obadiah.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 18 : 5 - 16.    Obadiah was sent by King Ahab to look for springs of water and valleys for the animals so that they might not die, because there was famine in the land of Samaria.     In search of these things, Ahab went to a different direction and Obadiah went to another direction. On their journey Obadiah met with Elijah, when Obadiah saw Elijah he recognized him and bowed at the feet of Elijah. Elijah then sent for Ahab. Elijah gave Obadiah an assurance that he will remain to see Ahab. To avoid being killed after Obadiah had explained how he fed one hundred prophets in the cave during Jezebel's persecution. Obadiah went to Ahab and delivered Elijah's Message. Ahab honored the call and appeared before Elijah saying \" Is it you, troubler of Israel?\" Elijah replied saying \" I have not troubled Israel but you have, and your father's house because you have forsaken the commandments of the Lord and followed Baal\".", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "What two lessons can be learnt from the encounter?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 18 : 5 - 16.    - The encounter taught that no sin committed by any one will go unpunished irrespective of who you are. This shows in the area where Ahab was punished with drought as a result   - The supremacy of God can not be subdued by any other being. He is a powerful God and reasons He was able to cause famine in the land.  - The encounter also taught that everyone recognizes the fact that God is a powerful God and that nothing is impossible for him to do. Reason why the unbelievers go to him when in need, just like Ahab had to call Elijah when he needed solutions to the famine that had befallen them.  - Learnt that the the prophets in Israel are respected. This was shown in the encounter by the way Obadiah reacted when he met with Elijah.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "State the content of the new covenant in   (i)   Jeremiah            (ii)  Ezekiel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Jeremiah 31: 31 - 34.      COVENANT IN JEREMIAH     Jeremiah had a message for the Isrealites who broke the convenant between their fathers and God.     Jeremiah sent them a message saying \" The days are coming, says the Lord, Judah, unlike that with their father, when they were led out of the land of Egypt, which they broke though he was their husband. By the new convenant, He will put this new law within them, and write it upon their hearts, I will be their God and they will be my people . For each man will no longer teach his neighbor and brother to know God who will be known by the least among them to the greatest, for He will forgive their iniquity and will remember their sins no more. This according to the Lord is immutable. Their cities shall be rebuilt and extended from the tower of Hananel to then corner gate, to the hill and their Valley shall be sacred to the Lord, protected and not overthroned or uprooted forever.     CONVENEANT IN EZEKIEL     This can be seen in Ezekiel 36 : 25 - 28.    The message passed across by Ezekiel came in that order to confirm that which Jeremiah brought to the people earlier. Ezekiel's message confirmed that of Jeremiah. Ezekiel came with a message saying that  He(God) will spinkle clean water upon Isreal and they shall be clean from their uncleanliness and idolatory. God promised giving Israel a new spirit removing the heart of stone and replacing with the heart of flesh, and  cause them to work in the statutes and be careful to observe his ordnances, live in the land given by their fathers and continue to be worshippers of God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM~~CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Outline five benefits of the covenants of Israel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Ezekiel 36 : 25 - 28 and Jeremiah 31: 31 - 34.  - God has prepared the new covenant to be embedded in the heart of people rather than the former where it was written on stones and tablets.  - According to the new Covenant, He(God) will their their and they will permanently be his people.  - The law will be unavoidable as no one will be able to claim not to know the law, the law will be known by everybody.  - God will be a merciful God and the Israelites will be forgiven of their sins.  -  As a result of the law being written  in their hearts the fear of the Lord will dwell among the people.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "What did Jesus teach about in any of the following during His sermon on the mount?  (i)  Earthly possessions           (ii)   Anxiety", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "EARTHLY POSSESSIONS     This can be seen in Matthew 6 : 19 - 24.    Jesus in His teaching told His followers not to put their treasures in earthly things where moths consume and robbers steal. He encouraged them to lay their treasures in heaven where it would be safe. According to Jesus, He said where you lay our treasures there your heart will be. Jesus then said that the eye is the light of the body, that if the eye is sound the whole body also will be full of light, but if the body is not sound the whole body would be full of darkness. Jesus then said, no man serve two masters at a time, he would either love one and hate one or he will be devoted to one and hate the other.     He then finished His teaching by saying that no one can serve God and mammon.     ANXIETY     This can be seen in Matthew 6 : 25 - 34.    Jesus also taught that one should be anxious over nothing, one shouldn't be anxious in life over what they shall eat or drink. He also said that they should not be anxious over their body and what they shall put on.      According to the teaching, Jesus said that life is more than food and clothing. He also that even the birds of the air neither sow or gather, but are fed by God. He then said that human beings are higher than the birds of the air but we still worry and are anxious over everything. He then asked a question if being anxious can add one cubit to ones life or stature. He further layed more emphasis about our anxiety on clothing saying that even the grasses get clothed by Him, how much more we humans. He then encouraged that we should have more faith in God by referring to us as \"men of little faith\".     Lastly Jesus said that we will should seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness and other things shall be added.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "In what five ways can the misuse of wealth lead to serious consequences for a nation?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Creates bad relationship between the poor and the rich.  - He makes the poor live a life in total allegiance to the rich.  -  It leads to the increased love of things of the world as the poor struggle to be like the rich and the rich struggle to remain rich.  - It leads to people not caring for one another, all people will work for will be for themselves alone. Selfishness would take a hold of the people.  -   It increases the gap between the rich and the poor.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Relate the encounter between Jesus and the three would-be disciples.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 8 : 18 - 22.    Jesus and His disciples were walking down the road when a certain man from the scribes asked that Jesus should allow him to follow Him(Jesus).  Jesus replied him saying \" Foxes have holes, birds of the air have nests, but the son of man has no where to rest his head\"\"  Then Jesus spoke to another man \" Follow me\" and the man said '' I will follow you but first let me go and sa goodbye to my people\" Then Jesus replied and said to him \" No one puts his hand in the plough and looks back is fit for the Kingdom of God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Mention any three demands of discipleship", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- A disciple must have total trust in God and must not be biased about his faith  - A disciple must put up with the habit of putting God first in whatever they do  -  A disciple must be willing to serve God and render service to man through the spirit and commandment of God  - Anyone who is willing to work as a disciple of God must be disciplined  - As a disciple you must always seek first the kingdom of a God  - As disciples we should do away with procrastinating the things and work of God  - Anyone who is called to be a disciple of God must not discriminate or hate anyone.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Narrate the story of the transfiguration.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 17 : 1 - 13 and  Mark 9 : 2 - 13    Jesus, Peter, James and John went up to a mountain there He was transfigured before them. His face was very bright and shined like light while His gown was as white as snow. In their presence James, John and Peter saw Elijah and Moses talking to Jesus about His departure. At this time, Peter and John and James were asleep but were awake to see His glory with then two persons.     Then Peter said \" Jesus it is good that we are here, let us build three booths, one for you, one for Moses and one for Elijah. As Peter still spoke a cloud  very bright came upon them, this made them afraid. Then they heard a voice from Heaven say unto them \" This is my beloved son in whom i am well pleased, listen to Him\". Immediately, the disciples fell on their faces and worshiped Him. Jesus asked them to stand up and not fear but tell no one what they have seen until when the son of man rises from the dead.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Give three points of significance in this story", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 17 : 1 - 13 and Mark 9 : 2 - 1    - One of the significance is that this was an encouragement for the task ahead for Jesus to carry on.  - At this point the disciples were assured of their doubts that Jesus was truly the Son of God.  - When Moses and Elijah appeared, it gave a sign that Jesus Christ came to fulfil the law and not abolish it.  - The disciples learnt more about Jesus Christ and his purpose on the earth, when they were asked not to reveal what they say till Jesus rises from the dead.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "What event led to the appointment of seven deacons in the early church?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Act 6 : 1 - 15    Hellenist murmured against the Jews for not allowing them to participate in the daily distribution of food. This caused a lot of problem in the early church, till the apostles found a solution to it. The apostles said to the people that is not going to be possible for them to engage in preaching and at the same time sharing and distributing the food. So they asked that honourable and reputable men who were filled with the Holy Spirit and have a wisdom enough to handle the task be chosen.  In the end, seven men were selected by the church and handed over to the apostles who prayed for them.     These were the seven Deacons of the early church, one of them was Stephen.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "What three lessons can Christians learn from this episode?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Act 6 : 1 - 15    - The reliability of the Church was increased as the appointment of the seven Deacons was able to curtail the murmuring in the church and it enabled them to concentrate more on the gospel.  - The Deacons helped the apostles in the jobs that arose in the church relieving them of several obligations and duties..  - It ended discrimination in the church among the Jews and Gentiles.  - Immediately the Deacons were appointed it helped the church become peaceful as everyone had the rights to get what they wanted.  - The appointment of the Deacons also helped end  favouritism within the church.  - As a result of the appointment of the Deacons the apostles were able to concentrate more on the word of God without distraction.  - The appointment enabled the gospel to spread to all Jerusalem, Samaria and Africa through Ethiopia.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "What was Paul's counsel concerning the use of spiritual gifts in the church", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1 Corinthians 12 : 1 - 31 and Romans 12 : 6 - 8    Paul in his teaching about spiritual gifts stated that, spiritual gifts are are gifts of grace from the Lord, as in born talents bestowed on us as humans by God himself.  According to him the spiritual gifts can be tested through checking if the person say \" Jesus is Lord\" it is of the God but if the person says \" Jesus is cursed\" it is of the devil.   Paul enlisted nine spiritual gifts which includes:   i.    Utterance of wisdom  ii.   Utterance of Knowledge  iii.   Faith  iv.   Healing Power  v.   Miracle Working  vi.   Prophecy  vii.  Differentiating between spirits.  viii.  Speaking in tongues and interpreting of tongues.    Paul then further explained this spiritual gifts by comparing it with the human body and its parts, Paul said that the whole parts of the human body have a very important role that it plays and this specific roles can't be carried out by other parts. If a part of the body is not available to carry out that important role, no other part can do it, the whole parts of the body work together. God has created the whole parts of the body to work in relationship with one another to make the body perfect just as He had wanted it to be. According to him, some weaker parts are granted with greater respectability to avoid misunderstanding in the body. If one body rejects the entire body suffers. So also with spiritual gifts, they work hand in hand with one another.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "THEME FROM SELECTED EPISTLES     List three ways in which spiritual gifts are misused today", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1 Corinthians 12 : 1 - 31 and Romans 12 : 6 - 8    (i)    The use of spiritual gifts today includes to carry out preposterous acts in church which causes disunity and misunderstanding in the church.  (ii)    The use of spiritual gifts to exhort people of their money and also enslave the people.  (iii)    The use of spiritual gifts by occults claiming it is the power of God at work in the house of God.  (iv)    Witchcraft powers prophesy too and perform wonders, this in come cases conflicts one another and people end up being confused because not everybody has the spiritual inclination to discern when the spirit of God is at work.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Highlight the teaching of Paul on Christian giving as contained in Corinthians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Corinthians 9 : 1 - 15    - By giving they will receive riches and blessings from God for their good works.  - God will increase the fruit and what they reap from their land, multiply their resource and increase the harvest of their land  -  According to Paul's teaching, God will release to the cheerful givers his blessing and that they will have enough to make them give more.  -   Giving also encourages others to give just like the Macedonians also learnt how to give when they saw the Corinthians do so.  - Paul employed them to individually and willingly contribute what they have originally decided to give in his mind.  -  He taught that if you sow sparingly you will reap sparingly but if you sow bountifully you will reap bountifully.  - This serves as a test to the Christian life oof every Christian.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "In what two ways can people benefit from giving?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Corinthians 9 : 1 - 15    - By giving, we help solve problems that abounds in the life of the receiver.  - It increases unity among the people and make them believe in one another.  - Giving is a way of giving hope to those that have lost hope in the society.  - It increases peace and love in the church.  - It can also help grow human efficiency through the offering of training skills and also awards of scholarship.  - It will enhance stability in the economic and personal status of the people and country.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Give Paul's teaching on \" dignity in labour\"  in Thessalonians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 1 - 18.    Paul got the news of how some Thessalonians  refused to work on account of their imminence of the Parousa, so they became lazy and prevented others from working and also denied them of bread.   Paul wrote against this in his letter and commanded the Thessalonian believers to stay away from any person among them that refused to work. Paul told them that he didn't defraud anyone but worked hard to earn his living. Despite the fact that he had the right to do so as a Preacher of the word to depend on them but he has chosen to live an exemplary life by working hard. Paul then instructed the people that whosoever choose not to work should not eat. He later encouraged the lazy Thessalonians to work hard to earn a living, after which he passed a judgement that anyone who refuses to work and obey what the letter has instructed should be isolated.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "What four lessons can be derived from the teaching?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 1 - 18    - As a Christian you must be hardworking and be honest in what you do.  - Not doing anything is a sin and create an avenue for the devil to come into ones life.  - When you have work doing, it makes people respect you.  - As Christians we were taught in Paul's teaching not to encourage idleness by giving alms to the lazy people.  - Idleness brings shame and disrespect to man.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Highlight James teaching on  faith  and  works", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Hebrews 11 : 1 and James 2 : 14 - 26    According to the Bible, Faith is the substance of things hoped for and evidence of things not seen, for by this the men of old gained approval. James in his teachings on faith called upon christians to be not only the hearers of the word but also the doers of them. He also taught that they christians should do away with deceit.  He then continued by letting them know that  (ii)      faith is the foundation upon which christianity was built, true christianity requires practical manifestation ones faith by obeying the word of God in totality.  (ii)      By faithfully practicing what the word of God states without doubt.  (iii)     By withdrawing from doing evil to others and saying bad words against them.  (iv)     He also showed being faithful by doing that which the word of God teaches.  (v)     By living a life that is christ-like just as we are called christians for being like Christ.  (vi)    One's work can prove ones faith  (vii)    James concluded that as the body apart from the spirit is dead so faith without work is dead.     James made the believers to realize that anyone who doesn't keep to all what was stated with his faith cannot be a true child of God, he's just the hearer of the word alone and not the doer.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2010>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2010", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "What two lessons can Christians learn from the teachings?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Hebrews 11 : 1 and James 2 : 14 - 26.    - Learnt that as a Christian we should'nt speak bad about others.  - When you give advice to people we should also learn as Christians to put in effort to make it work out.  - Every Christian should be a worker in the house of God.  - As Christians we should endeavour to help the poor and the needy.   - Hardwork pays  - Anyone that doesnt work is a Lazy person  - Christians should introduce training, scholarship and teachings that will help people become independent and hardworking to be able to provide for themselves.  - Christians should obey the authority above them.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "Highlight the main features of God's covenant with Abraham.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 17 : 1 - 21.   - God told Abram to obey Him, work before Him and also be blameless.  - God said He would establish His covenant with Him, and with his descendants.  - God said He will multiply him exceedingly and he'll father many nations.  - God said Abram will posses all the land of Canaan.  - God asked that every male child must be circumcised on the eight day.  - God also said that every uncircumcised male should be cut off because he had broken the covenant.  - God now changed Abram's name to Abraham and Sarai's name to Sarah.  - God promised Abraham that Sarah will be blessed with a son and she'll also be a mother of Nations.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "State three reasons for covenant relationships.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "A covenant is a sacred agreement between God and His children. God sets specific conditions, and He promises to bless us as we obey these conditions.   - Covenants help to define and help consecration and commitment to the conditions.  - Obedience to conditions of covenants brings materials blessing.  - Obedience can also lead to change in life's situation and circumstances.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Explain the circumstances that led to the rejection of Saul as the King of Israel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Samuel 15.  - God told Saul that He was going to punish the Amalekites for their opposition to the Israelites on their way from Egypt to the land of Cannaan.  - God told Saul to utterly destroy the Amalekites, both man and woman and every other living thing.  - Saul and his army attacked the Amalekites in battle but he spared the life of Agag, their king and the best animals (sheep and oxen).  - Saul only destroyed what he felt was bad and worthless.  - God spoke to Samuel  that Saul has not obeyed His commandment.  - Samuel confronted Saul, but Saul defended it saying he spared the best to sacrifice it to God.  - Samuel promptly condemned his actions, and told him that God had rejected him.  - As Samuel turned to go, Saul held on to his skirt which tore in the process, which led Samuel to say  God has torn the Kingdom of Israel from him and given it to another.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Mention two consequences of Saul's rejection as king.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Samuel 16    - God led Samuel to anoint someone else, David, as king.  - God's spirit left Saul and an evil spirit tormented him.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Give an account of the report of the spies Moses sent to the land of Canaan.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Numbers 13 : 16 - 33    God instructed Moses to send out spies, 12 in number to spy Canaan to assess her land's fertility and militay capabilities.  When they returned after 40 days, they gave some good reports about the land being very productive and fertile.     However, 10 out of the 12 spies gave bad and discouraging reports about the land being filled with giants, and that the Isrealites were like grasshoppers to them and cannot defeat them. Only Joshua, the son of Nun and Caleb, the son of Jephunneh warned them not to fear, that they were able to possess it.  The bad report prevailed and the camp of Israel heard it and were discouraged.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Identify two lessons than can be drawn from this incident.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- We humans see and appraise situations based on our faith and courage.  - We must be bold, trust in God and always remember how we might have helped us in negative situations in time past.  - We must see situations as God sees them, i.e  we must have faith in God.  - We must not allow people's opinion of situations discourage us from doing what God wants us to do.  - There are consequences for not having faith in God.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Outline the main issues Jeremiah addressed in his prophesy of doom to Israel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The book of Jeremiah has many major themes within it. Judgement is one of the more notable ones. The majority of Jeremiah's oracles against Israel were messages of judgement, yet always in the context of repentance being possible. The main issues to be judged were   - Israel's forsaking God and going after idols.  - Israel's forgetting God's help in time past.  - High level of injustice and oppression of the poor and disadvantaged.  - Sexual immorality, adultery and perversion.  - Corruption, oppression, robbery and civil disobedience.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Indicate two quantities exhibited by Jeremiah that is worthy of emulation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Humility - Jeremiah humbled himself so God could fill him and use him.  Boldness - He was very bold to deliver God's message in spite of the evils in the society then.  Obedience - He was obedient to deliver the message.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Give an account of the Mission of the Seventy.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 10 : 1 - 24  Jesus sent out the Seventy disciples.   - There were to go two by two.  - There were to go into every town and village He was to visit Himself.  - He warned them that He was sending them out as lambs in the midst of wolves.  - They were to carry no purse, bag or sandals.   - They were not to greet anyone as they went.  - Whichever house or town they were accepted, they should stay and accept any hospitality offered them.  - Whichever house or town they were rejected, their peace will return to them and that they should shake off the dust of their sandals as a witness against the city.  - Their message should be that the Kingdom of God is near.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "What two problems are encountered by evangelists today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Hostility from town and countries that don't want the gospel. This leads to persecution, imprisonment and death.  - Lack of finance and donations to travel and meeting their personal and operational needs e.g purchase of bibles for free distribution, audio equipments   - Poor living conditions in areas where they have to evangelize e.g rural areas with no good drinking water.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "What did Jesus teach about Himself as the True Vine?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 15 : 1 - 9    Jesus wanted His friends, not only those eleven, but those of all time, to know that He was not going to desert them, even though they would no longer enjoy His physical presence. His living energy—His spiritual reality—would continue to nourish and sustain them just as the roots and trunk of a grape vine produce the energy that nourishes and sustains its branches while they develop their fruit.    Jesus went on to remove any misunderstanding about what He meant (John 15:4). He said that no branch can even live, let alone produce leaves and fruit, by itself. Cut off from the trunk, a branch is dead. Just as a vine's branches rely on being connected to the trunk from which they receive their energy to bear fruit, Jesus' disciples depend on being connected to Him for their spiritual life and the ability to serve Him effectively.     Then Jesus underscored His point even more strongly by saying, \"Apart from me you can do nothing\" (John 15:5). This illustration of the vine and branches is no thoughtless generality or careless simile. It is absolute, stark reality. No believer can achieve anything of spiritual value independently of Christ Jesus. He also reminds us that there are some who are \"in\" Him who bear no fruit. But these are not, as some would suppose, true branches that just happen to be fruitless. All true branches bear fruit. Just as we know a healthy, living tree by the good fruit it produces, so do we recognize fruitless branches as having no connection to the True Vine.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what three ways is this teaching significant to Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jesus is the source of vitality and life  - Christians must follow Jesus to live very productive lives.  - Christians that abide in Jesus can ask and it will be given unto them.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Describe the mission of Peter in Lydia and Joppa.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Acts 9 : 32 - 43    In Lydda, God uses Peter to heal a man named Aenas who had been bedridden for eight (8) years. This mircale made residents of Lydda and Sharon to believe and turn to God.     At Joppa, a disciple named Tabitha or Dorcas dies. Other disciples then send for Peter to come over from Lydda when they hear he is there. When he comes, they show him her good works of charity. Peter then goes to where Dorcas' body is laid, prays and commands her to arise. She opens her eye and sits up. Peter then calls the saints and present her to them alive. This makes many Joppa residents also believe and turn to God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "State three lessons that can be learnt from this mission.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Miracles and healing can convert a lot of people to the gospel.  - The power of God through the name of Jesus Christ heals and makes alive.  - Doing good works and charity can speak for one in negative situations. That was moved the disciples at Joppa in the case of Dorcas.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Highlight the story of the cleaning of the Temple in the Gospel of Matthew.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 21 : 12 - 17    Jesus and his disciples travel to Jerusalem for Passover, where Jesus expels the merchants and money changers from the Temple, accusing them of turning the Temple into a den of thieves through their commercial activities.      In anger, Jesus overturned their tables and chased them away. The blind and lame then came to Him and He healed them, but when the Cheif Priest and the scribes saw the wonderful things He did and the children shouting \"Hossanna to the son of David\", they were indignant and asked Jesus \"Do you hear what these children are saying?\". Jesus replied \"Yes, have you never heard, out of the mouth of babes and sucklings, God has brought forth praise\". Jesus then left to Bethany.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "In what two ways is the Church defiled today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Church leaders turning the church to a money-making venture by exploiting members.  - Members treating the religious and spiritual issues with levity and contempt.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Outline the arguments used by Paul to defend the Resurrection.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Corinthians 15 : 12 - 34    Paul outlined the following facts to drive home the truth about the resurrection of Jesus Christ.    - He reminded them on his early teaching about the subject. He said that he delivered the doctrine as he had received it.    - He also told them how Jesus appeared to his disciples after His resurrection, including Peter, James and five hundred others.    - Paul also mentioned how Jesus appeared to him though he was the least of all apostles.    He argued that Jesus couldn't have been raised if there was no resurrection and that if He was not raised, then his preaching and those of others were in vain and that would render their faith useless and make them remain in sin.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "In what three ways is the Resurrection significant to believers?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Resurrection represents Jesus eternal nature. He is the Beginning and the End; The Alpha and Omega.    - It shows His power and victory over death and other natural circumstances.    - It lays the foundation for eternal life. Life is eternal, and we believers are promised eternal life with Christ.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Outline the features of the new life in Christ as stated by Paul in Colossians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Colossian 3 : 1 - 7.    - Seeking those things which are above.    - Setting affection on things above and not on earthly things.    - We are dead to this world and alive to Christ, appearing in His glory.    - We should put off the old nature of sin such as fornication, uncleanness, inordinate affection, evil concupiscence, and covetousness, but rather put on the nature of the new man which is renewed in the knowledge of Christ.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "State three practices which can have negative effect on the Christian Community.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Ambition to hold positions.    - Lust for power and money.    - Lack of love.    - Bearing of false witness.    - Envy and jealousy.    - Worldliness and following patterns of the world.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight Peter's advice to Christians living among non-Christians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter also pointed out that believers are \"aliens and strangers\". A believer is a foreigner and pilgrim living without a permanent home or citizenship. He only temporarily lives in this world and is not to participate in its ungodliness. Peter said, \"Keep your behavior excellent among the [unsaved], so that . . . they may on account of your good deeds, as they observe them, glorify God in the day of visitation. The Lord uses a holy life to draw the lost to Christ. When unbelievers become Christians, they glorify God.     As believers, we're to have proper relationships with others in part to evangelize the lost (1st Peter 2:13 - 3:12). That involves how we relate to those in positions of authority (1st Peter 2:13-20), our spouse (1st Peter 3:1 - 7), other believers (1st Peter 3:8 - 13), and everyone in general.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "In  what three ways can Christians promote good relationship with non-christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- We must live good lives that is worthy of emulation by non-christians. Our lifestyle must portray Christ so that other can see.    - We must show love and care to others.    - We are called to preach the gospel to non-believers.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "According to Peter, what should be the Christian attitude in the face of persecution?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "First, Peter wanted the persecuted believers to know their identity as Christians. At the beginning of the section he identified them as \"chosen\" and toward the end he identified them as \"a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for God's own possession\". Knowing their identity encouraged the believers to \"proclaim the excellencies\" of God, who called them out of sin to live righteously.     After speaking of our identity in Christ and our relationship to society, Peter then explains how to live securely in an unfriendly society. A believer needs to arm himself with a trust in the power of righteousness to triumph over persecution and suffering. During times of hostility, we're to have confidence, not be in turmoil.     The early church experienced great persecution, but that's not the case for the contemporary church in most of the world. Physical persecution exists in some parts, but in our nation it's not as overt and aggressive as that. However, there seems to be a mounting hostility toward Christianity in our society. Many non-Christians treat immorality as an alternate lifestyle and believe man can solve his problems in whatever way he chooses. Christians in our nation can expect to face increasing hostility from personal and governmental levels.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2011>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2011", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "State three types of persecution Christians may encounter today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Insults and assaults.    - Denial of our rights.    - False accusations.    - Being taken for granted.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Explain how Moses became the son of Pharoah's daughter.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Exodus 2 : 1 - 10    Moses was born at a time Isrealites were slaves in Egypt. He was born to Hebrew parents, Amram and Jochobed at time Pharaoh ordered that all male children born to Hebrews must be killed. At birth, his mother hid him in the river for 3 months.    Pharaoh's daughter then came to the river to bath, and saw him and had compassion on him. Moses' sister, who probably was standing by rushed to her asked that she got a nurse for her. Pharoah's daughter agreed, and so she went to call Moses' mother to nurse the child. When the child grew, he was taken to the palace where he was named \"Moses\" meaning \"drawn from water\" and he became the son of Pharaoh's daughter.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Explain in three ways how this prepared Moses for his future leadership role.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Moses was able to see the suffering of his people firsthand.    - It made him compassionate.    - It also made him a bold and courageous leader.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "Narrate the story of David's sin against Uriah", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Samuel 11 and 12.    David committed Adultery with Bathsheba, Uriah's wife and she discovered she was pregnant. When David knew, he sent for Uriah to come home from battle. David then asked him to go home, probably so he could be with his wife and thus transfer the pregnancy to him. Uriah declined to go home. David then decided to send him back to battle, but with a letter to Joab, the Army commander that Uriah should be put in position where the battle was tough and,  then he should be isolated. This was done, and Uriah was killed. After mourning her husband, Bathsheba became David's wife.    God was displeased with this and sent Nathan to him, and he pronounced God's judgement against him.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "What two lessons can Christians learn from this incident?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Sin of adultery and murder are grievous sins.    - Unconfessed sins can lead to many other sins.    - Sin has very negative consequences.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Describe King Nebuchadnezzer's attack on Judah.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Kings 24.    When King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon defeated Neco of Egypt and Babylonians took over Judah. Jehoiakim became a puppet of Babylon. He then rebelled against the Babylonians and this made Nebuchadnezzar to attack Judah repeatedly to weaken her. Later. Nebuchanezzar sent an army to Judah but he died before they arrived.    Jehioachim, his 18 year old son was placed on the throne. Within 3 months, he surrendered to Nebuchadnezzar. The temple was ransacked by Nebuchadnezzar and all its treasures were taken by the Babylonians. The king, high officials and skilled men were deported to Babylon where Jehoiachim died.    21 year old Zedekiah was made king of the remnants of Judah but he rebelled against Nebuchadnezzar. He fled but was captured and brought before King Nebuchadnezzar in Riblah. His sons were killed before him. His eyes were also plucked out before he was later executed.    A Babylonian army commander now came to Jerusalem to burn the house of the Lord, the King's house and all the good buildings and then  take all the able men into captivity to Babylon. He left the poor people to be vine dressers and plough men in Jerusalem.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "List four effects of war on a nation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Great destruction of life and property.    - Homelessness and wide-spread poverty.    - Famine and food shortage.    - Breakdown of law and order.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "State three criticisms Isaiah made against Israel's system of worship.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Isaiah 1 : 10 - 15    - He addressed them as if there were people of Sodom and Gomorrah.    - He criticised their burnt offering of rams, fat of beasts and blood of bullocks, lambs or goats.    - He also criticised their vain oblations and incense burning.    - He condemned their sabbaths and calling of assemblies.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "What three suggestions did Isaiah give for Israel's return to God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He advised them to make themselves clean.    - They should put away their evil doings and cease to do evil.    - They must learn to do well, seek judgement and relieve the oppressed.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>4>c", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "c", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "In what three ways can your country return to God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- They must do away with idolatrous worship, and worship God in spirit and truth.    - They must stop oppressing the poor and showing partiality to the rich.    - They most do away with worldliness and vain acts.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MARK 1: 16-20; 2: 13-17", "question": "Narrate Jesus' encounter with the Gerasene demoniac.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 8 : 26 - 40    Jesus and his disciples went to the country of the Gerasenes, opposite Galilee. There was a man who had demons and lived naked in a cemetery. When he saw Jesus, he cried out, fell down and said with a loud voice \"What have I to do with thee, Jesus, thou Son of God most high. I beseech thee, torment me not\". He cried out this way because Jesus had commanded the unclean spirit to come out of him. Jesus then asked for his name and he replied \"Legion\" for the demons in him were many.  The demons implored Jesus not to send them into the bottomless pit but that they enter a herd of swine nearby. Jesus allowed them The devils went out, and then the herd ran violently down a steep place into the lake and were choked to death.    On seeing what happened, the swine keepers went to tell the people in the city, who came out and saw the previously mad man in his right sense and clothed. They were afraid, and they begged Jesus to leave their country.    Jesus left, but the healed and begged to follow Jesus. Jesus declined but asked him to go home and share with people what He did for him.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "In what two ways can the society improve the conditions of mental patients?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Providing them with proper medical care in the hospital.    - Providing them with spiritual care and prayers.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Narrate the trial of Jesus before Pilate and the Roman authorities as recorded in Matthew.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 27 : 11 - 26.    While before Pilate, Jesus was asked whether He was the King of the Jews.. He answered in the affirmative. He was then accused by the chief priests and elders, he answered nothing. Pilate then asked Jesus why He remained silent in spite of all the allegation levelled against Him, yet He didn't answer. There was a custom that a prisoner would be released by the governor during the feast so Pilate asked if he could release Jesus or Barabbas, because he knew Jesus was only arrested out of envy. It was also at this time that Pilate's wife sent a message that he shouldn't have anything to do with Jesus, the righteous man.    The people, under instruction of the chief priest and elders asked that Barabbas be released and Jesus be crucified. Pilate then washed off his hand and delivered Jesus to be crucified.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Give two reasons why Pilate was wrong in condemning Jesus to death.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Pilate even said that he didn't find Jesus guilty of anything worthy of death.    - He had facts that the Jesus was only accused because of envy.    - His wife even testified that Jesus was a just man.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Describe Phillip's missionary activities in Judea and Samaria.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Acts 8 : 5 - 40    Phillip went to Samaria and proclaimed the gospel to them and many were converted when they heard him and saw the signs that he did as he was able to cast out demons and heal the paralysed. There in Samaria, he converted Simon, the magician who had been deceiving many people into believeing he has the great power of God. After Phillip's preaching, the people deserted Simon and followed him, and based on this Simon also got converted and baptized.    The apostles, who later heard of the success of Phillip sent Peter and John to encourage the new converts.    From Samaria, God directed Phillip towards Gaza where he met an Ethiopian Eunuch, a minister of Candace, the Queen of the Ethiopians returning home after worshipping in Jerusalem. God directed him to join the Eunuch in his chariot which he did. Phillip then explained to him the bible verse he was reading and preached the good news of Jeus to him, and later baptized him.     As they continued on their way, the Bible says that Phillip was caught up by the Lord, and was found at Azotus while the Eunuch continued on his way.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "State three problems facing the work of evangelism in your country.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Lack of funding for spiritual and materials need.    - Hostility by the community or town to be evangelized.    - Materialism.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "Describe the healing of the man at the pool of Bethesda.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 5 : 2 - 9.    There was a pool called Bethesda, just by the Sheep gate in Jerusalem. There was a multitude of sick people there and one of them was a man paralysed for thirty-eight years. When Jesus saw him, he asked if he wanted to be healed. The man replied that there was no one to take him into the pool, because at a certain time, the angel of God stirs the water and anyone who steps in first would be healed. Jesus asked him to take up his bed and walk. The man was made whole immediately and took up his bed and walked.    When the Jews saw the man carrying his bed, they accused him because it was the Sabbath. The man told them that it was Jesus that told him to do it. When asked to identify the man that told him to do so, he couldn't because Jesus had walked away.    Jesus later saw him in the temple and warned him to sin no  more or a greater evil will befall him. The man then told the Jews that it was Jesus that healed him and they accused Jesus for healing on the Sabbath. Jesus simply told them that since God, His Father is working, He too is working.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND POWER", "question": "State two reasons why Jesus performed the healing miracle.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- To show that He is a compassionate God.    - To fulfill His divine mandate on earth, part of which was to heal.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Outline the qualities of a new life in Christ as contained in Paul's letter to the Colossians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Colossian 3 : 1 - 7.    - Seeking those things which are above.    - Setting affection on things above and not on earthly things.    - We are dead to this world and alive to Christ, appearing in His glory.    - We should put off the old nature of sin such as fornication, uncleanness, inordinate affection, evil concupiscence, and covetousness, but rather put on the nature of the new man which is renewed in the knowledge of Christ.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "List four qualities of a genuine Christian.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- A Christian must show love.    - A Christian must be joyful.    - A Christian must be committed to doing what is right, true and fair.    - A Christian must be generous in deed and preach the gospel.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight Paul's advice to the Thessalonian church on the matter of idleness.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 6 - 18.    Paul command the Thessalonians Christians to avoid any lazy person among them. He reminded them that he did not extort money from any one but worked hard to earn his living. Paul told them that he had a right as a Preacher to depend on them for maintenance, but has chosen to work in order to set an example for them. He had earlier instructed that anyone who is not willing to work should not eat. He commanded and encouraged lazy ones to work hard and earn their living. He advised them not to be fed up in well-doing. He also advised anyone who refuses to obey the instruction in this letter to be isolated. Such a lazy fellow should not be regarded as an enemy but rather should be warned as a brother.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "State three consequences of idleness in the society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Idle people place a burden on the society, both financially and physically.    - Being idle open one up to be used as a vice for evil activities.    - Idleness reduces one's ability to fend for oneself.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Explain Paul's teaching that Christians are children of God through Christ.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Romans 6 - 7 and Galatians 3 - 4    Every man was under the law and kept under restraint until faith was revealed. The law was our custodian until Christ came that we may be justified by faith. Now that faith has come, we are no longer custodians to the law, for in Christ, we are all sons of God through faith. The teaching implies that Christians owe their sonship to God through Jesus who reconciled believers to God in faith.    Through Baptism, the believers in Christ has put on Christ. A believer become one in Christ Jesus, whether Jew or Gentile. Now Christ believers are Abraham's children, heirs according to promise and not according to law. As a young heir remains under guardians and trustees until the date set by his father, so believers as babes were formerly slaves to the elemental spirits of the world. At the appointed time, God sent forth his son, born of a woman, born under law so that believers might receive adoption as sons. Now that Christians are adopted as sons, God has sent the spirit of his son into their hearts so they boldly call God \"Father\". Hence, through God, Paul explained, Christians are no longer slaves but sons if sons are heirs.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Give three implications of this doctrine of sonship of God.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Chrstians have been redeemed by Jesus Christ from the curse of the law.    - A christian today is now a Son of God through Jesus Christ.    - We have access to God the Father, through Jesus Christ.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "With reference to first Peter, how should Christian leaders relate to their followers?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Peters 5 : 1 - 4    Peter advised elders to to look after God's flock with tender care. They should work not as being under any external constraint but willingly; not with the desire to make material gains with a presumptious and domineering spirit but as examples to be copied by the flock, so that at the appropriate time, they might attain the crown of glory.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2012>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2012", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "State any three problems which confront Christian leaders today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Fighting for positions.    - Misunderstanding over doctrinal issues.    - Envy and jealousy.    - Stealing and misappropriation of church funds.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Give an account of Joshua's farewell address.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Joshua 24.     Joshua gathered all the tribes of Isreal together at Shechem and then he summoned the elders, heads, judges and officers of Israel before God and he delivered his farewell speech to them.    He told them the history of Israel from the time of Abraham down to Moses. He also told them of how God called Abraham, how Israel entered into slavery and how God delivered them and brought them to the promised land, giving them victories over various enemies; the Canaanites, the Amorites, the Moabites, Jericho, Perizzites, Hittites, Girgashite and Jebusites.    He called on them to worship and serve God due to His goodness and kindness to them. He asked them to show sincerity and faithfulness in service. He also asked them to put away strange gods and serve the Lord and the people also expressed their readiness to serve the Lord.    He then reminded them that God will punish unfaithfulness, and thereby cautioned them to be serious of their pledge. He now affirmed that he and his family will serve the Lord, and then asked them to choose whom they'll serve. They all confirmed their pledge to serve God and renewed the covenant by writing down the law. He then set a stone as witness against the people.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Outline two leadership qualities which he manifested during this occasion.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Joshua showed love and concern as a leader by assembling Israel to remind them on the need to be faithful to God.    - He also showed courage and foresight. It takes foresight in a leader to assemble and address his followers when about to exit the leadership stage.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Give an account of the healing of Naman.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Kings 5.    Naaman, a commander of the Syrian Army, was a leper. He a main servant who told him there was a prophet in Isreal who could cure him of his leprosy.  Naaman then told his king, who now gave him a letter to the king of Isreal. The king of Israel felt sad when he got the letter and thought it was just a way for the king of Syria to battle against him. Prophet Elisha heard about it and asked the king to send Naaman to him.    When Naaman came, the prophet just sent word that he should go and dip himself into the River Jordan seven times and he'll receive his healing. Naaman initially refused but later agreed. He got his healing, and then came back to the prophet to give gifts in appreciation. The Prophet Elisha refused it all and asked him to go in peace. Naaman got on his way, and also took some sand from Israel to Syria so he could worship the God of Isreal.    As Namaan was on his way, Gehazi acting out a plot caught up with him, telling him that his master, Prophet Elisha later asked for some gifts. Naaman gave him. When Gehazi got back, Elisha asked him where he had been, he lied. Elisha told him where he had been, and then cursed him and his family with the leprosy that Naaman was cured of.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "What three lessons can be derived from this story?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Blessing and healing can come our way from anybody, even those we feel are lower than us.    - God can heal us using His servants.    - Simple obedience is important for God to heal.    - Greed is a terrible sin that can lead to many problem.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "How was greed demonstrated in the life of Gehazi?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Kings 5.    Gehazi was the servant of the Prophet Elisha. After Naaman's healing, he offered gifts to the Prophet Elisha. He refused it, but Gehazi's didn' like it. After Naaman went, Gehazi ran after him and said that Elisha just had some visitors and would need some gifts. Naaman then gave him 2 talents and 2 festal garments.     When he returned, Elisha asked him where he had been, he lied but Elisha told him he had seen him. He cursed him that the leprosy of Naaman should be transferred to him and his family.     Gehazi actually lied to collect the gifts for himself which shows greed.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Give three areas in the society where greed is prevalent.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Educational institutions - Cheating by students.    Commercial institutions (such as markets) - Sellers inflating the prices or deceiving buyers by false measures.    Law enforcement officers - Collecting of bribes by officers such as policemen and judges.    Religious institutions - Pastors miss-appropriating church funds.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Highlight the message of Isaiah to the people of Judah.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Isaiah 1 : 10 - 15    - He addressed them as if there were people of Sodom and Gomorrah.    - He criticised their burnt offering of rams, fat of beasts and blood of bullocks, lambs or goats.    - He also criticised their vain oblations and incense burning.    - He condemned their sabbaths and calling of assemblies.    - He advised them to make themselves clean.    - They should put away their evil doings and cease to do evil.    - They must learn to do well, seek judgement and relieve the oppressed.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "In what two ways can Christians ensure God's holiness in their country?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- We must do away with idolatrous worship, and worship God in spirit and truth.    - We must stop oppressing the poor and showing partiality to the rich.    - We most do away with worldliness and vain acts.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Narrate the story of the healing of the paralytic.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew  9 : 1 - 8.    Jesus was preaching in a house in the city of Capernaum. People brought their sick ones to be healed by Jesus and the whole place was filled to capacity, and so a paralytic couldn't be brought in the normal way. His friends climbed up the stairs to the roof, removed part of the roof and let him down to where Jesus was preaching. When Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic \"My son, your sins are forgiven\".   This didn't go down well with certain scribes and Pharisees present and they challenged Jesus' power to forgive sins. They said it was a blasphemy as only God could forgive sins. Jesus corrected them and told them He had power on earth to forgive sins. He then proved to them that the paralytic had been healed by asking him to take his bed and go home. The man did as he was instructed.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "In what three ways is faith relevant to the Christian?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Faith is necessary to please God.    - Faith is important to God to heal us.    - Faith is essential in our prayers to God.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "\"...Who is my neighbour?...\" How did Jesus answer this question?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 10 : 25 - 37.     This question was asked by a lawyer. To answer this question, Jesus told them the parable of the good samaritan.  The parable goes thus.    A man, travelling from Jerusalem to Jericho was waylaid by robbers along the road who beat him, took all his belonging and left him half dead.    A priest came along the road, saw him but continued without helping him. Same for a levite, until a Samaritan came and saw the wounded man.    The samaritan treated him, bandaged his wounds and even took him to an inn and paid for the care of the man, telling them that should they incur cost in his absence, he'll pay when he comes back.    Jesus then asked the lawyer who was a neighbour to the man from the 3 example. The lawyer chose the samaritan, as the one who showed mercy on him. Jesus then told him to do as the samaritan had done.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "In what three ways can Christians show good neighbourliness?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- By showing love.    - By offering to help others in need.    - By comforting others in distress or anguish.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Summarize Jesus' teaching about himself as the Resurrection and the Life.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in John 11 : 25 - 27.    Lazarus, Jesus' friend was sick. He lived in Bethany. His sister, Mary and Martha sent for Jesus. Jesus came after 4 days, and by this time Lazarus had died and was buried. When he arrived, Martha came to meet Him. She told Him that if he was there, Lazarus won't have died.  She further added that she believes whatever Jesus asked God, God'll do it. Jesus then told her Lazarus will rise again. Martha replied that she knew Lazarus will rise on the resurrection day. Jesus then said to her \"I am the resurrection and the life. He who believes on me though He dies, yet he shall live and whosoever lives and believes on me shall never die\".", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Give two assurances Christians have in Christ as the Resurrection and the Life.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Christ resurrection from death is a strong basis for our gospel and faith in God.    -  It represents our eternal life, when we moved from life on earth to life in heaven.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Relate Luke's account of Jesus' appearance to the men going to Emmaus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 34 : 13 - 33.    Cleopas and his friend were on their way to Emmaus when Jesus met them. It was about 7 miles from Jerusalem.  He joined them in their discussion though they didn't know who He was. They told Him about the recent happenings in Jerusalem as regards Jesus' death and resurrection. Jesus then explained to them the necessity of it all. As they reached their destination, Jesus made to go further but they pleaded with him to stay as it was late. As they wanted to eat bread, Jesus broke it and gave them. Their eyes were opened immediately and then Jesus vanished from their sight.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "State two lessons that can be derived from this encounter.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jesus appearance showed He was alive. Even a lot of His disciples didn't believe He was alive.    - His appearance encouraged and strengthened their faith in Him and His words.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Highlight Peter's teaching on humility.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter's advise to on humility to youths was to be respectful to the elders and be clothed with humility because God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble.    He still urged them to be sober and vigilant because the devil sought to devour them. He advised them to resist him with faith in God, also knowing that other christians have experienced same suffering. He also urged them to cast their cares on the Lord and He will sustain them. He assured them that the grace of God who had called them to eternal glory by Christ Jesus will make them perfect.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Identify any three qualities of a humble person.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Respect for authority.    - Gentleness in action and in words.    - Selflessness in service.    - Uprightness and diligence.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>10>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight Peter's guidelines on Christian living among non-Christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter also pointed out that believers are \"aliens and strangers\". A believer is a foreigner and pilgrim living without a permanent home or citizenship. He only temporarily lives in this world and is not to participate in its ungodliness. Peter said, \"Keep your behavior excellent among the [unsaved], so that . . . they may on account of your good deeds, as they observe them, glorify God in the day of visitation. The Lord uses a holy life to draw the lost to Christ. When unbelievers become Christians, they glorify God.     As believers, we're to have proper relationships with others in part to evangelize the lost (1st Peter 2:13 - 3:12). That involves how we relate to those in positions of authority (1st Peter 2:13-20), our spouse (1st Peter 3:1 - 7), other believers (1st Peter 3:8 - 13), and everyone in general.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>10>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "What three challenges can Christians face among non-Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Insults and assaults.    - Denial of our rights.    - False accusations.    - Being taken for granted.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>11>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Outline Paul's teaching on Dignity of Labour.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 2nd Thessalonians 3 : 6 - 18.    Paul command the Thessalonians Christians to avoid any lazy person among them. He reminded them that he did not extort money from any one but worked hard to earn his living. Paul told them that he had a right as a Preacher to depend on them for maintenance, but has chosen to work in order to set an example for them. He had earlier instructed that anyone who is not willing to work should not eat. He commanded and encouraged lazy ones to work hard and earn their living. He advised them not to be fed up in well-doing. He also advised anyone who refuses to obey the instruction in this letter to be isolated. Such a lazy fellow should not be regarded as an enemy but rather should be warned as a brother.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>11>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "State two ways by which Christians should uphold this teaching.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- We must discourage laziness and associated attitudes.    - We must encourage members on the dignity of labour.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>12>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "Give James' exposition on partiality in the church.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in James 2.    James advised all Christians to do away with any act of partiality in the church. He specifically asked not to treat people based on their appearance and dressing as God honours those who are despised on earth but are humble and faithful in spiritual affairs because it is the earthly rich who are the oppressors of the faithful poor.     He then commanded that we fulfill the royal law of loving our neighbours as ourselves and hence all our actions and thought must be geared towards fulfilling law.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2013>12>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2013", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "Highlight three ways impartiality is promoted in our society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Merit-based appointment of public official.    - Merit-based and transparent awarding of contracts.    - Non-discrimination against tribe, sex or religion.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>1>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Describe God's creation of Light.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 1 : 4 - 5.    God created Light of the first day by saying \"Let there be light\" and then there was Light. God saw the Light was good and went ahead to separate the Light from darkness. He called the Light Day and the darkness Night.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>1>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Describe God's creation of Woman.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 2 : 21 - 23.    God realized that Adam still needed a helper. He then caused a deep sleep to fall on him and took a rib out of man, created woman and brought her to man. Adam now described her as \"the bone of his bone and the flesh of his flesh\" and called her \"Woman\".", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "In what three ways does creation reveal God's nature.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- God is omnipotent. He's the all powerful and supreme being.    - God made everything good and for His pleasure.    - He is a God of order and pattern.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Relate how Israel asked for a King to rule them.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Samuel 8.    Samuel made his sons, Joel and Abiah judges over Isreal as he became old. They however didn't walk in his ways. They took bribes and perverted justice.    The elders of Isreal then came to meet Samuel at Ramah. They told him his sons were not walking in his ways therefore he should appoint a king to govern over them and lead them to battle, just like their surrounding nations.    Samuel was displeased and prayed to God concerning it.  The Lord told him to listen to them, that it was Himself they rejected and not Samuel. Samuel rehearsed to them what the Lord told him concerning the manner of the king they'll have. The people still insisted on their request.    Samuel dismissed them, and later anointed Saul to become their king based on God's direction.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Identify four consequences of the King's disobedience to God.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He was rejected by God.    - He was replaced by God and a new king was anointed.    - God's spirit left him, and an evil spirit tormented him.    - He couldn't hear from God again so he went to consult a witch to conjure the spirit of the dead.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "What role did King Hiram of Tyre play in Solomon's preparation towards the building of the temple?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 5.    Hiram, the King of Tyre was friend to King David. When he heard that Solomon was anointed King in David's place, he sent words of friendship to him.    Solomon replied him, saying that David his father was unable to build a house for God because of the wars with which his enemies surrounded him with until the Lord put them under his feet.      Now Solomon told him that he purposed to build a house for God so Hiram should command that the cedars of Lebanon which are highlight valued for building palaces and temples should be sent to build the Temple of God. Solomon also promised to pay any wages Hiram will ask for.    When Hiram got the message, he was very happy and he supplied Solomon all the timber of cedar and cypress he desired. Solomon gave him wheat and oil for the provision of his household in return.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Indicate three benefits of making friends.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- To show care to one another.    - To protect one another.    - To share good things among one another.    - To teach and learn from one another.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Outline Amos' vision of a basket of ripe fruit.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Amos 8 : 1 - 14.    God showed Amos a basket of ripe fruits. It means that the time was ripe, and God would no longer spare His people Israel. In those days, the songs of thanksgiving for harvest would be turned to waiting. Joy would be turned off and silence of despair would exist.    Amos saw  the end of those who trampled upon the needy and bring the poor of the land to an end. Those who asked when the new moon would be over; so that they may sell grain and sabbath that they may offer wheat for sale that they may make the ephah small and shekel great, and deal deceitfully with false balances, tha they may buy the poor for silver and the needy for a pair of sandals.    The Lord swore by the pride of Jacob. Israel took pride in the fact that the Lord was her God.    The day of the Lord is described as one in which world order is disrupted and light is turned to darkness as if creation is being undone. God said He would their feast into mourning and their celebrations into sorrow. In that day, the fair virgins and the young men shall faint for thirst; both physical and spiritual thirst. The strength sapped, and even the lovely girls and strong boys of the nation will become useless.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "State three practices that Amos condemned.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He condemned traders who were involved in cheating.    - He spoke against judges and officers who perverted justice by taking bribes.    - He condemned oppression in the society.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MATTHEW 4: 18-25; 8: 18-22; 9:9-13 ;", "question": "Highlight Jesus' encounter with Matthew, the tax collector.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 9 : 9 - 3.    Matthew as a tax collector and at work when Jesus called him. He answered and followed Jesus. He invited Jesus and other tax collectors into his house. The Pharisees saw Jesus dining with the tax collectors and sinners and then challenged his disciples why Jesus was doing so. Jesus answered and said \"Those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick. Go and learn what this means, I desire mercy and not sacrifice, for I have not come to call the righteous but the sinners\".", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "What three lessons can be drawn from the encounter in (a) above.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jesus wants sinners to repent from their sins.    - Jesus doesn't discriminate against sinners or any class of people.    - Jesus wants to have mercy on us.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "What demands did Jesus make of the prospective disciples He encountered?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 8 : 19 - 22.    To the first disciple, Jesus said \"Foxes have holes and birds have nests, but the son of man has no where to lay His head\". To the second disciple, He said \" Follow me, and let the dead bury their dead\".    Overall, Jesus demanded His disciples to follow Him, without looking or turning back, saying that anyone that looks back is not fit for the Kingdom of God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Identify any three attitudes that true disciples of Jesus must exhibit.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "These are the attributes   - Love.    - Humility.    - Patience.    - Generous.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "Summarize Peter's speech on Pentecost day.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Acts 2 : 14 - 40.    After seeing the disciples speaking in new tongues, Peter had to tell the crowd that they were not drunk but rather, they were filled with the Holy Ghost, as it was prophesied by Prophet Joel. He went further to tell them how Jesus Christ who they crucified was raised from death by God, and had given them the Holy Ghost. The people were moved by the message and asked what they should do.    Peter advised them to repent and be baptized in the name of Jesus for the forgiveness of sins. It turned out that 3,000 people repented and were baptized that day.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "What three changes occurred in the life of the disciples after the coming of the Holy Spirit on the Pentecost day?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The Holy Ghost made them bold and fearless in proclaiming the gospel.    - They did miracles.    - They had power to heal the sick.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "\"Is any among you sick? Let him call for the church and let them pray over him\"    What else did James say about effective prayer?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in James 5 : 13 - 18.    James asked that anointing in the name of Jesus coupled with the prayer of faith will save a sick person and God raise up such person. If the person had committed sins, it will be forgiven.    James also asked Christians to confess their sins one to another and pray for one another so they might be healed. He said the prayer of a righteous man as great power in its effect. He mentioned the story of Elijah who prayed that it not rain for 3 and a half years,and it didn't, and then prayed that it rained, and it did.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Outline three reasons why some prayers are not answered.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Unconfessed sin.    - Asking amiss.    - Lack of faith.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Discuss how Peter exhorts Christians to be good citizens.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Peter 2 : 13 - 19.    Peter advised that a good citizen must submit to every ordinance for the Lord's sake. Good citizens are to show respect to rulers who have been put there by God to punish evil doers and praise the righteous. A good citizen  must also submit to the authority and guidance of God, and not use freedom as a cover-up for evil. A good citizen is to honour all men, love the brotherhood of believers, fear God and honour the rulers.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2014>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2014", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "In what three ways is Peter's exhortation to Christians significant?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It helps we Christians to be examples to the unbelievers.    - We are showing obedience to God by being good citizens.    - We are improving the society by being good citizens.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Highlight the problems encountered by Joseph with his brothers.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 37.    Jacob loved his second youngest son Joseph very dearly. Even as a young boy, Joseph had shown his great mental gifts and his piety. Joseph also grew up to be very wise and learned. The brothers were jealous of the special favors which their father bestowed upon young Joseph. With misgivings, they viewed Joseph's company when he joined them at the age of seventeen to become a shepherd like his brothers.    Thus the relationship between Joseph and his brothers became strained. This strained relationship was brought to a climax when Joseph began to tell about his dreams which, by their very nature, affirmed his brothers' fears that he aspired to rule over them. Once Joseph told them that he had dreamed he had been binding sheaves in the field, together with them, and that their sheaves had suddenly bowed before his own. On another occasion, Joseph told his brothers of having a dream in which the sun and the moon and eleven stars had paid their respects to him.    Jacob warned Joseph against telling such dreams to his brothers, and bade his sons to disregard these dreams, for he did not wish to see strife among them. In his heart, however, he knew that there was truth in Joseph's dreams, and that Joseph was destined to become a great and powerful ruler.    One day Joseph was staying home with his father, while his brothers were with the flocks near Shechem. For a long time Jacob had no news from his sons. Worried over their fate, he sent Joseph to find them and bring word from them. Wandering all over the fields in search of his brothers, Joseph met a man who told him that they had moved in the direction of Dothan. Joseph followed them and, indeed, found them there. From afar, Joseph's brothers saw him approach. They could not mistake his coat of many colors that their father had given him, and their jealousy was aroused. They threw him into a nearby pit. Reuben had planned to take him out eventually, and return him to his father, unharmed. In the meantime, Reuben went off to assist his father. But when he returned to the pit, Joseph was not there, for his brothers had sold him to a passing caravan of Ishmaelite merchants.    Joseph's brothers soon repented of their action. Unable to tell Jacob the truth, they slaughtered a goat and dipped Joseph's coat, which they had taken from him, into the blood. Then they sent the blood-stained garment to their father, telling him that they had found it. Jacob recognized the special garb he had made for Joseph, and thought that his favorite son had been torn to pieces by a wild animal. For many years Jacob mourned the loss of Joseph and refused to be consoled.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Indicate how Joseph and his brother were reconciled.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Genesis 42 - 45.    Not only was Egypt hit by: the famine, but also all the neighboring countries, Canaan among them. Many people from near and far came to Egypt to buy provisions, since only in the land of Egypt had the famine been anticipated and prepared for. Jacob therefore ordered his sons to go and buy food in Egypt.    Thus Joseph knew immediately when his ten older brothers arrived in Egypt to buy corn for their father's house. Only Benjamin did not come. Joseph had his brothers brought before him. Joseph recognized his brothers, but they did not recognize him, for when they had last seen him he was but a youngster, and it would have been difficult for them to imagine that this powerful royal personage was their own brother. Joseph thought of his dreams and of their jealous attitude towards him and decided to test them. Through an interpreter, so that they might not guess his identity, Joseph addressed them harshly  \"Where do you come from?\" And they said, \"From the land of Canaan to purchase food.\"     \"You are spies!\" Joseph accused them.    \"No, sir,\" they replied; \"your servants have but come to purchase food. We are twelve brothers and our father is in Canaan; the youngest is at home with our father, and one brother disappeared many years ago.\"    Joseph pretended that he was not convinced, and told his brothers that he would not let them go away till one of them went to fetch their youngest brother, to prove the truth of their words. Then he had them put into prison.    On the third day of their imprisonment, Joseph spoke to his brothers again. He told them that he would not keep them in prison any longer, and that in order that they might have an opportunity to prove their honesty, one of the brothers should remain in prison as a hostage. The rest, however, were instructed to return to Canaan with their food and to bring back their youngest brother. Joseph could not help overhearing his brothers' conversation, full of distress and regret. They believed that the trouble that had befallen them was a punishment from God for their heartlessness on that fateful day when they had thrown Joseph into the pit.    Joseph was overcome with love and pity for his brothers when he saw how sorry they were for their cruelty to him; he withdrew quietly and wept. Then he hardened himself, washed his eyes, and returned to his brothers with a look upon his face so harsh that it made them wince. He ordered his men to bind Simeon, who was next to the eldest. But Simeon terrified the men, and they were powerless to carry out Joseph's order. Thereupon, Manasseh, Joseph's oldest son, seized Simeon, and bound him. The brothers were taken back by the unusual strength of the young Egyptian prince. Such strength they thought possible only in a descendant of Jacob.    Having secretly ordered that the money his brothers had paid for the food be returned to their sacks, Joseph sent them away, warning them to bring their youngest brother with them the next time they came to Egypt.    The brothers thanked Joseph and left for Canaan, their mules packed with corn. On the way, they stopped at an inn. One of them opened his sack to take out some food for his animal, and was astonished to find that his money had been returned to him. Now they were even more frightened than before, because they felt that more trouble was in store for them.    Arriving home, they told their father everything that had happened. When they emptied the corn, they discovered all the rest of the money they had paid for it, in their sacks. Fear overcame everyone of them. When they told their father that they would have to take Benjamin with them to Egypt in order to save Simeon, he said in great distress, \"Joseph is gone, and Simeon is not here; now you want to take Benjamin away. If any mischief should befall him on the way, you will bring my gray head with sorrow to the grave. My son shall not go with you!\"    The provisions were used up and famine again threatened Jacob's household. Jacob asked his sons to return to Egypt to buy food (Genesis 43:4). \"If you send our brother with us, we cannot go to Egypt,\" Judah said, \"The man warned us repeatedly, saying, 'You shall not see my face if your brother is not with you!\"    Jacob did not conceal his great anxiety for Benjamin's safety, and finally Judah vouched with his own life for the safety of the boy. With starvation threatening the entire household, Jacob could no longer delay his sons' going to Egypt and permitted Benjamin to go with them. He told his sons to return the money they had found in their sacks, and advised them to take some fine presents for the ruler of Egypt. Then, he blessed them and sent them on their way.    When the brothers appeared before Joseph, and Joseph saw that Benjamin was among them, he told his representative to bring them into the house, and to prepare a meal for them. The man did so. Joseph's brothers were suspicious of the unexpected hospitality. They approached the supervisor and told him of the strange return of their money when they had first purchased food in Egypt. They assured him that they had brought the money back with them, together with more money for the new purchases. The supervisor allayed their fears, telling them that he had received the money, and that the money they had found in their sacks was a gift from God. Then he brought Simeon to them. Simeon told them how well he had been treated, and greatly relieved, they all sat down at the table.    When Joseph arrived, his brothers presented him with the gifts Jacob had sent him. He greeted them cordially and inquired after their aged father. Then he welcomed Benjamin; but on seeing his youngest brother, Joseph was overcome with emotion, and had to withdraw, so that his brothers might not see the tears that were about to burst forth from his eyes.    Returning to his brothers, Joseph presided over the feast. For the first time since they had sold Joseph, the brothers felt really merry and happy, for although they did not know it, there they were, all twelve of them together. Only Joseph knew, and he thought how well it was for brothers to live together in peace and harmony!    Many a time Joseph surprised them by his intimate knowledge of their personal lives. For instance, he seated them according to their age, and called them by their names. He pretended to get all this knowledge from his \"divine cup\" which he kept putting up to his ear, as if it were revealing many secrets to him. After the meal, Joseph gave them all presents; to Benjamin, however, he gave five times as much as to the others.    Joseph still wanted to see how much they were willing to sacrifice for one an other. After the meal, he told his supervisor to fill the sacks of his brothers with provisions, and again to put their money on top. His own \"magic\" cup, however, he ordered to be put in Benjamin's sack. The man carried out Joseph's orders, and the next morning, unaware of the plot, Joseph's brothers set out for Canaan, happy that everything had gone so well.    Hardly had they left the city, when the supervisor came riding after them and reprimanded them for stealing his master's \"divining cup.\" What ingratitude for the kindness with which he had treated them! In vain did they protest, reminding him that they had even returned the money they had found in their sacks the last time. Why should they now steal what belonged to his master? They agreed to have their belongings searched, and said that if one of them had stolen the cup, he would die, and that the others would serve as slaves.    The supervisor, however, said that the thief alone would be held responsible and taken into bondage, and that the rest could go home free.    Convinced of their innocence, the brothers unloaded their packs. The search began with the oldest and went down to the youngest. When Benjamin's sack was opened, the brothers were shocked. There the cup lay, mute evidence of a crime they knew Benjamin could not have committed. Tearing their clothes in great despair, the brothers decided they would stick together, one for all and all for one. How different they were now from what they had been many years earlier, when they had turned deaf ears to Joseph's plight!    All the brothers now returned to Egypt to try to save the innocent Benjamin.    When the brothers returned to Joseph, they fell down before him and proclaimed their innocence. They could not understand how such a thing had happened, they said, and expressed the belief that the discovery of the cup in Benjamin's sack was some kind of punishment for their sins; they added that they were ready to take the consequence-they would all be Joseph's slaves!    But Joseph refused their offer and said that only the one in whose possession the cup had been found was to remain as slave; the others could return to their father in Canaan.    Then Judah stepped forward and began to plead for Benjamin. Judah began by accusing the harsh governor of a plot to enslave them from the start. He warned him of the unusual strength of the sons of Jacob. Cleverly, Joseph replied that his divining cup had already told him that two of them had destroyed a whole city, but that he was not impressed.    Then Judah changed his tactics and appealed to Joseph's heart. He recounted the whole story of Jacob and his two beloved sons, whom his favorite wife, Rachel, had borne him in his old age. Judah told of his father's grief when one of them had disappeared from home. He revealed that should they come home without the other one, their aged father would never survive the calamity. Finally, Judah offered himself in the boy's place, pointing out that he would be of so much more value than Benjamin as a slave.    Judah's moving appeal and spirit of self-sacrifice in behalf of his brother well being tore Joseph's affectionate heart apart. He knew that his brothers had changed completely, and that they would rather die than give Benjamin away as a slave. Joseph could now forgive them for all they had done to him, which, after all, he knew was for the best. Joseph felt that he could no longer play the hateful role he had assumed in order to test his brothers. His tears were bursting forth, and he longed to embrace his beloved brothers. Sending all the Egyptian associates and attendants out of the room, Joseph, with tears in his eyes, exclaimed in Hebrew, in a voice shaking with emotion (Genesis 45:3): \"I am Joseph! Is my father still alive?\"    So stunned were his brothers that they could not answer him. Joseph realized their embarrassment and possible fear of him, and he continued to talk to them with brotherly affection which soon put them at ease. He told them not to worry about having sold him as a slave, for it had been God's will to send him to Egypt to save their lives from hunger. Then he asked them to hurry back to Jacob and tell him that they had found his lost son, Joseph. He asked them to tell their father that despite the many years of absence from home, in an environment of idolatry and immorality, he had remained the same Joseph his father had known and loved. Joseph thereupon begged his father to come to Egypt with his whole household, where Joseph would take care of them. In Goshen, a province of Egypt, they could settle and live in peace and plenty, for the years of famine were not yet over. There he would take care of them as best he could.    Joseph embraced his brother Benjamin and kissed him, and then he embraced all his other brothers. All eyes were full of tears, tears of happiness and of gratitude to God for His boundless mercy.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>1>c", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "c", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "What three lessons can be learnt from the relationship between Joseph and his family?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Joseph had a forgiving and generous spirit.    - Wisdom is profitable to direct. Joseph was very wise in dealing with his brethren to test if they had changed.    - Jealousy is a great evil and can lead one to plenty other evils.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Discuss the appointment of Joshua as Moses' successor.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Numbers 27 : 18 - 23.    At that time, God told Moses to go up to the mountain of Abarim and see the Promised Land, for like his brother Aaron, he was not to enter the Promised Land, because they had disobeyed God's order in the Desert of Zin.    Moses then asked for a successor to lead the children of Israel into the Promised Land, and God pointed to his disciple Joshua. God ordered Moses to put his hands on Joshua's head to invest him with full authority of leadership, and to present him to Elazar and the entire community. Moses could now die in peace, satisfied that his beloved flock would have a worthy shepherd.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "What three qualities of Joshua can be recommended for leaders of today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- He was a bold and courageous leader. Leaders should endeavour to be bold in spite of negative circumstances.    - He had a different mind set and spirit that believed in God. They must totally trust and submit to God and believe that He'll do as He has promised.    - He had great physical energy. Leaders must also ensure that the are healthy enough to carry out their divine tasks.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "Describe how the supremacy of God was made manifest during the contest on Mount Carmel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in 1st Kings 18 : 20 - 40.    The entire nation was assembled on Mount Carmel, and the four hundred and fifty prophets of Baal came there also, proud and contemptuous and sure of their victory over Elijah. Ahab the king appeared too, eagerly anticipating the outcome of the momentous contest.    Facing the entire people, Elijah addressed them sternly: \"How long will you waver between two sides? If the L-rd be God, follow him; and if Baal be God, then follow him!\" The people did not reply, and Elijah's voice rang forth again: \"I have been left as the only prophet of God; but the prophets of Baal number four hundred and fifty men; therefore give us two bullocks. Let the Baal's prophets choose one bullock for themselves, cut it in pieces, and lay it on the altar; but put no fire under it. I will prepare the other bullock and lay it on the altar without putting fire under it. Then they shall call on the name of their gods, and I will call on the name of the Lord; and the God who answers by fire, shall be the true God!\"    The people voiced their approval and immediately the prophets of Baal picked one bullock and prepared it for the altar. Then they prayed and called on the Baal from morning till noon. But there was no sign of an answer. Elijah ridiculed them and bade them call louder as their god might be asleep or engaged in other and more important business. Not realizing the irony of Elijah's words, the prophets cried louder and louder, and leaped wildly around the altar. They even cut their own flesh until their blood spurted forth, as was their custom. But cry as they might, Baal replied neither to their voices, nor to their wild and desperate gestures. Thus they raged furiously till late in the afternoon, yet there was no sign of an answer.    Then Elijah called upon the people to gather around him. In the name of God he built an altar of twelve stones, symbolizing the number of the Hebrew tribes, and ordered a wide trench dug all about it. Then he laid the other bullock on the altar and had water poured over it, till the trench was filled to the brim. Having completed all these preparations, he stepped before the altar and prayed to God. \" Lord God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel! Let it be known this day that Thou art God in Israel, and that I am Thy servant, and that I have done all these things at Thy word. Hear me, O Lord, hear me, that this people may know that Thou art the Lord God, and thus turn their hearts back again.\"    Hardly had he finished praying when a flame of fire came down from God and consumed the offering, and the wood, and the stones, and the earth, and licked up even the water that was in the trench. Seeing this, the amazed and overawed people prostrated themselves and exclaimed: \"The Lord He is God! The Lord He is God!\" Then, at Elijah's command, they seized the prophets of Baal, led them to the brook of Kishon, and slew them.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "In what three ways can the church fight against immoral acts in a society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Church must speak against worldliness.    - Church leaders and members must strive to be Godly examples to follow.    - There should be encourage for those who do right and punishment for those who do wrong.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Give an account of Amos' encounter with Amaziah the priest?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Amos 7 : 10 - 15.    Stepping fearlessly into the midst of the celebrating crowds in Bethel, before the temple Jeroboam had built for the worship of the calves, Amos announced the terrible punishment God would bring upon the sinful people of Israel. The boldness of the prophet's speech drew upon him the wrath of the priests, especially of their leader Amaziah.     The latter sent word to King Jeroboam II and told him that Amos had conspired against him and that he was telling the people that their king would be killed and that the House of Israel would be exiled. Jeroboam II had too much respect for the prophet to punish him, and God rewarded him for it. But Amaziah the priest did not rest. He incited the people against the prophet and warned him to flee to Judah where people of his kind would be more welcome, adding that he should never return to Bethel.     Amos replied to Amaziah that he was no professional prophet, nor prophet disciple, but a simple man from the land who earned his living as a breeder of sheep. He came to Bethel because God had sent him to speak in His name and warn His people of their impending doom. Amos therefore continued to prophesy.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Indicate any three practices in your society that needs to be condemned.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Bribery and corruption.    - Immorality.    - Drug abuse.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "Examine the baptism of Jesus as narrated in Matthew's gospel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Matthew 3 : 13 - 17.    Jesus, aged thirty years came down from Nazareth to Galilee to be baptized by John in River Jordan. John protested that it was Jesus that should rather baptize him and not the other way round. Jesus told him to do it, in order to fulfill all righteousness.     After Jesus had done it, the Bible says that the Heavens were opened and the Spirit of God descended on Jesus like a dove and a voice from Heaven was heard saying \" This is my beloved son in whom I'm well pleased\".", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "In what two ways is baptism relevant to christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It is a symbolic sign for physical cleansing.    - We as Christian must do it to mark the beginning of our salvation through Jesus Christ.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Describe the appearance of the risen Christ to the two men on their way to Emmaus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Luke 34 : 13 - 33.    Cleopas and his friend were on their way to Emmaus when Jesus met them. It was about 7 miles from Jerusalem.  He joined them in their discussion though they didn't know who He was. They told Him about the recent happenings in Jerusalem as regards Jesus' death and resurrection. Jesus then explained to them the necessity of it all. As they reached their destination, Jesus made to go further but they pleaded with him to stay as it was late. As they wanted to eat bread, Jesus broke it and gave them. Their eyes were opened immediately and then Jesus vanished from their sight.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "What three benefits do Christians derive from the resurrection of Jesus?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jesus Christ being raised from the dead signifies our victory over sin and death.    - It also signifies that He is the Son of God, and that we are also now the Sons of God by believing on Him.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Describe how Saul became converted.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in Acts 9 : 1 - 25.    When Stephen was martyred for preaching the gospel, Saul was an eyewitness. Saul's name means destroyer and he was certainly living up to his name as \"there arose on that day a great persecution against the church in Jerusalem, and they were all scattered throughout the regions of Judea and Samaria, except the apostles.  Devout men buried Stephen and made great lamentation over him.  But Saul was ravaging the church, and entering house after house, he dragged off men and women and committed them to prison\" (Acts 8 : 1b - 3).    In Acts 9:1 - 2 we see that Saul was \"still breathing threats and murder against the disciples of the Lord, went to the high priest and asked him for letters to the synagogues at Damascus, so that if he found any belonging to the Way, men or women, he might bring them bound to Jerusalem.\"   He didn't just persecute Christians; he actually sought letters to expand his campaign of terror against them.      When Saul was on his way to Damascus to \"breathe out more threats and murder against the disciples of the Lord\" (Acts 9:1) \"suddenly a light from heaven shone around him. And falling to the ground he heard a voice saying to him, \"Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?\" And he said, \"Who are you, Lord?\" And he said, \"I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting\" (Acts 9:3b-5).  Jesus actually uses a form on intimacy with Saul by saying his name twice.  Jesus asked Saul why he was persecuting Jesus.  Interestingly, when Christians are persecuted, it is actually Jesus they are persecuting because they are representing Him so Saul was not simply persecuting Christians, it was as if he was doing it to Jesus!    When Saul encountered Jesus on the Damascus road, he was temporarily blinded.  He was then led into the city by the men with him who heard a voice but saw no one.    The Lord appeared unto Ananias and told him that he was to \"Rise and go to the street called Straight, and at the house of Judas look for a man of Tarsus named Saul\" (Acts 9:11).  When Ananias protested, knowing that Saul was the destroyer of Christians, God told him 'Go, for he is a chosen instrument of mine to carry my name before the Gentiles and kings and the children of Israel.  For I will show him how much he must suffer for the sake of my name.'  So Ananias departed\" When Ananias found Saul he told him that \"the Lord Jesus who appeared to you on the road by which you came has sent me so that you may regain your sight and be filled with the Holy Spirit.\"  And immediately something like scales fell from his eyes, and he regained his sight. Then he rose and was baptized\"       Once Saul was saved he didn't waste much time witnessing for Christ and \"immediately he proclaimed Jesus in the synagogues, saying, \"He is the Son of God.\"  And all who heard him were amazed and said, \"Is not this the man who made havoc in Jerusalem of those who called upon this name? And has he not come here for this purpose, to bring them bound before the chief priests?\" But Saul increased all the more in strength, and confounded the Jews who lived in Damascus by proving that Jesus was the Christ\" (Acts 9 : 20 - 22).   Once Paul started proclaiming the gospel, he fell victim to what he was formerly doing and ended up in chains.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Identify any three visible signs of a convert.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- There is a change in behaviour and conduct.    - The person begins to radiate joy and happiness.    - The will also be eager to learn the Word of God.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Highlight the relationship between faith and works according to the teaching of James.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This can be seen in James 2 : 14 - 26.    James, in his letter outlines the evidence of true faith. The idea of claiming to have faith is not enough. Genuine faith is evident by works and so faith and works are inseparable. He declsred that Abraham's faith was evident in the way he offered to sacrifice Isaac and was justified.    He also added that works serves as a measure of justification while faith is the basis of justification itself. Rahab was also declared righteous for her action in welcoming the spies and helping them escape. Faith and works are essential to each other as the body and spirit. Faith does not exist without works. A christian life is characterized by his good works.    He added that if we say we love God but hate our fellow man whom we can see, you do not show your faith in God whom you claim you love. Holy living and charitable works show true and genuine faith.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "In what three ways can Christians demonstrate their faith in works?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- By showing love.    - By being hardworking and not lazy.    - By living in holiness and saying away from sin.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "What was Peter's advice to Christians living among non-Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter also pointed out that believers are \"aliens and strangers\". A believer is a foreigner and pilgrim living without a permanent home or citizenship. He only temporarily lives in this world and is not to participate in its ungodliness. Peter said, \"Keep your behavior excellent among the [unsaved], so that . . . they may on account of your good deeds, as they observe them, glorify God in the day of visitation. The Lord uses a holy life to draw the lost to Christ. When unbelievers become Christians, they glorify God.     As believers, we're to have proper relationships with others in part to evangelize the lost (1st Peter 2:13 - 3:12). That involves how we relate to those in positions of authority (1st Peter 2:13-20), our spouse (1st Peter 3:1 - 7), other believers (1st Peter 3:8 - 13), and everyone in general.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2015>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2015", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "What three challenges can Christians face among non-Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- False accusation.    - Discrimination.    - Deliberate intimidation and oppression.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "SECTION A  THEMES FROM THE OLD TESTAMENT    Describe how Moses responded to God's call.*", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "a) Bible Passage: Exodus 1 :1 - 6  Moses was a flock keeper and he kept his father inlaw's flock when God called him. He was led by his flock on that day to a mountain called Mount Horeb. That was where God appeared to him as a flame of fire from a burning bush. When he looked at the direction from which he was being called, he realized that the bush was on fire but the leaves weren't burning. He wondered why the bush wasn't burning so her decided to know why. As he turned to go to the place God called him \"Moses! Moses! and he replied \"Here I am\", God then told him to step forward and take off his shoes, for the land which he was stepping on was a holy ground. God said to Moses, I am the God of thy Fathers, Abraham, Isaac and Jacob at this point Moses hid his face for he was afraid to look on God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "SECTION A  THEMES FROM THE OLD TESTAMENT  State three reasons why people refuse to accept leadership roles.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-  They fear commitment  -  They do not trust themselves well enough, it can also be regarded as low self-esteem  -  Most of them lack the vision", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Recount the effect of the behaviours of Eli's children on Israel as a Nation?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "1 Samuel 4: 1-end  As a result of the bahaviours of Eli's children, many misfortunes fell on the people of Israel  The Nation of Israel failed in battle against the philistines  The Ark of God was taken and the two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas were slain.  When Eli heard of the death of his sons Hophni and Phinehas, it caused his death.  When Phinehas wife heard of the death of her husband and father in law, she gave birth prematurely and she later died.  And the priesthood position was taken away from the family of Eli", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL", "question": "What two lessons can be learnt by parents from Eli's attitude?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Parents should raise their children in the way of the Lord.  - There is consequence for every sin committed   - They should not turn deaf ears to what the spirit is saying   - Parents should teach their children the fear of the Lord.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "Narrate the circumstance that led to the rejection of Rehoboam as a King of Israel?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the death of Solomon, his son Rehoboam was made king by the tribe of Judah. He then travelled to be crowned king at Shechem by the people in the North in order put the kingdom at peace. Jeroboam was on exile in the land of Egypt when he heard the news before he returned home and led a number of people to Shechem to meet with Rehoboam. The group of people delegated by Rehoboam requested that he reduces the burden that was placed on them so they could do thier duties well. Rehoboam seeked advice from the elderly counsellors of his father about the reply he will give to the people of Shechem, they told him  to listen to the delegates and yield to their demands to reduce their burden.  He sought advice from his contemporaries and they adviced him to say to the Northerners of the tribe of Shechems that \"My little finger is thicker than my father's loins, whereas my father chastised you with whips, I will chastise you with scorpions\". This actually meant that the peoples troubles will be more than the one they experienced in the days of his father.     So when the Israelites saw that Rehoboam was not ready to reduce their problems but increase them instead they broke away from the kingdom saying \"We have no inheritance in the son of Jesse. To your tents O Israel\". The people of Shechem then made Jeroboam their king instead of Rehoboam.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "- What three factors can lead to the rejection of a political leader?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- When the leader has no respect for others  - When a leader is indecisive  - When he is selfish  - When he breaks the law of the land  - When the leader perform acts that are immoral.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "Relate the story of Hosea's marriage to Gomer.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God instructed Hosea to take a wife that is a harlot. This was actually to show how Israel has forsaken the land and practiced idolatry. Hosea took Gomer, the daughter of Diblaim, who gave birth to three children, the first was named Jezreel which means \"God will punish the house of Jehu for the blood of Jezreel and would put an end to the kingdom of Isreal. Her second child was a female and was named \"Lo-Ruhamah\" which means God no longer pity the people of Israel while the third child was \"Lo-Ammi\" which was because Israel was no longer the people of God nor was God their God. After the birth of all her three children Gomer left Hosea to be with  some other lover of hers. Hosea requested that she comes back but she ignored him, he asked his children to go plead with her to come back but it didn't work. Gomer loved the things of the world she was getting from her lovers, despite all this Hosea still loved her. The love of Hosea for his wife was a show of God's love for the Israelites.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : GOD’S DIVINE LOVE – HOSEA", "question": "Mention three factors that ensure a stable marriage", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Both loving one another   - Combine use of financial resources  - Patience and Tolerance  - Being faithful and committed to work  - Having to forgive one another", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MARK 1: 16-20; 2: 13-17", "question": "SECTION B  THEMES FROM THE SYNOPTIC GOSPELS AND THE ACT OF THE APOSTLES    Highlight Jesus' call of the twelve disciples.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to the word of God, Jesus sought for divine consent and guidance from God to help him choose the disciples, which was stated in the book of Luke 5.     The twelve disciple had different occupation the were fishermen, tax collectors and politicians. In the book of Mark he called Simon Peter and his brother Andrew at the Sea of Galilee as they were fishermen. Jesus told them to follow him that he will make them fishers of men and they did. Later on, he saw James the son of Zebedee and John his brother, who were also fishermen. He called them and they followed him. On their way they met with Levi and Jesus asked him to follow him to be His disciple.    A feast was organized and a later during the feasting the tax collectors annoyed the scribes and Pharisees. Their accusations led Jesus to giving them a response which he said \" I came not to call the righteous  but sinners to repentance\".", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "SECTION B  THEMES FROM THE SYNOPTIC GOSPELS AND THE ACT OF THE APOSTLES  Identify four good qualities of a Christian leader", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-    He must be committed to his leadership roles  -  He must have a vision and foresight   -  He must be selfless and sacrificial   -  A good leader must have good moral standards  -  A good leader must be accountable   -  A good leader must live life as a role model", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "\"And a young man followed him with nothing but a linen cloth about his body and they seized him...and ran away naked\".. Trace the events that led to this incident in the life of Jesus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus and his disciples made ready for the passover then in the evening Jesus and his disciples were gathered at the table and they ate. Jesus said that one of his disciples at the table will betray him and they all one after the other started asking \"is it I\". Then he answered and said unto them \"It is one of the twelve, that dippeth with me in the dish. The Son of man indeed goeth, as it is written of him: but woe to that man by whom the Son of man is betrayed! good were it for that man if he had never been born.\" And as they ate Jesus took bread and broke it and gave them saying \"Take eat this is my body\", he also took a cup and gave them saying it is his blood and they all drank from it. The disciples sung hymns and went to Mount  Olives.  And Jesus said \"All ye shall be offended because of me this night: for it is written, I will smite the shepherd, and the sheep shall be scattered.. But after that I am risen, I will go before you into Galilee\". Peter said he will not offend Jesus but Jesus replied and said unto them that \"Verily I say unto thee, That this day, even in this night, before the cock crow twice, thou shalt deny me thrice.\"    Later they came to a place called Gethsemane, Jesus ordered his disciples to stay and wait for him while he goes to pray, he took with him, Peter, James and John! Jesus bowed down and prayed that God should let the cup pass over him. When Jesus got back he found the disciples sleeping, so he said unto Peter \"Simon, sleepest thou? couldest not thou watch one hour?   Watch ye and pray, lest ye enter into temptation. The spirit truly is ready, but the flesh is weak\". He went away and came back and still met them sleeping and he said again to them \"Sleep on now, and take your rest: it is enough, the hour is come; behold, the Son of man is betrayed into the hands of sinners.   Rise up, let us go; lo, he that betrayeth me is at hand\" . As he spoke, soldier came from the religious leaders, with Judas Iscariot (who betrayed him) to arrest him. All the disciples forsook him and fled. A certain man followed him with nothing but a linen cloth about his body and they seized him", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Give four reasons why some people forsake their friends", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "b)   When the friend fails to support them when the needs arises  - When the friend is not purpose driven  - When the friend is not making effort to make the friendship work  - When the friend cares less about the other  - When the friend is being hypocritical", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Highlight the activities of Peter in Lydda and Joppa.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter went to visit christians who were outside Jerusalem to encourage them in faith, He visited Lydda where he met a man named Ananaes who had been on the bed for a  long time as a result for his sickness. Peter prayed for him and he instantly got healed. As a result of the healing, many people at Lydda and the nearby town got converted. While there, a disciple called Tabitha died at Joppa. She was a woman who was always helpinng people and doing good by helping the poor. The fellow brethren at Joppa who heard of Peter's miracle at Lydda asked him to come see them. When Peter finally arrived, he was taken to upper room where Tabitha was laid. Some women who were widows cried and tore their clothes while they wept. Peter sent out all the mourners while he prayed that Tabitha to come to life. God heard his prayers and she rose up. Peter lifted her up and presented her alive to the disciples. After this miracle there was so much joy and those who heard of it turned and believed in God.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Identify two ways by which some Pastors were hiding behind miracles to cause havoc in the society today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-   Some so-called men of God us divers means to pray which can be questioned as related to the word of God.  -   They solicit money and other financial inducement for prayers and miracles  -   Many people do not receive the miracles after the prayer.  -   Some pastors are arrogant and abusive  -    Some men of God acquire satanic means for powers.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "SECTION C  THEMES FROM SELECTED EPISTLE    Explain James' advice to Christians to be doers of the word and not hearers only.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "James advised that christians should not err from the word of God and that every good thing comes from God. He advised that christians should be swift to hear the word, slow to speak and slow to anger. He also asked that christians should lay aside all filthiness and superfluity of naughtiness and recieve meekness the engrafted which is able to save our lives but be doers of the word and not hearest only and not deceiving ourselves. He said that if anyone be the hearer alone and not the doer of the word, it is like a man beholding his natural face in a glass, looks at his face and goes his way and then they immediately forget the what manner of man he was. James added \"But whoever looks at the perfect law and continues and being not a forgetful hearer but one who does the work and this man shall be blessed in his deeds\". James said that If any man be religious and controls not his tongue, but deceives his own heart and as such, his religion is vain.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "SECTION C  THEMES FROM SELECTED EPISTLE  State two factors that hinder Christians from doing the will of God", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Lack of self control and selflessness  - Love of the things of the world  - Some experiences encountered along the way  - Lack of being committed to the work of God  - Bad influence", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Relate Peter's teaching on submission to authority.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter's teaching was of the opinion that we submit ourselves to the laws and ordinances of man for the Lord's sake whether it be from man, from kings or from a supreme authority or anyone that is sent to make laws for the unjust and to favour those that has been of good character.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2016>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2016", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "- State seven ways a Christian can be a good citizen.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- By obeying the law  - By being self disciplined  - By loving one another as themselves.  - They should honor the leadership placed above them.  - They should help defend those who are in need of help and are helpless.  - By being obedient to the road instructions.  - By regularly paying their taxes.  - By doing community services.  - By teaching the people the word of God.  - By being self disciplined.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Narrate the dream of Pharoah", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Pharaoh the King dreamed of seven sleek and fat cows coming out of the Nile. He saw some seven other slim and thin cows. According to the scripture, the thin and slim cows swallowed the fat ones.    He dreamed again of seven plump and good ears of corn growing in one stalk. Another seven thin and blighted ears came up also; gain the seven thin and blighted ears of corn ate up the good plump ones.     When he woke up, he was troubled and afraid, so he summoned all the magicians and wise men of Egypt. But unfortunately his wise men could not interprete the dreams. Then the chief butler remembered how Joseph had effectively interpreted his dreams in prison; for this reason, the chief butler recommended Joseph to Pharoah. Pharoah narated his dreams to Joseph. It should be noted that Joseph emphasized that it is only God that give good and reassonable answers to dreams. Joseph eventually gave good and acceptable interpretations to Pharoah's dreams", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "In what three ways did the interpretation of the dreams affect Joseph and his people?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Joseph was honoured with a royal marriage   - Joseph too the advantage of his position to save his people during famine   - Pharoah made Joseph the leader of his household and people", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DEBORAH", "question": "Trace the circumstances that led to the call of Deborah to battle with Jabin", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to the book of Judges chapter 4, the Israelites in the time of Joshua took a covenant/oath that they would not mix the worship of Yahweh with the worship of other gods.     But, Israel defected from worshipping God alone and instead served Baal and Ashtoreth, the gods of Canaanites.     Yaweh was displeased by this behaviour and thus delivered Israel into the hands of their enemy who oppressed them severely and plundered them.     This become their every time experience so that whenever they went to war, they were defeated as God had planned. As a result of their suffering and punishment, the people prayed to God for deliverance from their oppressors.     Yahweh was moved by the groaning of the of the oppressed Israelites and raised up Judges who delivered them from their enemies.    However, when the judges died, Israel went back to sin against God. Thus, the background to the call of Deborah followed a pattern of disobedience punishment, prayer for forgiveness and deliverance through one of the Judges.     It was after the death of one of such Judges (Ehud) that Israel sinned against God who gave them up to the Canaanite king - Jabin to oppress them for twenty years. When Israel cried for mercy, God raised Deborah, a prophetess and a judge to come to their rescue.     Upon God's instruction, Deborah summoned Barak to gather 10,000 men at mount Tabo against Jabin and his army commander, Sisera.     Deborah added that God had promised to give them victory to Barak. Barak, however, insisted that  he would go to the battle if only Deborah went with him. Deborah agreed but added that the victory would go to a woman. When Sisera heard that Israel had gone to mount up to mount Tabor, he called up his men to fight against Barak and Deborah but the Canaanite were defeated. After losing his entire army, Sisera fled on foot to the tent of Jael, the Kenite to seek Asylum.     he was given hospitality but when he was asleep, Jael drove a peg into his forehead with a hammer and killed him. She presented his body to Barak who was pursuing Jabin. Jabin, the king of canaan was also killed and the Israelites became free again and lived in peace and prosperity, whereas disobedience leads to pain and suffering and defeat.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Mention three ways women can contribute to national development", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- There are women in soccer and other entertainment   - They are involved in rural and urban development   - We have women in NGO's fighting for women's right, etc.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "Ouline the circumstances that led David to serve in the house of Saul", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In the war with the Amalekites, Saul was to utterly destroy the people and everything in the land (Holy war). Though Saul defeated the Amalekites and destroyed all the people, he spared Agag, the king of the Amalekites and the best of live stock to sacrifice to the Lord. Samuel told Saul that to obey is better than sacrifice and because Saul rejected the word of the Lord, God had also rejected him from being king.     After the disobedience, the spirit of the Lord departed from him and he was tormented by an evil spirit from the Lord. Saul's servant suggested that a man skillful playing the lyre should be employed to help sooth Saul whenever he was tormented. Saul agreed to this suggestion and requested for the service of a skillful musician. One of the servants recommended David, son of Jesse, a Bethlehemite.     David was described as a brave man and a worrior, one who speaks well and a fine man and that the Lord was with him.     To this end, Saul send messengers to Jesse that he needed david's services because he was pleased with him. Jasse gave David some bread, wine and a kid as gifts to Saul. David thereafter started working in the service of Saul. Saul loved David greatly and made him his armour-bearer. He sent message to Jesse requesting David to remain in his service. Whenever Saul was tormented, David played his lyre and Saul felt better and the evil spirit left him.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "What three lessons can leaders learn from the causes of Saul's downfall?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Disobedience can terminate God's plan for one life.   - Leaders must be role modele   - Saul lacked courage to stand by the truth.   - There is need for leaders to be prayerful.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "Describe King Josiah's religious reforms in Israel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the discovery of the book of the law in the temple, king Josiah initiated some religious reforms. Josiah ordered Hilkiah, the priest to bring out all the vessels made for Baal and Ashtrah and all other gods. He burnt them outside Jerusalem in the field of kidron and took the ashes of Bethel. He deposed the idolatrous priest whom the king of Judah had ordained to burn incense in high places to honour Baal and other gods. He broke down the houses of the male cult prostitutes which had taken over the house of the Lord. He went all over the city and defiled and chased out the high priest from the temple where they burned incensestothe gods. He defiled the Topheth to prevent people from sacrificing their sons and daughters as burnt offerings to Molech.     He removed the horses the king of Judah dedicated to the worship of the sun god at the entrance of the temple and burned them. He destroyed all the altars put in place by Manasseh, Solomon, Jeroboam and other kings before him.     Josiah carried out his reforms up to the northen kingdom, he removed the shrines of the high places that were in the city of Samaria Bethel which the Israelites had made. Josiah killed and burned the bodies of all the priest of the high places. Afterwards, he restored the passover feast and Sabbath and commanded the people to keep it as it is written in the book of the covenant, i.e., he restored the ancient faith. He abolished idolatry, witchcraft, sooth saying, sorcery, divination from Judah/Jrusalem. Altars at the high places were demonished and worship was centralized in Jerusalem.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "State four ways Christians can maintain the purity of their religion", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Seeking forgiveness whenever one transgresses   - Following the moral teachings of the Bible   - Obedience to the Word of God  - Maintainance of harmonious co-existence", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "Describe the temptation of Jesus as recorded in the gospel of Matthew", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Following the baptism of Jesus Christ, He was led by the Holy Spirit to be tempted of the devil. Before this, he had fasted for forty days and forty nights, and at the end of the fasting, He was very farmished. It was at this point that the tempter (devil) came to him sayin, \"if truly you are the son of God, command these stones to become loaves of bread.\" Jesus responded by saying, \"It is written that: \"man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds from the mouth of God.\" The devil then took Him to the pinnacle of the temple and said to him, \"if truly you are the son of God, throw yourself down; for it is written, \"He will give His angel charge over you and they will bear you up in their hands, lest you strike your foot against a stone. Then Jesus replied and said to him, \"Again it is writtten: thou shall not tempt the Lord thy God and Him only shall thou serve\". The devil took Jesus to a high mountain and showed him all the kingdoms of the word and their glory. He said to Him, \"All these I will give you, if you will fall down and worship me.\" Jesus rebuked the devil to go away, saying that one must worship only God. Then at this point, the devil left Jesus; and the angels of the Lord come and ministered to Him.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "In what three ways were the temptations significant to Jesus in his ministry ?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Through the temptation esus accepted suffering as a means of achieving God's purpose which was the redemption of mankind   - With His victory over Satan, Jesus answered his followers that with the Word of God, they too can overcome the devil.   - The temptation signaled the preparation of Jesus for His ministry. It helped him to emplore what his mission entailed", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>6>a>i", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "i", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Highlight the activities of each of these characters during the crucifixion of Jesus Christ:   The Two Robbers", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Two robbers were crucified with Jesus one on the right and the other on the left. The book of matthew records that one of them joined the chief priest and passersby to mock Jesus, as king, \"Are you not the Christ? Save yourself and save us.\" One of the robbers rebuked him pointing out that Jesus was innocent yet was being crucified. And unlike Jesus, they deserved to be reprimanded for their misdemeanuors. This thief pleaaded with Jesus to remember him in His Kingdom and Jesus did assure him a place in paradise.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>6>a>ii", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "ii", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Joseph of Arimathea", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Joseph of Arimathea happened to be a rich and respected member of the council (Sanhedrin). He was a good and a righteous man; he was also a secret disciple of Jesus. He understand that it was unconventional according to the Jewish custom to have a dead body hang on the tree (cross) over night. He approached Pilate and requested for the body of Christ for burial. Pilate being assured of Jesus' death released the body. He intended to bury Jesus because he was aware that the next day was Sabbath.   Joseph took the body of Christ and wrapped it in a clen linen shrould/cloth. Afterwards, he laid the body of Christ in his own new tomb, where nobody had ever been laid. He closed the entrance of the tomb with a great rock and departed.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "In what three ways are the behaviour of the robbers significant to Christians?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Irrespective of our sins, Jesus Christ is ready to forgive us if we humbly repent from our sins.  - Salvation is available even at the least hour   - We should not mock the weaknesses of others.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Describe the Command Living of the Early Church", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the arrival of the Holy Sspirit at Pentecost Peter gave a powerful speech and close to three thousand converts were made, and they became part of the body of the early church. These new converts were then baptised.     Their lives were characterized by a strong bond of fellowship because they were of one heart and soul. They devoted themselves to the teaching of the apostle and fellowshiping together. Fear came upon them as signs and wonders were performed by the apostles. Their togetherness was shown in the practice of joint ownership of possession (property). They shared the proceeds amongst themselves according to their needs and there was no needy person among them. Day by day, the Lord added to their number. They devoted themselves to breaking of bread from one house to another with gladness and sincerity of mind.     They praised God and they had favour with all the people. The apostle gave testimony to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus, and grace s upon them. Those who had land or houses sold them, and brought the money to the apostles to be shared; i.e no one owned what he possessed. Notable among the donors was Joseph (Barnabas) who willingly sold his field and brought the money and laid it at the apostle's feet.     However, Ananias and Sapphira his wife, were not sincere in giving out their possession and were instantly punished.     Another significant even which nearly marred the unity of the early church was the uneven distribution of provisions. However, this was resolved by the appointment of deacons.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "What three lessons can be learnt from the life of the Early Church?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The spirit of altruism (giving and taking), i.e symbiotic reciprocity was dominant. Hence, we should learn to give and share.   - The need for honesty in the church   - Evil intention and insincerity mar unity and co-operation. This should be avoided in the present day church.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "Recount James' advice to christians on how the poor and the rich should be treated in the church", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "James admonished the Christians not to show partiality to anyone (either rich or poor) and to accept that everyone is equal before God. He pointed out to them that they are ambassadors of Christ and should hold on firmly to the faith of our Lord Jesus Christ. An example, James pointed out that a man who is well dressed and another man (poor) who is dressed shabbily should be treated equally. he stressed further that if preferential treatment is given tothe rich man over the poor man, then one is guity of partiality. He made it clear that showing partiality is not only causing division but also assuming the role of judges that perpetrate evil intentions or thought.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "State four reasons why people should not discriminate against each other", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It prevents the acceptance of the Gospel   - It encourages rain glory and psychophancy   - It promotes unhealthy rivalry   - It breeds tribalism", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Outline Peter's teaching on Christians' attitude to civil authorities", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "As a christian you should be law-abiding and have respect for contributed authority. Christians are expected to discharge their ivic duties and responsibilities promptly to all men. Peter taught that a good Christian should submit himself to every man's instructions and directives; that this is a sign of humility. He stressed further that it is God who appointed rulers and leaders to rebuke wrong doers and to reward those who do good.     He added that the good conducts of Christians would put to shame the ignorance of foolish men. As men who had been liberated from the curse of the law, a good Christian citizen should live as a freeman without using his freedom as an excuse for evil; but he should live as an obedient servant of God; also he should respect every man and love the brotherhood.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2017>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2017", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "State three reasons for submission to civil authorities", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It enhances peace and harmony   - It is a service to God as it was God's command that Christians should be submissive to authorities   - Christians' obedience to the law influences people to come to know the true God.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Outline in chronological order, the first creation story.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The First Creation Story (Genesis 1:1-31)  In the beginning God created the heavens and the earth. The earth was without form and void and darkness was upon the face of the deep; and the spirit of God moved upon the face of the waters.     On the first day, God created light and He separated light from darkness; He called the light, day and the darkness called he night. On the second, the heaven (firmament) were created; on the third day, God created, dry land, sea and plant bodies. On the fourth day, God created two great lights Sun and Moon to rule the day and night respectively. On the fifth day, sea animals and birds were created. God, on the sixth day created man in His own image and gave him dominion over all the things He created; God also allowed man to give name to the living creatures.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Give  three reasons why man is regarded as the crown of creation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Man was given the ability to subdue the earth   - Man was given the creative ability of God   - Man has the ability to distinguish between good and evil.  - Man was to give names to other creatures, indicating his superiority   - Man was the last to be created, thus crown of all creation", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Give an account of the report brought to Moses by the twelve spies.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "An Account of The Report Brought to Moses by The Twelve Spies (Num. 13:1-33; 14:1-19)     When the Israelites got to the Wilderness of Paran at Kadesh, God told Moses to select twelve men, one from each tribe. They were given the mandate to survey the strengths and weakness of the promise Land; and also to find out if the land was fertile or not. The Spies were also asked to find out whether the inhabitants were weak or strong; few or many for 40 days.     Having surveyed the land, they realized that the land was fertile. As proof, the spies came to the valley of Eschol where they cut a branch with a cluster of grapes; they also cut pomegrenates and figs to show that the land was fertile and flowing with milk and honey.     They however, stressed that the people who lived on the land were strong; they stressed further that the cities were fortified and the descendants of Anak (very tall and strong) lived on the land, as well as the Hittites, Amorites and Jebusites. Majority of the spies emphasised that the men of Canaan were of great stature and the Israelites looked like grasshoppers before them, they claimed it was a land that devoured its inhabitants. However, Joshua and Caleb did not agree with their reports, but insisted that they should go and possess the land, since they could overpower them.     According to Joshua and Caleb, God can help them to defeat the Canaanites; they charged the Israelites not to be afraid. But as a result of the report given by majority of the spies, Israelites complained bitterly against Moses and saying it was better if they had waited in Egypt enduring the hardship than coming to the wilderness to die. They suggested that a leader should accompany them back to Egypt. The people were so angry that they attempted to stone Caleb and Joshua. God threatened to destroy the people with pestilence and disinherit them, but Moses interceded on their behalf.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "What three lessons can political leaders learn from the mission of the spies?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- The need for transparency in public service, i.e, nothing should be hidden from the people   - Bold and faithful people should be appointed as leaders.   - Political leaders are not to be discouraged by negative reports.   - Exageration is to be avoided, if its purpose is to put fear in the people.   - Fear can paralyze an individual or a nation, it can make one to lose its destiny.   - Political leaders should do their best to give their people hope and positive vision", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "Recount the story of the death of Saul on Mount Gilboa.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Story of The Death of Saul on Mount Gilboa (1 Samuel 31:1-13)    There was a battle (war) between the Philistines and the Israelites at Mount Gilboa where Israel suffered defeat as they fled. They overtook Saul and his sons and succeeded in killing them (Jonathan, Abinadab and Malchishua). As the war got intensified, the Philistine archers, hit and wounded Saul badly. Saul requested that his armour bearer kill him so as to avoid being killed by the uncircumcised Philistines. Saul's armour bearer refused to kill him, Saul committed suicide by falling on his sword. Seeing Saul dead, the armour bearer also killed himself. The Israelites fled from their cities on hearing the death of Saul and his sons. The next day, the Philistines settled in the abandoned cities of Israel and send words of victory over Israel to their men in Philistine. Saul's head was cut off and his armour stripped off as trophies of their victims. These were sent into the temple of Ashtaroth to ascribe victory to their gods. Saul's body was then fastened to the wall of Bathshan to make fun of him. However, the people of Jabesh-Gilead went bravely at night to remove Saul and his son's bodies from Bethshan. The bodies were brought to Jabesh where they were burnt and the remains buried under the tamarisk tree. This was to avoid further abuse and humiliation on the Israelites.     The people fasted seven days to mourn Saul and his sons. These were done to reciprocate how Saul saved them once when they were threatened by Nahash, the Ammorite king.", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONSEQUENCES OF SAUL’S DISOBEDIENCE : SAUL", "question": "State two effects of disobedience.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Effects of Disobedience   1. Disobedience breaks up relationships   2. Disobedience attracts the individual to dangers   3. Disobedience makes us to lose favour with God.   4. Disobedience tarnishes one's reputation", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "Highlight four punishments Amos warned Israel about if they failed to repent.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Punishments Amos Warned Israel Against if They Failed to Repent . (Amos 2:6, 4; 5:1-24; 7)     - Amos prophesied that the Samaritan would be taken to exile in hooks like a fish and cast into Harmon   - Those who looked forward to the day of the Lord as a day of joy and exoneration would be disappointed as it would turn out to be a day of judgement and severe punishment.  - Songs of thanksgiving for harvest would be turned to sadness   - According to Amos, the people would suffer famine not of food or drink but for the word of God.  - Worship involving sacrifices, prayers, songs on feast and sacred days would incur God's displeasure, hatred and rejection.   - All businessmen who exploited the poor in the course of their transaction would have their hopes dashed while their feast would turn into mourning.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "List three sins Amos condemned which are prevalent in our society today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Bribery and Corruption   - Cheating in market with false weights   - Robbing the poor of their properties   - Injustice in the law court   - Sexual immorality   - Paying lip service to God   - Bearing false witness   - Not keeping the Sabbath and feast days holy   - Idolatry   - Cult prostitution", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE BAPTISM", "question": "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased. Discuss the events which led to the above statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"This is my Beloved Son, with Whom I am well pleased.\" (Matthew 3:13-17, mark 1:9-11; Luke 3:21-22)     According to the gospels, Jesus came down from Nazareth of Galilee to be baptized by John the baptist in the river Jordan. Matthew accounts that John recognized Jesus as the expected Messiah when he saw Him. He wondered why Jesus should come to him for baptism since Jesus was superior to him. Hence, John was hesitant in baptizing Jesus.    However, jesus persuaded John to baptize him saying let it be so now, for thus it is fitting for us to fulfill all righteousness. John then consented and had Jesus baptized. As Jesus came out of the water, the heavens opened and the spirit of the Lord descended upon Him like a dove. Then a voice came (which as heard) from heaven saying, \"this is my beloved son with whom I am well pleased.\"     The text above alluded to the baptism of jesus as an event that marked Jesus' call into ministry. The voice quoted confirmed Jesus as the Messiah. Jesus got baptized in order to indentify himself with the sinners he came to save (redeem)   The Holy Spirit which came upon Jesus led and guided Him to do God's will. Going to John for baptism was a sign of lending support to John's work.", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "What four steps can Christians take to become committed to God?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Obedience to God's commandments   - Engaging in church duties and activities   - Being prayerful and God fearing   - Purity and holiness by living a morally upright life   - Obedience to civil authority   - Readiness to accept responsibility   - Scripture studies and its application to life", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Outline the roles women played in the resurrection stories according to the Synoptic Gospels.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Roles Women Played in The Resurrection Stories According to the Synoptic Gospels. (Matt. 28:1-10, Mark 16:1-11, Luke 24:1-11).     According to the synoptic gospels, women were, the first to go to the tomb of Jesus. Matthew wrote that the women went to the tomb after the Sabbath was fully completed. Mark said it was after the Sabbath had past and very early in the morning at the rising of the sun. The women were Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James and Salome. Luke added Joane, the wife of Chuza.    According to Mark, these four women brought sweet spices to annoint the body of Jesus for further embalming.     While on their way, the women wondered who would help them roll away the rock at the entrance of the tomb. Matthew however reported that there was a great earthquake before the women got there.     An angel of the Lord from heaven rolled back the stone and sat upon it. For fear of the angel, the guards were frightened and become like dead men. The angel told the women not to be afraid, for jesus had risen and they should come and see where he was laid. The angel told him to go quickly and tell the disciples that he had arisen and was going to Galilee where they would meet him. Matthew did not say that the angel appeared to the women but only to the guards. According to Mark, when the women entered the tomb they saw a young man sitting at the right side, in a white robe and when they went in, they did not find the body of Jesus, thus they were perplexed: The women then saw the vision of the angel who gave them information regarding the resurrection of Christ. They were asked to inform the disciples. Mark made emphasis to Peter. The women left quickly from the tomb with awe and ran to tell the disciples that Jesus had risen.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : DEBORAH", "question": "What three roles do women play in the Church today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- They help in the liturgy by joining the choir to sing in the church   - Some women study hard and with faith, they become pastors, Rev. Sisters and Prophetesses in some churches, women are powerful prayer warriors.  - Most of the cleaning activities to keep the church tidy and other church decorations are spear headed by women.   - Several women societies are formed to help or support the running of the church   - Some women give out their properties for the use of the church.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Relate Peter's miraculous escape from prison.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Relate Peter's Miraculous Escape From Prison. (Acts 12:1-9)     Herod Agrippa opposed and persecuted the church. He killed James, the brother of John. When Herod realized that the death of James pleased the Jews, he went ahead to arrest Peter. This arrest took place during the celebration of the feast of the unleavened bread. Herod intended to have Peter killed after the Passover celebration. The night before the day Herod planned to kill Peter,, Peter was bound with chains and placed between two soldiers, he was heavily guarded to prevent his escape. While Peter was in prison, constant prayers were said on his behalf. As Peter was asleep, an angel of the Lord appeared to him and a light shone in the cell. The angel touched and woke him up saying, get up quickly. Immediately, the chains fell off from his hands and the angel told him to dress up which Peter obeyed. The angel then commanded Peter to follow him. Peter thought that he was dreaming all the while. But when he passed through the first and second gates and came to the Iron Gate leading into the city, the gate opened on its own accord. When the angel left Peter, he realized that the Lord had sent an angel to rescue him from the power of herod. Peter immediately went to the house of Mary the mother of John where the brethren had gathered to pray for him in the middle of the night. When Peter knocked at the door, Rhoda identified his voice and told the brethren that Peter waas at the door knocking.     But the brethren expressed disbelief thinking Rhoda had lost her mind. They opined that the one at the door might be Peter's angel (ghost). Eventually, when the door was opened and they saw Peter, they were amazed and wanted to shout for joy but Peter restrained them. Peter explained how his release from prison happened and he later fled from Jerusalem. As Peter could not be found in the morning after a search, Herod ordered for the execution of the guard.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "State three factors that motivate people to pray", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Factors that Motivate People to Pray     - When people sin against God, they pray to confess their sins and ask for forgiveness.   - When led by the Holy Spirit or fellowship of believers   - To seek God's counsel or favour in making important decisions   - The desire for spiritual growth   - To bless or consecrate an object   - To dedicate or commit oneself to God   - To obtain protection against the devil", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : FAITH AND WORKS", "question": "Recount James' argument that faith without works is dead.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Faith Without Works Is Dead    14 What does it profit, my brethren, if someone says he has faith but does not have works? Can faith save him? 15 If a brother or sister is naked and destitute of daily food, 16 and one of you says to them, \"Depart in peace, be warmed and filled,\" but you do not give them the things which are needed for the body, what does it profit? 17 Thus also faith by itself, if it does not have works, is dead.    18 But someone will say, \"You have faith, and I have works.\" Show me your faith without [a]your works, and I will show you my faith by [b]my works. 19 You believe that there is one God. You do well. Even the demons believe—and tremble! 20 But do you want to know, O foolish man, that faith without works is [c]dead? 21 Was not Abraham our father justified by works when he offered Isaac his son on the altar? 22 Do you see that faith was working together with his works, and by works faith was made [d]perfect? 23 And the Scripture was fulfilled which says, \"Abraham believed God, and it was [e]accounted to him for righteousness.\" And he was called the friend of God. 24 You see then that a man is justified by works, and not by faith only.    25 Likewise, was not Rahab the harlot also justified by works when she received the messengers and sent them out another way?    26 For as the body without the spirit is dead, so faith without works is dead also.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Mention three benefits of faith to a Christian.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Faith in Jesus then results in a series of astonishing benefits. Here are six.  Salvation    2 Tim 2:10 says that there is 'salvation in Christ Jesus', we are rescued from the power of sin & death, that meant we were living under the judgement of God. Christ saves us, redeems us, rescues us. Captivity to freedom, guilty to not guilty, death to life.  Freed    Paul in his letter to the Galatians accuses false brothers of infiltrating the church and spying on the 'freedom we have in Christ Jesus' and to make them again slaves (Gal 2:4). Later on Paul reaches a crescendo with his great rallying cry    \"It is for freedom that Christ has set us free. Stand firm then and do not let yourselves be burdened again by a yoke of slavery\" – Gal 5:1    What are we freed from? We are freed from the law. The law has revealed our sinfulness and we were 'prisoners by the law, locked up...' (Gal 3:23). Faith frees us by God's grace to live by the Spirit and freely love God as were made to.  Remade    The old has gone, the new has come. We are a new creation proclaims Paul in 2 Cor 5:17. I know some people struggle with Paul but when he comes to declaring to the followers of Christ the promises of God in Christ, he really has few rivals. Through faith in Christ there is an absolute and decisive disruption – the old dies and the new rises. It's why the church needs to rediscover a more forceful, robust, muscular teaching of baptism and the empowering of the Spirit. Come up out your grave Lazarus, you're no longer dead. Leave those old ways, you are alive in Christ!  Alive    I nearly stole my own thunder there, but it's a truth that not enough Christians take hold of, 'count yourselves dead to sin but alive to God in Christ Jesus' (Rom 6:11). Sin cannot be preached or explained as mistakes, mere errors of judgement, inconvenient dead ends in our journey of self-discovery but the real sign of death living within – the proof that the tumour is malignant not benign. It is also our resurrection hope, that just as we died with Adam, we will be raised with Christ (1 Cor 15:22). We do a disservice to the power of the resurrection when we make sin out to be akin to a headache than can be self-managed instead of a disease that is killing us.  Loved    Some of the other truths are critical to grasp and contain power to change how we think and live but our generation has in so many ways grown up in an environment where experience trumps all. Much of the contemporary worship movement is fuelled by worshippers who desire to not just know that God loves them but feel it deep within. But the bedrock of God's love is demonstrated in all of the above and it is the reason why in Rom 8:37-39 Paul can so confidently declare that 'nothing in all creation will be able to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord'. Faith in Christ unites us with him and brings us into the love that the Father has for His Son.  Sent    As the Father sent the Son, so the Son sends His people (Jn 17:18). What God has done for us in Christ, He will bring to life within us so He can bless the world through us. As a saved, freed, renewed, living and loved people we are sent to a broken world to do good works that the Father has prepared for us (Eph 2:10) to do. We are a people of light, to shine light in dark places and this not apart from faith in Christ but precisely the out working of that same faith. It gives all His people purpose and calling, a mandate to go and be ambassadors of God's anointed one.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Highlight Peter's reasons for calling on Christians to remain loyal to their masters in all situations.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Believers Should Submit to Authorities to Honor God    Submit yourselves for the Lord's sake to every authority instituted among men: whether to the king, as the supreme authority (emphasis mine).  1 Peter 2:13    The first reason believers are called to submit is because of the Lord. Peter says we should submit for \"the Lord's sake.\" This is the reason that believers can demonstrate lives full of submission even amidst persecution. It is because they live a life of submission to the Lord.    Look at what Paul taught in Romans 13:1–2,    Everyone must submit himself to the governing authorities, for there is no authority except that which God has established. The authorities that exist have been established by God. Consequently, he who rebels against the authority is rebelling against what God has instituted, and those who do so will bring judgment on themselves.    Paul says believers must submit because there is no authority except that which comes from God and to rebel against the authority is to rebel against God. We see this very clearly in the scenario with David and Saul. David had been anointed as future king, and yet King Saul wanted to kill him. He threw a spear at David, had soldiers come to his house to take him, and chased him through the mountains, and yet David always said this, \"I will not touch God's anointed. Who can touch God's anointed and be guiltless?\" Look at what he says:    But David said to Abishai, \"Don't destroy him! Who can lay a hand on the LORD's anointed and be guiltless? As surely as the LORD lives,\" he said, \"the LORD himself will strike him; either his time will come and he will die, or he will go into battle and perish. But the LORD forbid that I should lay a hand on the LORD's anointed (emphasis mine).  1 Samuel 26:9–11    See, for David, he realized that if he touched God's anointed, he would be guilty before God. He saw God as establishing Saul's leadership even though he was in rebellion.      Many are guilty before God because they have touched God's authority by their criticism, their abuse and attacks, and not only have they touched these people but touched and disrespected God.    Does this mean we do not recognize wrong? Certainly, we do, but the manner in which we do it makes all the difference in the world. Does our response mock, belittle, disrespect, or encourage rebellion in others? If we have done that, we have dishonored God.    The reason we submit is for the Lord's sake that we may honor him and also to avoid being disciplined by him. Paul said this in Romans 13:2, \"Consequently, he who rebels against the authority is rebelling against what God has instituted, and those who do so will bring judgment on themselves\" (emphasis mine).", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2018>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2018", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "List three virtues worthy of practice by Christians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The highest virtue, according to Aristotle was intellectual contemplation. In addition, there are an additional 12 virtues that can also be attributed to Aristotle and they are as follows:      - Courage – bravery and valor    - Temperance – self-control and restraint     - Liberality – bigheartness, charity and generosity       - Magnificence – radiance, joie de vivre     - Pride – self-satisfaction    - Honor – respect, reverence, admiration       - Good Temper – equanimity, level headedness    - Friendliness – conviviality and sociability     - Truthfulness – straightforwardness, frankness and candor    - With – sense of humor – meaninglessness and absurdity      - Friendship – camaraderie and companionship    - Justice – impartiality, evenhandedness and fairness", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Highlight the story of how the Israelites crossed the Red Sea.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Attempts by Moses to lead the Israelites out of Egypt met with stiff opposition from pharaoh after God has given him the mission to lead his people out of Egypt. God who has shown Moses series of signs that he should perform to convince the people also hardened Pharaoh's heart in order to bring untold suffering on the Egyptians. The Lord afflicted the Egyptians with a lot of plagues before Pharaoh reluctantly allowed the Israelites to go.    As soon as the let them go to worship their God in the wilderness, he pursued them again to bring them back, this was due to his regrets for letting them go and because God had hardened his heart so that he would achieve victory over them and his host [Exodus 14:14]. As the Egyptians drew near and caught up with them at Pihahiroth, the Israelites became afraid, they accused Moses that he deliberately wanted them to die in the wilderness. But Moses comforted them when he said;                       \"Fear not, stand firm and see the salvation of the lord, which he will                        work for you today; for the Egyptians whom you see today, you shall                         never see again         God instructed Moses to stretch out his rod over the Red sea. Moses stretched his rod over the sea, the sea was divided and the Israelites passed through a dry land. The Egyptians pursued them into the sea, God commanded Moses to stretch his rod again over the sea and the sea closed. This led to the drowning of the Egyptians. Having successfully delivered the Israelites from the bondage of Egypt, God fulfilled the covenant He had made with their father, Abraham. Having seen this, the people came to believe in Yahweh and in Moses His servant.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "State two lessons which Christians can learn from this incident.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Like Moses, Christians should demonstrate high sense of patriotism and render selfless service whenever they are called upon to lead people.  - As Christians, we should respect, fear, and depend on God to guide us in all our ways.  - Fear and panic weaken our faith and cause us to speak evil against God.                                                                                  - As good and faithful Christians, God will always protect us against evils and enemies.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>2", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "2", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "However, I will not tear away all the kingdom, but I will give one tribe to your son, for the sake of David my servant. Recount what led to above pronouncement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Due to the relative peace that reigned during the time of Solomon, after he had established himself as king of Israel, he lived in luxury. King Solomon engaged in so many expensive projects that required a lot of men and material resources. He raised forced labour and the citizenry were heavily taxed to finance these projects. He also started loving many foreign women of whom God had warned him not to marry, those women including the daughter of Pharaoh, and Moabite, Edomite, Sidonian and Hittite women. He married seven hundred wives and had three hundred concubines, they actually turned away his heart from following the way of the Lord. Solomon built high places for the gods his wives brought into Israel and made sacrifices to them  God was not pleased with Solomon because he did not follow Him wholeheartedly as his father David did. This led to the fall of Solomon and break of Israel as a nation into two parts. The Lord said to Solomon:               ''Since this has been your mind and you have not kept my  Covenant and my statutes which I have commanded you, I will  Surely tear the kingdom from you and will give it to your servant.  Yet for the sake of David your father, I will not do it in your days.....''  One tribe (Judah) was to be retained for the sake of David and for the sake of Jerusalem which Yahweh had chosen. This decision by God was actually fulfilled in the days of Rehoboam who reigned after King Solomon.", "marks": "15", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Outline Nehemiah's immediate reactions to the news about the state of affairs in Jerusalem.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "NEHEMIAH'S IMMEDIATE REACTIONS TO THE NEWS ABOUT THE STATE OF AFFAIRS IN JERUSALEM        Nehemiah, the son of Hachaliak and a cupbearer to king Artaxerxes of Babylon was visited by Hanai and Some certain men of Judah. Nehemiah wanted to know the state of Jerusalem and her inhabitants. Nehemiah was told that the remnants of the land were in great trouble and affliction. He was also told that the wall of Jerusalem also is broken down, and the gates thereof are burned with fire. When Nehemiah heard these words, he became sad and wept bitterly for days, and fasted, and prayed before God for several days.       Nehemiah on a faithful day after he had prayed to the Lord, went up to the king to give him his cup of wine as he has always been doing but with a sad countenance. The king asked him about what had happened and he told the king what had happened to the city of his fathers and where he was born. He was allowed to go to rebuild the wall of the city. On his arrival in Jerusalem, he delivered the king's letters to the governor of the provinces. In the letters, it was written that the materials needed by Nehemiah for the reconstruction of the city be supplied to him.This was done and the reconstruction work on the walls of Jerusalem began in earnest. Nehemiah went in the night to inspect the walls of Jerusalem so that that were broken down. Nehemiah said:                 \"Let us build the walls of Jerusalem so that we                   may no longer suffer disgrace\".    The people responded and the work started, but Samballat and Tobiah opposed the reconstruction work.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Identify three virtues that can be learnt from Nehemiah's reactions..", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "THE LESSONS FROM NEHEMIAH'S RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JERUSALEM  - Nehemiah showed a spirit of love for his nation.   - Nehemiah motivated his people into action.  - His faith in God was demonstrated through prayer.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "NATURE OF GOD : TRUE RELIGION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE – AMOS", "question": "I am no prophet, nor a prophet's son; but I am a herdsman and a dresser of sycamore trees. Give an account of the events that led to this statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "At the tirac of Amos, who was among the herdsmen of Tekoa, there was a high level of social and moral decadence in Israel. The focus of his prophesy was mainly the injustice which had eaten deep into the social life of the Israelites, from the days of Uzziah king of Judah, and in the days of Jerusalem the son of Joash king of Israel. The ordinances and statutes of God as given by Moses were not strictly followed.In fact, there was no true fear of God in the mind of the people .Amos said:            \" The Lord will roar from zion, and utter his              voice from Jerusalem; and the habitations              of the Shepherds shall mourn, and the top              of Carmel shall wither\".  This was to warn them about their ways and to tell them about the punishment that awaits them if they fail to repent from their evil ways. God through Amos said;            \"For three transgressions of Israel and for four,             I will not turn away the punishment thereof; because             they sold the righteous for silver and the poor for a pair              of shoes. They that trample the head of the poor into the             dust of the earth and turn aside the way of the afflicted\"  By this statement, Amos was invariably addressing various issues in Israel like Judges taking bribes and perverting justice, the poor who were being robbed of their properties, sexual immoralities. When the Priest of Bethel, Amaziah, heard all these things Amos had spoken, he sent to Jeroboam king of Israel, saying,         \"Amos hath conspired against thee in the midst          of the house of Israel; the land is not able to bear all           his words\".  Amos was then ordered to go back to Judah where he belonged, to prophesy. Then Amos answered and said:      \"I am no Prophet, nor a Prophet's son; but I am       a herdsmen and a dresser of sycamore trees\".", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Identify three reasons for which people complain about activities of some men of God today.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "THREE REASONS FOR WHICH PEOPLE COMPLAIN ABOUT ACTIVITIES OF SOME MEN OF GOD TODAY  - Some of the men of God do not practice what they preach.  - Owing to the fact what people have in mind and tend to do may not be what is revealed to the men of God by God. These things might not favour them at that instant.  - Some men of God condemn and judge activities of people painting them as unacceptably bad.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Relate the trail of Jesus before the Sanhedrin according to Mark's gospel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "THE TRIAL OF JESUS BEFORE THE SANHEDRIN ACCORDING TO MARK'S GOSPEL.        The trial of Jesus can be found in the three canonical synoptic gospels. In relation to the gospel of Mark, after Jesus was betrayed by Judas Iscariot with a kiss at the garden of Gethsemane and taken away, he was taken to the council where the high priest and all the chief priests, the elders and the teachers of the law were together. Peter followed himhim at a distance right into the courtyard of the high priest. There he sat with the guards and warmed himself at the fire. The chief priests and the whole Sanhedrin were looking for evidence against Jesus so that they could put him to death, but they did not find any.        Many testified falsely against him, but their statement did not agree. Then some stood up and gave this false testimony against him;       \"We heard him say I will destroy this temple made with human hands        And in three days, I will build another not made with hands\".  Yet even then, their testimony did not agree. Then the high priest stood up before them and asked Jesus, \" Are you not going to answer?, what is these testimony that these men are bringing against you? \". Jesus remained silent and gave no answer. The high priest then asked him again;      \" Are you the Messiah, the son of the blessed one?\".  Jesus answered and said \"I am\". The high priest rented his garment and said 'why do we need more witnesses?', with that he stirred up the mind of others in the courtyard against Jesus and all agreed and condemned as worthy of death. He was spat upon and beaten by the people and guards as he was taken away.  The gospel of mark was the only book the recorded that Jesus prophesy about the cock crow(three times).", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Give two reasons for which people bear false witness against others.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "TWO REASONS FOR WHICH PEOPLE BEAR FALSE WITNESS AGAINST OTHERS.  - People bear false witnesses against anothers on the basis of the hatred they have towards the person.  - Also people tend to bear false witnesses against another for selfish interest such as money, property or position.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : JESUS AT GETHSEMANE", "question": "My soul is very sorrowful, even to death; remain here and watch with me. Give an account of what happened to Jesus after he made this statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the last supper, and when they had sung an hymn, Jesus went out into the mount olives with Peter, James and John. There He told his disciples that;          \"My soul is very sorrowful, even to death;            remain here and watch with me\".  Jesus went a little further to pray and said in his prayers:            \" My Father, if it be possible, let this cup             pass from me, nevertheless not as I will but               as thou will\".  He came back to the disciples and found them sleeping, he woke them up and went back to pray. For the second time he prayed, repeating the same words. Again, he came back and discovered that the disciples' eyes were heavy with sleep. He left them, went away to pray again and came back to the disciples and said to them:                  \"Are you still sleeping and taking your                   rest?. Behold the hour is at hand and                    the son of man is betrayed into the hands of the sinners\".  While he was still speaking, Judas , one of his disciples came with a great crowd with swords and clubs from the chief priest and elders of the people. Before hand, the betrayer i.e Judas had given them a sign that  \" the one he kisses, is the man\".  Judas came up to Jesus and kissed him and said:                    \"Hail master\"  Immediately, the guards came up to him and seized him. One of the disciples of Jesus (Peter) stretched out his hand, drew his sword and cut off the ear of the slave of the high priest. Jesus was against this, he took the ear and inserted it right back to its position and said:                      \"Have you come out as against a robber with                       swords and clubs, to capture me?, day after                         day I sat in the temple teaching and you did                       not seize me. But all this has taken place for                         the scriptures might be fulfilled\".  At this juncture, His disciples fled and he was taken away.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Identify two ways by which one can assist a fellow Christian going through challenges.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Praying for the Christian fellow.   - Counselling the Christian.   - Helping the Christian in need, financially.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Give an account of Stephen's defence before the Sanhedrin.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "ACCOUNT OF STEPHEN'S DEFENCE BEFORE THE SANHEDRIN     Stephen was one of the seven deacons selected to carry out daily distribution of food and ensure the welfare of the less privileged people in the early church. Stephen was full of grace and power; he performed great wonders and signs among the people. Some of the Jews could not withstand the wisdom and the spirit with which he spoke. This led to the rise of the false allegations that was secretly instigated against him by these men. Stephen was said to blasphemed against Moses, the law and God, he was said to claimed Jesus would destroy the temple and many more. These accusation by Jewish law constituted serious offence punishable by death.       When Stephen was arraigned before the council, he surprised them by failing to refute the allegation. He decided to trace the history of the Jews to show them that they had been noted for persecuting the prophets of God. Before the council, Stephen also referred to them as stiff-necked people, uncircumcised in heart and ears. These statement angered the people the more, based on this he was dragged out of the city and stoned to death.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "State three lessons that can be learnt from Stephen's defence", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "LESSONS TO LEARN FROM STEPHEN'S DEFENCE   - Persecution is part of the heritage of Christians and they should not be discouraged by such things; rather persecution should make them strong in their faith.  - Stephen's defence, persecution and stoning helped to introduce Saul who later became Paul, the apostle to the gentiles.  - The trust, faith in God and righteousness of heart can make us stand anywhere, anytime to defend what is right. Because the righteous are as bold as a lion.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Therefore confess your sins to one another, and pray for one another, that you may be healed... What other teachings did James give on effective prayer?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "JAMES' TEACHINGS OF EFFECTIVE PRAYERS            St. James gave several teachings on the conditions to how an effective prayer can be answered and how we should pray in faith and believe that God will answer the prayer against all odds. St. James also said that no matter the suffering, Christians must persevere, they must not doubt because if they do, they might not receive answers to their prayers. He said in his words that;                  \"If any of you lack wisdom, let him ask God,                   who gives to all men generously and without                    reproaching, and it will be given to him\".  He also said concerning people that doubt that;                  \" But let him ask in faith without doubting,                    for he who doubt is like a wave of the sea                   that is driven and tossed by the wind\".  Another condition for the effective prayer that can be drawn from the words of St.James is that Christians must not ask wrongly. They must pray according to the will of God and with right motive. For this, it is essential to ask for wisdom from God for direction when we pray. According to St. James, the fervent prayer of the righteous has great power in its effects. So, to make our prayer effective, Christians should endeavor to live a righteous life.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "In what three ways are Christians misusing prayers today?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "WAYS CHRISTIANS MISUSE PRAYERS TODAY      There are several ways through which christians misuse prayers today, some of these are as follows;  - Christians pray some specific prayers at the wrong time in their lives. St. James stated in his book various types of prayers that ought to be prayed at various time and conditions.  - Some Christians use prayers to destroy others' lives. The essence of prayer isn't to rain curses on other persons, even if they are our enemies.   - God knows what is best for his children, but instead some christians tend to use prayer to ask for the wrong things from him.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight the attitude Peter recommended for Christians living among people of other faiths.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Christians live in communities with non-christians. In most cases, people are often jealous of Christians and are very fast at pointing accusing fingers at them to show that they are not righteous as they claim to be. Peter in his epistle outlined some of the attitude and expected roles of Christians living among people of other faith. He tried to warn Christians to abstain from any form of social vices and maintain a high moral standard of living.        He also included that they should avoid the passion of the flesh and things that hinder their spiritual growth. They must maintain good conduct among non christians, so that in case of false accusation, people would see their good deeds and glorify God. Again as men who live under the freedom of Christ, they should not use their freedom as pretext for evil, but as servants of God, they should honour all men, love their brothers , fear God and honour their leaders. St. Peter advised servants to submit themselves to their earthly masters. Christians should bear even where there is a case of unjust punishment. They should be responsible and faithful in carrying out their duties. In summary, christians should maintain high moral standard wherever they find themselves.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2019>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2019", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "State two factors that can make Christians turn away from pleasing God", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "FACTORS THAT CAN MAKE CHRISTIANS TURN AWAY FROM PLEASING GOD  - When Christians forsake God, forgetting all He has done for them and turn their heart to lesser gods.  - Another factor is lack of faith and believe in God can make christians turn away from pleasing God.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CREATOR", "question": "Highlight how God changed a formless earth to a lace of life and activity", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "God change the formless earth to a place of activities by creation, wherever there is life there will be activities God created both the living and nonliving things to shape the formless earth. In Gen 1:2-28, God created everything within six days. On the first day God created, the light and he separate the light from darkness. He called the light day and the darkness night, on the second day, God created the firmament in the sky, the significant of this is to separate the waters above and waters under the firmament.  On the third day, God created the dry land earth, and the gathering together of waters He called seas. He also created the grass, the herb, fruits of all kind. On the fourth day, God created the sun, the moon and the stars to give light to the earth. The greater light (Sun) to rule the day and the lesser light to rule the night the (significant of the lights are to divide the light from darkness, to give light upon the earth, for signs and for seasons, and for days and years.    On the fifth day, God created all the living creatures. He created the fish of the sea and other living creatures living therein; birds of the air and their kinds and saw that they good. He commanded them to multiply in the sea and on the land.  God created animals of various kinds on the sixth day. He also created man in his own image. God commanded man to be fruitful and multiply. On the seventh day God rested. These are what God did to shape the formless earth and turn it to a place of activities.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "State four ways by which humans are destroying God's creation", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Humans are destroying God's creation through the following human activities:  -\tCivilization has caused humans to cut down trees for Furniture, paper, buildings etc without replanting them.  -\tIndustrialization: Toxic waste are released by industry into the sea which in turn poison animals, pollute water and the soil, plants, air, etc  -\tEnmity between humans result to war and of course the killing of men, women, children and animals.  -\tHuman not obeying the commandments of God.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Outline God's instruction to Joshua on his assumption of leadership over Israel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Shortly after the death of Moses, the lord called Joshua and assured him of victory and success in his leadership assignments. God instructed Joshua on the way he should work in order to have good success. This instruction was explicit in Joshua 1:8 \"This Book of the Law shall not depart from your mouth, but you shall meditate on it day and night, so that you may be careful to do according to all that is written in it. For then you will make your way prosperous, and then you will have good success\"   In addition, God instructed him on his new assignment, which was leading the Israelites across River Jordan to take possession of the land. The city of Jericho was their target and eventually, under Joshua's leadership and the help of God, the wall of Jericho was conquered.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Identify three lessons that political leaders can learn from Joshua's experience", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The three lessons political leaders can learn from Joshua are:  -\tTo be strong and courageous to lead the people according to the will of God.  -\tTo read, observe and meditate the law book of the Lord day and night   -\tTo take instruction from God as Joshua did.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "Recount how David resisted taking Saul's life at the wilderness at Ziph", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "When the people of Ziph revealed to Saul where David was hiding, he rose up with his men in search of David in the wilderness of ziph. David who had noticed that Saul was after his life sent some of spies to confirm Saul's presence in the wilderness. Then David arose and came to the place where Saul had pitched, and Abner, the captain of his host, as they were all asleep. Abishai who was with David requested David to allow him to pin Saul to the earth but David refused and said in: 1Samuel 26:9 \"And David said to Abishai, Destroy him not: for who can stretch forth his hand against the LORD's anointed, and be guiltless?  26:10 David said furthermore, As the LORD liveth, the LORD shall smite him; or his day shall come to die; or he shall descend into battle, and perish.  26:11 The LORD forbid that I should stretch forth mine hand against the LORD's anointed: but, I pray thee, take thou now the spear that is at his bolster, and the cruse of water, and let us go\"     When David had gone far away from Saul's tent, he called upon Abner and reprimanded him for his failure to keep proper watch over his master. David asked him about Saul's spear and jar of water.  Saul recognized David's voice, repented of his sin, and promised never kill him without any cause.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "Identify four benefits of self-control", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It strengthens one's faith in the promises of God.  - It helps to guide ones decision   - It helps to fear and obey God's will  Self-control makes one' to wait patiently and to trust God for his promises to come to fulfilment", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Outline Solomon's prayer at the dedication of the temple", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The account of King Solomon's prayer at the dedication of the temple is recorded in 1kings8:22-28. King Solomon stood before the altar of the Lord in the presence of all congregation of Israel and he prayed as he acknowledge that there is no God like God in heaven above or on earth beneath. He requested of the Lord to keep his promises he gave to David his father. In addition, He prayed that God's words to David should be verified. He prayed that God's eyes may be open towards the temple at night and day and that God should hear the prayers, which his servant shall make towards him in this temple. Solomon prayed that God should forgive and restore his people when enemy smites Israel down. He prayed that, if there be a in the land famine, pestilence, blasting, or the enemy besiege the land and even if their enemy carry them away captive, if they repent and pray unto God that God should deliver them. Finally, King Solomon blessed the people of Israel and offered a sacrifice of peace offering. He offered two and twenty thousand Oxen and a hundred and twenty thousand sheep to the lord.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "In what three ways can leaders use resources for the development of the society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Leader can use resources for the development of the society by:  - Building social amenities such as schools, hospitals, etc.  - To help the less privilege in the society, for example the widows, the orphans,etc  - To create employment opportunities for the people living in the society", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Do not be afraid, henceforth you will be catching men. Describe the circumstances under which the above statement was made", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The circumstance under which the statement: don't be afraid, henceforth you will be catching men\" is recorded in the book of Luke5:1-11.  It was accounted that Jesus was standing by the lake of Gennesaret when he saw two boats by the lake. The anglers had gone out of them and were washing their nets. Jesus got into one of the boats, which belong to Simon. He asked him to put out a little from the land. Jesus then sat and taught the people from the boat and shortly after speaking, he said to Simon: \"launch out into the deep, and let down your nets for a draught.\" However, Simon who had toiled all night doubted and replied him saying: \"Master have toiled all the night, and have taken nothing: but at your word I will let down the net\" Luke 5:5.  When they tried again, they had a big catch that their net nearly broke by the weight of the fish. They even called in the assistance of their friends to help them.  When peter saw this miracle he was astonished, he fell on his knees and said, \"Depart from me, for I am a sinful man\". Then Jesus said to him,'' Do not be afraid, henceforth you will be catching men\". Luke5:10  As soon as they brought their boat to shore, they left everything and followed Christ.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : MARK 1: 16-20; 2: 13-17", "question": "Mention three factors that prevent people from becoming committed Christians", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The three factor that prevent people from becoming committed Christian are:            - Lack of willingness to endure hardship for the sake of gospel.  - Lack of willingness to pay the ultimate price.  - Lack of commitment to Christ.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Describe the burial of Jesus as narrated by the synoptic Gospel", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to the synoptic gospel i.e. Mathew, Luke, Mark and John. The burial of Jesus took place in the evening of the day of his crucifixion.  A rich man, joseph of Arimathea who was also a disciple of Jesus went to Pilate and asked for the body of Jesus. Pilate ordered it to be given to him. Then joseph took the body, wrapped it in a clean linen, and laid it in his own new tomb. He rolled a great stone at the entrance of the tomb and departed.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : AHAB", "question": "State three ways in which money is overspent during funerals in the society", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Three ways in which money is overspent during funeral in the society  - Society pressure.  - To put up a fake life  - Lack of initiative of what to use money on.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION B>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Describe the circumstances under which Peter was rescued from prison", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "As Herod Agrippa opposed and persecuted the church, he killed James, the brother of John. Then he realized that the death of James pleased the Jews, he then arrest peter with the intention to have him killed after the Passover celebration. However, in the prison, Peter was bound in chains and heavily guarded with soldiers. But, constant prayers were said on his behalf by other disciples. Then in the prison, an angel of the lord appeared, touched and woke him up, saying \"get up quickly\" immediately the chains fell off from his hand.  The angel then commanded Peter to follow him; Peter thought that he was dreaming. As he passed through the first and the second gates and came to the Iron Gate leading into the city, the gate opened of its own accord.  Then the angel left, Peter realized that the lord has sent an angel to rescue him. Peter went straight to the house of Mary the mother of John Mark where the brethren gathered to pray for him. When Peter knocked at the door, Rhoda identify his voice and told the brethren that Peter was at the door but they all expressed disbelief and said it could only be his ghost but they finally opened the door and found peter standing at the door. They all rejoice.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2020>SECTION B>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2020", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "What three lessons can be learnt from the incident above?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-The power of intercession: it is good to intercede for loved ones going through affliction  -Faith in God: All through the tribulation, Peter's faith in God did not falter, there is a good reward for faith in God.  -Christian should show love to one another", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Highlight the contributions of Cyrus to the return of the Jews from exile.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Ezra 1 v 1 - 11, King Cyrus is attributed to have aided the return of the Jews in the following ways:    - Cyrus issued a decree for all Jews to return to Jerusalem.    - He offered both financial and legal aid.    - He returned the vessels that were stolen from Jerusalem by Nebuchadnezzar.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "State three measures a nation can take to prevent God's wrath.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Before the coming of Jesus Christ, God was constantly angry with his people for their enormous sins against him. Though his love for man drew him closer to his people whom he directly spoke with, their sins instigated God's wrath which ends in merciless punishment, such as death, generational curses, loss in battles, and so on. Nevertheless, every nation needs to acknowledge God's will to prevent his wrath as it can be done in so many ways:    -\tObeying God's Commandments (Deut. 28: 1-9, Ex 32: 1-20)    God gave his people ten commandments as guidance to please him. He observes the sins of the world before delivering the commandments. Therefore, obeying his commandments will make him happy and prevent his wrath. Moses even advises the people of Israel in the Old Testament to obey God and faithfully keep his commandments. He further explains God's blessings as rewards of a nation's obedience to the commandments, which will bring success and fruitfulness to such a nation. For example, after God has given the ten commandments to the people of Israel through Moses, they made a golden calf and worshipped it while Moses was with God in the mountain. They disobeyed the third commandment, \"Thou shalt not serve any other God except me,\" which led to their destruction by death.     -\tAbstinence from Sins (Gen. 6-7, 19: 1-25)    God hates sins and that is why he warns us to desist from them. Before the arrival of Christ, the holy ones serve as intermediaries between God and man. They represent God's mouth in advising a nation to avoid sins, but the resistance in doing the right thing attracts God's wrath, just as seen in the stories of Noah and the fall of Sodom and Gomorrah. In the story of Noah, everyone was evil in God's sight except Noah and his family. So, God instructed Noah to build a boat out of good timbers and make rooms for himself, his family and different kind of animals so as to escape God's wrath. God destroyed the people with flood for forty days and nights. While in the story of the fall of Sodom and Gomorrah, God was also angry at the people's grievous sins which made him spare Lot and his family because they were sinless. And, he destroyed the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah with burning sulphur. All of these happened as a sign of God's wrath.    -\tObeying God's messages sent by his people (Jonah 4: 1-11)    People are bound to commit sins against God, but God is an All-forgiving one. He is ready to listen to a nation if she calls on him for the repentance of sins. However, there are nations who do not know God and commit several atrocities out of ignorance. But God, in his infinite mercies, sends his faithfuls to them so they can repent from their sins. Even though he is angry with such nations, he would forgive them as long as they have prevented his wrath by obeying his message(s) sent by his messengers. For instance, God was upset with the people of Nineveh which prompted him to send Jonah to them as regards to their sins. Despite Jonah's misbehaviour, he preached to them and they became converted christians. So, God changed his mind in punishing them because of their repentance. That is how they prevented God's wrath.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "Narrate the circumstances that led to Joseph's encounter with Pharaoh.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "( Numbers 13: 16-33 ; 14:1-10; 27:15-23)    Joseph was a man of profound intelligence with special spiritual gift of interpretation of dreams. His father Jacob loved him more than any of his children, because he was the son of his old age; for this reason, he made him a coat of many colors. This attracted hatred from his brothers against him. The relationship was farther worsened by the two dreams Joseph had which he told his brothers. In the first one, he said to his brothers.     \"Hear this dream which I have dreamed: behold we were binding sheaves in the field, and lo, my sheaf arose and stood upright; and behold your sheaves gathered round it, and bowed down to my sheaf.\" ( Genesis 37:7)    When his brothers heard this, they hated him the more. Again, he had another dream and told both his father and brothers, \"Behold I have dreamed another dream; and behold the sun, the moon, and eleven stars were bowing down to me.\" (Genesis 37:9)    This enraged his brothers and they conspired to kill him. The opportunity came when they were pasturing the flock at Shechem and their father sent him(Joseph) to go and see how they were faring. They threw him into a pit but later reconsidered and sold him out to some midianite traders. When the traders got to Egypt, they resold Joseph to Potiphar, an Egyptian army officer. While in Potiphar's house, he served diligently but he was falsely accused of raping Potiphar's wife which led to his imprisonment.    While in prison, he interacted well with the  other prisoners and interpreted the dreams of two inmates and one of them ended up becoming the chief butler. Joseph's first encounter with Pharaoh was when he interpreted his dream. Pharaoh had a two dreams which frightened him and he called all the nobles and magicians in Egypt to give him the interpretation but they could not. Then the chief butler whom Joseph had earlier interpreted a dream for when they were together in the prison remembered him and recommended him to Pharaoh. With the spirit of God in him, he gave Pharaoh perfect interpretation of the dream. He informed Pharaoh that both dreams were one. The seven good cows and ears both represented seven years of abundance while the seven lean and gaunt cows and seven empty ears blighted by the east wind indicated seven years of famine. Joseph pointed out that the famine would be severe that the years of bountiful harvest would be forgotten. He then made recommendations to Pharaoh on how to control the situation.     Due to the fact that Joseph was a man of immense intelligence and the only one whom God had given the wisdom to interpret the dream, Pharaoh appointed him as the second in command in Egypt and put him in charge of storage and distribution of grains.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSEPH", "question": "State three lessons which can be learnt by leaders from Joseph.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Leaders should learn to be men of integrity, honesty and humility and they should always be ready to serve.     - Leaders should always humble themselves and be at peace with everybody because they do not know who God will use to bless them.    - No human effort can stop one's destiny once one trusts and serves God diligently. So, leaders should learn to depend solely on God.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : AHAB", "question": "Outline the role played by Jezebel in the death of Naboth.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "1 Kings 21:1-19    Naboth had a vineyard in Jezreel, near the palace of Ahab. Ahab desired the vineyard and requested it from Naboth, so as to use it for a vegetable garden, in exchange for another vineyard or money.    Naboth refused to grant the request, pointing out that it was not right for him to give out his father's inheritance. Ahab went home in a bad mood and refused to eat. His mood attracted the attention of his wife, Jezebel, who wanted to know why the king was so upset. Ahab narrated to her how Naboth had refused to allow him take his vineyard in exchange for a better vineyard or money. Jezebel asked him to cheer up and eat his food, assuring him that he would have possession of the vineyard.     She wrote a letter in the name of the King, addressed to the elders and nobles of Jezreel with the instruction that they should proclaim a fast, set Naboth on high in their midst and set two base fellows to accuse Naboth of cursing God and the King. They were to take him out and stone him to death. The instruction was successfully carried out by the elders and nobles of Jezreel.    When Jezebel heard that Naboth was dead, she informed Ahab to go and take possession of Naboth's vineyard. Ahab arose and went to take possession of the vineyard, in accordance with her directive.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI", "question": "Give three reasons for which people are greedy.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Lack of contentment    - Envy    - One's selfish desire to acquire others property.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Highlight the promises God made to Joshua when he was appointed to lead the Israelites.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The book of (Joshua 1: 1-10) talks about the promises God made to Joshua when he was appointed to lead the Israelites. After the death of Moses, the lord spoke to Joshua, the son of Nun, Moses Minister saying:    \" Moses my servant is dead; now therefore arise, go over this Jordan, you and all this people, into the land which I am giving to them, to the people of Israel\".     The promises God made to Joshua goes thus:    - Every place that the sole of your foot will tread upon I have given to you, as I promised to Moses.    - From the wilderness and this Lebanon as far as the great river, the river Euphrates, all the land of the Hittites to the Great Sea toward the going down of the sun shall be your territory.    - No man shall be able to stand before you all the days of your life; as I was with Moses, so I will be with you; I will not fail you or forsake you.    - Be strong and of good courage; for you shall cause this people to inherit the land which I swore to their fathers to give them. The Lord your God is with you wherever you go.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : JOSHUA", "question": "Explain three benefits of fulfilling one's promises.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It builds your self esteem and confidence.    - It helps you have complete faith in yourself.    - It makes others view you as someone that is mature, reliable and has self confidence.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Recount the events that took place after Herod Agrippa I killed James.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Recount the event that occurred after Herod Agrippa 1 killed James (Acts 12: 1-24)    Apart from Saul, Herod Agrippa 1 is another prosecutor of christians. He opposed and prosecuted some members of the church, including James, the elder brother of John (sons of Zebedee). When he knew that James' death pleased the Jews, he arrested Peter and this occurred during the Festival of the Unleavened Bread. Peter was imprisoned to prepare him for his trial after Passover. But the members of the church were praying earnestly while Peter was in the prison. Then, an angel came to release Peter the night before his trial. The chains on Peter's hands fell off immediately the angel touched him. He instructed Peter to put on his sandals and wears and to follow him out of the prison.     After his release, Peter went straight to Mary's house (the mother of John Mark) where people gathered to pray for Peter's release. The members of the church didn't believe in Rhoda, one of the servants, when she brought the news of Peter's arrival. At last, they believed her and opened the door for him. They were amazed to see him and Peter narrated how the Lord had brought him out of prison. The next morning, King Herod heard about Peter's escape and killed the guards who watched over him. The opposition to the Gospel led to more success in the Apostle's efforts to spread Christianity rather than stopping it.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "State three factors that motivate Christians to pray.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "State three factors that motivate Christians to pray (James 1: 2 - 8, 5: 13-18)    Prayer is a means of communication between God and man. It is referred to as the master key that opens the door of God's hearings to our intentions. Since christian means \"Christ like,\" we are enjoined to be emulate Jesus' prayerful life. However, there are factors that motivate Christians to pray:  -\tSupplication/Petition prayer: Christians pray for personal needs. People constantly seek God's favour in times of troubles or other intentions. It may be for healing in health of mind and body, breakthrough in financial, spiritual or physical problems, or success in one's endeavours.     -\tConfessional prayer: When people commit sins against God, they confess their sins and plead for God's forgiveness through prayers. Christians are to pray with sincerity and remorse for any sins they have committed. James also admonishes Christians to confess their sins to one another and ask for forgiveness for such sins.     -\tThanksgiving prayer: Christians also pray to adore and thank God for his mercies and miraculous works in their lives. They thank him for the present, past and future graces. Since \"Thank You\" is what God needs from us, Christians praise him with words and actions.     -\tIntercessory prayer: Christians are motivated to pray for their loved ones, especially for those who can not pray for themselves. Some pray for the dead, the sick, their children's needs and many more.    Prayer connect us to God and guide us as Christians on every path of life. Therefore, James advises us to have faith regardless of any kind of trails that comes our way, which is expected of us as Christians while we pray.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "How was the problem of discrimination solved in the early Church by the Apostles?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "James 2:1-13    Discrimination is an unfair preference of something or someone over the other.    James used the instance of a person who comes into the Christian's assembly with a gold ring and wearing a splendid apparel and a poor person who comes in to the congregation with shabby clothes to explain the concept of discrimination to the church.     He said of they respect the man with a splendid apparel and offer him a good place to seat while the poor on shabby clothes to sit under their footstool, they are then discriminating and being judges of evil thought. He explained that God has chosen those who are poor in the eyes of the world to be rich in faith and heirs of the kingdom to those who love him, James reminded them that if they really fulfill the scripture they will love their neighbor as themselves, but if they show favouritism to people , they have sinned and convicted by the law as offenders.    He told them to act as those who are judged under the law of liberty and treat everyone as themselves not discriminating.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "State three effects of discrimination in society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It leads to low self-esteem of some individuals in the society.    - It leads to inferiority complex in the society    - It leads downfall of the society.    - Disunity/ Division in the society.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION B>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Narrate how Paul escaped the attempt on his life in Damascus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Acts 21: 27-36    After the conversion of Saul, he's name was changed to Paul. He started preaching the gospel he once hated and persecuted. He went to the temple to pray and some Jews in Asia saw him in the temple and the mobilize the people against him that he has polluted the temple by taking some Greeks to the temple thereby desecrating the temple. The people became angry, they dragged him out of the temple trying to kill him, then, the word came to the captain of the city that Jerusalem was in uproar, the captain immediately sent his soldiers. when the people saw the captain and his soldiers, the angry mob stopped beating Paul, the captain commanded that Paul should be bound with two chains, the captain asked the people the offense of Paul and different people said different things. As Paul came out to say what happened the angry mob started shouting and the soldiers took him away from the place because of the violence of the mob.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION B>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "Identify three reasons for which people wish evil for others.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Jealousy    - Hatred    - Because others are better than they are", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "According to Peter, what are the necessary requirements a citizen should have to make him/her responsible?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "According to Peter, in (1 Peter 2 13-17) he said it is a right practice of Christianity for Christians to obey the ruling authority, pay their taxes, show honour to whom honour is due, and above all, live lives that will be worthy examples to others. To this end, Peter in his epistle said a good citizen is he, who for God's sake, subjects himself to every human institution or authority. He respects the authorities or the rulers who have been appointed by God to punish evil doers and praise those who do the right thing. By doing the right thing, the good citizens put to shame the ignorance of foolish men. A good citizen should live as a free man, without using his freedom as a pretext for evil, but he should live as a servant of God whose lives should influence the life of the wicked. Above all; he should honour all men, love the family of Christ, fear God and honour the rulers and Kings.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "In what three ways can a good citizen help to develop his/her nation?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- A good citizen can help to develop his Nation by paying taxes, voting during elections, obeying the law, engaging in legitimate work, serving as good examples to others. He should also be dedicated to duty, and should be a respecter of man, the ruling authority and God.    - A good citizen should join voluntary organisations such as Boy's Scout, Girl's guide, Boy's Brigade, Red cross society, church youth etc.,to enhance the improvement and betterment of the society.    - A good citizen should also take part in public enlightenment campaigns to eradicate illiteracy, drugs peddling, armed robbery etc. He should avoid engaging in any trade or activity that would sabotage the country.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Discuss the necessary conditions under which a Christian's prayer can be answered.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "There are certain conditions or rules that will make our prayers effective, and answerable. Some of them are:    - Faith: Faith is defined in Hebrews 11:1 as, 'The assurance of things hoped for, the evidence of things not seen.' It is an absolute or complete trust in God and in His power. James advised that while we are addressing our problems to God, we should ask in faith, without doubt. Faith is very important in our prayer life. It attracts God's response. A faithless prayer is a powerless prayer, as it is written, 'A double- minded person is unstable in all his ways and receives nothing from God.'    - Righteousness: This simply refers to purity of heart. For our prayers to be effective, we must endeavor to abstain from sin. However, James, having known the moral weakness of man, advised that in order to place ourselves and our prayers at an acceptable status before God, we should confess our sins to one another because a sinner's prayer is an abomination in God's sight. We should also be remorseful and ask for forgiveness. The prayer of a righteous man availeth much.    - Perseverance: Praying persistently, with steady effort, and trusting God is necessary for fruitfulness in our prayer life.    - Fervency: For our prayers to be effective, we must pray with total concentration, seriousness and sincerity. A good example was the prayer of Hannah. She prayed fervently to God to give her a child and it was so. A lot of people in the bible prayed fervently and they received answers, people like; Elijah, Peter, Joshua, Jesus Christ.    - Humility: It means lowliness of heart and absence of self-exaltation. For our prayers to be effective, we must show total surrender and submission to God.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2021>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2021", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "State three types of Christian prayers.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Intercession: This is a type of prayer that Involves praying on behalf of others; this signifies concern for one another.    - Confession: It is a means of exposing our sins in humility and with the conviction of not falling back to them. It is a sign of repentance. This type of prayer is included in the Lord's prayer, \"And forgive us our trespasses as we forgive those who trespass against us\".    - Petition: It simply refers to requesting things from God. The bible support this prayer in Matthew 7:7 which says \" Ask and it shall be given to you; seek, and you shall find; knock, and the door shall be opened unto you\".", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Give an account of the story of the crossing of the Red Sea by the Israelites under the leadership of Moses.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Pharʹaoh told the Israelites to leave Egypt after God brought the 10th plague on the Egyptians. About 600,000 Israelite men left, as well as many women and children. Also, a large number of other people, who had become believers in Jehovah, left with the Israelites. They all took their sheep and goats and cattle with them. Before they left, the Israelites asked the Egyptians for clothes and for things made of gold and silver. The Egyptians were very much afraid, because of that last plague upon them. So they gave the Israelites everything they asked for.    After a few days the Israelites came to the Red Sea. There they rested. In the meantime, Pharʹaoh and his men began to feel sorry that they had sent the Israelites away. 'We have let our slaves go!' they said. So Pharʹaoh changed his mind once more. He quickly got his war chariot and his army ready. Then he began to chase after the Israelites with 600 special chariots, as well as all the other chariots of Egypt.When the Israelites saw Pharʹaoh and his army coming after them, they were very much afraid. There was no way to flee. The Red Sea was on one side of them, and here the Egyptians were coming from the other direction. But God put a cloud between his people and the Egyptians. So the Egyptians were not able to see the Israelites to attack them.    God then told Moses to stretch his stick out over the Red Sea. When he did, God caused a strong east wind to blow. The waters of the sea were parted, and the waters were held up on both sides. Then the Israelites began to march through the sea on dry ground. It took hours for the millions of people with all their animals to get safely through the sea to the other side. Finally the Egyptians were able to see the Israelites again. Their slaves were getting away! So they rushed into the sea after them. When they did, God caused the wheels of their chariots to fall off. The Egyptians became very much afraid and began to cry out: 'God is fighting for the Israelites against us. Let's get out of here!' But it was too late.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "Mention three lessons that can be learnt about the nature of God from the above incident.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-God wanted the Egyptians to know that He is the LORD.  Though God had a covenant responsibility to bring the Jewish People out of Egypt, he was also concerned about the spiritual condition of the Egyptians. \"I will harden Pharaoh's heart, and he will pursue them.  But I will gain glory for Myself through Pharaoh and all his army, and the Egyptians will know that I am the LORD.\"  (Exodus 14:4)    - God took the Israelites on the long way because He had great plans for them.  He had plans to transform them into a holy nation by giving them His word in the form of the Tablets of the Ten Commandments, written by His own hand.  He planned to create a civil and spiritual society by giving them the Torah or Five Books of Moses, which He would dictate to His prophet. He not only took them out of slavery into freedom, he recreated a people who were, in every sense, free.  They were transformed from cowering fearfully before the Red Sea to courageously fighting to take possession of the Promised Land.    -God wanted to demonstrate to the Israelites that he could sustain them even in the wilderness.  He miraculously supplied this massive nation with water from a rock, Manna from heaven and even meat in the form of flocks of birds. God also wants us to radically rely on Him so that He will supernaturally demonstrate to us that He is our provider, even in the toughest of times.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL", "question": "Relate the events that led to the pronouncement of punishment on the household of Eli.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Eli had two sons, Hophni and Phinehas, and these two sons of Eli were very wicked.Both sons were priest like their father, but they abused their position and misused the people and their offerings. Whenever someone would come to the Temple to give their offerings to God (this offering was of meat), the two sons would send their servants to take the meat off the fire and bring it back to them.Now the custom of the time was that the priest could take the meat off the fire only after the fat had burned, but the two sons demanded that they get their meat raw. They even threatened to take it from some people by force. This was a great sin in the eyes of the Lord.    Eli heard the news of this when he was very old, and he asked them several times why they were doing such things. He argued, \"If a man sins against another man, one can intercede for him with the Lord; but if a man sins against the Lord, who can intercede for him? \" The sons did not listen to their father and they continued their evil ways, but Eli looked the other way and ignored their crimes. God was not happy with this at all and he sent a man of God to give him a message. God had chosen Eli's family as the ones who would be the priests, but God told him, through the messenger, that he honoured those who honoured him. Because of Eli's great dishonor, God gave him a punishment. God condemned that every man of Eli's family shall never be an old man and that Hophni and Phinehas shall both die on the same day. God also established a new priest and a lasting house for him. Those who would be left of Eli's family would grovel at the feet of the new priest.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL", "question": "State three ways by which parents can make their children responsible.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Parents should teach their children the fear of the Lord in everything they do.    - Parents should have time to teach their children the word of God.    - The consequences of evil relationship between men and women must be pointed out to children.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SIN, REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS", "question": "I have done wrong; return my son David, for I will no more do you harm...   Recount the events that led to this apology.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "AFTER David kills Go·liʹath, Israel's army chief Abʹner brings him to Saul. Saul is very pleased with David. He makes him a chief in his army and takes him to live at the king's house. David is a very good player of the harp, and Saul likes the music that he plays. But one day Saul's jealousy causes him to do a terrible thing. While David is playing the harp, Saul takes his spear and throws it, saying: 'I will pin David to the wall!' But David dodges, and the spear misses. Later Saul misses David again with his spear. So David knows now that he must be very careful. Soon, David ran away.    When David heard that Saul had come after him, he sent out spies to confirm Saul's presence in the wilderness and the report he received was positive. That night, David and Abishai went into Saul's camp and found Saul sleeping, for the Lord had put a deep sleep upon him and his soldiers. Saul's spear was stuck to the ground by his head and his commander, Abner, and his men were sleeping round about him. Abishai saw this as an opportunity to get rid of Saul, saying God had delivered him into the hands of David. He sought permission from David to pin Saul down with one strike and kill him but David refused to give the order. David said, instead, that Saul should be allowed to live because he was the Lord's anointed and therefore should not be touched. According to David, at the right time, God himself would kill him, or he would die in battle or he shall die a natural death when he comes to the end of his life. They therefore allowed Saul to live. However, they took Saul's spear and water jar away.    Saul, recognizing David's voice, greatly repented. He called out to him. David asked Saul why he had been chasing him. If it was the Lord that had sent him, the Lord should accept a sacrifice and let it be but if it is men that have stirred his spirit to pursue him, the Lord must curse those men. Saul became remorseful. He regretted all his actions, even how he had chased David to kill him. He promised never to pursue him again and asked him to come back because he, David, had made the life of Saul precious in his hands.", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "What two qualities can we derive from David's attitude?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-David was kind and his kindness came from the heart of God.  David did not have kindness of his own to show the house of Saul.  Saul had chased David and made his life miserable.  Instead, it was the kindness of God that he wanted to give away.    -David kept his promise.  In 1 Samuel 18 and 20, David had promised Jonathan that he would not cut off his love from the house of Saul, once Jonathan was gone.  And so David was a covenant keeping man.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "Recount Josiah's response to the discovery of the  Book of the Law in the temple.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Josiah was among Judah's few \"godly kings,\" those who reigned in righteousness. When he was only 8 years old, Josiah succeeded his father, Amon, as king in Judah. Years before Josiah came to the throne, Judah had turned toward idolatry. During the reign of Amon, wickedness prevailed.Although he was but a boy, Josiah \"did that which was right in the sight of the Lord, and walked in all the way of David . . . and turned not aside to the right hand or to the left.\" (2 Kings 22:2). During the 18th year of Josiah's reign, work was begun to repair the temple. Hilkiah, the high priest, found \"the book of the law in the house of the Lord.\" (2 Kings 22:8.)    The book of the law was read publicly. Josiah and people of Judah entered into a solemn covenant to act according to its injunctions. When Josiah heard the book read, \"he rent his clothes,\" an ancient sign of despair. Because of what he heard read from the book of the law, Josiah instituted a reform program. He ordered the destruction of idols and groves (places where idols of nature were worshipped). Josiah ordered all the altars be removed, except in Jerusalem, thereby making that city the only sanctuary in all Judah. The conclusion of the reforms instituted by Josiah was marked by the celebration of the Passover in a new manner and with unusual solemnity.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "Identify  three  ways in which the religious situation today is similar to that of Josiah's days.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-As it was in Josiah's days when the people were filled with immoral acts, so also we have in our society today people we think to be practising the religion, but instead are far away from God's way.  -There are many corrupt preachers in our society and the church today.  - Crimes and various vices are rampant in the church today", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : JESUS AT GETHSEMANE", "question": "My soul is very sorrowful, even to death; remain here and watch with me.     Give an account of what happened to Jesus after he made this statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The statement was made at the Garden of Gethsemane on the Mount of Olives. He prayed throughout the night, periodically returning to His disciples to find them sleeping. The Gospels recount Jesus chastising them for their weakness and inability to keep watch during this time of deep need, a time when He prayed so earnestly the Gospel of Luke said \"His sweat was like drops of blood falling to the ground\" (22:44). When He returned to wake His friends the third time, however, Jesus appeared resolute, ready to face the path His Father had laid before Him. \"Are you still sleeping and resting?\" Jesus asked. \"Enough! The hour has come. Look, the Son of Man is delivered into the hands of sinners. Rise! Let us go! Here comes My betrayer!\" (Mark 14:41-42).    Just then, Judas, one of Jesus's twelve disciples, arrived with a large crowd armed with swords and clubs. With a kiss, Judas betrayed Jesus, and the Son of God was seized and arrested (Mark 14:43-46). One of Jesus's disciples — John says it is Peter — attempts to defend Jesus, drawing his sword and slicing off the ear of Malchus, the servant of the high priest (John 18:10). But after His all-night agony of sorrow and prayer, Jesus knew what needed to happen. He would have no violence or resistance. \"Jesus answered, 'No more of this!' And He touched the man's ear and healed him\" (Luke 22:51). Then, He went with the crowd willingly. At that, as Jesus had predicted, \"All the disciples deserted Him and fled\" (Matthew 26:56).    Later, after His death and resurrection, the Book of Acts, also known as Acts of the Apostles, places Jesus again upon the Mount of Olives (Acts 1:12). The disciples asked Jesus whether He would now be restoring the kingdom to Israel. Jesus responded, \"'It is not for you to know the times or dates the Father has set by His own authority. But you will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes on you; and you will be My witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.' After He said this, He was taken up before their very eyes, and a cloud hid Him from their sight\" (Acts 1:6-9).", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : JESUS AT GETHSEMANE", "question": "State two ways by which one can assist people going through challenges.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-Convince them to trust God's plan in their life despite the obstacles.    - Pray with them and for them as God has the power over all.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "You wicked servant; I forgave all that debt because you besought me...     Outline the circumstances that led to the above statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The parable tells the story of a king who was calling in debts from his servants. One servant owed a huge amount of money, 10,000 talents. He could not pay. The king ordered that the man and his family (wife and children) should be sold into slavery to pay off the debt. After the man pleaded for mercy and begged for more time (it would take multiple lifetimes for this person to pay back the debt), the king decided to have compassion and forgave the debt.    This same servant was owed a relatively small amount (100 denarii) by another servant. Ironically, even though he had just been granted mercy, the unforgiving servant demanded that the other's debt be paid. When the fellow servant was unable to pay, the unforgiving servant sent him to debtors' prison until he paid.    His actions were seen and reported to the king. Upon hearing that the forgiven servant refused to also forgive, the king removed his mercy from the man and sent him to be tortured until his debt was paid.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "State three reasons for which people find it difficult to forgive", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "-There's too much anger that causes a lack of self-control.    -One may feel misunderstood and find it hard to trust or let the offensive party in.    -One may be scared to forgive, in fear of getting hurt again.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION B>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "Give an account of how the prophecy of Joel was fulfilled on the day of Pentecost.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The first thing we note is a strange, and wondrous promise from God in Joel 2:28 is that God will \"pour out His spirit on all flesh\". We see this same language of something being poured out (c.f. Joel 2:23). There, God promises that He will pour down on His people abundant, providential rain, the early and letter rain, as before (Joel 2:23c) This same language of pouring helps us to understand what the pouring out of God's spirit. It tells us that God's act of giving His spirit to His people will be generous, widespread, and visible: like torrential rain flowing down.     We also should note who this pouring out of the Spirit is for. In the rest of Joel 2:28, God addresses different categories of the people of Israel: the sons and daughters (Joel 2:28b), the old, and the young (Joel 2:28c). This blessing of the Holy Spirit is for all flesh: all of God's people will receive His Spirit.  We should also pay further attention to the people groups mentioned in this verse. From the youngest to the oldest, from the servants to those with more, God's spirit will be poured out to all, without distinction of gender, class, educational levels, or wealth (Joel 2:28).  All of His people will receive His Spirit.    Peter references this same passage from the book of Joel.  Peter does so in reference to Pentecost, where Peter refers to this text to refute the claim that these followers of Christ were just really drunk.", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION B>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE HOLY SPIRIT AT PENTECOST", "question": "In what two ways was the fulfilment of Joel's prophecy on the day of Pentecost significant?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- It commemorates the descent of the Holy Spirit on the Apostles and other disciples following the Crucifixion, Resurrection, and Ascension of Jesus Christ.    -It marks the beginning of the Christian church's mission to the world.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "Recount the teachings of James in which he remarked that love your neighbour as yourself.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "\"My brothers, show no partiality as you hold the faith in our Lord Jesus Christ, the Lord of glory. For if a man wearing a gold ring and fine clothing comes into your assembly, and a poor man in shabby clothing also comes in, and if you pay attention to the one who wears the fine clothing and say, 'You sit here in a good place,' while you say to the poor man, 'You stand over there,' or, 'Sit down at my feet,' have you not then made distinctions among yourselves and become judges with evil thoughts? Listen, my beloved brothers, has not God chosen those who are poor in the world to be rich in faith and heirs of the kingdom, which he has promised to those who love him? But you have dishonored the poor man. Are not the rich the ones who oppress you, and the ones who drag you into court? Are they not the ones who blaspheme the honorable name by which you were called?    If you really fulfill the royal law according to the Scripture, 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself,' you are doing well. But if you show partiality, you are committing sin and are convicted by the law as transgressors. For whoever keeps the whole law but fails in one point has become guilty of all of it. For he who said, 'Do not commit adultery,' also said, 'Do not murder.' If you do not commit adultery but do murder, you have become a transgressor of the law.\"    James 2:1-11    As he did in his letter's opening, James again addresses his readers with the phrase, \"my brothers.\" He's talking to those within the community of faith, and in chapter two, he continues to teach them what it looks like to function as members of that community. At the forefront of this section is the call to avoid \"partiality,\" and here he specifically addresses partiality when it comes to wealth or status. Instead of showing favoritism, we're to love our neighbors as ourselves.    His argument goes like this: He exhorts his readers to change, then he offers a hypothetical situation (verses 2-4), asks rhetorical questions (verses 5-6), appeals to experience (6-7), shows how different actions could hypothetically pan out (verses 8-11), and concludes by calling them to therefore speak and act differently.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "Identify three negative effects of discrimination among Christians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Maltreatment of fellow christians.    -It breeds hate even when God asks us to love our neighbour as ourselves.    - It leads to disunity which can in turn lead to conflict and violence.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Outline Peter's recommendations that believers should interact with unbelievers in the society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Peter advised the Christians living among non-Christians to abstain from fleshy lust since it battles against the soul.  - He told them to engage in honest conversation among the Gentiles so that even if they speak against them, their good works would force the Gentiles to glorify God.  - Peter told them to subject themselves to every human institution whether it is the Emperor himself or the Governors that have been sent to reward those who do good and punish those who do wrong. According to Peter, if they do this, they will put to silence the ignorance of foolish men.  - He advised them to live as free men but should not use their freedom as a pretext to engage in evil. They should live as servants of God. They should honour all men, love the brotherhood, fear God and honour the emperor. Peter explained that they would receive no glory if they are punished for doing the wrong thing, but if they are punished for doing the right thing and they endure, it is acceptable before God.  - Peter concluded that Christ himself suffered the same fate. According to Peter, Jesus was reviled but he did not reply. Therefore, people must copy Christ's example.", "marks": "12", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2022>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2022", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "State three ways by which christians can live above reproach in their society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- They should not be arrogant or quick-tempered.    - They should perform their civil obligations and obey rules and regulations.    - They should avoid violence or greed for gain.", "marks": "3", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLES : MOSES", "question": "Examine the events that led to the marriage between Moses and Zipporah", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The marriage between Moses and Zipporah is a significant event in the biblical narrative, particularly found in the Book of Exodus in the Old Testament. The story sheds light on the early life of Moses and his experiences in Midian before he becomes a pivotal figure in leading the Israelites out of Egypt.    Before his marriage to Zipporah, Moses had grown up in the Egyptian palace as the adopted son of Pharaoh's daughter. However, he was aware of his Hebrew heritage and the oppression of his people by the Egyptians. One day, witnessing an Egyptian beating a Hebrew slave, Moses intervenes and kills the Egyptian. Fearing repercussions, he flees from Egypt and settles in the land of Midian.  In Midian, Moses arrives at a well, where he encounters seven sisters who are trying to water their father's flock. However, other shepherds are preventing them from doing so. Moses helps the women water their flock, which leads to an introduction to their father, Jethro (also known as Reuel), who is a priest of Midian. Jethro is grateful to Moses for helping his daughters and invites him to stay with them.  Moses accepts Jethro's offer and becomes a shepherd for Jethro's flock. He lives with Jethro's family and becomes integrated into their community. This provides him with a new sense of purpose and a safe haven away from the dangers he faced in Egypt. Moses becomes particularly close to Jethro's daughter, Zipporah. Over time, their interactions deepen, and their relationship evolves. Moses eventually marries Zipporah, making her his wife. The marriage is a significant step in Moses' personal journey, as it ties him even more closely to the Midianite community.  After their marriage, Moses and Zipporah have a son, whom they name Gershom. In a later event, while Moses is on his way back to Egypt after God's call to deliver the Israelites, he has a near-fatal encounter with God. In response, Zipporah circumcises their son and touches Moses' feet with the foreskin, seemingly as a symbolic act of obedience and appeasement to God. This act highlights the significance of obedience to God's commandments.   The marriage between Moses and Zipporah not only demonstrates the personal growth and transformation of Moses during his time in Midian but also serves as a turning point in his life's journey. Zipporah and her family offer Moses a haven of acceptance and a chance to rebuild his life away from Egypt. Additionally, their marriage signifies Moses' integration into a non-Israelite community, foreshadowing his later role as a leader who bridges different cultures during the Exodus.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Examine two reasons for which people seek asylum", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "People seek asylum for various reasons, primarily to escape persecution and violence. Firstly, people may seek asylum due to political reasons. They may be persecuted because of their political beliefs or affiliations. Secondly, people may seek asylum due to religious persecution. They may be targeted because of their religious beliefs or practices. In both cases, individuals or groups seek asylum in countries where they believe they will be safe and their rights will be respected.", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Recount how the diplomatic relations between Tyre and Israel enhanced the building of the temple during Solomon's reign.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "During King Solomon's reign in ancient Israel, diplomatic relations between the city-state of Tyre and Israel played a crucial role in enhancing the construction of the First Temple in Jerusalem. The cooperation between these two entities facilitated the acquisition of resources, skilled labor, and technical expertise necessary for the ambitious project. Tyre, located on the Mediterranean coast and known for its maritime and trading prowess, held a significant place in the ancient world. It maintained friendly relations with Israel, which was ruled by King Solomon, known for his wisdom and grand building projects.    The enhancement of diplomatic relations can be attributed to several key factors. Tyre was a major trading partner for Israel, providing essential resources such as cedar wood and other building materials required for constructing the temple. Tyre's forests were abundant in high-quality cedar, which was highly valued for its durability and beauty. The partnership enabled Solomon to acquire the necessary resources in substantial quantities.   Tyre possessed skilled craftsmen, including masons, carpenters, and other artisans, who had expertise in working with stone and wood. These skilled workers were instrumental in constructing the intricate details of the temple, ensuring its architectural magnificence. The collaboration between Tyre's craftsmen and Israelite builders contributed to the successful execution of the project.   King Hiram of Tyre had a friendly relationship with King Solomon. The two kings exchanged letters and gifts, solidifying their alliance. In the biblical account found in the Book of 1 Kings, Chapter 5, Hiram expresses his respect for Solomon's father, King David, and agrees to support the construction of the temple by providing materials, labor, and expertise. The friendly ties between Tyre and Israel extended to cultural and religious exchange. The temple was to be a sacred place of worship, and the collaboration between the two nations demonstrated a level of religious tolerance and mutual respect for each other's traditions.  The partnership was mutually beneficial. Israel gained access to the resources and expertise necessary for the grand temple project, while Tyre enjoyed the economic advantages of trade and enhanced political relations with a powerful neighboring kingdom.    The successful diplomatic relations between Tyre and Israel during Solomon's reign exemplify how collaboration and cooperation can lead to the accomplishment of monumental projects. The construction of the First Temple stands as a testament to the shared efforts and resources of both nations, contributing to the historical and cultural legacy of the region.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Highlight two benefits of diplomatic relations among nations.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Diplomatic relations among nations have several benefits. Firstly, they promote peace and stability. When countries maintain diplomatic relations, they are more likely to resolve their differences through dialogue rather than resorting to conflict. Secondly, diplomatic relations facilitate economic cooperation. Countries can negotiate trade agreements that benefit their economies. They can also collaborate on international projects and initiatives.", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS : THE REIGN OF KING JOSIAH", "question": "Recount the events that took place in Judah after the death of King Josiah to the deportation of the Jews", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "After the death of King Josiah of Judah, several significant events unfolded that ultimately led to the deportation of the Jews. King Josiah had been a righteous and reform-minded ruler who sought to restore the worship of Yahweh and eliminate idolatry in Judah. However, his death marked a turning point in the kingdom's fortunes.  King Josiah died in battle against Pharaoh Necho II of Egypt at the Battle of Megiddo in 609 BCE. His untimely death left a power vacuum in Judah.  After Josiah's death, his son Jehoahaz (also known as Shallum) became king. However, his reign was short-lived, lasting only three months. Pharaoh Necho II captured Jehoahaz and took him as a prisoner to Egypt.  Pharaoh Necho II appointed Jehoahaz's older brother, Eliakim, as the new king of Judah. Eliakim changed his name to Jehoiakim and became a vassal of Egypt. During his reign, Jehoiakim paid tribute to Egypt, but he also faced pressure from the rising Babylonian Empire.   The Babylonian king Nebuchadnezzar II defeated the Egyptian forces at the Battle of Carchemish in 605 BCE. This victory marked the beginning of Babylon's dominance in the region. Nebuchadnezzar then turned his attention to Judah and besieged Jerusalem. Jehoiakim initially submitted to Babylonian rule but later rebelled.  Jehoiakim died during the Babylonian siege of Jerusalem in 598 BCE. His son Jehoiachin (also known as Jeconiah) succeeded him. However, Jehoiachin's reign lasted only three months before Nebuchadnezzar captured him and many of Jerusalem's elite.   Nebuchadnezzar II deported Jehoiachin, along with thousands of skilled workers, officials, and nobles, to Babylon in 597 BCE. This event marked the beginning of the Babylonian exile, which would have a profound impact on Jewish history and identity.   Nebuchadnezzar appointed Zedekiah as the puppet king of Judah. Zedekiah initially obeyed Babylonian authority, but he later rebelled, leading to another siege of Jerusalem. In 586 BCE, Nebuchadnezzar's forces breached the city walls, destroyed the Temple, and captured Zedekiah. This event marked the end of the independent Kingdom of Judah. The destruction of Jerusalem and the Temple by the Babylonians in 586 BCE was a catastrophic event in Jewish history. Many more people were deported to Babylon, and the kingdom's political and religious center was devastated.    The events from Josiah's death to the Babylonian exile marked a period of decline, political upheaval, and displacement for the people of Judah. The Babylonian exile, in particular, played a crucial role in shaping the future of Judaism, as the exiled Jews began to develop a stronger sense of religious identity and community during their time in Babylon.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "State four causes of civil unrest in a nation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Civil unrest in a nation can be caused by a variety of factors. These include:   - Economic Inequality: When there is a wide gap between the rich and the poor, it can lead to civil unrest. The poor, feeling marginalized and neglected, may resort to protests and demonstrations to express their dissatisfaction.   - Political Corruption: Corruption in the government can also lead to civil unrest. When citizens perceive that their leaders are corrupt, they may take to the streets to demand accountability and transparency.   - Social Injustice: Injustices such as racial or ethnic discrimination can lead to civil unrest. People who feel that they are being treated unfairly due to their race or ethnicity may resort to civil unrest to fight for their rights.   - Lack of Basic Amenities: When the government fails to provide basic amenities such as clean water, electricity, healthcare, and education, it can lead to civil unrest. People may protest to demand these basic services.", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE", "question": "Let us build with you for we worship your God as you do, and we have been sacrificing to Him ever since.     Narrate the events that followed this request of the Samaritans.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The request of the Samaritans to build with the Jews is recorded in the book of Ezra. After the Jews returned from exile in Babylon, they began to rebuild the temple in Jerusalem. When the Samaritans, who were living in the region, heard about this, they approached Zerubbabel and the heads of the families and said, 'Let us help you build because, like you, we seek your God and have been sacrificing to him since the time of Esarhaddon king of Assyria, who brought us here.' But Zerubbabel, Jeshua and the rest of the heads of the families of Israel answered, 'You have no part with us in building a temple to our God. We alone will build it for the LORD, the God of Israel.' This caused the Samaritans to become hostile and they tried to discourage and frighten the Jews to keep them from building. They even bribed officials to work against them and frustrate their plans during the entire reign of Cyrus king of Persia and down to the reign of Darius king of Persia.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "State four causes of tensions among neighbours.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Tensions among neighbours can be caused by several factors. These include:   - Noise: Excessive noise from loud music, machinery, pets, or arguments can cause tensions.   - Property Boundaries: Disputes over where one property ends and another begins can lead to tensions.   - Pets: Issues related to pets, such as noise, smell, or pets damaging property, can cause tensions.   - Privacy: If a neighbour feels their privacy is being invaded by another, it can lead to tensions.", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "Then Jesus said to him, begone Satan! For it is written, you shall worship the Lord your God and Him only shall you serve .   Narrate the events that took place before Jesus made the above statement as recorded in Matthew.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The events that took place before Jesus made the above statement are recorded in Matthew 4:1-10. After Jesus was baptized, He was led by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil. After fasting forty days and forty nights, He was hungry. The tempter came to Him and said, 'If you are the Son of God, tell these stones to become bread.' Jesus answered, 'It is written: Man shall not live on bread alone, but on every word that comes from the mouth of God.' Then the devil took Him to the holy city and had Him stand on the highest point of the temple. 'If you are the Son of God,' he said, 'throw yourself down. For it is written: He will command His angels concerning you, and they will lift you up in their hands, so that you will not strike your foot against a stone.' Jesus answered him, 'It is also written: Do not put the Lord your God to the test.' Again, the devil took Him to a very high mountain and showed Him all the kingdoms of the world and their splendor. 'All this I will give you,' he said, 'if you will bow down and worship me.' Jesus said to him, 'Away from me, Satan! For it is written: Worship the Lord your God, and serve Him only.'", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATION", "question": "Highlight three lessons which Christians can learn from Jesus encounter with Satan in 5(a).", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "From Jesus' encounter with Satan, Christians can learn several lessons.   - The Importance of Scripture: Jesus used Scripture to counter Satan's temptations. This shows the importance of knowing and understanding the Bible.   - The Need for Spiritual Discernment: Jesus recognized Satan's attempts to twist Scripture and responded with correct understanding. This highlights the need for spiritual discernment.   - The Power of Resistance: Jesus resisted Satan's temptations, showing that it is possible to resist temptation with God's help.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Lord, how often shall my brother sin against me, and I forgive him?     Narrate Jesus's response to the above question.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Jesus's response to the question 'Lord, how often shall my brother sin against me, and I forgive him?' is found in Matthew 18:21-22. Peter asked Jesus this question, and Jesus replied, 'I do not say to you, up to seven times, but up to seventy times seven.' This response was to emphasize the importance of forgiveness in the Christian faith. Jesus was not literally saying that one should forgive 490 times, but rather that forgiveness should be limitless. He further illustrated this with the Parable of the Unforgiving Servant, which teaches about the immense forgiveness that God has shown us and how we should likewise show the same to others.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Outline three benefits one stands to gain in forgiving others.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Forgiving others has several benefits. Firstly, it leads to peace of mind. Holding onto grudges and anger often leads to stress and anxiety. By forgiving, one can let go of these negative emotions and achieve peace. Secondly, forgiveness promotes healthier relationships. It allows for reconciliation and the resolution of conflicts. Thirdly, forgiveness can lead to personal growth. It can help one to develop empathy, understanding, and compassion. Lastly, in the Christian context, forgiving others is a command from God and is necessary for one's own sins to be forgiven by God (Matthew 6:14-15).", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION B>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Outline the circumstances that led to the untimely death of Ananias and Sapphira.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The untimely death of Ananias and Sapphira, as recorded in Acts 5:1-10, was a result of their deceit and hypocrisy. The early Christian church had a practice where members sold their possessions and gave the proceeds to the apostles to distribute to those in need. Ananias and Sapphira sold a piece of property but kept back part of the money for themselves, while pretending to give all of it. When confronted by Peter, they lied about the amount they received from the sale. As a result, they were struck dead as a divine judgment.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION B>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "State four lessons the church of today can learn from the actions of Ananias and Sapphira that led to their death.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The actions of Ananias and Sapphira that led to their death provide several lessons for the church today. Firstly, God values honesty and integrity. They were not obligated to sell their property or give all the money, but they were judged for their deceit. Secondly, God sees and knows everything. We cannot hide anything from Him. Thirdly, the story warns against hypocrisy. As Christians, we should be genuine and not pretend to be what we are not. Lastly, it teaches about the severity of God's judgment. God is loving and merciful, but He is also just and righteous.", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "Outline James' instructions to Christians on how to conduct effective and result-driven prayer.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "James' instructions on how to conduct effective and result-driven prayer are found in James 5:13-18. He advises Christians to pray in all circumstances, whether in joy or in suffering. He emphasizes the importance of faith, stating that the prayer of a righteous person is powerful and effective. He also encourages confession of sins and prayer for each other for healing. Furthermore, he uses the example of Elijah to illustrate that earnest prayer can yield miraculous results. Overall, James instructs Christians to be persistent, faithful, and sincere in prayer.", "marks": "7", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : EFFECTIVE PRAYERS", "question": "State four factors that hinder prayer from being heard and answered.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Prayer is a spiritual communication between man and God, a two-way relationship in which man should not only talk to God but also listen to Him. Prayer to God is like a child's conversation with his father. It is natural for a child to ask his father for the things he needs. There are several factors that can hinder prayer from being heard and answered. These include:    - Sin: Sin separates us from God and hinders our prayers. God is holy and there is a barrier that exists between Him and us when we live in sin. Isaiah 59:2 says 'But your iniquities have separated between you and your God, and your sins have hid his face from you, that he will not hear.'    - Doubt: Doubt is another factor that hinders our prayers from being answered. James 1:6-7 says 'But let him ask in faith, nothing wavering. For he that wavereth is like a wave of the sea driven with the wind and tossed. For let not that man think that he shall receive any thing of the Lord.'    - Selfishness: When we ask with wrong motives, our prayers will not be answered. James 4:3 says 'Ye ask, and receive not, because ye ask amiss, that ye may consume it upon your lusts.'    - Unforgiveness: Holding grudges or not forgiving others can hinder our prayers. Mark 11:25 says 'And when ye stand praying, forgive, if ye have ought against any: that your Father also which is in heaven may forgive you your trespasses.'", "marks": "8", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Highlight Peter's advice to elders and the youths of the church on how to promote good relationship.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Peter's advice to elders and the youths of the church on how to promote good relationship can be found in 1 Peter 5:1-5. Peter, being an elder himself, exhorts the elders among the believers to shepherd the flock of God that is among them, not by compulsion but willingly, not for shameful gain, but eagerly. They should not lord it over those in their charge, but be examples to the flock. This means that elders should lead by example, showing humility, patience, and love in their dealings with the members of the church.    To the younger members of the church, Peter advises them to be subject to the elders. He further advises everyone to clothe themselves with humility toward one another, for 'God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble.' This means that the youths should respect the elders and learn from their wisdom and experience. They should also show humility, recognizing that they have much to learn and that all believers are equal in the sight of God.    By following Peter's advice, elders and youths can promote good relationships within the church, fostering unity and mutual respect among its members.", "marks": "10", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2023>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2023", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS", "question": "Indicate three ways by which conflict retards the growth of the church.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Conflict is a state of disagreement or argument between people, groups, or ideas. In the context of the church, conflict can arise due to differences in beliefs, values, or goals among its members. Conflict can retard the growth of the church in several ways:    - Diversion of Resources: When there is conflict, the church's resources (time, money, energy) are often diverted to resolving the conflict instead of being used for the growth and development of the church.    - Loss of Members: Conflict can lead to the loss of members. Some members may choose to leave the church rather than be part of the conflict. This reduces the number of people in the church and can slow down its growth.    - Damage to Reputation: Conflict can damage the reputation of the church. Outsiders may view the church as a place of strife and discord rather than a place of love and unity. This can discourage potential new members from joining the church.", "marks": "5", "difficulty": "1"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "In what three ways was Israel affected by the unwise policies of Solomon?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Solomon's unwise policies had significant adverse effects on Israel:    Heavy Taxation and Forced Labor: Solomon's extensive building projects, including the construction of the Temple and his palaces, imposed heavy taxes and forced labor on the Israelites. This created widespread discontent and economic strain, leading to increased burdens on the populace and fostering resentment among the tribes.    Religious and Cultural Compromise: Solomon's marriages to foreign princesses and his tolerance of their religions led to the introduction and acceptance of idolatry in Israel. His policy of allowing the worship of foreign gods undermined the centrality of Yahweh worship and weakened the religious unity of the nation, contributing to a decline in spiritual and moral integrity.    Political Instability and Division: The discontent generated by Solomon's policies contributed to political instability. After Solomon's death, the northern tribes, feeling marginalized and oppressed by his administration, rebelled against his successor, Rehoboam. This rebellion led to the division of the kingdom into the northern kingdom of Israel and the southern kingdom of Judah, significantly weakening the nation's unity and stability.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : THE UNWISE DECISION OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM", "question": "Identify three character traits of leaders that make them unpopular.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Three character traits of leaders that often lead to unpopularity are:    Arrogance: Leaders who display arrogance tend to be perceived as out of touch with the needs and concerns of their constituents. Arrogance involves an inflated sense of self-importance and a disregard for others' opinions and contributions. This trait alienates followers and diminishes trust, making it difficult for leaders to build meaningful relationships and garner support.    Inconsistency: Leaders who frequently change their positions, policies, or decisions without clear rationale create confusion and frustration among their followers. Inconsistency undermines credibility and reliability, leading to a lack of confidence in the leader's ability to provide stable and coherent direction. This unpredictability can erode support and lead to dissatisfaction.    Lack of Transparency: Leaders who are secretive or evasive about their actions, decisions, and intentions often face criticism and mistrust. A lack of transparency can create perceptions of dishonesty or corruption, leading to suspicions about the leader's motives and integrity. This trait can foster a negative environment and diminish the leader's legitimacy and support.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Explain three challenges that confronted the Jewish returnees during the rebuilding of the temple.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "During the rebuilding of the temple in Jerusalem after the Babylonian exile, the Jewish returnees faced several significant challenges:    Opposition from Local Peoples: The returnees encountered resistance from neighboring peoples, such as the Samaritans and other local groups, who felt threatened by the Jewish restoration efforts. These opponents used various tactics, including political manipulation and legal challenges, to disrupt and delay the rebuilding process. Their interference created significant obstacles for the returning Jews, causing delays and complications in the construction.    Economic Difficulties: The returnees struggled with limited resources and financial constraints. Rebuilding the temple required substantial funds and materials, which were difficult to secure due to economic hardship and the challenges of managing resources in a post-exilic context. The lack of sufficient economic support affected the progress and quality of the reconstruction efforts.    Internal Disputes and Leadership Issues: The process was also hindered by internal conflicts and disputes among the Jewish returnees. Leadership struggles, differing priorities, and a lack of unity among the returnees created friction and impeded effective decision-making and cooperation. These internal issues undermined the collective effort needed for the successful rebuilding of the temple.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Highlight three factors that stand in the way of development in your country.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In Nigeria, three factors that hinder development are:    Corruption: Corruption at various levels of government and institutions diverts resources from development projects, undermines efficiency, and erodes public trust.    Inadequate Infrastructure: Poor infrastructure, including unreliable electricity, inadequate roads, and insufficient healthcare facilities, limits economic growth and affects quality of life.    Political Instability: Frequent political instability and conflicts disrupt governance and development efforts, creating an uncertain environment for investment and progress.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "O Nebuchadnezzar; we have no need to answer you in this matter ...   Recount the event that necessitated the above statement by the three exiled Jews.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The statement \"O Nebuchadnezzar; we have no need to answer you in this matter...\" is from the biblical story of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, who were three Jewish exiles in Babylon during the reign of King Nebuchadnezzar II. This event is recorded in Daniel 3.    Nebuchadnezzar had constructed a massive golden image and decreed that all subjects in his kingdom must worship it. He set up a scenario where, at the sound of various musical instruments, everyone was required to bow down to the image. Failure to comply would result in being thrown into a fiery furnace.    Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, who were faithful to their God, refused to bow to the golden image. Their refusal was seen as defiance against the king's command, which incited the king's anger. They were summoned before Nebuchadnezzar and given another chance to worship the idol. When they remained steadfast in their refusal, Nebuchadnezzar's rage escalated.    Before the king, the three men made their famous declaration: \"O Nebuchadnezzar, we have no need to answer you in this matter...\" This statement signified their unwavering faith in God and their refusal to compromise their beliefs. They believed that God would deliver them from the furnace, but even if He did not, they would not bow to any other god.    In response, Nebuchadnezzar had the furnace heated seven times hotter than usual and ordered the men to be thrown in. Miraculously, they emerged unharmed, with no evidence of fire on them, and a fourth figure, appearing as a divine being, was seen walking with them in the flames. This miracle demonstrated the power of their faith and resulted in Nebuchadnezzar praising their God.", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "FAITH IN GOD : FAITH AND COURAGE", "question": "Outline four ways in which Christians can maintain their faith in God.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Christians can maintain their faith in God through:    Regular Prayer: Engaging in daily prayer strengthens their relationship with God, seeking guidance, comfort, and spiritual connection.    Study of Scripture: Reading and meditating on the Bible helps deepen understanding of God's will, promises, and teachings, reinforcing faith.    Active Church Participation: Being involved in church services, fellowship, and community activities provides support, encouragement, and opportunities for spiritual growth.    Living According to Christian Principles: Practicing love, forgiveness, and integrity in daily life aligns with Christian values and demonstrates commitment to faith.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : THE CONDITION OF THE NATION", "question": "Give an account of the incident that made the Jews describe King Cyrus of Persia as the Lord's anointed.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The Jews described King Cyrus of Persia as \"the Lord's anointed\" due to his pivotal role in the return of the Jewish exiles from Babylon and the restoration of their temple in Jerusalem. This recognition is rooted in biblical accounts, particularly in the Book of Isaiah.    In 539 BCE, King Cyrus II of Persia conquered Babylon, ending the Babylonian Empire's dominance. This victory was seen as a significant event for the Jewish people, who had been exiled in Babylon following the destruction of Jerusalem and its temple by Nebuchadnezzar II in 586 BCE.    The critical incident that led to the Jews' description of Cyrus as \"the Lord's anointed\" is detailed in Isaiah 45:1, where Cyrus is explicitly named as God's chosen instrument. The passage states: \"This is what the Lord says to his anointed, to Cyrus, whose right hand I take hold of to subdue nations before him and to strip kings of their armor.\" This designation signifies that Cyrus was seen as divinely appointed to fulfill God's plan for the Jewish people.    Cyrus's decree in 538 BCE, which allowed the Jewish exiles to return to Jerusalem and rebuild their temple, was a fulfillment of prophetic promises made by God through the Hebrew prophets. His policy of allowing exiled peoples to return to their homelands and rebuild their places of worship was unprecedented and significant.    Cyrus's actions aligned with Jewish expectations of divine intervention and restoration, leading to his recognition as \"the Lord's anointed.\" The term \"anointed\" usually reserved for Israelite kings, symbolized Cyrus's role in executing God's will and bringing about the restoration of the Jewish community and their religious practices. His favorable decree was seen as a direct intervention by God, making him a key figure in Jewish history.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "CLOSENESS", "topic": "CONCERN FOR ONE’S NATION : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF THE NATION", "question": "Identify three ways by which immigrants can contribute to the welfare of their host nation.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Immigrants can contribute significantly to their host nation's welfare in several ways:    - Economic growth: Immigrants often fill labor shortages in various sectors, from low-skilled jobs to highly specialized roles. They bring diverse skills, entrepreneurial spirit, and innovation, starting businesses that create jobs and stimulate economic activity. Their contributions to the workforce can increase productivity and tax revenues, benefiting the overall economy.  - Cultural enrichment: Immigrants bring diverse traditions, languages, cuisines, and perspectives, enhancing the cultural fabric of their host nation. This diversity fosters creativity, promotes cultural exchange, and can lead to increased tolerance and understanding among different communities. It can also boost tourism and create new markets for goods and services.  - Demographic balance: Many developed countries face aging populations and declining birth rates. Immigrants, who are often younger and of working age, can help balance the demographic structure. This influx of younger workers can support social systems like pensions and healthcare, which rely on a robust working-age population to fund benefits for retirees.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Highlight Luke's account of the demands of discipleship.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Luke's Gospel provides a detailed account of Jesus' teachings on discipleship, emphasizing the demanding nature of following Christ. Throughout his narrative, Luke highlights several key aspects of discipleship that Jesus presents as essential for those who wish to be his followers.    Absolute commitment: Luke records Jesus' teachings that underscore the need for total dedication to following him. In Luke 9:57-62, Jesus encounters three would-be disciples, each of whom faces a challenge to their commitment. Jesus emphasizes that discipleship requires putting him before family obligations, personal comfort, and even farewell to loved ones. This passage illustrates that discipleship demands unwavering focus and prioritizing Jesus above all else.  Self-denial and cross-bearing: In Luke 9:23-24, Jesus states, \"If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross daily and follow me.\" This teaching emphasizes that discipleship involves rejecting self-centeredness and embracing daily sacrifice. The image of cross-bearing implies a willingness to endure hardship and potential persecution for the sake of following Christ.  Renunciation of possessions: Luke's account frequently highlights Jesus' teachings on the dangers of wealth and the need to prioritize spiritual riches over material ones. In Luke 14:33, Jesus declares, \"So therefore, any one of you who does not renounce all that he has cannot be my disciple.\" This radical call to detachment from material possessions underscores the all-encompassing nature of discipleship.  Counting the cost: Luke 14:25-33 contains Jesus' teachings on the importance of carefully considering the demands of discipleship before committing. Using the analogies of building a tower and going to war, Jesus emphasizes the need for thoughtful commitment, understanding that following him may come at great personal cost.  Love for enemies: In Luke 6:27-36, Jesus teaches his disciples to love their enemies, do good to those who hate them, bless those who curse them, and pray for those who mistreat them. This radical ethic of love challenges disciples to go beyond conventional morality and embody the transformative power of God's love.  Persistence in prayer: Luke's Gospel emphasizes the importance of persistent prayer in the life of a disciple. The parable of the persistent widow (Luke 18:1-8) encourages disciples to pray continually and not lose heart, illustrating the need for unwavering faith and perseverance.  Servant leadership: In Luke 22:24-27, Jesus redefines greatness for his disciples, emphasizing that true leadership in his kingdom is characterized by service rather than domination. This teaching challenges disciples to adopt a countercultural approach to power and influence.  Witnessing and mission: Luke's account of Jesus' final instructions to his disciples in Luke 24:44-49 emphasizes their role as witnesses to his death and resurrection. This commission extends the demands of discipleship beyond personal transformation to active participation in spreading the gospel message.  Dependence on the Holy Spirit: Luke's Gospel concludes with Jesus' promise of the Holy Spirit (Luke 24:49), which is further elaborated in the book of Acts. This emphasizes that meeting the demands of discipleship is not achieved through human effort alone but through reliance on divine empowerment.    Throughout Luke's account, the demands of discipleship are portrayed as all-encompassing, requiring a radical reorientation of one's life around Jesus' teachings and mission. While these demands are challenging, Luke also emphasizes the transformative power of following Jesus and the ultimate reward of participating in God's kingdom.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "Outline three characteristics expected of a potential disciple", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Based on Luke's account, three key characteristics expected of a potential disciple are:    - Unwavering commitment: A disciple must be willing to prioritize following Jesus above all else, including family obligations, personal comfort, and material possessions. This commitment involves a readiness to \"deny oneself\" and \"take up one's cross daily\" (Luke 9:23), indicating a willingness to endure hardship and sacrifice for the sake of following Christ.  - Radical love and service: Disciples are called to embody a transformative ethic of love that extends even to enemies (Luke 6:27-36). This love is expressed through service, as Jesus redefines greatness in terms of servanthood rather than domination (Luke 22:24-27). A potential disciple must be ready to challenge conventional notions of power and adopt a lifestyle of selfless service to others.  - Persistent faith and prayer: Luke emphasizes the importance of unwavering faith and continuous prayer in the life of a disciple. Through parables like that of the persistent widow (Luke 18:1-8), Jesus teaches that disciples should pray continually and not lose heart. This characteristic involves maintaining trust in God's promises and purposes, even in the face of challenges or apparent delays in answers to prayer.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE TRIALS OF JESUS : CONDEMNATION OF JESUS", "question": "Describe how Jesus was pronounced guilty before Caiaphas, the High Priest.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The trial of Jesus before Caiaphas, the High Priest, is a pivotal moment in the Gospel narratives, particularly described in Matthew 26:57-68, Mark 14:53-65, and Luke 22:54-71. While John's Gospel provides less detail about this specific encounter, it does mention Jesus being brought before Annas and then Caiaphas (John 18:13-24). Let's examine how Jesus was pronounced guilty before Caiaphas, synthesizing the accounts from the Synoptic Gospels.  After Jesus' arrest in the Garden of Gethsemane, he was first brought to the house of Caiaphas, where the Sanhedrin, the Jewish ruling council, had gathered. This nighttime trial was highly irregular, as Jewish law typically required trials to be held during daylight hours.  The trial began with the religious leaders actively seeking false testimony against Jesus to justify putting him to death. Matthew's account emphasizes that despite many false witnesses coming forward, their testimonies did not agree. This lack of consistent evidence posed a problem for the council, as Jewish law required the testimony of at least two witnesses to be in agreement for a conviction.  Eventually, two witnesses came forward claiming that Jesus had said he could destroy the temple and rebuild it in three days. This statement, likely a misinterpretation of Jesus' words about his body being the temple (John 2:19-21), was seen as blasphemous. However, even these testimonies were not in perfect agreement.  Throughout this process, Jesus remained silent, not offering any defense against the false accusations. His silence fulfilled the prophecy in Isaiah 53:7, which describes the suffering servant as one who \"was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth.\"  Frustrated by Jesus' silence and the lack of conclusive evidence, Caiaphas decided to directly question Jesus. He demanded, \"I charge you under oath by the living God: Tell us if you are the Messiah, the Son of God\" (Matthew 26:63). This question was crucial, as it aimed to elicit a response that could be construed as blasphemy.  Jesus' reply was pivotal: \"You have said so. But I say to all of you: From now on you will see the Son of Man sitting at the right hand of the Mighty One and coming on the clouds of heaven\" (Matthew 26:64). This response combined two significant Old Testament references: the Son of Man from Daniel 7:13-14 and the Lord's declaration to the Messiah in Psalm 110:1. By affirming his identity as the Messiah and associating himself with these divine figures, Jesus provided the high priest with the grounds for a blasphemy charge.  Caiaphas' reaction was immediate and dramatic. He tore his clothes, a traditional Jewish expression of grief or horror, and declared, \"He has spoken blasphemy! Why do we need any more witnesses? Look, now you have heard the blasphemy\" (Matthew 26:65). This act of tearing his garments, while customary for hearing blasphemy, was ironically against the law for a high priest (Leviticus 21:10).  The high priest then asked the council for their verdict, and they unanimously declared Jesus to be \"worthy of death\" (Matthew 26:66). This pronouncement of guilt was based on their interpretation of Jesus' claim as blasphemy, which under Jewish law was punishable by death.  Following this verdict, some members of the council began to mock and abuse Jesus. They spat in his face, struck him with their fists, and taunted him to prophesy who had hit him, fulfilling Isaiah's prophecy about the suffering servant being struck and spat upon (Isaiah 50:6).", "marks": "11", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "State two lessons that can be drawn from Jesus' trial.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Two important lessons can be drawn from Jesus' trial before Caiaphas:    - Integrity in the face of injustice: Jesus maintained his composure and integrity throughout an unjust trial. He remained silent in the face of false accusations, only speaking when directly questioned about his identity. This demonstrates the power of maintaining one's principles and truth even when facing severe opposition or unfair treatment. It teaches us the importance of staying true to our convictions, even in challenging circumstances.  - The cost of standing for truth: Jesus' unwavering commitment to his identity and mission, even knowing it would lead to his condemnation, illustrates the potential cost of standing for truth. His response to Caiaphas, affirming his messianic identity, sealed his fate but also fulfilled his purpose. This teaches us that sometimes, upholding the truth and staying true to one's calling may come at a great personal cost, but can ultimately serve a greater purpose.", "marks": "4", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION B>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Give an account of the events that led to the appointment of the seven deacons.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The appointment of the seven deacons, as recorded in Acts 6:1-7, was a significant development in the early Christian church. This event occurred during a period of rapid growth and increasing complexity in the Jerusalem church community. Let's examine the sequence of events that led to this important decision.    Growth of the Church:  Following the Day of Pentecost and the apostles' preaching, the early church in Jerusalem experienced rapid growth. Acts 2:41 mentions that about 3,000 people were baptized in a single day, and Acts 4:4 notes that the number of believers grew to about 5,000 men. This exponential growth brought both blessings and challenges to the nascent Christian community.  Communal Living and Distribution of Goods:  The early church practiced a form of communal living where believers shared their possessions and provided for one another's needs (Acts 2:44-45, 4:32-35). This system involved the daily distribution of food and other necessities, particularly to those in need, such as widows.  Emerging Conflict:  As the church grew, a problem arose concerning the daily distribution of food. Acts 6:1 states, \"In those days when the number of disciples was increasing, the Hellenistic Jews among them complained against the Hebraic Jews because their widows were being overlooked in the daily distribution of food.\"    This complaint highlighted a cultural and linguistic division within the early church. The Hellenistic Jews were Greek-speaking Jews who had adopted many Greek customs, while the Hebraic Jews were native to Palestine and spoke Aramaic. This cultural divide led to perceived or actual inequities in the care of widows from different groups.    The Apostles' Response:  When this issue was brought to their attention, the Twelve Apostles recognized the need for action. However, they also realized that managing this distribution system themselves would divert them from their primary responsibilities. Acts 6:2 records their statement: \"It would not be right for us to neglect the ministry of the word of God in order to wait on tables.\"    This response demonstrates the apostles' commitment to their core mission of prayer and the ministry of the word, while also acknowledging the importance of addressing the practical needs of the community.    Proposal for a Solution:  The apostles proposed a solution that would address the immediate problem while preserving their focus on spiritual leadership. They suggested selecting seven men from among the believers to take charge of this important task. Acts 6:3-4 outlines their proposal: \"Brothers and sisters, choose seven men from among you who are known to be full of the Spirit and wisdom. We will turn this responsibility over to them and will give our attention to prayer and the ministry of the word.\"    This proposal is significant as it demonstrates a willingness to delegate authority and create new leadership roles within the church structure.    Qualifications and Selection:  The apostles set clear qualifications for these new leaders. They were to be:      Full of the Spirit  Full of wisdom  Of good reputation    These criteria ensured that the chosen individuals would have both the spiritual maturity and practical skills necessary for the task.    Implementation and Appointment:  The proposal pleased the whole community (Acts 6:5). Seven men were chosen: Stephen, Philip, Procorus, Nicanor, Timon, Parmenas, and Nicolas. Notably, all seven have Greek names, suggesting they were likely chosen from the Hellenistic Jewish community to address the specific concerns raised.    These men were presented to the apostles, who prayed for them and laid their hands on them, officially appointing them to their new roles (Acts 6:6).    Positive Outcomes:  The appointment of these seven deacons (though they're not explicitly called deacons in this passage) had immediate positive effects. Acts 6:7 reports, \"So the word of God spread. The number of disciples in Jerusalem increased rapidly, and a large number of priests became obedient to the faith.\"    This resolution of the internal conflict allowed the church to refocus on its mission, resulting in continued growth and even the conversion of many Jewish priests.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION B>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH", "question": "Explain three ways by which conflict can be resolved in the society.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Three effective ways to resolve conflict in society are:    - Dialogue and negotiation: Encouraging open communication between conflicting parties can lead to mutual understanding. This involves active listening, empathy, and a willingness to compromise. Facilitated discussions or mediation by neutral third parties can help structure these conversations productively.  - Education and awareness: Many conflicts stem from misunderstandings or lack of information. Promoting education about different cultures, beliefs, and perspectives can reduce prejudices and foster tolerance. Public awareness campaigns and inclusive curricula in schools can play a crucial role in this process.  - Institutional reforms and policies: Implementing fair and equitable policies can address systemic issues that often underlie societal conflicts. This might involve legal reforms to protect minority rights, economic policies to reduce inequality, or the creation of institutions dedicated to conflict resolution and peacekeeping. Ensuring these policies are transparently enforced can build trust and reduce tensions in society.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION C>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "\"... Have a seat here, please, while you say to the poor man, stand there or; sit at my feet.\"     Recount how the above situation was addressed by James in the church.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The passage referenced is from the Epistle of James, specifically James 2:3, which is part of a larger discussion on favoritism and discrimination within the church. James addresses this situation in James 2:1-13, providing a pointed critique of showing partiality based on social status or wealth. Let's examine how James approaches this issue in detail.    Setting the Scene (James 2:1-4): James begins by presenting a hypothetical scenario in a gathering of believers. Two men enter: one wearing fine clothes and gold rings (indicating wealth), and another in poor clothes. The church members react differently to each, offering the rich man a good seat while telling the poor man to stand or sit on the floor. This scenario vividly illustrates the problem of favoritism based on outward appearances.  Rhetorical Question (James 2:4): After describing this scene, James asks a rhetorical question: \"Have you not discriminated among yourselves and become judges with evil thoughts?\" This question serves to make the readers reflect on their actions and motivations.  God's Perspective (James 2:5): James reminds his readers of God's view, stating that God has chosen those who are poor in the eyes of the world to be rich in faith and to inherit the kingdom. This assertion challenges the worldly values that prioritize material wealth over spiritual riches.  Contrasting Behaviors (James 2:6-7): James points out the irony in favoring the rich, noting that it is often the rich who exploit the believers and drag them into court. He also mentions that it is often the wealthy who blaspheme the noble name of Christ. This serves to further highlight the misplaced nature of such favoritism.  The Royal Law (James 2:8-9): James then introduces the concept of the \"royal law\" found in Scripture: \"Love your neighbor as yourself.\" He argues that if believers truly follow this law, they are doing right. However, showing favoritism is a sin and a violation of this law.  The Unity of the Law (James 2:10-11): To emphasize the seriousness of this sin, James explains that breaking one point of the law is equivalent to breaking the entire law. This underscores that showing favoritism is not a minor infraction but a significant breach of God's commandments.  The Law of Liberty (James 2:12-13): James concludes this section by encouraging believers to speak and act as those who will be judged by the \"law that gives freedom.\" He emphasizes that judgment without mercy will be shown to anyone who has not been merciful, but mercy triumphs over judgment.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION C>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLES OF JAMES : IMPARTIALITY", "question": "In what three ways does the situation above affect the progress of society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The situation of favoritism based on wealth or status, as described by James, can significantly hinder societal progress in three key ways:    - Perpetuation of inequality: By giving preferential treatment to the wealthy, society reinforces existing economic disparities. This can lead to reduced social mobility, as those without means are denied opportunities for advancement, thus creating a cycle of poverty and privilege.  - Erosion of social cohesion: Favoritism breeds resentment and division among different socioeconomic groups. This fragmentation can weaken community bonds, reduce cooperation, and hinder collective problem-solving, ultimately slowing societal development.  - Misallocation of resources and talent: When society values wealth over merit or character, it risks overlooking or underutilizing the potential contributions of less affluent individuals. This can result in a loss of diverse perspectives, innovative ideas, and valuable skills that could otherwise drive societal progress and address complex challenges more effectively.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION C>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "But you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation ...   Outline Peter's expectations of the people described above.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "In 1 Peter 2:9, the apostle Peter describes the Christian community as \"a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession.\" Through this description, Peter highlights the special status and expectations of believers. His message is aimed at encouraging the early Christians to live up to the high calling that their unique identity in Christ affords them. Below is an outline of Peter's expectations of these people, based on the attributes he assigns to them.    Live as a \"Chosen Race\"  Peter refers to Christians as a \"chosen race,\" signifying their special election by God. This phrase evokes the idea of being set apart, similar to how Israel was chosen by God in the Old Testament. Peter expects Christians to recognize that their identity is not by accident but by divine design. As a chosen people, they are to reflect God's purpose in their lives by living according to His will. This calls for a life of moral purity, commitment, and dedication to God's commandments. Their status as a chosen people means they are to serve as a model for others, demonstrating the transformative power of God's grace.     Function as a \"Royal Priesthood\"  Peter's designation of the believers as a \"royal priesthood\" indicates a dual role. First, it implies that they belong to God's kingdom, sharing in His royal status. Second, as a priesthood, they have the responsibility of mediating between God and humanity. In the Old Testament, priests were responsible for offering sacrifices and interceding for the people. In the New Testament context, Peter is calling believers to offer spiritual sacrifices—such as worship, prayer, and service—that are pleasing to God (1 Peter 2:5). Moreover, they are to act as ambassadors of God's kingdom, bringing His message of reconciliation to the world.     Uphold the Character of a \"Holy Nation\"  Peter describes Christians as a \"holy nation,\" calling attention to the concept of holiness, which means being set apart for God. This expectation extends beyond mere ritual purity to include moral and ethical living. Believers are called to stand out from the world by their conduct, which should be aligned with the values of God's kingdom rather than worldly principles. Peter expects Christians to embody this holiness in every aspect of their lives—how they interact with others, how they speak, and how they treat the marginalized. Their holiness should be a testimony to the transforming power of the Gospel.     Serve as a \"People for His Own Possession\"  Being described as \"a people for His own possession\" underscores the idea that Christians belong exclusively to God. This expectation implies a deep sense of loyalty and devotion. Christians are to live in a way that reflects their belonging to God, not merely as individuals but as a collective community. This collective identity is to be characterized by love, unity, and mutual support. Peter expects believers to be a distinct community that glorifies God, not only through their personal conduct but also in how they live together as a body of Christ.     Proclaim God's Marvelous Works  Finally, Peter expects the chosen people to \"proclaim the excellencies of him who called you out of darkness into his marvelous light.\" This involves bearing witness to the redemptive work of Christ. Christians are to be evangelists, sharing the message of salvation and the transformative power of God's grace. Their lives should be a reflection of the spiritual change they have undergone, inspiring others to come to know God. This proclamation is not limited to words but extends to actions that reflect God's goodness.", "marks": "9", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2024>SECTION C>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2024", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : CHRISTIANS LIVING AMONG NON-CHRISTIANS", "question": "Explain three factors that stand in the way of peaceful co-existence among people.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Three key factors that hinder peaceful co-existence among people are:    - Cultural Differences and Intolerance: Misunderstandings or prejudices arising from diverse cultural backgrounds often lead to conflict. When individuals or groups are intolerant of others' beliefs, customs, or languages, it creates divisions and fosters resentment.    - Economic Inequality: Disparities in wealth and access to resources can lead to tensions between different social groups. Poverty and competition for limited resources can incite conflicts, as those disadvantaged may feel marginalized and oppressed.    - Political Instability and Poor Governance: In regions where governments are corrupt, ineffective, or unjust, mistrust and anger among the populace can lead to unrest. The absence of fair laws or systems that protect citizens' rights further exacerbates conflicts, making peaceful co-existence difficult.", "marks": "6", "difficulty": "2"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>1>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Outline the roles played by King Hiram of Tyre in Solomon's preparations towards the building of the temple.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Provider of Timber: King Hiram supplied cedar and cypress wood from Lebanon—premium timber essential for building the temple.    - Provision of Skilled Artisans: He sent expert craftsmen, notably Huram-Abi, a man renowned for his wisdom and technical expertise, to contribute to the temple's detailed design and construction.    - Support in Transportation: Hiram facilitated the movement of timber by shipping it in rafts across the sea to Joppa, from where it was transported overland to Jerusalem.    - Diplomatic Relationship: He upheld a cordial alliance with Solomon, building on the strong friendship he had previously established with Solomon's father, David.    - Bilateral Trade Arrangement: Hiram and Solomon formed a trade partnership—Solomon provided agricultural goods like wheat and oil in return for building materials and skilled labor.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>1>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "MAKING DECISIONS : SOLOMON’S WISDOM", "question": "Identify three benefits a nation derives from good diplomatic relations.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Promotion of Peaceful Coexistence: International relations foster mutual understanding and diplomatic engagement, enabling nations to resolve conflicts peacefully and maintain global stability.    - Expansion of Trade and Economic Growth: Strong international ties open up access to foreign markets, encourage investment, and promote the exchange of goods and services, thereby boosting economic development.    - Strengthened Security Cooperation: Through international alliances, countries collaborate on military operations, intelligence sharing, and joint efforts to combat terrorism, cybercrime, and other cross-border threats.    – Exchange of Knowledge and Technology:  International relations facilitate the sharing of scientific research, technological innovations, and best practices in fields like medicine, agriculture, and education, helping countries advance more rapidly.    – Humanitarian Support and Disaster Relief:  Through global partnerships, countries can receive aid and support during natural disasters, pandemics, or humanitarian crises, reducing suffering and speeding up recovery.    – Promotion of Cultural Exchange:  Diplomatic ties encourage tourism, student exchange programs, and cultural festivals, helping people appreciate and respect other cultures, which strengthens global harmony.    – Joint Action on Global Issues:  International cooperation enables countries to tackle shared challenges such as climate change, environmental degradation, and public health emergencies through coordinated strategies and global agreements.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>2>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "SUPREMACY OF GOD : ELIJAH AT MOUNT CARMEL", "question": "Recount how the supremcy of God was made manifest during the contest on Mount Camel.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The contest on Mount Carmel occurred during a period when the Israelites, under King Ahab and Queen Jezebel, had abandoned God to worship Baal. In response, the prophet Elijah challenged Baal's prophets to a public showdown to reveal who the true God was. He summoned the people of Israel to Mount Carmel and set the terms: both Elijah and the prophets of Baal would prepare a bull for sacrifice but would not set it on fire. The God who responded with fire would be declared the true God.    The prophets of Baal went first. From morning till evening, they shouted, danced, and even cut themselves in a frenzy, calling on Baal. Despite their desperate efforts, there was no response—no fire, no voice—proving Baal's powerlessness. Elijah mocked their failure, suggesting that perhaps their god was asleep or too busy to answer.    When Elijah's turn came, he rebuilt the Lord's altar using twelve stones, symbolizing the twelve tribes of Israel. He arranged the wood, prepared the bull, and had water poured over the entire offering three times until it drenched the altar and filled the surrounding trench. Elijah then prayed, asking God to reveal Himself and turn the hearts of the people back to Him.    At once, fire from heaven fell, consuming the sacrifice, the wood, the stones, the dust, and even the water in the trench. Witnessing this, the people fell to the ground and cried out, \"The Lord, He is God!\" This undeniable display of divine power exposed Baal as false and affirmed God's supremacy. Elijah then ordered the arrest and execution of the prophets of Baal, underscoring that God alone deserves worship and that His authority cannot be challenged.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>2>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "In what three ways can the Church fight against immoral acts in the society?", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Teaching Sound Doctrine: The church must consistently preach and uphold biblical teachings and moral values, shaping the character and behavior of its members in alignment with God's standards.    - Providing Spiritual Counseling: Through mentoring and guidance, the church should support individuals battling immoral influences, helping them overcome temptations and make godly choices.    - Engaging in Community Outreach: By offering educational programs, social support, and positive alternatives, the church can reach those outside its walls and promote moral transformation in the wider society.    - Setting a Godly Example:  Church leaders and members must model upright living, demonstrating honesty, compassion, humility, and integrity, which others can emulate both within and outside the church.    - Organising Youth and Discipleship Programmes:  Targeted programmes can help nurture young people in faith, teach them moral values, and equip them to resist peer pressure and societal immorality.    - Praying for Moral Revival:  Through intercessory prayers and spiritual warfare, the church can seek God's intervention in restoring righteousness and moral consciousness in individuals and the nation.    - Condemning Evil and Injustice Publicly:  The church should speak out boldly against corruption, violence, injustice, and all forms of immorality, serving as the moral conscience of the society.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>3>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLE: AMOS", "question": "Give an account of Amos' encounter with Amaziah, the priest.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The story of Amos and Amaziah, found in Amos 7:10–17, takes place during the reign of King Jeroboam II—a time when Israel was economically prosperous but morally corrupt. Idolatry was widespread, the poor were oppressed, and the nation had turned away from God. To address this, God sent Amos, a prophet from Judah, to warn Israel of impending judgment.    Amaziah, a priest at Bethel—a major religious center that had sadly become a hub for idol worship, especially of a golden calf—was alarmed by Amos' bold prophecies. Amos proclaimed that Israel would fall and its people would be exiled. Amaziah saw this message as a threat to national stability, religious authority, and the king's reign.    In response, Amaziah reported Amos to King Jeroboam, accusing him of inciting rebellion. He then confronted Amos directly, telling him to leave Israel and return to Judah to prophesy there, insisting that Bethel was the king's sanctuary and not a place for such messages.    Amos, however, stood firm. He clarified that he was not a prophet by profession or by training, but a shepherd and a dresser of sycamore trees whom God had called to deliver His message to Israel. His authority came not from human institutions but from God Himself.    Amos then delivered a stern prophecy against Amaziah: his wife would become a prostitute, his children would die by the sword, his land would be divided, and he himself would die in exile. It was a powerful warning about the consequences of rejecting God's word and silencing His messenger.    Despite opposition from powerful figures like Amaziah, Amos remained faithful to his divine calling. The story highlights the tension between true prophecy and corrupt religion, and shows how God can use ordinary people to speak truth and call a nation back to righteousness.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>3>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "LEADERSHIP ROLE: AMOS", "question": "From the account  in 3a, state three practices that need to be condemned.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "From the account in 3a, the practices that need to be condemned are:    - Idolatry: The worship of idols, such as the golden calf at Bethel, which led the people away from the true God.    - Religious corruption: Priests like Amaziah used their positions to protect false worship and oppose genuine prophetic messages from God.    - Opposition to God's messengers: Attempting to silence prophets like Amos, who were sent by God to speak the truth, reflects a rejection of divine authority and guidance.    – Hypocritical Worship:  The Israelites engaged in religious rituals and sacrifices while living in sin. Amos condemned their worship as meaningless because it lacked genuine righteousness and obedience (Amos 5:21–24).    – Trust in Pagan Nations and Military Might:  Israel placed confidence in alliances and military strength rather than relying on God, showing spiritual unfaithfulness and pride (Amos 6:13).    – Mixing True Worship with Pagan Practices:  The people blended the worship of Yahweh with Canaanite religious customs, defiling the purity of their faith and disobeying God's commandments (Amos 5:26).    – Neglect of the Covenant Relationship:  Israel broke the covenant by failing to uphold God's laws, especially those concerning justice, mercy, and exclusive worship, betraying the special relationship God had established with them (Amos 3:2).", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>4>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "SIN AND ITS CONSEQUENCES", "question": "'Behold, while the child was yet alive, we spoke to him and he did not listen...' Recount the incident that led to the above statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The statement \"Behold, while the child was yet alive, we spoke to him and he did not listen...\" refers to an incident involving King David, found in 2 Samuel 12:15-23.    The background of this event is David's sin with Bathsheba, the wife of Uriah. After committing adultery with her and arranging Uriah's death in battle, David took Bathsheba as his wife. God was displeased with David's actions and, through the prophet Nathan, pronounced judgment. One of the consequences was that the child born to David and Bathsheba would die.    Shortly after Nathan delivered the message, the child became very ill. David was deeply troubled-he fasted, lay on the ground, and prayed earnestly for the child's life. His servants tried to comfort him, but he refused to eat or rise from the floor.    On the seventh day, the child died. However, the servants were afraid to tell David, thinking he might harm himself, since he had been so distraught while the child was alive. They said among themselves, \"Behold, while the child was yet alive, we spoke to him and he did not listen to our voice; how then can we say to him the child is dead?\"    Surprisingly, when David realized the child was dead, he got up, washed himself, changed his clothes, worshipped God, and ate. When asked why he reacted that way, David explained that while the child was alive, he hoped God might show mercy. But now that the child was dead, he said, \"I shall go to him, but he shall not return to me.\"    This incident highlights David's deep repentance, his understanding of God's sovereignty, and his acceptance of divine judgment.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION A>4>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD : DAVID’S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD", "question": "State three benefits Christians derive from submitting to the will of God.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Three benefits Christians derive from submitting to the will of God are:    Inner peace and assurance: When Christians align with God's will, they experience a deep sense of peace, knowing they are under His guidance and protection, even in difficult times.    Spiritual growth and maturity: Submission to God's will helps believers develop faith, patience, and obedience, drawing them closer to God and strengthening their spiritual character.    Divine favor and blessings: Obeying God's will often results in God's blessings, direction, and provision in various areas of life, including relationships, health, and purpose.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>5>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL", "question": "Describe the appearance of the risen Christ to the two men on their way to Emmaus.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The event is recorded in Luke 24:13-35. After Jesus' resurrection, two disciples were walking to the village of Emmaus, about seven miles from Jerusalem. As they walked, they discussed the recent events surrounding Jesus' crucifixion and the reports of His resurrection.    Jesus joined them on the road, but they did not recognize Him. He asked what they were talking about, and they expressed surprise that He seemed unaware of the major events in Jerusalem. They told Him about Jesus of Nazareth, whom they had hoped was the one to redeem Israel, and how He was crucified. They also mentioned the astonishing news from some women who claimed Jesus had risen.    Jesus then explained the Scriptures to them, beginning with Moses and the Prophets, showing how they all pointed to the Messiah's suffering and glory.    When they reached Emmaus, Jesus acted as if He would continue on, but they urged Him to stay since evening was approaching. During the meal, Jesus took bread, gave thanks, broke it, and gave it to them. At that moment, their eyes were opened-they recognized Him, and He immediately vanished from their sight.    Filled with excitement and awe, the disciples hurried back to Jerusalem to tell the others about their encounter and how they had recognized Jesus in the breaking of the bread.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>5>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE CRUCIFIXION, BURIAL AND RESURRECTION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION", "question": "Explain two benefits Christians derive from the resurrection of Christ.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Triumph Over Sin and Death: Jesus' resurrection stands as a powerful demonstration of His victory over sin and death. By rising from the grave, He broke the power of death and opened the way to eternal life for all who believe in Him. This assures Christians that death is not the final destination but a gateway to everlasting life with God (1 Corinthians 15:54-57). It gives believers confidence that, just as Christ rose, they too will be raised to life.    - A Transformed Life in Christ: The resurrection also represents the beginning of a new spiritual life for believers. According to Apostle Paul, just as Christ was raised from the dead, those who put their faith in Him are spiritually reborn (Romans 6:4). This new life enables Christians to break free from the control of sin and live in alignment with God's will, empowered by the Holy Spirit to fulfill His purpose for their lives.    – Confirmation of Jesus' Divinity and Mission:  The resurrection affirms that Jesus is truly the Son of God, as He had foretold His death and resurrection (Romans 1:4). It validates His claims, teachings, and redemptive mission, proving that He is the promised Messiah and Savior of the world.    – Foundation of the Christian Faith:  Without the resurrection, the Christian message would be empty. Paul declares that if Christ had not risen, faith would be futile and believers still trapped in sin (1 Corinthians 15:14,17). The resurrection is central to the gospel and the basis of Christian hope.    – Assurance of Justification:  Through His resurrection, Jesus secured the believer's justification—being made right with God (Romans 4:25). It means that Christ's sacrificial death was accepted by God, and those who believe in Him are now declared righteous in God's sight.    – Source of Hope and Encouragement in Trials:  The resurrection offers hope in times of suffering, persecution, and hardship. It reminds Christians that just as Christ endured suffering but triumphed, they too will overcome present struggles and share in His glory (1 Peter 1:3–6).", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>6>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "'You wicked servants, I forgave you all that debt because you besought me...\" Trace the circumstance under which this statement was made.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "This statement is drawn from Matthew 18:21-35, where Jesus tells the Parable of the Unforgiving Servant in response to Peter's question about forgiveness. Peter asked how many times he should forgive someone who sins against him-suggesting up to seven times. Jesus replied, \"not seven times, but seventy times seven,\" teaching that forgiveness should have no limit.    To illustrate this, Jesus told a parable about a king who decided to settle accounts with his servants. One servant owed him an enormous, unpayable debt (10,000 talents). When he couldn't pay, the king ordered that he and his family be sold. The servant pleaded for patience, and the king, moved with compassion, forgave the entire debt.    Soon after, the same servant found a fellow servant who owed him a much smaller amount (100 denarii). Instead of showing mercy, he demanded payment and had the man thrown into prison when he couldn't pay. Other servants saw this and reported it to the king.    The king summoned the unforgiving servant and rebuked him: \"You wicked servant, I forgave you all that debt because you pleaded with me. Should you not have shown the same mercy to your fellow servant?\" In anger, the king handed him over to be punished until he repaid everything.    Jesus concluded by warning that God will deal similarly with anyone who refuses to forgive others from the heart. The parable strongly emphasizes that since God has shown us great mercy, we must also be willing to forgive others freely and sincerely.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>6>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "JESUS’ TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS", "question": "Outline two reasons for which forgiveness is beneficial to Christians.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Rebuilding Broken Relationships: Forgiveness plays a vital role in restoring damaged relationships. When Christians choose to forgive, they mirror God's love and mercy, which helps rebuild trust and foster peace. This act of grace promotes reconciliation-whether in families, churches, or communities-and encourages unity. It also enables believers to live out Jesus' command to love others just as He has loved them (John 13:34).    - Freedom from Emotional and Spiritual Burdens: Harboring anger and bitterness can weigh heavily on the heart and soul. Forgiveness liberates Christians from these emotional chains, bringing inner peace and healing. Letting go of grudges not only leads to personal wholeness but also deepens one's spiritual growth. Jesus emphasized that extending forgiveness to others is key to receiving God's own forgiveness (Matthew 6:14-15), establishing a continuous flow of grace and freedom.    – Obedience to God's Command:  Forgiveness is not optional for believers—it is a direct command from God. Jesus taught that Christians must forgive not just once, but repeatedly (Matthew 18:21–22). Obeying this instruction reflects true discipleship and a heart that is aligned with God's will.    – Reflection of God's Nature:  When Christians forgive, they reflect the character of God, who is rich in mercy and slow to anger (Psalm 103:8–12). Forgiveness is a mark of spiritual maturity and Christlikeness, showing that the believer has been transformed by God's grace and is willing to extend that same grace to others.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>7>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD : GOD, THE CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE", "question": "Give an account of Gamaliel's intervention during the arrest of the apostles.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The account of Gamaliel's intervention is found in Acts 5:33–40. After Peter and John were arrested for preaching about Jesus' resurrection, the Jewish leaders became enraged and wanted to execute them. However, Gamaliel, a respected Pharisee and teacher of the law, who was highly regarded by the people, stepped in with a wise warning.    He reminded the Sanhedrin of previous rebellious leaders—Theudas and Judas the Galilean—who had attracted followers but ultimately failed when their leaders were killed and their movements fell apart. Gamaliel advised that if the apostles' mission was of human origin, it would collapse on its own. But if it was truly from God, then opposing it would mean fighting against God Himself.    His reasoning persuaded the council. Though the apostles were flogged and ordered not to speak in Jesus' name, they were released. Gamaliel's intervention not only saved their lives but also allowed the early church to continue its growth, highlighting the importance of patience, discernment, and acknowledging God's sovereignty in spiritual matters.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>7>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION TO THE GENTILES : MISSION TO THE GENTILES", "question": "State three ways by which Christians can promote the growth of the Church.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "- Evangelism and Gospel Outreach: Church growth is largely driven by evangelism-actively sharing the message of Jesus Christ with others. Through personal witness, organized outreach, or public preaching, Christians help spread the gospel, inviting others to follow Christ and become part of the church.    - Authentic Christian Living: When believers live out their faith with sincerity-showing love, humility, and integrity-they become living examples of the gospel's power. This kind of Christ-like lifestyle draws others to the faith and encourages them to explore and join the church community.    - Creating a Supportive Church Family: A warm and caring church environment helps promote growth. By fostering fellowship, offering support, and encouraging spiritual development through Bible studies, prayer groups, and mentorship, Christians help build a church that welcomes newcomers and strengthens existing members.    – Discipleship and Leadership Development:  A growing church invests in teaching and mentoring its members to become mature disciples of Christ. Through intentional discipleship and leadership training, believers are equipped to serve, teach, and lead others, thereby multiplying the church's influence and ensuring sustainable growth.    – Prayer and Dependence on the Holy Spirit:  Church growth is ultimately a spiritual process that requires divine guidance. Persistent prayer and reliance on the Holy Spirit empower believers, open doors for evangelism, and break spiritual barriers. When a church earnestly seeks God's presence, transformation and expansion follow (Acts 2:42–47).", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>8>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "THE CALL AND DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP : LUKE 5: 1-11; 9: 57-63; 14: 25-33", "question": "'But you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, God'sown people.' Highlight Peter's exhortation to Christianson the above statement.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The statement \"But you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, God's own people\" is taken from 1 Peter 2:9, where the Apostle Peter offers a powerful exhortation to Christians about their identity and purpose in Christ.    Here is a summary of Peter's exhortation based on that statement:    Identity in Christ:  Peter reminds believers that they are not ordinary people—they have been specially chosen by God. Unlike those who reject Christ, Christians are part of a spiritual lineage marked by God's favor and purpose.    A Royal Priesthood:  Christians are called priests and royalty in a spiritual sense. This means they have direct access to God through Jesus Christ, and they are to serve Him with devotion, offering spiritual sacrifices such as worship, obedience, and good works.    A Holy Nation:  As a holy nation, Christians are set apart from the world. They are called to live in holiness, reflecting God's character in their conduct and being a moral example to others.    God's Own Possession:  Peter emphasizes that believers belong to God, they are His treasured people. This belonging comes with the responsibility to live in a way that honors God and reflects His love and truth.    Purpose: To Proclaim God's Greatness:  Christians are called not just to enjoy their new identity but to declare the praises of God, who called them out of darkness into His marvelous light. Their lives should be a testimony to God's mercy, grace, and transformative power.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>8>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "SIN AND ITS CONSEQUENCES", "question": "Outline three ways by which Christians can avoid the temptation of sin.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The ways by which Christians can avoid the temptation of sin are:    - Studying and Obeying God's Word:  Regular reading and meditation on the Bible equips Christians with spiritual wisdom and strength to resist temptation. God's Word acts as a guide and a shield against sinful desires (Psalm 119:11).    - Prayer and Dependence on God:  Through constant prayer, Christians seek God's help to stay strong and vigilant. Jesus taught His followers to pray, \"Lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil\" (Matthew 6:13), emphasizing the need for divine support.    - Avoiding Sinful Influences and Environments:  Christians can resist temptation by staying away from situations, places, or people that encourage sinful behavior. Surrounding oneself with godly influences and accountability partners helps maintain a righteous path.    – Fasting and Self-Discipline:  Fasting helps Christians train their bodies and minds to submit to God's will rather than worldly desires. It builds self-control and spiritual alertness, making it easier to resist the pull of sin (Galatians 5:16–17).    – Fellowship with Other Believers:  Staying connected to a community of faithful Christians provides encouragement, correction, and accountability. Regular fellowship through church meetings, Bible study, and Christian friendships strengthens one's resolve against sin (Hebrews 10:24–25).    – Focusing on Eternal Rewards:  Keeping a heavenly perspective motivates believers to live righteously. Remembering the eternal consequences of sin and the rewards of obedience helps Christians make godly choices even when tempted (Colossians 3:1–2).    – Confession and Repentance:  When believers fall, promptly confessing sin and genuinely repenting helps prevent deeper entanglement in temptation. It restores the relationship with God and renews spiritual strength to overcome future struggles (1 John 1:9).", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>9>a", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "a", "group": "", "topic": "SIN AND ITS CONSEQUENCES", "question": "Recount the teaching of James in which he remarked that for whoever keeps the whole law but fails in one point has become guilty of all of it.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "The teaching referred to is found in James 2:8–11, where James emphasizes the importance of obeying the entire law of God, not just selected parts of it.    In this passage, James is addressing the issue of partiality, especially the unfair treatment of the poor in the church. He teaches that showing favoritism is a sin, even if someone obeys other parts of the law. He then makes the striking statement:  \"For whoever keeps the whole law but fails in one point has become guilty of all of it.\" (James 2:10)    James supports this by reminding his audience that the same God who said, \"Do not commit adultery,\" also said, \"Do not murder.\" Therefore, breaking even one commandment is a violation of the whole law because all commandments come from the same divine source. To break one is to break the unity and integrity of the law.    His teaching highlights that:    Sin is not selective—we cannot choose which commandments to obey and which to ignore.    Obedience to God must be complete, not partial.    All sins are serious in God's eyes, and even a single act of disobedience makes a person accountable before God.    Ultimately, James urges Christians to live by the \"law of liberty\"—the law of love and mercy—and to avoid hypocrisy by practicing justice and humility in all aspects of their lives.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}, {"id": "theory>CRK>2025>SECTION B>9>b", "subject": "CRK", "year": "2025", "type": "Theory", "sub_label": "b", "group": "", "topic": "THE EPISTLE OF 1 PETER : GOOD CITIZENSHIP", "question": "Highlighht three negative effects of discrimination.", "images": [], "marking_scheme": "Discrimination in any form, whether based on race, gender, religion, ethnicity, social class, or physical ability, poses a serious threat to the development and unity of any society. It not only undermines the principles of justice and equality but also disrupts social cohesion, economic progress, and the overall well being of citizens. Here are some significant ways in which discrimination hinders the growth of a society.    - Firstly, discrimination limits access to opportunities and resources. When individuals or groups are treated unfairly due to prejudice, they are often denied equal access to quality education, employment, healthcare, and political representation. This creates a system where talent is wasted and potential is stifled, as many capable people are shut out simply because of their background or identity. A society that marginalizes certain groups deprives itself of the full range of skills, perspectives, and innovations needed for sustainable development.    - Secondly, discrimination breeds social division and conflict. When people feel excluded or treated unjustly, it leads to resentment, tension, and sometimes even violence. Discriminatory practices erode trust among citizens and between the public and institutions. This weakens national unity and makes it harder to foster a sense of belonging and shared purpose. A divided society struggles to cooperate on important issues, making progress slower and more fragile.    - Thirdly, discrimination damages mental and emotional well being, which in turn affects productivity and social participation. Victims of discrimination often suffer from low self esteem, depression, anxiety, and a sense of hopelessness. These emotional burdens can hinder their ability to contribute meaningfully to the society, whether in the workplace, the classroom, or civic life. Moreover, a society that tolerates discrimination sends the message that some lives are worth less than others, creating a toxic environment that discourages mutual respect and empathy.    - Fourthly, discrimination hinders economic growth and development.  By sidelining certain groups from participating fully in the economy, discrimination leads to underemployment and inefficiency. When qualified individuals are denied jobs or promotions due to bias, it results in a misallocation of human resources. This not only affects personal livelihoods but also reduces overall productivity and innovation. Inclusive economies, on the other hand, benefit from a diverse workforce that brings a wider range of ideas, talents, and solutions to complex problems.    - Fifthly, discrimination undermines democratic values and human rights.  A just and fair society is built on the principles of equality and respect for all individuals. When discrimination is allowed to persist, it contradicts these values and weakens the rule of law. People lose faith in legal and political institutions if they see them as biased or corrupt. This erosion of trust can lead to political apathy, civil unrest, and even the collapse of democratic systems if left unchecked.    In conclusion, discrimination is a destructive force that undermines equality, weakens social bonds, and suppresses human potential. For any society to grow and thrive, it must strive to eliminate discrimination in all its forms and promote a culture of inclusion, fairness, and respect for all people. Only then can the full talents and contributions of every individual be harnessed for the collective good.", "marks": "1", "difficulty": "3"}];